aS'<div class="entry">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<p>As a Clearwater personal injury attorney I am often asked, \r\n&#8220;Should I call the police to the scene of the accident?&#8221; Yes. Many \r\nreasons exist to call the police to the scene of an accident regardless \r\nof how minor the impact or damage is.<br />\r\nFirst, let&#8217;s talk about why people don&#8217;t call police to the scene. </p>\r\n<p>Obviously if you&#8217;re in a car accident, you were likely en route to a \r\ndestination. If you&#8217;re like me, you were probably running late. As a \r\nresult, we desire this to be over as quickly as possible. Many assume \r\nthat the presence of a police officer will result in an extended delay. \r\nSimply, this is not true. Generally, it only takes law enforcement a few\r\n minutes to make it out to the scene. An officer will do a quick report,\r\n and gather relevant information and witnesses. Secondly, people believe\r\n that it is bothersome to call a police officer for a minor collision. \r\nThis is not true. Police officers and other units under the control of \r\nthe police are employed for matters such as this. This is part of their \r\nduty. </p>\r\n<p>So, why should the police be called to the scene of every accident? \r\nTo document what happened. Inevitably, we want to trust that others will\r\n be honest and tell exactly what happened in the accident. However, many\r\n individuals will distort the facts in an effort to prevent an increase \r\nto the costs of their respective insurance premium. Without the accident\r\n documented correctly from law enforcement it will simply come down to \r\ntwo separate stories and the insurance carriers involved will incur \r\ndifficulty in determining who was actually liable. Secondly, a person \r\ncan claim to have never been in an accident or can provide a false name.\r\n Without police there to ensure the accident is documented properly, a \r\nperson can be lied to or given false information.</p>\r\n<p>In conclusion, it is important for us to call the police to the scene\r\n of any accident we are involved in. This does not add considerable time\r\n to the resolution of the matter and the benefits far outweigh the \r\ninconveniences. The police can properly document the accident, \r\nillustrating you were not at fault. In addition, they might issue a \r\ncitation to the at fault party further solidifying you did not \r\ncontribute to said accident. Lastly, by using law enforcement you can \r\nguarantee a proper exchange of names and driver information. For all of \r\nthose reasons, it is imperative for each of us to call a police officer \r\nto the scene of every accident. </p>\r\n<p>- Bryan C. Hannan, Esq.</p>\r\n<p><em>Bryan Hannan, Esq., is a Clearwater personal injury attorney and a\r\n Tampa Bay brain injury lawyer who limits his practice to insurance \r\nclaims arising from, automobile accidents, insurance carrier bad faith, \r\ntraumatic brain injuries and wrongful death. For more information, do \r\nnot hesitate to contact Bryan at: <a href="mailto:bryan@dolmanlaw.com">bryan@dolmanlaw.com</a></em></p><p></p><p><a href="http://www.facebook.com/dolmanlawgroup">Find us on Facebook</a></p><p><a href="http://www.twitter.com/dolmanlaw">Find us on Twitter</a><br /><em></em></p>\r\n\t\t\t\t</div><!--more-->&#8220;Should I call the police to the scene of the accident?&#8221; Yes. Many \r\nreasons exist to call the police to the scene of an accident regardless \r\nof how minor the impact or damage is.\r\nFirst, let&#8217;s talk about why people don&#8217;t call police to the scene.'
