aS'<p><strong>By John Cooper</strong>, Norfolk Industrial Accidents lawyer</p><p>Some of the biggest awards in personal injury cases concern brain injuries. Why? Because you may never recover from a brain injury in the same way as a broken leg often heals.</p><p>The biggest personal injury case in Virginia in 2013 was a $14 million settlement to an industrial worker who suffered blindness and a traumatic brain injury in an accident, according to&#160;<i>Virginia Lawyers Weekly.</i></p><p>The case concerned a machine shop operator who was blinded in an accident involving an automated machine. The 49-year-old machine operator was hit between the eyes by a broken metal shaft that went flying out of the machine at 270 miles per hour.</p><p>This was a terrifying and dreadful industrial accident that left him with extensive skull fractures, mild traumatic brain injury and immediate loss of sight in one eye. He later lost sight in the other. The plaintiff argued defects in the machine caused the accident.</p><p>The case was settled in mediation. The attorneys for the plaintiff were Matthew Broughton, Gregory Habeeb, Catherine Huff and Robert Evans.</p><p>Every year there are a number of industrial accidents in Hampton Roads. At the end of 2013, a&#160;<a  rel="nofollow" href="http://www.cooperhurley.com/blog/osha-probes-death-of-worker-at-lyons-shipyard-in-norfolk-va/">worker was killed at the Lyons Shipyard in Norfolk.</a>&#160;He was hit by a heavy piece of equipment.</p><p>In another industrial accident a&#160;<a  rel="nofollow" href="http://www.cooperhurley.com/blog/newport-news-injury-lawyer-report-worker-is-burned-at-auto-repair-center-in-newport-news/">worker suffered burns at an auto shop in Newport News</a>. If you have been hurt in an industrial accident, call the Cooper Hurley Injury Lawyers or see <a  rel="nofollow" href="http://www.cooperhurley.com">www.cooperhurley.com</a>.</p>'
