aS'<p class="MsoNormal">In continuation of reviewing the New Jersey criminal justice\r\nsystem, following the <a href="http://criminal.lawyers.com/blogs/archives/28156-NJ-Criminal-Defense-Process-Series-Part-I,-Investigation-and-Arrest.html" title="NJ Criminal Defense Process Series: Part I, Arrest/Investigation">investigation phase</a>, law enforcement or the county\r\nprosecutor may file a complaint.&#160; Civilians\r\nmay also file complaints, which are then forwarded to the county prosecutor for investigation, if the alleged offense is a crime.&#160; The person who files\r\nthe complaint is called a complainant, and the person charged with the\r\noffense(s) is the defendant.&#160; Complaints\r\nare normally completed and sworn in at the local municipal court of the town or\r\ncity where the alleged offense occurred.&#160;\r\nWhen a civilian complainant submits a complaint, the municipal court\r\njudge, the court clerk, or a police officer must administer an oath to the\r\ncomplainant in order to properly allege that what is contained in the complaint\r\nis true.&#160; From that moment on, the\r\ncomplaint is an official court document and enters into the criminal justice\r\nsystem.</p><p class="MsoNormal"><b>Warrant Complaint</b></p><p class="MsoNormal"><b></b>There are two types of complaints: a warrant complaint and a\r\nsummons complaint.&#160; The warrant complaint\r\ncontains an arrest warrant which authorizes any law enforcement officer in the\r\nState of New Jersey to arrest the defendant.&#160;\r\nComplaints for the following offenses usually include an arrest warrant:</p><p class="MsoNormal" /><ul><li>Murder</li><li>Kidnapping</li><li>Aggravated Manslaughter</li><li>Manslaughter</li><li>Robbery</li><li>Aggravated Sexual Assault</li><li>Sexual Assault</li><li>Aggravated Criminal Sexual Contact</li><li>Criminal Sexual Contact</li><li>Aggravated Assault</li><li>Aggravated Arson</li><li>Arson</li><li>Burglary</li><li>Drug crimes</li><li>Weapons offenses</li><li>Conspiracy or attempts to commit such crimes</li></ul>A court may also issue and arrest warrant for the following\r\nevents:<br /><p class="MsoNormal" /><ul><li>Failure to respond to a summons.</li><li>Judge or court clerk believed the defendant is\r\neither a danger to himself, to others or to property.</li><li>There are one or more outstanding arrest warrants\r\nfor the accused.</li><li>The whereabouts of the defendant is known and\r\nan arrest warrant is necessary to subject that person to the jurisdiction of\r\nthe court.</li><li>The judge or the court clerk has reason to\r\nbelieve that the defendant would not appear in response to a summons.</li></ul><p font-weight: bold;">Summons Complaint</p><p>The other form of complaint is a summons complaint, in which\r\ncase the offense or circumstances does not meet any of the above conditions.&#160; A summons complaint notifies the defendant of\r\nhis charges and provides a court date on which the defendant must appear.&#160; Failure to appear can lead to an arrest\r\nwarrant.</p><p>There are many cases in which an accused can be arrested\r\nwithout a complaint.&#160; Once the arrest is\r\ncompleted, the accused becomes the defendant and a formal complaint must then\r\nbe filed.</p><p>If you have a pending summons or an arrest warrant or have\r\nbeen arrested for allegedly committing a crime, contact an experienced criminal\r\ndefense attorney to discuss your matter.</p><!--more-->In continuation of reviewing the New Jersey criminal justice system, following the investigation phase, law enforcement or the county prosecutor may file a complaint.&#160;Civilians may also file complaints, which are then forwarded to the county prosecutor for investigation, if the alleged offense is a crime.&#160;&#160;The person who files the complaint is called a complainant, and the person charged with the offense(s) is the defendant.&#160;'
