aS'Fosamax is the brand name of a Merck &amp; Co. drug product which contains alendronic acid.&#160; Alendronic acid is prescribed to patients with osteoporosis, a bone disease in which bone density declines, leading to falls and fractures.&#160; Fosamax, as well as Fosamax +D which contains additional Vitamin D, is used to treat osteoporosis by helping patients grown new bone in place of that which has been lost.&#160; Merck\'s patent for Fosamax expired in 2008, and the drug has since then been produced generically .<br /><br />Although the pharmacology for Fosamax and its generics indicates that it is meant to increase healthy bone growth, thereby limiting the damage from osteoporosis, there are some serious side effects which Merck urged users to consider before taking the drug.&#160; Merck marketed the drug as a &quot;biophosphonate,&quot; and the attendant warnings were typical for this class of drug.&#160; Merck stated that patients should consider avoiding dental surgery, as deterioration of the jawbone may result from surgery performed while taking this type of drug.&#160; Other, lesser side effects indicated by Merck were skin rash and occasional joint, bone, or muscle pain.<br /><br />However, Merck did not release information that the drug might cause a rare type of bone fracture, known as a &quot;low-energy&quot; break.&#160; Low-energy breaks can occur from as little as standing height, and involve the femur, or the large bone of the thigh.&#160; Typically, patients experience a short fall, such as tripping or simply falling to the floor, which in most cases would result only in bruising.&#160; However, in Fosamax patients, these short falls may result in a broken femur.&#160; <br /><br />These types of fractures occurred in the thigh bones of several patients taking Fosamax, prompting investigation into the reasons for these types of breaks. Studies showed a link to the use of Fosamax and these femoral fractures.&#160; These studies seemed to indicate that the <a href="http://www.bestattorney.com/pharmaceutical&#95;litigation.html">defective drug</a> caused the thigh bone to become brittle and more likely to break than in patients who were not taking Fosamax.<br /><br />The Food and Drug Administration, or FDA, finally issued a warning about Fosamax and its generics in May of 2010.&#160; This warning stated that there was a link between biophosphonates and atypical bone fractures.&#160; In October of 2010, the FDA backed up its earlier findings by requiring Fosamax and its generics to change their labeling to reflect the new findings about bone fractures.&#160; However, to date, no recall is forthcoming from the FDA.<br /><br />Merck has not acknowledged, to date, any link between atypical thigh bone breaks and Fosamax.&#160; However, at least 100 people have filed lawsuits as the result of fractured thigh bones which they believe are attributable to Fosamax.&#160; One plaintiff recovered $8 million in a single suit.<br /><br />Many expert personal injury attorneys are turning their attention to Fosamax cases.&#160; In some cases, class action suits are planned; in others, plaintiffs prefer to file suit individually.&#160; If you feel you have been injured by taking Fosamax, especially if you have experienced an unexplained thigh bone fracture, talk to an experienced <a href="http://www.bestattorney.com/fosamax.html">Fosamax lawyers</a> immediately.<br /><!--more-->Fosamax is the brand name of a Merck &amp; Co. drug product which \r\ncontains alendronic acid.&#160; Alendronic acid is prescribed to patients \r\nwith osteoporosis, a bone disease in which bone density declines, \r\nleading to falls and fractures.&#160; Fosamax, as well as Fosamax +D which \r\ncontains additional Vitamin D, is used to treat osteoporosis by helping \r\npatients grown new bone in place of that which has been lost.&#160; Merck\'s \r\npatent for Fosamax expired in 2008, and the drug has since '
