aS"<p>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;I had a short trial this week in Monroe County Family Court in which the following occurred:</p><p /><p /><p>items of domestic violence and police reports not reflected in the Petition were not allowed into evidence;</p><p /><p>items of profanity of father directed toward mother were considered protected speech under First Amendment to Constitution;</p><p /><p>scope of respondent's duties at work as school teacher in Brockport limited in examination;</p><p /><p>chalked words on respondent's front porch during child exchange such as beware of the fat man were</p><p /><p>not considered harrassment, since ambiguous meaning and source;</p><p>a rifle in respondent's home last year was sold by respondent to a relative to avoid </p><p>confiscation during temporary order of protection issued two months ago;</p><p /><p>respondent's attorney objected to nearly every question I asked of her client.</p><p /><p /><p>Petition dismissed.&#160; The petitioner did not testify.</p><p /><p /><p /><p>The case will contiue with a modification of custody [mutual] request in September.&#160; Also, father charges</p><p /><p>mother with contempt for not following August 2009 order.</p><p /><p /><p>The temporary order of protection in effect {no contact} was rescinded and child exchanges will continue</p><p /><p>at a coffee shop.</p><p /><p /><p /><p>Although the parties were advised by Court dismissing petition to be civil to one another, this is seen by </p><p>Counsel as specious, when the First Amendment construed by Court to protect all speech, whether profane</p><p>or unkind or ambiguously threatening.</p><p /><p>Hon. Sidney Farber</p><p>Debra Indivino for Respondent</p><p>Lawrence Mort, Rochester, for Petitioner</p><!--more--><p>Trial is an art and not a science.</p><p /><p>Judges have wide discretion in determining the scope of attorney's examination, cross examination and procedure.&#160; If not appealed an adverse verdict becomes the law, and</p><p>must be lived with.</p><p /><p>Assuming mother testified and had transcripts of texts in which father called her bad </p><p /><p>names, would the verdict have been different, due to impeachment of father's credibility.&#160; In my estimation, No.</p><p /><p />"
