aS'<p></p><p><p font: 90%/175% \'Lucida Grande\',\'Lucida Sans Unicode\',Verdana,sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px;">A Michigan based taxpayer operated commercial vessels on the Great Lakes. The then applicable Single Business Tax (repealed effective the end of 2007) apportioned the company&#8217;s income to Michigan in proportion that its Michigan revenue miles bore to all of its revenue miles.</p><p font: 90%/175% \'Lucida Grande\',\'Lucida Sans Unicode\',Verdana,sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px;">Taxpayer argued that revenue derived 3 miles beyond the Michigan shoreline were not Michigan revenue miles. The Court of Appeals (the state&#8217;s intermediate appellate court) held for the state.&#160;<em>Andrie, Inc. v. Department of Treasury</em>, Michigan Court of Appeals, No. 291758, Unpublished (February 11, 2011);<a color: rgb(102, 119, 85);" href="http://coa.courts.mi.gov/documents/opinions/final/coa/20110201&#95;c291758&#95;42&#95;291758.opn.pdf">http://coa.courts.mi.gov/documents/opinions/final/coa/20110201&#95;c291758&#95;42&#95;291758.opn.pdf</a>.</p><p font: 90%/175% \'Lucida Grande\',\'Lucida Sans Unicode\',Verdana,sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px;">The Court said that &#8220;(a)s a general principle, a State may not tax value earned outside its borders.&#8221; It said that Michigan law provides for an apportionment formula for transportation companies based upon the number of revenue miles that a company does in the state for the year to the revenue miles done everywhere.</p><p font: 90%/175% \'Lucida Grande\',\'Lucida Sans Unicode\',Verdana,sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px;">The taxpayer first argued that applying a revenue apportionment formula to it (apparently as opposed to the standard apportionment formulas applied to most businesses) violated its constitutional right to equal protection. The Court dismissed this challenge because it was rational to use a revenue mileage formula for apportioning the income of transportation companies.</p><p font: 90%/175% \'Lucida Grande\',\'Lucida Sans Unicode\',Verdana,sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px;">The Court also dismissed the taxpayer&#8217;s federal constitution commerce clause argument that the revenue mile formula unfairly apportioned income to Michigan &#8220;because the &#8230; (Michigan) &#8230; apportionment formula &#8230; was created specifically to fairly apportion the tax based on each taxpayer&#8217;s activity in the state.&#8221;</p><p font: 90%/175% \'Lucida Grande\',\'Lucida Sans Unicode\',Verdana,sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px;">The taxpayer then cited a 1987 case where a Michigan court held that the state had no sufficient nexus or connection to tax income earned by seamen working on vessels travelling on the Great Lakes. The Court did not find that case persuasive, principally because the seamen in that case were not Michigan residents; whereas the taxpayer &#8220;was not merely providing services on ships plying the Great Lakes, but instead was earning business income based on its services provided in the Great Lakes, and its primary place of business was in Muskegon, Michigan.&#8221;</p><p font: 90%/175% \'Lucida Grande\',\'Lucida Sans Unicode\',Verdana,sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px;">After dismissing the above constitutional attacks, the Court dealt with the central issue of the case; whether revenue miles derived on the Great Lakes were earned &#8220;in Michigan&#8221;, within the meaning of the apportionment statute. The Court agreed with the taxpayer, that the United States Supreme Court considered the Great Lakes the &#8220;high seas&#8221; for purposes of the federal constitution&#8217;s grant of nonexclusive jurisdiction to federal courts to hear &#8220;admiralty and maritime&#8221; cases: &#8220;Nevertheless, the tax in question does not impermissibly interfere or intrude with the federal admiralty jurisdiction, and there is no indication that the admiralty authority would occupy the field and preempt a state from apportioning a tax based on travel on the high seas within a state&#8217;s boundaries.&#160;&#160; The authority to tax plaintiff is warranted based on plaintiff&#8217;s residence and primary location in Muskegon.&#8221;</p><p font: 90%/175% \'Lucida Grande\',\'Lucida Sans Unicode\',Verdana,sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px;"><strong>Comment</strong>: The Court said at the outset that the statutory challenge was based upon revenue miles earned 3 miles beyond the Michigan shoreline. This attack must be based upon the old rule that measured a country&#8217;s jurisdiction up to 3 miles from its shoreline. The Court apparently held that revenue miles earned 3 miles beyond the Michigan shoreline were &#8220;in Michigan&#8221;. However, it never specifically discussed the 3 mile issue.</p></p>'
