aS'Today, I received word of the approval last week of an I-130 visa petition on one of my <a href="http://www.bretzlaw.com/">law firm&#8217;s</a> same-sex marriage cases.&#160; This was welcome and momentous news for me, as well as for my clients, Mr. Alan Tulin (U.S. citizen petitioner) and his spouse Mr. Carlos Beserra Luis (Brazilian beneficiary).&#160;&#160; The approval came as a result of the U.S. Supreme Court&#8217;s landmark decision on June 26, 2013, in the case, United States v. Windsor, No. 12-307.&#160; The top court&#8217;s decision struck down Section 3 of the federal 1996 Defense of Marriage Act (DOMA) as unconstitutionally discriminatory.&#160; The section had arbitrarily (a) limited the meaning of the words &#8220;marriage&#8221; and &#8220;spouse&#8221; to refer to a legal union between one man and one woman and (b) caused the denial of federal benefits to legally married same-sex couples.&#160; The top court&#8217;s decision applies only to marriages performed or &#8220;celebrated&#8221; in the U.S. States (13 in total to date) plus the District of Colombia that have legalized same-sex marriages. &#160;<br /><br />The landmark case was originally filed by Edith Windsor in U.S. District Court.&#160; As a surviving spouse, she had sought a federal estate tax exemption.&#160; It was denied because her same-sex marriage was not recognized under DOMA.&#160; The Supreme Court decision overturning DOMA enabled the estate to qualify for the exemption.&#160; On the day of the decision, President Obama instructed his Cabinet to &#8220;review all relevant federal statutes to ensure this decision, including its implications for Federal benefits and obligations, is implemented swiftly and smoothly.&#8221;&#160;&#160; And so, although this case grew out of a federal estate tax issue, the top court&#8217;s decision impacted other areas of federal law governing benefits and protections previously denied to married same-sex couples.&#160;&#160; &#160;<br /><br />In the area of immigration law, what comes immediately to mind is that a U.S. citizen or lawful permanent resident in a same-sex marriage can now sponsor a spouse for a family-based immigrant visa.&#160; Even though a same-sex marital couple may live in a state that does not recognize their union, their marriage is legally valid for immigration purposes if it was performed or &#8220;celebrated&#8221; in a marriage equality state.&#160; My abovementioned clients&#8217; case is an example of this.&#160; Mr. Tulin and Mr. Beserra Luis were lawfully married in Massachusetts, but filed their visa petition from New Jersey which has not yet become a marriage equality state. <br /><br />Many other aspects of immigration law are positively affected by the top court&#8217;s decision.&#160; These include fiance/fiancee petitions, derivative immigration status, petitions previously denied solely due to DOMA, and a reduced residence period requirement for naturalization.&#160;&#160; On the other hand, there are some unfavorable consequences.&#160; In the case of family preference immigrant visas, those who previously qualified as &#8220;unmarried sons and daughters&#8221; of U.S. citizens due to non-recognition of their same-sex marriages would now fall into the category of &#8220;married sons and daughters&#8221; of U.S. citizens.&#160; This would subject them to a longer waiting period for an immigrant visa.&#160; What is more unfortunate is that those who previously qualified as &#8220;unmarried sons and daughters&#8221; of lawful permanent residents (LPR) due to non-recognition of their same-sex marriages would be rendered ineligible for a immigrant visa because LPRs are not legally able to sponsor married sons and daughters. &#160;<br /><br />However, other positives are waivers and forms of relief from removal requiring a qualifying relative.&#160; A waiver of inadmissibility based on extreme hardship to an immigrant&#8217;s USC or LPR spouse is now possible for married same-sex couples.&#160; A same-sex spouse will now have access to forms of relief of removal based on marriage that include adjustment of status, cancellation of removal, waivers under sections 212 (h) and (i) of the Immigration and Nationality Act, and VAWA protection.<br /><br />This article highlights some of the benefits afforded to married same-sex couples as a result of the Supreme Court&#8217;s landmark decision striking down Section 3 of DOMA.&#160; The article was provided by Bretz &amp; Coven, LLP, which <a href="http://www.bretzlaw.com/">practices immigration law in New York City </a>and throughout the United States.&#160; For more in-depth information and advice on this and other immigration matters, contact Senior Partner, Kerry Bretz at <a href="http://www.bretzlaw.com/contact">http://www.bretzlaw.com/contact</a>.<br /><br />'
