aS'<div>Vehicle technology designed to prevent people from driving while intoxicated has made great strides in recent years. In fact, some people believe that within the next decade, cars will have alcohol sensors that eliminate drunk driving altogether. Machines have been developed that can read blood-alcohol content via a fingerprint scan, and eye scan, and a person&#8217;s sweat. <br /><br />For those in Northern Virginia, a&#160;<a href="http://www.thomashwilsonlaw.com/"><strong>Manassas DUI lawyer</strong></a> could be a knowledgeable resource in the various types of technologies available for current use. <br /><br />One current&#160;<a href="http://www.thomashwilsonlaw.com/Firm%20Info/Practice%20Areas/DUI%20and%20DWI.aspx">DUI</a> prevention technology called an <a href="http://www.dadss.org/">ignition interlock</a> requires drivers to give a breath sample every time they start their cars. If the technology detects any trace of alcohol, the car will not start. Although this approach has been highly successful in preventing convicted drunk drivers from repeating their actions, it is not appropriate for the general public. Those who do not drink or do not drink and drive feel that the technology is unnecessary and intrusive. <br /><br />As the search continues to create a technology that is more realistic for widespread use, some of the qualities that researchers and technicians are looking for include: </div><div><ul><li>Accuracy</li><li>Cost-effectiveness</li><li>Maintenance-free</li><li>Not intrusive</li></ul><p />What people think Studies show that a majority of Americans support advancements in vehicle technology that could prevent drivers from driving while intoxicated. In 2006, Mothers Against Drunk Driving (MADD), the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA), the Auto Alliance, and the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety came together to create a <a href="http://www.madd.org/Drunk-Driving/Drunk-Driving/Campaign-to-Eliminate-Drunk-Driving/Advanced-Technology.aspx">panel on advanced alcohol detection technology</a>. Their collaborative research will explore the potential benefits of alcohol detection technologies, as well as their overall feasibility and any public policy changes that might arise because of their use. <br /><br />Some potential methods of DUI prevention these groups are exploring include: <ul><li>Touch-based systems to measure blood alcohol levels through the skin</li><li>Visible light that could measure blood alcohol levels through spectroscopy</li><li>Various eye movement measurement technologies</li><li>A more advanced method of breath testing</li></ul><p>Although studies estimate that the creation of an accessible and non-intrusive advanced alcohol detection technology for vehicles could prevent up to 9,000 automobile accident deaths each year, unfortunately, that technology is not available at this moment. As is, many Americans have suffered from the results of driving while intoxicated, both as victims and those responsible, who if arrested can face severe fines, penalties, and possible imprisonment for their actions. </p>DUI lawyers in ManassasIf you or someone close to you has been involved in a DUI situation, it is important to contact an experienced&#160;<a href="http://www.thomashwilsonlaw.com/en/Firm%20Info/Practice%20Areas/DUI%20FAQ.aspx">DUI&#160;attorney in Manassas</a>&#160;who can explain your rights and fight on your behalf in a court of law. Protect your rights and contact the Manassas Law Office of Thomas H. Wilson today for effective drunk driving defense. </div><!--more--><p>Former Virginia Commonwealth\'s Attorney Thomas H. Wilson writes about the latest technology that could help prevent DUI, and how a <a href="http://www.thomashwilsonlaw.com/"><strong>Manassas DUI lawyer</strong></a> can assist if you are arrested for drunk driving in Virginia.</p>'
