aS'<p>Tort law is a fancy name for the civil wrongdoing of others. These include personal injury cases and other wrongdoings where someone is directly at fault for another person\'s physical, legal, or economic harm. Holding these people accountable generally results in a lawsuit claim that is filed by the wronged party, depending on the type of case that occurs. Tort is divided into three basic categories; intentional torts, liability torts, and negligent torts. Most cases that are filed in civil court are designated as negligence or liability, although intentional cases are seen, as well. </p>\r\n<p>Negligent tort law covers cases where someone has fault from sheer accident. For example, a company might not be directly liable for your slip and fall injury if there was ice in the parking lot, but they are negligent because they could have fixed the situation so that you didn\'t fall in the first place. Intentional tort is a case where someone meant to do wrong and did so effectively. This includes running a company improperly, manufacturing dangerous products, and other types of cases where someone intentionally did something that harmed another person. Finally, there are liability torts. Product liability is the biggest case here. Such is an example when you use a knife according to the directions and still manage to cut your finger off. This is strict liability on behalf of the product manufacturer and they need to be held accountable.</p>\r\n<p>Working with tort law is what <a href="http://www.getmejustice.com/" target="&#95;blank">personal injury lawyers</a> do best. Their job is specifically to understand the different types of cases that can occur and what they can do to help you get the best outcome when you are involved with this type of case. A tort can cause physical, emotional, economic, or legal damage. It doesn\'t always have to be an actual injury, but in most cases it will be. Defamation, trespassing, and other issues are also considered under tort law. </p>\r\n<p>It\'s going to be up to you to learn about tort law and how it affects your case, no matter what type of situation you are in. The world of tort law is basically about holding someone responsible for the injury or damage caused to another. There are thousands of lawyers who specialize in this type of law and can help people get the settlements and victories that they deserve from a case like this, no matter what actually occurred or who was at fault. </p><!--more-->Tort law is a fancy name for the civil wrongdoing of others. These include personal injury cases and other wrongdoings where someone is directly at fault for another person\'s physical, legal, or economic harm.'
