aS'The Bankruptcy Abuse Prevention and Consumer Protection Act of 2005 (11 U.S.C. &#167;547) defines the ninety days prior to the date an individual debtor files for bankruptcy as the preference period.&#160; A debtor may request that a creditor return any money collected during the preference period.&#160; The question then becomes does a creditor always have to return the money?&#160; The answer is not always. <br /><br />The Act discusses several instances in which creditor may not have to return the money. One such instance is when the amount of money collected from a debtor (with primarily consumer debts) during the preference period is less than $600 (11 U.S.C. &#167;547(c)(8)). The United States Bankruptcy Court for the District of Delaware has yet to address the question of whether creditors may keep any money below $600 collected during the preference period and only need to return funds in excess of $600 or whether to join the majority and find that $600 is a threshold amount. Meaning, if a creditor has received $600 or more during the preference period the creditor must return the whole amount collected.&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; &#160;<br /><br />Clark C. Kingery, P.A. is a debt collection law firm located in Delaware.&#160; This blawg is intended as a place to weigh in on questions that arise in our practice as well as items of general interest to creditors and the small business community. &#160;<br /><br />This is not intended to be legal advice, as each set of circumstances is different and the status of the law can change. To discuss this topic further as pertains to your individual circumstance, please contact us at www.kingerylaw.com or (302)428-1915.&#160;<!--more-->The Bankruptcy Abuse Prevention and Consumer Protection Act of 2005 (11 \r\nU.S.C. &#167;547) defines the ninety days prior to the date an individual \r\ndebtor files for bankruptcy as the preference period.&#160; A debtor may \r\nrequest that a creditor return any money collected during the preference\r\n period.&#160; The question then becomes does a creditor always have to \r\nreturn the money?&#160; The answer is not always.'
