aS'<p>There are still those, even within the school professionals community, who defiantly insist that school bullying is just some kind of &quot;rite of passage&quot; and not worth increased&#160;administrative time and effort to address.&#160; The&#160;harmful effects of bullying in schools, and the statistics&#160;truly showing how widespread it is, is now so well-documented that it cannot be seriously debated.</p><p>And then a case comes along to prove the point, not in a&#160;subtle way, but tragically with a thunderbolt.</p><p>Reports have just been released about a Boston-area case where the local prosecutor has indicted nine&#160;teenagers, 18 years of age and younger, for the kind of systemic, abusive and inhumane&#160;alleged treatment that can crush the will of any parent, or a child who&#160;survives such treatment.</p><p>Tragically in this case, the 15-year-old student could not according to news reports, and she committed suicide after allegedly being subjected to treatment that resulted in indictments for statutory rape, violations of civil rights, and criminal harassment.&#160; </p><p>A 15-year-old, with a lifetime of dreams, gone.&#160; A 15-year-old, who according to news reports, on the day of her death, was seen being bullied by a&#160;school faculty member and several students.&#160; A 15-year-old, who was bullied by males and females alike.&#160; </p><p>For true bullying, the response from a school&#160;official in any capacity that it is a &quot;rite of passage&quot; should make you sick to your stomach.&#160; Continue documenting&#160;school bullying when it occurs.&#160; Continue to report it.&#160; Schools in Georgia are required to&#160;have an anti-bullying policy.</p><p>Take the bullying&#160;seriously, as if you want it stopped immediately.&#160; Take the bullying seriously, as if it could cause extreme harm.&#160; Calmly, coolly and professionally consider speaking at a school board meeting, armed with statistics and articles about the harms of school bullying.&#160; Request that the school board members become educated&#160;on the subject, if they are not.&#160;&#160;Suggest to the school board members that education cannot occur if a student does not feel&#160;safe in school.&#160; </p><p>You have to ache when you read an article like the one about this 15-year-old student, who must have felt so alone at the end of her life.&#160; It&#160;takes no courage -- absolutely none, zero, nada&#160;-- to say that bullying is a &quot;right of passage.&quot;&#160; It takes much courage to wrap your arms around someone who has been targeted,&#160;and to tell them that you stand with them, and that they are not alone.</p><p>Best regards.&#160;&#160;&#160;</p><p />'
