aS'<p>\r\n\r\nTelemarketing scams are one of the most common financial crimes which target elderly citizens.&#160; In fact, according to the American Association of Retired People (AARP) one out of six consumers fall victim to telemarketing scams each year, for an estimated total of over $40 billion.&#160; Furthermore, around 80% of these victims are elders.&#160; There are several reasons as to why scam artists target the elderly, and several common scams to be aware of.&#160; However, it is important to know that law makers are aware of this epidemic, and that the laws are on your side.&#160; Further, if you or your loved ones have fallen victim to such scams, <a href="www.burnsattorneys.com">an experienced trial attorney</a> can help you and your loved ones secure the justice that you deserve.</p><p>Scam artists target elder citizens for a variety of reasons.&#160; One reason is that elder citizens are thought to be friendlier and more willing to talk to telemarketers than others.&#160; Another reason is that elders tend to be more patriotic and respectful towards authority.&#160; Telemarketers take advantage of this by pretending to be associated with the government.&#160; Perhaps the most troubling reason that scam artists target elders, however, is that elders are often embarrassed to admit that they have fallen victim to these schemes.&#160; Yet many of these scam artists are highly sophisticated and, simply put, really good at what they do.&#160; Thus, if you have fallen victim to one of these common schemes, there is nothing to be embarrassed about.&#160; Further, if you suspect that one of your loved ones has fallen victim, there are several indicators to look out for, including: (1) unusual bank activity or withdrawals of large sums of money, (2) disappearance of funds or possessions, (3) entry forms and prizes from contests, and (4) payments made for &quot;free&quot; merchandise or vacations.&#160; In addition to these common indicators, there are several common schemes that you may want to be aware of.</p><p>One common scheme is the prize promotion scheme.&#160; Under this scheme, a phony telemarketer will call a person and tell them that they have won a prize, but that they must first make a purchase or payment before they can collect.&#160; Another common scheme is the fake charity.&#160; In this scheme, a scammer will call and ask for contribtions to a charitable organization that does not actually exist.&#160; To make matters worse, scammers often make up names that sound similar to real charitable organizations.&#160; Finally, another common scheme is the credit card repair offer.&#160; In this scheme, the caller will claim to be able to fix or erase negative information from your credit report.</p><p>If you or your loved ones have fallen victim to financial elder abuse, such as the telemarketing schemes mentioned above, CONTACT US at (213) 687-8080 or visit our website at <a href="http://www.burnsattorneys.com">www.burnsattorneys.com</a>. </p>'
