aS"<p>In these difficult financial times, I am often asked what assets can a judgment creditor (&quot;<em>JC</em>&quot;)&#160;go after?&#160; This question obviously comes from a debtor that has resigned himself (itself,&#160;if a business entity)&#160;to the fact that he owes a&#160;creditor money, the creditor has sued him or is about to sue him, and there is little benefit to be gained by spending money defending the lawsuit.&#160; This requires an analysis of the laws in Texas exempting certain assets from execution (the process of collecting a judgment that is final).</p><p>Let's start with the easy part.&#160; Corporations and other entities have no exempt property. All of the assets of a business entity are subject to seizure.&#160; But remember, there is not a whole lot of benefit to a JC seizing assets of a business entity that are subject to a prior perfected security interest, and where there is little or no equity in the assets.&#160; If the JC seized those assets, payment would have to be made to the party holding the prior perfected security interest or that party will itself foreclose that security interest and take the asset from the JC.</p><p>With regard to an individual, the JC must determine if the judgment debtor's property is exempt from creditor's claims under one or more statutes.&#160; You can find a lot written on this topic.&#160; Let me try to summarize by stating simply that the following assets <u>cannot</u> be reached by the JC holding a final judgment against an individual:</p><ul><li>the home is exempt regardless of value (with some restrictions on acreage)</li><li>home furnishings, tools of the trade, clothing, vehicles and other specific personal property listed in the Texas exemption statutes are exempt, up to $30,000 for an individual and $60,000 for families</li><li>life insurance, retirement plans and wages are exempt, without any dollar limitation</li></ul><p>Knowing the property that is exempt from execution is important to know for anyone thinking about suing on a debt.&#160; Of course, there are reasons that you might want to sue on that debt in any event, and even knowing that it might not be immediately collectible.&#160; However, that is fodder for another blog at another time.</p><p>Nothing in this post should be considered legal advice by the reader. Let's face it,&#160;you don't know&#160;me and&#160;I don't know you.&#160; My aim is to provide the reader with some useful, but general, information about the topic.&#160; For a legal opinion that has teeth, consult your personal lawyer about your specific facts and circumstances.&#160; If you have no lawyer and like what you see here, then contact my law office to see if my services fit your needs. To do so, simply click on my name above and you will be directed to my website.&#160; When responding, please refer to this <strong>Blog No. 32.</strong></p>"
