aS'<div id="blog-content"><div text-align: left;" class="paragraph editable-text">Frequently, I am asked at what age is a person considered a juvenile rather than an adult for criminal justice purposes in Illinois?</div><div text-align: left;" class="paragraph editable-text"></div><div text-align: left;" class="paragraph editable-text">The\r\n answer to that question depends on the offense. In general, persons  \r\ncharged with misdemeanors in Illinois are juveniles until the age of 18 \r\n and those charged with felonies until the age of 17. However, and it is\r\n a  big however, 15 and 16 year olds facing certain felony charges are  \r\nautomatically charged as adults per statute. Moreover, the Juvenile  \r\nCourt Act provides that in certain circumstances, a prosecutor can file a\r\n  petition and, after a hearing, the Court may decide to transfer a \r\njuvenile to adult court. It is very important that juveniles facing \r\ncharges are represented by experienced counsel. Experienced counsel will know the law and how it applies to the fact situation faced by the young person.</div><div text-align: left;" class="paragraph editable-text"></div><div text-align: left;" class="paragraph editable-text">Lori G. Levin</div><div text-align: left;" class="paragraph editable-text">Attorney at Law</div><div text-align: left;" class="paragraph editable-text">180 N. LaSalle Street, Suite 3700</div><div text-align: left;" class="paragraph editable-text">Chicago, IL 60601</div><div text-align: left;" class="paragraph editable-text">312-972-3756</div><div text-align: left;" class="paragraph editable-text">www.lorilevinlaw.com</div><div text-align: left;" class="paragraph editable-text">levin@lorilevinlaw.com</div>  </div>'
