aS'When an infant is being restricted of oxygen before or during birth, or what is known as birth asphyxiation, a condition named <a href="http://www.fagellaw.com/Information&#95;Center/Brain&#95;Cooling.aspx" title="hypoxic ischemic encephalopathy HIE">hypoxic ischemic encephalopathy or HIE</a> may occur.&#160; HIE will continue to develop over the next several hours as the lack of proper oxygen and blood supply to the brain of the infant will cause additional events to occur within the brain as it attempts to repair itself.&#160; When HIE is mild, there shouldn&#8217;t be a major problem and the baby can be resuscitated.&#160; If the HIE is significant, the baby&#8217;s brain may cause even greater damage to itself as it tries to repair the problem. <br /><br />The good news is the baby usually has several hours before the brain damage becomes permanent.&#160; This gives doctors an opportunity to apply brain cooling to help give the baby a fighting chance for a normal life with little to no permanent brain damage.&#160; By placing the baby&#8217;s brain into a mild hypothermia, a brain cooling procedure can help reduce the infant&#8217;s temperature by 3 to 4 degrees Celsius for 72 hours after birth.&#160; This is done with a water cooled cap or a cool fluid filled blanket.&#160; Reducing the brain temperature of the baby helps slow down or stop dangerous chemical reactions that would cause additional brain injuries without the cooling.&#160; This appears to be the only medical treatment known to help a baby with HIE avoid serious and permanent brain injuries, including cerebral palsy in many cases assuming the following conditions are met:<br /><ul><li>Babies who have HIE must be given the brain cooling procedure within 6 hours of birth</li><li>Babies must have sustained brain damage</li><li>Babies must have been in gestation beyond 36 weeks</li></ul>Doctors need to be careful in making these determinations and take great care in applying brain cooling; otherwise they may cause additional brain damage.&#160; Once the baby&#8217;s temperature has been lowered to 33 degrees Celsius for 72 hours, the baby&#8217;s temperature can be slowly increased back to normal over the next 6 hours. &#160;<br /><br />For an informative video about the brain cooling procedure please visit <a href="http://www.fagellaw.com/Video&#95;Center/Types&#95;of&#95;Cases/Brain&#95;Cooling.aspx" title="brain cooling video">brain cooling video</a>. <br /><br />Visit us on Facebook and Twitter:<br /> Facebook: <a href="https://www.facebook.com/birthinjury" title="Facebook">https://www.facebook.com/birthinjury</a><br /> Twitter: <a href="https://twitter.com/fagellaw" title="Twitter">https://twitter.com/fagellaw</a><br /><br /><!--more-->Brain cooling allows newborn children with HIE resulting from birth hypoxia to avoid permanent or additional brain damage from occurring.&#160; This article discusses what the brain cooling procedure is and the conditions that must be met for the procedure to be successful.'
