aS'<p MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt">Can Those Psychotherapist-Patient Records Really Be Released to the Public?</p><p MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; You&#8217;ve undoubtedly heard about the &#8220;Clergy Cases&#8221; involving the Franciscan Friars of California, Inc. (the Franciscans) who were sued by 25 plaintiffs alleging that they had been sexually abused as minors by the Franciscan brothers.&#160; The case settled several years ago for a total sum of $28,450,000.00 to be paid to plaintiffs by the Franciscans and the Roman Catholic Archbishop of Los Angeles.&#160; &#160;&#160;</p><p TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt">Interestingly, the individual friars who purportedly committed the acts of sexual molestation were never named as defendants in the action; however, the confidential files of Samuel Charles Cabot, Mario Cimmarusti, David Johnson, Gus Krumm, Gary Pacheco and Robert Van Handel (the Individual Friars) which included documents the Individual Friars claimed were subject to the psychotherapist-patient privilege, were produced during the litigation.&#160; The psychiatric reports were obtained in order for the Franciscan&#8217;s to make personnel decisions and to arrange for treatment so the friars could continue their ministry on behalf of the order.&#160;&#160;&#160; The trial court determined that the Individual Friars&#8217; voluntary disclosure of their psychiatric reports to their religious order operated as a waiver of the psychotherapist-patient privilege, even though the friars were told and believed their psychological records would be kept confidential, since the purposes of the disclosure were not reasonably necessary for diagnosis or treatment.&#160; As part of the settlement agreement, the Franciscans and the Roman Catholic Archbishop of Los Angeles, agreed that the confidential files of the Individual Friars could be disclosed to the public, even though the Individual Friars were not parties to that agreement and did not consent to the disclosure of their files to the public.&#160; The trial court determined that the Individual Friars constitutional right of privacy did not preclude disclosure of their confidential files pursuant to the settlement agreement.&#160; &#160;The Individual Friars appealed that decision.</p><p TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt">Upon review, the California Court of Appeal, Second District, Division 8, held that the confidential files of the Individual Friars who were not parties to the litigation could be publically released.&#160; Although it was noted that the state&#8217;s constitutional right of privacy, Article 1, Section 1 (of the California Constitution), protects an individual&#8217;s reasonable expectation of privacy, that right is not absolute and must be considered against other important competing interests.&#160; Specifically, the court found that the public disclosure of confidential files which included psychiatric reports regarding the Individual Friars did not violate the friars&#8217; right of privacy under the state constitution since the compelling social interest in disclosure of information relating to sexual predators of children outweighed the friars&#8217; privacy interests.&#160; </p><p MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt">Virginia L. Ekelund, Esq. is an attorney with the DOYLE GOLDE GROSSMAN Family Law Group, Danville, California. Our vision brings together a team of highly experienced and distinguished family, trust and estate attorneys all of whom deliver specialized knowledge, strategic insight and tactical planning.&#160; Since 1984 we have dedicated ourselves to this mission.&#160; We are very proud of our five attorneys and our talented support team which includes California State Bar Certified Family Law Specialists, brilliant staff attorneys, and committed and experienced Certified Paralegals and technical staff.&#160;&#160; We practice our profession with integrity, strength and commitment to our clients. </p><p MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt">FamilyTrustsandEstates.com</p><p TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt">925-314-2333</p>'
