aS'<p>Spousal maintenance (alimony) is an amount of money that is sometimes paid by one spouse to the other during and after a divorce proceeding.&#160; </p><p>The court may award <a href="http://www.bcmlawoffice.com/aop/st-paul-alimony-attorneys/" target="&#95;blank">spousal maintenance</a> payments to one spouse if it believes that that spouse lacks sufficient property or the ability to support him or herself through employment, and is based on the standard of living that the couple enjoyed during the marriage. If one spouse is caring for a child, the court may decide that, in light of all the circumstances, it is appropriate for the parent not to be required to seek employment outside the home.&#160; &#160;</p><p>The amount of spousal support awarded will be based on what the court finds to be fair, without regard to allegations of marital misconduct on either side.&#160; Depending on the circumstances, the award may be temporary or permanent.</p><p><b><i>What are the factors that the judge takes into account in setting the amount of support?&#160; </i></b></p><p>While there are no specific formulas for spousal support specified in <a>the statute</a>, the following factors are taken into account:&#160; </p><ul type="disc"><li>The standard of living enjoyed by the couple during the marriage</li><li>The duration of the marriage, and if one party was a homemaker, the length of time that the party was not working outside the home</li><li>The type of education or training that would be required to allow the spouse to find suitable work</li><li>The chances that the spouse would eventually become self-supporting, taking into account the age and physical condition of the spouse</li><li>The other financial resources of the spouse seeking support, including any marital property or child support already awarded</li><li>The ability of the other spouse, who is being asked to provide support, to meet his or her own financial needs while also meeting the needs of the spouse asking for support</li></ul><p>A St. Paul family law firm can help you understand the law of spousal support in Minnesota and how it might be applied in your specific situation.&#160; &#160;</p><em><strong>Let A St. Paul, Minnesota family law firm help you through your divorce</strong></em><p>Bowden<strong> </strong>&amp;<strong> </strong>Cyr, PLLC offers sound legal counsel for clients going through divorce and other challenging life situations. If you have questions about whether spousal support might be available in your divorce, call <a href="http://www.bcmlawoffice.com/" target="&#95;blank">Bowden &amp; Cyr, PLLC</a> at 651-288-2844 today. The firm helps clients work out fair and workable support arrangements.</p><p>Bowden<strong> </strong>&amp;<strong> </strong>Cyr, PLLC</p><p>7825 3<sup>rd</sup> Street N., Suite 204</p><p>St. Paul, Minnesota 55128</p><p>651-288-2844</p><!--more-->Spousal support (alimony) is available in Minnesota if the court feels that one party does not have sufficient property or the ability to earn sufficient income, based on the standard of living that the couple enjoyed during the marriage. An award of support may be temporary or permanent, and is designed to allow a spouse to become self-supporting, if the court feels that this is possible given the spouse&#8217;s age, condition, education and the amount of time that the spouse has been out of th'
