aS'<p>You invested with your stockbroker because you trusted him to do the right thing for you, to act in your best interest.&#160; Instead, you lost hundreds of thousands of dollars that you depended on, money you worked for and saved all your life.&#160; You understood that there was risk in investing, but your losses weren&#8217;t caused by the market crash -- your broker mishandled your account.&#160; </p><p><b><i>You may be able to recover money</i></b> <b><i>if you can show that your broker&#8217;s conduct caused your losses</i></b>.&#160; You will greatly increase your chances of collecting a significant recovery by hiring an experienced <a href="http://dougstonelaw.com/practice-areas/Westchester-securities-arbitration-lawyer/">securities arbitration attorney</a> &#8211; someone who knows the securities arbitration process and understands how the securities industry works.&#160; A securities arbitration attorney knows how to investigate and evaluate a claim against a brokerage firm.&#160; An experienced securities attorney can obtain documents and information from you and the brokerage firm that is critical to your ability to collect money.&#160; An experienced attorney knows the common defenses to investor claims and knows how to present your case effectively so that you are most likely to recover your money.</p><p>What is securities arbitration?&#160;It is a dispute resolution process that is used for most disputes with brokerage firms.&#160;When you opened your brokerage account, the firm forced you to sign a customer agreement, which included a statement that FINRA (the Financial Industry Regulatory Authority) securities arbitration would resolve any disputes regarding your account.&#160;Arbitration is a faster and cheaper alternative to a court case.&#160;Your attorney starts the process by preparing and filing a Statement of Claim for you.&#160; </p><p><b>To prevail in arbitration and recover investment losses, an investor must convince a </b><b>FINRA arbitration panel that misconduct by the brokerage firm and/or the broker caused the losses</b>.&#160; Customers who recover money from firms like Merrill Lynch or Morgan Stanley usually convince the arbitrators that they clearly told their brokers what they wanted and trusted the brokers to act in their best interests, but they did not do so.</p><p>Many securities arbitration cases boil down to questions of suitability. Brokers are required to know their customers&#8217; investment objectives, experience, risk tolerance, income and net worth and must make sure that any recommendations they make are suitable and appropriate for each client&#8217;s situation.&#160;The broker must clearly disclose the risk of each investment.&#160; Common claims are that the broker made unsuitable investment recommendations or did not adequately disclose the risk of an investment.&#160;Other common claims involve unauthorized or excessive trading (churning) and failure to supervise.&#160; </p><p>If you believe you have a claim for damages against your brokerage firm, contact <a href="http://dougstonelaw.com/practice-areas/Westchester-securities-arbitration-lawyer/"><b>Westchester securities arbitration lawye</b><b>r</b></a>, <b><i>Douglas Stone</i></b> for a free case evaluation.&#160;Mr. Stone is a <a href="http://dougstonelaw.com/Westchester-attorney-douglas-stone/">securities arbitration attorney</a> with over 15 years of experience.&#160; Before he opened his law office in New Rochelle, he worked at Morgan Stanley and Smith Barney where he handled thousands of investor disputes.&#160;<a href="http://dougstonelaw.com/Westchester-attorney-douglas-stone/">Mr. Stone</a> may be reached by phone at <b>866 720-3754</b> or <b>914 636-2648</b> or by e-mail at <a href="mailto:dstone@dougstonelaw.com">dstone@dougstonelaw.com</a>.&#160; For more information on Mr. Stone and securities arbitration, go to <a href="http://www.dougstonelaw.com">www.dougstonelaw.com</a>.</p><!--more--><a href="http