aS"<p>The Suffolk County Legislature has taken steps over the past year&#160;to create&#160;a Suffolk County Traffic Violations Bureau that will&#160;replace the Traffic Violations Bureau operated by the NYS Department of Motor Vehicles and located in Hauppauge. The NYSDMV Traffic Violations Bureau&#160;presently prosecutes non-criminal traffic violations issued in the towns of Babylon, Brookhaven, Huntington, Islip and Smithtown. By establishing the County's own Traffic Violations Bureau, the Suffolk County Legislature hopes to maintain greater control over the processing and prosecution of traffic violations, to decrease police overtime costs in attending hearings and to increase revenue for the County.&#160;On August 17, 2012, Governor Cuomo signed legislation which allows Suffolk County to establish a County-run Traffics Violation Bureau.</p><p>The establishment of a Suffolk County Traffic Violations Bureau is potentially very advantageous to the County and its residents from a fiscal standpoint&#160;because Suffolk County will be able to retain a large part of the funds generated from the tickets issued in the above mentioned towns. It is uncertain at the moment what the ramifications will be for drivers&#160;as a result of the establishment of the&#160;Suffolk County Traffic Violations Bureau but it is hoped that&#160;the prosecutors of the County-run Bureau will be able to engage in plea bargaining&#160;that will offer the possibility of point reductions on moving violations. A plea negotiation is not offered at the present time on tickets in the NYSDMV Traffic Violations Bureau and drivers are customarily faced with&#160;having to go to a hearing&#160;if they wish to challenge a ticket. If the police officer appears for the hearing, the officer's testimony is usually very persuasive to the hearing officer.&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;</p><p>Unfortunately, the implementation of the County-run Traffic Violations Bureau, which is scheduled to open April 1, 2013,&#160;is hitting some speed bumps.&#160;As recently reported by Newsday, the Suffolk County Legislature last week did not go forward with an emergency resolution to approve start-up funds for the County-run Traffic Violations Bureau because of concerns on the part of some legislators related to the hiring plans for the Bureau and the location and design plans for the Bureau's office and operating space. It is anticipated that more specific plans for hiring, location and design&#160;will be submitted to the Legislature before the end of October. Let's hope that the plans for&#160;the Suffolk County Traffic Violations Bureau can get on track and make fast progress toward the opening date of April 1, 2013. Suffolk County, its residents and drivers have much to gain from a locally operated Traffic Violations Bureau.&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;</p>"
