aS'I\'ve known for a long time about the lengths insurance companies will go to avoid paying a claim. I&#8217;ve seen a lot in my years as a <a href="http://www.dlslawfirm.com/attorney-profiles/dianne-sawaya" title="Experienced Denver personal injury attorney">personal injury lawyer</a>, but the other day a client told me about an incident that still surprised me.<br /><br />This client had been in involved in a bad <a href="http://www.dlslawfirm.com/auto-accident-injury/car-accident-lawyer-denver" title="Denver car accident attorney">car accident</a>, and it turns out the other driver was uninsured. My client was hurt pretty badly, the stack of medical bills was piling up and she was facing a lengthy recovery and rehabilitation.<br /><br />At least one thing was in her favor: Her insurance policy had good uninsured/underinsured motorist coverage. At least she thought it was good, until she tried to use it.<br /><br />First came the call from the insurance company, which tried to convince her that her injuries weren&#8217;t really all that serious. To avoid all that hassle and paperwork why don&#8217;t we just settle things now, and here&#8217;s a check, they said.<br /><br />My client didn\'t fall for it. A little while later, my client got another call. This time is was her insurance agent on the line. He was just calling to check up on how she&#8217;s doing, and was everything being taken care of by the insurance company, and by the way, maybe you should think about taking a check to make all this go away.<br /><br />Okay, that one takes the cake. It&#8217;s probably not unusual for an insurance company to try to get out of paying a lot of big bills. After all, paying claims really cuts into the profit margin. But I don\'t think many people would expect insurers to put their own agents up to doing the insurance company&#8217;s bidding, cutting away at the trust between the agent and their client.<br /><br />Here are three important things to note from this experience:<br /><br />First, always have uninsured/underinsured motorist coverage on your policy. Yes, it costs a little more. But remember that a third of the drivers on Colorado\'s roads are uninsured. Can you afford to be without it?<br /><br />Second, insurance companies are not your friend &#8211; even when it&#8217;s your own insurer. Think otherwise at your own peril.<br /><br />And finally, if you&#8217;ve been injured in a car accident, you do need a personal injury lawyer. I can guarantee you that no insurance company would try a stunt like that with me &#8211; they know exactly how far they&#8217;d get.<br /><br />To learn more about insurance company tricks, give me a call at (303) 758-4777, email me at <a href="dls@dlslawfirm.com" title="Dianne Sawaya"></a>DLS@dlslawfirm.com or visit us on the Web at <a href="http://www.dlslawfirm.com" title="Colorado personal injury lawyer">www.dlslawfirm.com</a>.<!--more-->I\'ve known for a long time about the lengths insurance companies will go to avoid paying a claim. I&#8217;ve seen a lot in my years as a personal injury lawyer, but the other day a client told me about an incident that still surprised me.'
