aS'<p class="MsoNormal"><a href="http://www.bizjournals.com/kansascity/news/2013/03/06/kansas-city-chiefs-win-age-lawsuit.html">A\r\nKansas City jury returned a verdict in favor of the Chiefs football team</a>\r\nafter a trial on a former maintenance manager&#8217;s age discrimination claim.&#160;\r\nThe manager claimed that his firing was part of a pattern of pushing out older\r\nemployees.&#160; The team argued that he was fired for giving an employee a\r\nraise without authorization.<br /><br />The case is a textbook example of the battle between an\r\nemployee&#8217;s discrimination claim and the company&#8217;s legitimate reason for\r\ntreating the employee that way (here, termination).&#160; The employee has to\r\nconvince the jury that it&#8217;s more likely than not that the employer&#8217;s purpose\r\nwas discriminatory, even in part.&#160; Discrimination cases can turn into a\r\nreferendum on the employee&#8217;s personnel history.<a href="http://www.bizjournals.com/kansascity/print-edition/2013/03/01/reporter-page-kansas-city-chiefs.html"><br /><br />Several\r\nother employees had filed age discrimination claims against the Chiefs</a>.&#160;\r\nBut courts sometimes decide that a plaintiff can&#8217;t tell a jury about the way\r\nother employees were treated.&#160; The courts generally want a showing that\r\nthe other employees got the same treatment at the hands of the same manager or\r\nbased on the same manager&#8217;s decisions.&#160; The key is whether everyone was a\r\nvictim of the same discriminatory attitude or policy.<br /><br />There are no hard-and-fast rules in discrimination cases\r\nbecause plaintiffs often have to prove their case with circumstantial\r\nevidence.&#160; Even offhand comments like, &#8220;When are you retiring?&#8221; don&#8217;t\r\nnecessarily establish an age discrimination claim.&#160; We can help analyze\r\nyour employment situation and assess the strengths and weaknesses of your claims.&#160;\r\nIf you think you&#8217;ve been the victim of age discrimination, <a href="http://www.cookcraig.com/Contact&#95;Us&#95;Page.html">please call us to\r\nset up a consultation</a>.</p><p class="MsoNormal" /><p class="MsoNormal">\r\n\r\n</p><p>John C. Cook<br />(571) 732-3697<br />Cook Craig &amp; Francuzenko, PLLC<br />3050 Chain Bridge Road, Suite 200<br />Fairfax, VA 22030\r\n\r\n</p><p><br />\r\n</p><p>\r\n</p><!--more-->A jury found that the Kansas City Chiefs didn\'t discriminate based on age when they fired an older maintenance supervisor for giving an employee an unauthorized raise.&#160; Discrimination cases are difficult to prove when the company offers a legitimate nondiscriminatory purpose.&#160; Other employees\' treatment isn\'t always admissible in court.&#160; Employees often have to prove discrimination using circumstantial evidence and inference.'
