aS'When disasters strike, seconds and minutes may count in treating \r\ninjury victims.&#160; However, in some cases it may take a very long time for\r\n victims to receive the care they need.&#160; Now, a new <a  rel="nofollow" href="http://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2013/12/131216080322.htm">electronic system</a>\r\n designed to support rescue and first-responder personnel in the \r\nimmediate treatment of victims promises to help injury patients get \r\ntimely treatment.\r\nNatural Disasters Are Not The Only Time Care May Be Delayed\r\n<p>The initial thrust of the development design for this new system was \r\ntargeted for natural disasters when thousands of people may be injured \r\nat once.&#160; However, this same technology could also be useful in a major <a  rel="nofollow" href="http://www.scarlettlawgroup.com/practice-areas/automobile-accidents" title="accident">accident</a> scenarios, such as the multi-car pileups that sometimes occur on interstate highways.</p>\r\n<p>Besides natural disasters such as hurricanes or tornadoes, there are \r\nalso times when many people may be affected at once by an accident such \r\nas during a terrorist attack, a chemical plant accident or a train \r\ncrash.&#160; In circumstances such as this, the better the communication \r\nbetween relief workers the more rapidly victims will receive treatment.</p>\r\n<p>It is common practice to &#8220;triage&#8221; the victims of a major accident \r\naccording to the severity of their injuries.&#160; Those who are in danger of\r\n dying obviously receive first preference, while those who suffered only\r\n minor injuries are put off till last.&#160; Currently, rescue workers use a \r\ncolor-based system to tag victims according to the priority of their \r\ninjuries.&#160; Crucial data such as pulse and respiratory rate are written \r\non the tags by hand.</p>\r\n<p>Now, the European Union is sponsoring the <a  rel="nofollow" href="http://www.bridgeproject.eu">BRIDGE</a>\r\n project.&#160; This project is funded so that researchers at the Fraunhofer \r\nInstitute for Applied Information Technology or FIT can develop an \r\ne-triage center that immediately transmits pulse, respiration and blood \r\noxygen levels to emergency response control centers.&#160; A color-coded \r\nplastic armband is placed on the victims with a GPS sensor and an RFID \r\nchip so that rescue workers can not only locate the victim but will have\r\n instant access to his or her information.</p>\r\nWhat If I Am The Victim of An Accident?\r\n<p><a  rel="nofollow" href="http://www.scarlettlawgroup.com/" title="Scarlett Law Group">Scarlett Law Group</a> in <a  rel="nofollow" href="http://www.scarlettlawgroup.com/contact" title="San Francisco, California">San Francisco, California</a>, works with the victims of <a  rel="nofollow" href="http://www.scarlettlawgroup.com/practice-areas/catastrophic-personal-injury/catestrophic-injuries" title="catastrophic">catastrophic</a>\r\n accidents and the families of those who have lost loved ones to recover\r\n compensation for their injuries and losses.&#160; Contact Scarlett Law Group\r\n today for a free consultation on how you may be entitled to financial \r\ncompensation for medical bills and other costs related to your accident.</p>'
