aS'\r\n<p>Auto companies are coming under increasing fire from federal safety officials who believe these companies are doing little to minimize the risks of distracted driving. Ford Motor Company is now touting the results of a study it conducted in collaboration with the Virginia Tech Transportation Institute, which shows that the use of its Sync voice activated system minimizes the risk of distractions, and consequently, the risk of accidents.</p><p>The study compared 21 drivers aged between 19 and 51. The drivers drove a Ford Mercury Marina while initiating a phone call, changing music tracks and having a conversation using Sync.&#160; The same motorists were then made to perform the same activities - dialing a number, changing music tracks and talking on the phone manually using a cell phone. The study showed that motorists who used Ford\'s Sync system were able to complete the tasks much quicker. Most importantly, these motorists were able to perform these tasks without having to take their eyes off the road for too long. In contrast, the motorists who were performing these tasks with their hands, took their eyes off the road and hands off the steering wheel for longer periods of time.</p><p>When the motorists used a cell phone to dial a phone number, they took about four times longer than with Sync. When it came to changing music tracks, the motorists took up to 10 times longer to change tracks than when they used Sync.</p><p>Ford is obviously very pleased that its Sync voice activation system has been found to work much better at preventing driving distractions than the use of hand held cell phones. However, the company is going to have to do much more to please federal safety officials. Transportation Secretary Ray LaHood in particular has been very disapproving of voice activation systems like Ford\'s Sync. Secretary LaHood and <a href="http://aogllp.com/personal-injury-attorney-los-angeles" title="Los Angeles Personal Injury Lawyers">California personal injury lawyers</a> firmly believe that any kind of distraction while driving is far too much. In any case, studies by the National Safety Council have showed that the risks from using a cell phone while driving come from the actual conversation, and not the use of the hands.</p><!--more-->Ford Motor Company is  touting the results of a study it conducted in collaboration with the Virginia Tech Transportation Institute, which shows that the use of its Sync voice activated system minimizes the risk of distractions, and consequently, the risk of accidents.&#160; <a title="Los Angeles Personal Injury Lawyers" href="http://aogllp.com/personal-injury-attorney-los-angeles">Los Angeles personal injury lawyers</a> firmly believe that any kind of distraction while driving is far too much.'
