aS'\r\n<a href="http://www.brain-spineinjury.com/" title="Los Angeles Brain Injury Lawyer">California brain injury lawyers</a> and families of TBI victims should be interested in a new light therapy that has shown promising benefits in the treatment&#160; of brain injury patients.&#160; A study indicates that the use of LED lights could help aid the treatment of persons suffering from traumatic brain injury. &#160;<br /><br />The research was carried out by researchers from Boston University School of Medicine, Massachusetts General Hospital and Harvard-MIT Division of Health Sciences and Technology.&#160; The researchers found that the use of LED lights could have specific benefits for brain injury patients.&#160; The results of the study have been published in the Photo Medicine and Laser Surgery Channel.&#160; According to the researchers, the use of LED lights specifically on the scalp and forehead of traumatic brain injury patients could help improve cognitive function, and also help reduce the severity of post traumatic stress disorder in patients who suffer from traumatic brain injury.&#160; &#160;<br /><br />Post traumatic stress disorder is often a consequence of traumatic brain injury.&#160; Symptoms include anxiety, flashbacks, nightmares, social withdrawal, and memory loss.&#160; These symptoms often begin after a person has suffered a near-death experience.&#160; PTSD symptoms can often be seen in persons who have survived a serious auto accident, a natural disaster, a murder attempt or rape.&#160; Post traumatic stress disorder is also often seen in servicemen and women who return home from the battlefield.<br /><br />The most promising thing about this new LED light therapy is that the therapy can be self-administered by the patient.&#160;&#160; The announcement of the benefits of this light therapy has been made in an opportune month.&#160; March happens to be National Brain Injury Awareness Month, and March 16 was marked as Brain Injury Awareness Day on Capitol Hill.&#160; This month, the Brain Injury Association of America is drawing attention to the unseen and often neglected symptoms of a brain injury - including numbness, extreme drowsiness, headache, dizziness, loss of vision, loss of consciousness, slurring, vomiting and nausea.&#160; While treatment options for traumatic brain injury are currently limited, speed in beginning TBI treatment holds the key to limiting the long term effects of the injury.<!--more-->California brain injury lawyers\r\n and families of TBI victims should be interested in a new light therapy\r\n that has shown promising benefits in the treatment&#160; of brain injury \r\npatients.&#160; A study indicates that the use of LED lights could help aid \r\nthe treatment of persons suffering from traumatic brain injury. &#160;'
