aS"The <i>LA Times</i> recently reported, &#8220;With a high DUI rate and residents complaining of drunks on the streets, the city of Huntington Beach has imposed restrictions and employed new police tactics.&#8221;&#160; Unfortunately however, the story also revealed that tax money generated by partiers is still much needed, city leaders say. &#160;<br /><br />The investigation begins about 1:30 a.m. on a recent Friday in Huntington Beach's Main Street, typically busy by this time of night with bar crowd foot traffic.&#160; The scene described by the <i>Times</i> reporter was the following, &#8220;the air is crisp and salty, and despite the cold, women in colorful tube dresses are laughing and men in collared shirts are whistling in appreciation.&#8221;&#160; Sound familiar to residents of Orange County?&#160;&#160; &#160;<br /><br />Next, the report indicates that Police Sgt. James Schoales standing on a busy corner poses a familiar question to a 24-year-old man who is stumbling up the brick sidewalk.&#160; Schoales asks the man, &quot;How much have you had to drink tonight?&quot;&#160; The response is surprisingly not uncommon to a veteran officer and described by the reporter with whimsical accuracy,<br /><br /><i>The man, whose long light brown hair is disheveled, responds with uncanny precision,&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; counting on his fingers, and he slurs, but only slightly: &#8216;A Mind Eraser, Two shots of Jack Daniels, A Guinness and a Pabst Blue Ribbon, Two Irish Car Bombs, then three Bud Lights!&#8217;</i> &#160;<br /><br />Smiling, Schoales directs him to a line of cabs, the <i>Times</i> reporter explains.&#160; So how indicative is this encounter of a Friday night in Huntington?&#160; This particular night, the officers on duty &#8220;will break up two brawls, encounter a man passed out in the front seat of a cab and arrest a 21-year-old who voluntarily jumped off a 20-foot building. They will also usher numerous drunks home and aid others in finding a ride.&#8221;<p>In addition, local bartenders tell tales of throwing naked men out of clubs and breaking up bloody fights to the Times.&#160; Another unbelievable part of the story is this: &#8220;drunks wander so often into the wrong house looking for a place to sleep that police gave it a term &#8212; a &quot;Downtown 459&quot; &#8212; named after the state's penal code number for a burglary, since a resident's initial panicked call is because they think someone is trying to rob them.&#8221;</p><p>This sounds more like New Orleans than a city in California but sadly (in this case) the stats don&#8217;t lie.&#160; Huntington Beach is currently ranked number one in victims killed and injured in alcohol-involved traffic accidents among cities its size in California, according to the story, and DUI arrests are more than twice the number in Irvine, a college town roughly the same size.</p><p>Moreover, with 1,419 DUI arrests last year and a clear problem on their hands, city officials decided they needed to tackle the problem, hence the Times piece was subsequently written.&#160; In fact, the story revealed the &#8220;City Council placed restrictions on new bars &#8212; no beer pong or drink minimums, for example &#8212; and police began tracking where people had their last drink before their arrests.&#8221; </p>So is the new crack down working? Residents say, &#8220;urination, defecation, sex acts and theft are products of the&#160;alcohol problem and of a concentration of alcohol licenses in the area,&#8221; according to the story.&#160; Perhaps now is time for locals to have a voice on this issue and legislature to step in?&#160; It seems that the end goal is safety but the people in Huntington are far from reaching it.&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; &#160;"
