aS'<p>Bills similar to this have passed the Florida Senate many times only to fail in the House of Representatives. To date, there are thirty nine states plus the District of Columbia that have adopted bans on texting while driving. SB 52 outlaws texting while driving and was voted 9-0 in favor of this ban by the Florida Senate Communications Committee; however, it exempts emergency vehicles including the police. This ban makes texting a secondary crime, which means the police can cite a driver for texting, but only if they are stopped for other violations like speeding.\r\n\r\nUnder the provisions set forth by SB 52, the violation of the law will result in a fine of $30. In addition, if the violation results in or causes an accident, the driver&#8217;s license of the driver would be deducted 6 points.For this, you may need a <a  rel="nofollow" href="http://jamesdavisdefense.com/">criminal defense lawyer in Jacksonville</a>.</p><p>A Florida Department of Highway Safety and Motor Vehicles spokeswoman Courtney Heidelberg said the safety records for Florida highways show 171,538 vehicle crash reports filed in 2011&#8217;s first ten months involved 149 drivers that when the accident happened, were texting. The AAA&#8217;s foundation for Traffic Safety held a study that showed the concern for distracted driving is a growing concern, but still a common practice.\r\n\r\n</p><p>This study is known as the Traffic Safety Index and was put together based upon information received from 3,896 US residents age 16 and over. The conclusion of the index was that even though a lot of Americans do value their safety when driving and do support the laws that support unsafe driving such as speeding, they still tend to practice unsafe driving habits. The findings of the index were 88.5 percent of the drivers thought that using a cell phone during driving was a serious threat to the safety of motorist. In addition there were 67.3 percent who felt that being distracted while driving is a much bigger problem than it was just three years\r\nago.\r\n\r\n</p><p>Even with many of the people who were surveyed being concerned about people who were distracted while driving, they were for having a double standard in regards to measures that would discourage this behavior. As many as 68.8 percent confessed to having used a cell phone while driving at least one time within a 30 day period. As many as 31.9 percent confessed to using a cell phone &#8220;fairly often.&#8221; Only 57.9 percent of people surveyed considered using a cell phone when driving a serious safety threat and only 66 percent thought the practice as &#8220;unacceptable.&#8221; Unfortunately, it seems that distracted driving is a problem in the US that is growing.\r\n\r\nBecause of the increase of electronic devices, responsible drivers must always be alert to unsafe and distracted drivers. </p><p>If you or anyone you know has been in a traffic accident where you sustained injuries, it is in your best interest and to protect your right to compensation that you get legal representation right away. If you or a loved one has been in a traffic accident has sustained injuries, get in touch with the<a  rel="nofollow" href="http://jamesdavisdefense.com/"> Jacksonville Criminal Law Attorney </a>at James Davis Defense right away.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><!--more-->Senate Bill 52 was\r\nunanimously approved on March 7th by the Florida State Senate. This Bill 52\r\nwill impose a statewide ban on texting while driving.'
