aS'A collision between two trucks recently on Interstate 57 in Union County is yet another example of the common causes and frequency of major trucking accidents in Alabama. <p>James Woodly, 45, of Greenville, Miss., had legally parked his truck along the right side of the southbound lanes on I-57 to check his vehicle. At about 2 a.m. Warren Gross, 31, of Bloomfield, Mo., for unknown reasons, drove his semi across the fog line and collided with the left side of Woodley\'s parked truck. Gross\'s vehicle continued on until it veered into a ditch on the right shoulder.</p><p>The vehicles sustained major damage and had to be towed from the scene, but luckily there were no injuries reported. It is important to contact a reliable <a href="http://www.frankmwilsonpc.com/trucking-accidents/" target="&#95;blank">Alabama trucking accident attorney</a> if you are ever injured in a truck accident.&#160; If James Woodley had been in the driver\'s seat of his truck rather than outside checking it, he might not have walked away from the accident. </p><p>The accident is still under investigation, but there are several factors common to truck accidents that may indicate what caused the crash. The first and most apparent factor was the time of day. It was the dead of night, several hours before sunrise. Vehicle headlights cannot provide the clarity of daylight, and the repetitious, dark surroundings can make a driver feel very tired. These factors greatly impare one\'s driving ability, and are likely what Warren Gross was experiencing right before the accident. Because of his exhaustion, Gross probably did not notice that he was drifting onto the shoulder nor see Woodley\'s parked tractor-trailer.&#160;This is the conclusion we would draw from the&#160;few details provided by the <em><a href="http://www.carmitimes.com/area&#95;news/x1902476824/Semi-hits-parked-tractor-trailer-on-I-57-early-Tuesday" target="&#95;blank">CarmiTimes</a></em>.</p><p>Truck drivers are supposed to be skilled professionals in their trade, however that is not always the case. There are a few reasons that a truck driver might not be preforming as well as he should: </p><ul><li>Inadequate driver training </li><li>Lack of diligence in addressing safety concerns </li><li>Driver compensation that encourages faster driving </li><li>Drivers expected to handle more hours of consecutive vehicle operation than is safe </li><li>Delivery schedules that encourage drivers to overlook safety factors</li></ul><p>A truck accident can leave a victim with life-threatening injuries. In order to receive the compensation necessary to fully recover from a truck accident, you need serious representation. From his years as an <a href="http://www.frankmwilsonpc.com/truck-accidents/" target="&#95;blank">Alabama truck accident lawyer</a>, Frank M. Wilson has the proper experience and success in this complex area of law.</p><!--more-->A truck accident can leave a victim with life-threatening injuries. In order to receive the compensation necessary to fully recover from a truck accident, you need serious representation. From his years as an <a href="http://www.frankmwilsonpc.com/truck-accidents/" target="&#95;blank">Alabama truck accident lawyer</a>, Frank M. Wilson has the proper experience and success in this complex area of law.'
