aS'<b>What boaters should know if an accident happens&#8230;</b><br /><br />Summer is in full swing. With the Fourth of July just around the corner, fun on the water is calling. Unfortunately, many boaters are not prepared or even unaware of the laws governing the waterways.&#160; In the event of an accident or incident, do boaters understand what their responsibilities?<br /><br />Our waterways are patrolled by up to five agencies. Under federal law, boaters are required to report watercraft and <a href="http://clorelaw.com/practice-areas/watercraftboat-accident/" title="Charleston boat accident lawyer">boating accidents</a> to the authorities, even minor ones. In South Carolina, reports should be made to the Department of Natural Resources (DNR).<br /><br /><b>When and whether to file a report:</b><br />The operator of each watercraft involved in an accident is responsible for filing, according to the U.S. Coast Guard. The responsibility falls upon to the boat owner should the operator be physically unable to report an incident.<br /><br />When the following occurs, the operator or owner is required to report a boating accident within 48 hours:<br /><br /><ul><li>A personal injury requires medical treatment beyond first aid.</li><li>A person is missing from the vessel and death or injury is suspected.</li><li>A person dies within 24 hours of the occurrence. </li></ul><br />When an accident involving any watercraft or its equipment involving any of these situations, boaters are required to report within 10 days:<br /><br /><ul><li>Property Damage of $2,000 or more </li><li>There is a complete loss of any vessel</li><li>A person dies more than 24 hours after the occurrence</li></ul><br />Minor accidents not addressed above do not require reporting; however, if a person suffering injury which requires a trip to the ER you must report the incident.<br /><br />These laws are important for boaters to understand and abide by them.&#160; Charleston area doctors and medical professionals understand the reporting rules and will report incidents to the proper authorities. In such an instance, boaters can be cited for not reporting the incident. Authority will often want to administer toxicology tests too, since alcohol is frequently a contributing factor in boating accidents.<br /><br />Failure to report an accident to authorities may be considered by insurance companies when filing a claim.<br /><br />As the temperature increases, so too does the number of boaters on the water around Charleston. It&#8217;s imperative for watercraft operators and owners to understand the laws and safety regulations. As a <a href="www.clorelaw.com" title="Charleston personal injury attorney">personal injury attorney</a> who handles cases resulting from boating accidents, I can attest to what happens when the rules are not followed. Refinance of the laws on the water&#160; result in far more damage than that of the boating accident.<br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><!--more-->Each summer, the Charleston boating injury attorneys at Clore Law Group prepare for the increase in watercraft related injuries and death. With nearly 800,000 vessels register in the Carolina\'s, boat accidents are going to occur. Understanding the laws governing the waterways will help everyone on the water.'
