aS'<p MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt" class="MsoNormal">Over the years auto accident litigation has changed significantly in the state of Colorado. Because the law frequently does change, it is important that you seek out a firm with <a href="http://www.bellpollockinjury.com/">Denver injury attorneys</a> that stay on top of the new developments. Seek out personal injury attorneys who can explain the law to you in plain English. <p /></p><p MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt" class="MsoNormal">Described below are some of the changes to auto accident litigation in Colorado. <p /></p>Colorado is a fault state<p MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt" class="MsoNormal">One major area of change in <a href="http://www.bellpollockinjury.com/">personal injury law</a> is that Colorado now is a fault-based state for car accident injuries. What this means is that fault is looked at and used in making a determination of responsibility for payment of damages to a victim. Thus, if a driver injures another party, the at-fault party is responsible for medical bills and non-economic damages. Non-economic damages include pain and suffering, permanent disfigurement and permanent impairment. In a no-fault system the insurance company of the injured driver is on the hook for injuries to the insured, regardless of the fault of the injured party.<p /></p>Statute of limitations for auto accidents<p MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt" class="MsoNormal">You only have a limited amount of time to bring a personal injury action. Under Colorado law there is a general limitations period for personal injury of two years, while the <a mso-comment-reference: bq&#95;1; mso-comment-date: 20111108T1307" href="http://research.lawyers.com/Colorado/Colorado-Statutes-of-Limitations.html">statute of limitations period for injuries resulting from a motor vehicle accident is three years. </a>This means that you must bring your lawsuit within three years if you are injured in a car accident, and within two years for other personal injury lawsuits, or you may be barred from suing the other party. <p /></p>Cap on non-economic damages<p MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt" class="MsoNormal">While there is no cap on the amount you can collect for economic damages that arise in a car accident, there is a cap on non-economic damages. Economic damages include items such as past and future lost earnings, and your medical expenses. Non-economic damages include damages for pain and suffering. The cap for non-economic damages can range up to $936,030 depending on the particular set of circumstances surrounding your accident. <p /></p>Contact us<p MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt" class="MsoNormal"><p>&#160;</p></p><p MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt" class="MsoNormal">A personal injury lawyer at Bell &amp; Pollock, PC can meet with you to discuss how Colorado law applies to your particular accident. Contact <a href="http://www.bellpollockinjury.com/contact/">us at our offices</a> in Steamboat Springs or Greenwood Village, Colorado, to schedule your free initial consultation.</p><!--more-->Over the years auto accident litigation has changed significantly in the state of Colorado. Because the law frequently does change, it is important that you seek out a firm with Denver injury attorneys that stay on top of the new developments.'
