aS'<p>Did you know that Congress increased and extended the first-time homebuyer credit from the 2008 Act to cover purchases between January 1, 2009, and April 30, 2010?&#160; If you signed a binding sales contract by April 30, 2010, the tax credit applies to purchases completed by June 30, 2010.</p><p>Real estate law in&#160;Texas currently offers a fully refundable tax credit of 10 percent of the purchase price&#8212;up to $8,000 to first-time homebuyers.&#160; The original homebuyer credit lasted from April 8, 2008 through January 1, 2009, offering a maximum refund of $7,500.</p><p>The real estate laws place some limits on the homebuyer credit:</p><ul><li>The full tax credit applies to married couples filing jointly with incomes no greater $150,000&#8212;$225,000 after November 6, 2009; to individuals with incomes no greater than $75,000&#8212;$125,000 after November 6, 2009.</li><li>The credit does not apply to homes costing $800,000 or more.</li></ul><p>Real estate laws make the new homebuyer credit retroactive. In other words, if you purchased a home after April 2008 and did not apply for the tax credit, you can still do so.</p><p>A <a href="http://www.bowesandassociates.com/" target="&#95;blank">Plano real estate lawyer</a> can help you get the largest possible tax credit; if purchasing a home in&#160;in Texas, consult&#160;a real estate attorney to protect your interests every step of the way.</p><p>Information provided by the <a href="http://www.bowesandassociates.com/title-claim-validation-FAQs/" target="&#95;blank">Plano residential&#160;real estate law firm</a> of:<br />13111 N. Central Expy<br />Suite 200<br />Dallas, TX 75243<br />(214) 570-0505</p><!--more-->Did you know that Congress increased and extended the first-time homebuyer credit from the 2008 Act to cover purchases between January 1, 2009, and April 30, 2010? <a href="http://www.bowesandassociates.com/" target="&#95;blank">Plano real estate lawyer</a> Jason Bowes explains the Texas Housing and Economic Recovery Act.'
