aS'<p>While there are some differences with automobile, trucking accidents - these types of cases often times have a degree of common elements. But when you&#8217;re dealing with interstate trucking firms for example, there is a set of laws that Congress has enacted to - through the Department of Transportation to try to impose some protection for the public.</p><p>&#160;For example, there are laws that require strict compliance with drivers keeping accurate logs of their driving time, driving distances. There are limits on the amount of hours that they are allowed to drive in any particular period.&#160; Also there is enforcement by all the states to try to force compliance with that although we find that there is a lot of cheating that interstate trucking relies on speed and efficiency and sometimes drivers are overworked, underpaid, and the consequences are that they&#8217;re unsafe when they fall asleep or are spending way too many hours and losing concentration when they&#8217;re driving.</p><p>&#160;For instance there are specific areas of law that apply to trucking accidents that we don&#8217;t see in regular automobile collision cases. So there are certain laws, both federal and state laws that apply to certain types of cases and each of those have their unique characteristics. But in general we devote our time and resources passionately to all of those types of cases whether they&#8217;re motorcycle accidents, automobile collisions, or trucking collisions.</p><p /><!--more--><p>The <a href="http://www.bdjlaw.com/">Reno Nevada Injury Attorneys</a> at Bradley, Drendel &amp; Jeanney Law Firm discuss the differences among car, truck and motorcycle accidents.</p><p>The <a href="http://bdjlaw.com/practice-areas/reno-personal-injury/">Reno Nevada Injury Lawyer</a>, Tom Drendel&#160;specifically explains in detail the difference between car, truck and motorcycle accidents and how they are handled in the eyes of the law.</p>'
