aS'<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; "><b>Migraine headaches are torture</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">By Laura Casey<br />\r\nContra Costa Times </p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">The pain is most often described as\r\nMedieval torture. When a migraine headache sufferer has an attack, it feels\r\nlike his or her head is being crushed in a vice. Some feel like they\'re being\r\nhit in the forehead with a sledgehammer, others like their heads are being\r\npounded by nails.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">&quot;It is not something you wish\r\non your worst enemy,&quot; says Eileen Jones, a registered nurse who has\r\nsuffered from migraines for nearly 25 years. Jones, who faces chronic daily\r\nmigraines, says that since she started getting the headaches at age 36, her\r\nwhole world has shrunk.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">&quot;I tried to do whatever I like\r\nto do with my life,&quot; says Jones, a Piedmont resident. &quot;But the pain\r\nis the parent saying, \'No, you can\'t.\' &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">A migraine is not the kind of\r\nheadache most of us associate with a hangover or a stressful day. A universal\r\ncondition -- there are migraine sufferers in every culture and every country --\r\nthe notorious headaches affect nearly one in five women and one in 20 men, the\r\nNational Headache Foundation says. Some migraine suffers, such as Jones, can\r\nget debilitating headaches every day, while others much less frequently and\r\nless severely. </p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">The impact of migraines surfaced\r\nlast month when it was revealed that presidential candidate Rep. Michele\r\nBachmann (R-Minn.) is among the nearly 30 million Americans who suffer from\r\nthem. While some question whether a migraine sufferer can stand up to the job\r\nas president, each person\'s ability to deal with migraines depends on many\r\nfactors, including how well they respond to drugs and other treatment. </p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">One thing is certain, however --\r\nwhile new treatments continue to be tried, some with good results, there is no\r\nmagic bullet.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">Range of triggers</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">Migraines often come with a number\r\nof symptoms beyond throbbing head pain, says Dr. Kenneth Peters of the Northern\r\nCalifornia Headache Clinic in Mountain View. They are also associated with\r\nnausea, vomiting and sensitivity to light and sound. Their beginnings can be\r\ndramatic: About 15 percent of people who suffer from them experience an &quot;aura&quot;\r\n-- flashing lights or having a decreased area of vision -- shortly before they\r\nbegin.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">They can be triggered by stress,\r\nsounds, smells and foods, but often, they\'re triggered by nothing. Movement or\r\nexercise often exacerbates the pain, and many say the only way to cope is to\r\nlie down in a dark room. The pain usually lasts anywhere from four to 72 hours\r\nand is exhausting.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">A 2008 migraine survey by\r\nHarrisInteractive and Pfizer revealed that of the 3,000 American migraine\r\nsufferers polled, 66 percent say they tough out the pain and continue their\r\nworkdays, but they also averaged losing about four days of work a year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">&quot;Most migraines are very\r\ndisabling,&quot; Peters says. &quot;We see patients on work disability; they\r\ncan\'t function.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">He added that for some, daily headaches\r\nmake it impossible to work. Others can\'t plan their family life because it\'s\r\nvery difficult to do anything with the family when they are having a migraine.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">Jones, for example, was heartbroken\r\nto miss the rehearsal dinner for her son\'s wedding. </p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">&quot;I can\'t keep promises to\r\npeople,&quot; Jones says. &quot;That\'s the hardest part.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">Migraine sufferers typically get\r\ntheir first headaches in their late teens, or early 20s and 30s, Peters says.\r\nWoman are affected more often than men likely because of the &quot;estrogen\r\neffect,&quot; Peters says. It\'s not uncommon for a woman to experience\r\nmigraines during monthly menstrual periods. </p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">Dr. Alfred Scopp, a psychologist and\r\nco-founder of the Northern California Headache Clinic, says the level of\r\ndisability during a migraine attack can be equivalent to Stage 4 cancer or\r\nAIDS. </p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">&quot;With any recurring pain\r\ncondition or disabling condition, no one can imagine what it is like except the\r\nperson with that condition,&quot; Scopp says. &quot;I can\'t imagine what it is\r\nlike to be a diabetic. We can\'t really imagine the unpredictably or the fear\r\nthat you might have a bad headache. It\'s just the way it is.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">Taking away life</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">Jones abandoned her nursing career\r\nand learned to live with a certain amount of pain every day. She says she\'s\r\ntried everything to ease her agony, including checking into a one-month\r\ninpatient hospital program and having a occipital nerve stimulator implanted in\r\nher head -- its battery pack is visible on her chest.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">She stays busy volunteering for the\r\nRed Cross and by organizing a Miles for Migraine annual walk and run in\r\nOctober, which raised $10,000 for migraine research last year. She also travels\r\nwith a group of medical professionals to Washington, D.C., every year to ask\r\npoliticians to support headache research. </p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">Medicine has proved effective for\r\nAnna Soskin, 17, who is under the care of doctors at the UC San Francisco\r\nHeadache Center. Although she still has to deal with about three headaches a\r\nday that last about an hour each, that\'s better than a relentless all-day\r\nheadache. </p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">Still, she struggles. The Alameda\r\nresident has missed so much school she has to attend an extra year. She wants\r\nto go to college and land a great job but worries her headaches will keep her\r\non her parents\' couch through adulthood.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">&quot;There are times when it gets\r\npretty scary,&quot; she says. &quot;The doctors don\'t seem to be freaking out\r\nabout it, and they are trying to help me. So I am trying not to freak out about\r\nit.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">Livermore resident Marianne Portman\r\nbegan treating her migraine with holistic methods that included making changes\r\nin her diet and drinking a lot of water. Doctors such as Scopp also work with\r\npatients on nonmedicinal treatments such as learning how to maintain healthy\r\nlevels of stress and participating in cognitive behavioral therapy and\r\nbiofeedback.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">Although Portman still gets\r\nmigraines once every 10 days or so and they can last more than a day, she\r\nmaintains a sales job at a Pleasanton furniture store. </p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">&quot;I think there are many times\r\nthat it affects life tremendously,&quot; she says. &quot;I pray that the day I\r\nget my migraine is the day I have off work.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">She has considered going on\r\npermanent disability because of the frequency of the pain and the anguish she\r\nfeels. </p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">Hope for workers</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">While Bachmann has kept her\r\ntreatment private, neurologist Jerome Goldstein, director of the San Francisco\r\nHeadache Clinic, says there\'s no reason to believe her condition would affect\r\nher ability to do her job. Many people who suffer from migraine headaches hold\r\npositions of responsibility and power, he says, including airline pilots and\r\ndoctors.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">&quot;It\'s variable from person to\r\nperson, but I can say the vast majority of people we see at the San Francisco\r\nHeadache Clinic are very active, working and enjoying life,&quot; says\r\nGoldstein who recently was named president of the Headache and Facial Pain\r\nSection of the American Academy of Neurology.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">He points out that medications are\r\ngetting better and treatments are tailored to each patient. Some medications\r\ncan relieve a migraine within 20 minutes, depending on the type of headache the\r\nperson is suffering, and more are coming to market. Even Botox recently has\r\nbeen approved by the FDA to relieve pain for some migraine patients.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" line-height: normal; ">&quot;Most migraine headache\r\nsufferers can be helped,&quot; Goldstein adds, &quot;and can lead beautiful,\r\nnormal, complete and functional lives.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://www.shea-shea.com/">Shea\r\n&amp; Shea</a> is a nationally recognized personal injury law firm located in\r\nSan Jose, California.&#160; The firm has extensive experience in representing\r\nindividuals and their families in cases involving <a href="http://www.shea-shea.com/Catastrophic-Injury.aspx">catastrophic injuries</a>\r\nincluding <a href="http://www.shea-shea.com/Catastrophic-Injury/Wrongful-Death.aspx">wrongful\r\ndeath</a> and <a href="http://braininjury.shea-shea.com/">traumatic brain\r\ninjury</a>.&#160; Since 1966, Shea &amp; Shea have successfully represented the\r\nseriously injured and their families in both state and federal\r\ncourts.&#160;&#160; To learn more, visit us at <a href="http://www.shea-shea.com/">www.Shea-Shea.com</a> or telephone\r\n888-989-SHEA.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">&#160;</p>'
