aS'<p>It would seem that sometimes football can be as dangerous as it looks. In a <b>practice session in Texas, Zach Shaver, a freshman football player</b>, was blocked by a lineman, knocking both players to the ground. Though the players tried to overcome their collision and continue on, <b>Shaver fell back down, unable to get up. He was airlifted to a hospital, but sustained a severe head injury, and later died in the hospital.</b> (<a href="http://www.kwtx.com/home/headlines/89499537.html">http://www.kwtx.com/home/headlines/89499537.html</a>) </p><p>Roughly a week after his accident, and the exact cause of Shaver&#8217;s death is still uncertain, though it is believed to be related to a head injury. Practice was undergone in full gear with full protection, yet this was not enough to shield 18-year old Shaver. </p><p>Traumatic brain injuries are all too common with minor or major head injuries, and they are also an all-too common cause of death. Because <b>TBIs are so frequent, there are specialized lawyers for such accidents that involve these injuries.</b></p><p><i>The <a href="http://www.blackmanlegal.com/">personal injury lawyers</a> at Blackman Legal Group, a California-based law firm founded by renowned trial attorney, <a href="http://www.blackmanlegal.com/CM/Custom/Attorneys.asp#Blackman">Clifford Blackman</a>, has been representing injury victims since 1976, and have special expertise in cases involving <a href="http://www.spinal-injury-california.com/">spinal cord injury</a>, <a href="http://www.brain-injury-lawyer.com/">traumatic brain injury</a>, <a href="http://www.personal-injury-san-francisco.net/burn-injury.php">burn injury</a>, <a href="http://www.personal-injury-san-francisco.net/personal-injury-overview.php">catastrophic injuries</a> and <a href="http://www.wrongful-death-lawfirm.com/">wrongful death</a>.&#160; The nationwide toll-free number to call for a free consultation is <b>1-888-395-3551.</b></i></p>'
