aS'\r\n\r\n<p background: white; margin: 0in 0in 0pt; mso-line-height-alt: 12.0pt; mso-outline-level: 1;"><b>Trash pulls used as probable cause for a\r\nsearch warrant</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p background: white; margin: 19.2pt 0in; line-height: normal;">Recently, our firm had a case with a client\r\ncharged with possession of cannabis/Marijuana under 20 grams and paraphernalia.\r\nThe allegations against our client were brought after a search warrant was conducted\r\non the private residence of an individual&#8217;s home. The probable cause in the\r\naffidavit for a search warrant was based on a series of trash pulls conducted\r\nby the local&#160;Police Department.</p>\r\n\r\n<p background: white; margin: 19.2pt 0in; line-height: normal;">The local Police Department claimed that they\r\ndecided to investigate our client&#8217;s address because they followed an un-named\r\nknown drug dealer to our client&#8217;s residence on only one occasion. This vague\r\naccount of one instance was the only information the&#160;Police gave for\r\ndecided to open an investigation into our client. The investigation consisted\r\nof doing trash-pulls of our clients abandoned garbage to search for drugs or\r\nparaphernalia. This investigation lasted approximately 2 months with 7\r\ndifferent trash pulls. During the first 4 weeks, every trash pull came up\r\nnegative for drugs or paraphernalia. However, the&#160;Police Department\r\ndeemed it necessary to continue this investigation, even though valuable\r\nresources were being utilized on a cold case at the expense of taxpayers. This\r\ninvestigation by the&#160;&#160;police department totaled nearly two thousand\r\ndollars.</p>\r\n\r\n<p background: white; margin: 19.2pt 0in; line-height: normal;">In the coming weeks, 4 further trash pulls\r\nwere conducted which resulted in what the&#160;Police Department deemed\r\npositive results for 1 gram of Cannabis. In our office&#8217;s investigation of the case,\r\nwe reviewed the evidence the&#160;Police Department had in their possession.\r\nThe evidence consisted of 3 different zip-locked bags with no more than a\r\ncouple stems, seeds and ashy debris. The&#160; Police department put a vague\r\naccount of the evidence collected in an affidavit in support of a search\r\nwarrant. When carrying out the warrant, the&#160; Police kicked open our\r\nclients door and busted through his window without first announcing their\r\npresence. Their reasoning for this unannounced intrusion was that an officer\r\nspotted someone looking out of the window before they were able to announce.</p>\r\n\r\n<p background: white; margin: 19.2pt 0in; line-height: normal;">Our office was able to attack the methods used\r\nby the Police Department in wrongfully entering our client&#8217;s residence\r\nand violating his 4th amendment rights. If you have been arrested for a drug\r\ncrime, know your rights and call our office today. 407-323-6700</p>\r\n\r\n<p background: white; margin: 0in 0in 8.65pt; line-height: normal;" />\r\n\r\n<p background: white; margin: 0in 0in 8.65pt; line-height: normal;"><b>&#160;</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p margin: 0in 0in 10pt; line-height: normal;">&#160;</p>\r\n\r\n<!--more-->Our office was able to attack the methods used by the Police Department in wrongfully entering our client&#8217;s residence and violating his 4th amendment rights. If you have been arrested for a drug crime, know your rights and call our office today. 407-323-6700? Protecting the Rights of Veterans. Veteran Discount for Legal Services'
