aS'<p>Were you recently involved in a Kentucky auto accident?&#160; It is understandable that you may be unsure of what to do next.&#160; For your convenience, please consult the following list of steps you should take in the aftermath of an accident to best assure your rights are not jeopardized or violated.&#160; </p><p>After a Kentucky car accident, you should: </p><ul><li>Sign nothing.&#160; Insurance adjustors often show up at accident scenes to gather information.&#160; They ask numerous questions in order to determine who is at fault for the accident.&#160; Regardless of your role in the accident, answering insurance adjustors&#8217; questions without consulting a Kentucky car accident attorney could incriminate you.&#160; It is important you refrain from signing any documents that insurance adjustors may provide&#8212;doing so could limit or waive your rights to future financial compensation.</li><li>Compile as much information as possible.&#160; The scene of the accident can be your most valuable resource in a personal injury case.&#160; You should take photographs of all damage when possible, and interview any witnesses at the scene.&#160; In cases concerning Kentucky automobile accidents, photographic evidence almost always a vital element for building a strong argument.&#160; Additionally, accurately recording all particulars of witness reactions and obtaining their names and contact details is important.&#160; The more information you can compile, the stronger your Kentucky car accident case.</li><li>Consult a physician immediately.&#160; It is necessary to see a doctor for a full evaluation whether or not you have been obviously injured.&#160; You may be endangering your health if you fail to seek treatment because you are concerned about the financial cost.&#160; There could be internal injuries that you are unable to detect without a medical professional.&#160; Keeping detailed records of your treatment regime, including any medications prescribed, can actually help your case by providing you with official evidence of your injuries.</li></ul><p>Report the accident to your insurance provider right away.&#160; Failure to do so could be detrimental to your case.</p><p>Maintain all records.&#160; In addition to your medical records, you should keep any other files and/or receipts that pertain to your case.&#160; If you have been injured, it is strongly recommended that you keep a daily log of your injury and how it affects your daily life.&#160; Details such as a pain in your back that you feel when you tie your shoes are vital to your case. More importantly, if the injury heals over time, it may be difficult to remember just how painful it was several months prior to being in a setting where a judge or jury can hear your case.&#160; </p><p>Seek legal representation&#160; </p><p>You should consult a <a href="http://www.bullockcoffman.com" target="&#95;blank">Kentucky auto accident lawyer</a> immediately if you have been hurt in an accident.&#160; Experienced attorneys, such as those at Bullock &amp; Coffman, can represent you in transactions with insurance companies and courts, and ensure that you receive compensation for medical costs, lost income, and pain and suffering.&#160; Contact Bullock &amp; Coffman today for a consultation with our seasoned Kentucky car accident lawyers.</p><!--more--><p><a href="http://www.bullockcoffman.com/" target="&#95;blank">Kentucky auto accident lawyers</a> of Bullock &amp; Coffman talk about what you shold do after a motor vehicle accident.</p><p>Were you recently involved in a Kentucky auto accident?&#160; It is understandable that you may be unsure of what to do next.&#160; For your convenience, please consult the following list of steps you should take in the aftermath of an accident to best assure your rights are not jeopardized or violated.</p>'
