aS'<p class="WebText"><br />Common questions about criminal law include: </p><ul><li><div class="WebBulletList">How do people know if they are being arrested?</div></li><li><div class="WebBulletList">What should an individual do if arrested?</div></li><li><div class="WebBulletList">What are a person&#8217;s rights after being arrested?</div></li><li><div class="WebBulletList">What is a search warrant?</div></li><li><div class="WebBulletList">When can a person refuse a search?</div></li><li><div class="WebBulletList">Do the police have to inform people of their right to refuse a search?</div></li><li>How do people know if they are being arrested?</li></ul><p>Stops and detainments are brief questioning in the place where detained.&#160; If taken to the police station and held for a considerable time period, it is likely that an arrest is being made. </p><strong>What should an individual do if arrested?</strong><p class="Style1">*&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Do not resist arrest</p><p class="Style1">*&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Provide your correct name and address</p><p class="Style1">*&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Invoke the right to remain silent by voicing the desire not to answer </p><p class="Style1">*&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Request a lawyer</p><p>Law enforcement authorities may insist that cooperation and answering questions will make things go easier.&#160; This is generally not the case.&#160; They are gathering evidence for prosecution. Consult a lawyer before answering.</p><p><strong>What are a person\'s rights after being arrested?</strong> </p><p>When arrested, people have the right to:</p><p class="Style1">*&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Contact someone (it may take more than one call to reach someone, which is allowed)</p><p class="Style1">*&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Have an attorney present if appearing in a line-up for identification</p><p class="Style1">*&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Reasonable bail or bond if established by the court</p><p class="Style1">*&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; A speedy and public trial by an impartial jury (<b><a href="http://www.law.cornell.edu/constitution/sixth&#95;amendment">Sixth Amendment</a>)</b></p><strong>What is a search warrant?</strong><p>A search warrant is a court order issued by a judge that gives authorities the right to conduct a search for specific items in a specific place at a specified time.&#160; </p><strong>When can a person refuse a search?</strong><p class="WebText">If the person is not under arrest or the authorities do not have a search warrant, the person can often refuse to allow the search.&#160; If unsure about whether to allow the search or not, invoke the right to speak to a lawyer.</p><strong>Do the police have to inform people of their right to refuse a search?</strong><p>No.&#160; By allowing a search, the court considers that the person has waived his or her Constitutional rights.&#160; Anything found becomes admissible evidence.</p><em>Obtain experienced criminal defense</em><p>Graham, Allen &amp; Brown, PLLC is an experienced Tulsa, Oklahoma criminal law firm.&#160; Rely on our <a title="lawyers in Tulsa" href="http://www.lawtulsa.com/" target="&#95;blank">Tulsa lawyers</a>, who have more than 100 years of combined legal experience.&#160; Call 918.948.6171 or <a href="http://www.lawtulsa.com/">contact us online</a> to schedule a free consultation.</p>'
