aS'<p>A felony plea is an agreement between the court or the district attorney and the defendant in a criminal case to plead guilty in exchange for a specific punishment.&#160; Most felony cases in Orange County, California, are settled before trial by way of a plea agreement and often can be reduced to a misdemeanor or be given probation.</p><p>However, a felony plea agreement should contain the following elements and should be in writing:</p><p>1.&#160; A Statement of the Terms of the Plea</p><p>2.&#160; A Waiver of Constitutional Rights</p><p>3.&#160; An Advisement of the Direct Consequences of the Plea</p><p>4.&#160; The Immigration Consequences of the Plea</p><p>5.&#160; The Factual Basis for the Plea</p><p>6.&#160; A Statement of Findings by the Court</p><p>7.&#160; A Financial Disclosure for Restitution</p><p>In most cases, the court will refer the case to the probation department for a presentence probation report.&#160; The court will usually follow the presentence recommendation by probation.&#160; That is why is it very important to have an experienced <a title="Orange County Felony Attorney" href="http://www.scotthugheslaw.com/Areas-of-Practice/Criminal-Defense.aspx">Orange County Felony Attorney</a><a href="http://www.scotthugheslaw.com/Areas-of-Practice/Criminal-Defense.aspx"> </a>represent a person at their felony plea or sentencing hearing.</p><p>Contact <a title="Orange County Criminal Defense Lawyer" href="http://www.scotthugheslaw.com/Areas-of-Practice/Criminal-Defense.aspx">Orange County Criminal Defense Lawyer</a> Scott D. Hughes at (714) 423-6928 or scott@scotthugheslaw.com.</p><!--more-->A felony plea is an agreement between the court or district attorney and\r\n the defendant in a criminal case to plead guilty in exchange for a \r\nspecific punishment.&#160; '
