aS'<p>While marriage represents an emotional bond, from a practical standpoint dealing with finances is also part of married life. Many people regard a prenuptial agreement with distain, believing it is a precursor to certain divorce. However, discovering each others&#8217; financial views before marriage allows you to deal with them in advance, start out on the right foot, and avoid future conflict.&#160; </p><p><br />A prenuptial agreement is a financial contract prior to marriage that becomes effective once a couple marries. When one party has significant assets before marriage or anticipates a considerable increase in income after marriage, a prenuptial agreement can establish financial guidelines. Often people with children from a previous marriage consider drafting a prenuptial agreement to provide financially for children in the event of unforeseeable death or divorce.</p><p><br />Prenuptial agreements are recognized as legal and upheld by U.S. courts in all 50 states. A prenuptial agreement takes precedence over how state laws dictate property division or alimony during divorce or after death, and is a way of ensuring financial preferences are met. <a href="http://www.stateofflorida.com/Portal/DesktopDefault.aspx?tabid=64" target="&#95;blank">Florida divorce statutes</a> otherwise dictate alimony, health insurance, and the assignment of the estate based on equitable distribution.</p><p><br /><b>Advantages of a prenuptial agreement</b></p><p><br />A prenuptial agreement is an excellent financial tool that can offer advantages such as:</p><ul type="disc"><li>Debt protection from a spouse\'s previous debts</li><li>Separation of assets and property acquired during marriage </li><li>Safeguarding children\'s future inheritance</li><li>Keeping a family business in the family</li><li>Establishing how property is divided in the event of divorce or death</li></ul><p><br />Setting future guidelines to deal with finances, such as:</p><ul type="disc"><li>How to pay income taxes (separate or joint)</li><li>How to set up savings</li><li>Whether to set up joint accounts</li><li>Which spouse manages bill payment</li><li>Which spouse handles investments</li><li>How to support a spouse furthering his or her education</li><li>How to set up life insurance</li><li>What type of dispute resolution to use (mediation/arbitration) should conflicts arise</li></ul><p>The more complex your financial situation is (for example, involving family businesses and substantial investments or assets) the more important it is to draft a prenuptial agreement. </p><p><br /><b>Many couples can benefit from a prenuptial agreement</b></p><p><br />With today&#8217;s increasing divorce rates, couples of all economic classes can spare themselves from higher divorce costs by drafting a prenuptial agreement.Expensive divorces are proportionate to the extent of conflict involved&#8212;often finance related. A well-crafted prenuptial agreement, written when cool heads still prevailed, can protect your family from destructive and wasteful litigation. A&#160;<a href="http://www.garywms-law.com/aop/clearwater-divorce/" target="&#95;blank">Clearwater divorce lawyer</a>&#160;can review your situation and advise whether a prenuptial agreement can benefit you.</p><p>The Law Firm for Family Law Florida<br />4625 East Bay Drive <br />Suite 305<br />Clearwater, Florida 33766 <br />(727) 531-8737</p><!--more-->A prenuptial agreement is a financial contract prior to marriage that becomes effective once a couple marries. When one party has significant assets before marriage or anticipates a considerable increase in income after marriage, a prenuptial agreement can establish financial guidelines. Often people with children from a previous marriage consider drafting a prenuptial agreement to provide financially for children in the event of unforeseeable death or divorce.'
