aS'\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" margin: 0in 0in 0pt; text-align: justify; text-indent: 0.5in; mso-line-height-alt: 10.8pt;">June\r\n29, 2012 - COLORADO &#8211; Aspen Lawyer -- Matthew C. Ferguson now of the Matthew C.\r\nFerguson Law Firm, Aspen, Colorado successfully argued for Colorado Supreme\r\nCourt reversal of the Colorado Court of Appeals finding of bid rigging by\r\nattendees at a foreclosure sale in Pitkin County, Florida. Aspen Attorney Matt\r\nFerguson won the case at the trial level proving that the members of an LLC\r\nformed after the Public Trustee foreclosure sale by 3 bidders had not bid\r\nrigged. Ferguson represented the LLC that was deemed by the Pitkin County\r\nPublic Trustee to have been the successful high bidder at the 2007 foreclosure\r\nsale in Pitkin County. The Property Owner launched a series of challenges to\r\nthe foreclosure sale against the Pitkin County Public Trustee, the foreclosing bank\r\nand then Ferguson\'s client. Ferguson defended all those proceedings in the\r\nPitkin County, District Court. The bank also retained counsel and the issue of\r\nstrict compliance was also decided in favor of the bank by the Supreme Court.\r\nAmos\' technical notice compliance arguments were rejected by the Colorado\r\nSupreme Court, which found that the Property owner had indeed received timely\r\nnotice of the foreclosure sale and her redemption rights. The Court would not\r\nexpand its strict compliance holding in <i>Dews v. District Court, 648 P.2d\r\n662, 664 (Colo. 1982).</i> Rather the Court noted as pointed at by Aspen Lawyer\r\nFerguson at trial and thus in the appellate record that Amos and her attorneys\r\nhad the requisite Rule 120 notice of sale but chose not to challenge the pending\r\nforeclosure. Aspen lawyer Matt Ferguson helped defend the notice issues given\r\nhis client\'s investment in the property and Aspen Condominium at the Aspen\r\nAlps, and early defeat of the injunction efforts by Betty Amos against the\r\nPitkin County Public Trustee. </p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" margin: 0in 0in 0pt; text-align: justify; mso-line-height-alt: 10.8pt;">&#160;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" margin: 0in 0in 0pt; text-align: justify; text-indent: 0.5in; mso-line-height-alt: 10.8pt;">Holland\r\n&amp; Hart represented the property owner Betty Amos and her late husband\'s\r\nestate. Amos had failed to timely redeem, but sought to redeem after the\r\ndeadline. Ferguson and his client established at the TRO and Injunction phases\r\nthat an alleged redemption letter was ineffective and likely never sent. </p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" margin: 0in 0in 0pt; text-align: justify; text-indent: 0.5in; mso-line-height-alt: 10.8pt;">&#160;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" margin: 0in 0in 0pt; text-align: justify; text-indent: 0.5in; mso-line-height-alt: 10.8pt;">The\r\nproperty owner then unsuccessfully challenged the foreclosing bank\'s Rule 120\r\nproceeding for the Public Trustee sale and also failed to enjoin the Public\r\nTrustee from awarding the deed to Ferguson\'s client -- Aspen Alps 123, LLC.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" margin: 0in 0in 0pt; text-align: justify; text-indent: 0.5in; mso-line-height-alt: 10.8pt;">&#160;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" margin: 0in 0in 0pt; text-align: justify; text-indent: 0.5in; mso-line-height-alt: 10.8pt;">Just\r\nbefore trial, the property owner tried to add a bid rigging claim under\r\nColorado Antitrust Act, section 6-4-106, C.R.S. (2011). Plaintiffs\' untimely\r\nmotion to amend to add the antitrust claim was denied but bid rigging was then\r\nallowed as a defense at trial. The trial court found that no bid rigging had\r\nbeen established and awarded Ferguson\'s client the property, as well as fees\r\nfor an improper lis pendens.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" margin: 0in 0in 0pt; text-align: justify; text-indent: 0.5in; mso-line-height-alt: 10.8pt;">&#160;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" margin: 0in 0in 0pt; text-align: justify; text-indent: 0.5in; mso-line-height-alt: 10.8pt;">On\r\nthis limited and unusual trial record, the Colorado Court of Appeals reversed\r\ncertain of the trial court&#8217;s findings and held that bid rigging had occurred as\r\nopposed to joint bidding. The Colorado Supreme Court granted certiorari on the\r\nnotice and bid rigging issues and in fact on the issue of a remedy for the\r\nalleged bid rigging. </p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" margin: 0in 0in 0pt; text-align: justify; text-indent: 0.5in; mso-line-height-alt: 10.8pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" margin: 0in 0in 0pt; text-align: justify; text-indent: 0.5in; mso-line-height-alt: 10.8pt;">Critical\r\nto Matt Ferguson\'s limited liability company client and its 3 members, the\r\nColorado Supreme Court determined that, based on the limited trial record in\r\nthe case, the property owners had failed to establish bid rigging in violation\r\nof the Colorado Antitrust Act, section 6-4-106, C.R.S. (2011), as a defense.\r\nThus rather than looking to the certified issue of an appropriate remedy as\r\nraised by Holland &amp; Hart, aspen attorney convinced the Colorado Supreme\r\nCourt to look at the Court of appeals findings altogether. The Supreme Court\r\nreversed the Court of Appeals&#8217; antitrust finding and held that illegal bid\r\nrigging had not occurred. Aspen Alps lawyer noted the important and novel legal\r\nissues in the Colorado Supreme Court\'s decision and a balancing of the rights\r\nof bidders at foreclosure sales. Ferguson stated that he was &quot;delighted\r\nthat the members of the Aspen Alps 123, LLC were now vindicated after being\r\naccused by Amos and Holland &amp; Hart as bid riggers on the eve of trial and\r\nbeing found as such on the flimsiest of a record\r\nand with little or no due process.&quot; The Supreme Court of Colorado found\r\nthat the members of the LLC has simply pooled their resources to take title and\r\nfound nothing in the record that could support reversing the trial court\'s\r\nfinding that nothing had occurred that would have established an anti-trust\r\nviolation. Ferguson was able to adduce evidence at trial to counter the\r\nAnti-Trust defense that 2 of the 3 bidders, who had bid competitively and well\r\nabove the bank\'s bid, had no more funds to bid higher than the $1.860,000 that\r\nwas accepted by the Public Trustee for the Aspen Alps Condominium. </p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" margin: 0in 0in 0pt; text-align: justify; text-indent: 0.5in; mso-line-height-alt: 10.8pt;">&#160;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" margin: 0in 0in 0pt; text-align: justify; text-indent: 0.5in; mso-line-height-alt: 10.8pt;">Aspen\r\nAttorney Matt Ferguson can be reached at www.mattfergusonlaw.com or (970)\r\n925-6288.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" margin: 0in 0in 10pt; text-align: justify; line-height: normal;">&#160;</p>\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nJune\r\n22, 2012 - COLORADO &#8211; Aspen Lawyer -- Matthew C. Ferguson now of the Matthew C.\r\nFerguson Law Firm, Aspen, Colorado successfully argued for Colorado Supreme\r\nCourt reversal of the Colorado Court of Appeals finding of bid rigging by\r\nattendees at a foreclosure sale in Pitkin County, Florida. Aspen Attorney Matt\r\nFerguson won the case at the trial level proving that the members of an LLC\r\nformed after the Public Trustee foreclosure sale by 3 bidders had not bid\r\nrigged. Ferguson re'
