aS'How a Commercial General Liability Policy Protects Your Business<p>A commercial general liability (CGL) policy protects your business against bodily injury and property damage to third parties caused by your business&#8217;s acts. If your business has only one form of business insurance, it most likely is a CGL policy.</p><p>A CGL policy has three primary coverage sections:</p><ul><li>The <b>premises liability section</b> covers liability caused by a condition on your business&#8217;s premises or by your business&#8217;s operations in progress either on or away from the premises.</li><li>The <b>products liability section</b> &#8212; which exists for a business that manufactures, sells, handles, or distributes goods or products &#8212; covers liability for bodily injury or property damage arising out of your business&#8217;s goods or products.</li><li>The <b>completed operations section</b> covers bodily injury or property damage arising out of your business&#8217;s completed work.</li></ul><p>A CGL policy protects your business by paying the costs to defend against the third party&#8217;s claim and by paying a judgment or settlement to the third party.</p><p>A CGL policy covers the actions of certain people involved in your business:</p><ul><li>Partners or members of a joint venture who were acting in their official capacity</li><li>A corporation&#8217;s executive officers, directors, and stockholders who were acting in their official capacity</li><li>Employees who were acting in their capacity as an employee</li><li>A subsidiary of which the business owns more than 50 percent of the voting stock</li><li>An individual or entity with whom the business has a written agreement to indemnify</li><li>A newly acquired organization</li><li>Legal representatives for any liability arising from the maintenance or use of the business&#8217;s property in their care</li><li>Volunteers for the business who were acting under the business&#8217;s direction and within the scope of their responsibilities for the business</li></ul><p>A CGL policy contains exclusions to coverage. It is important that you read and understand them. Here is a list of some exclusions in a CGL policy:</p><ul><li>Intentional injury</li><li>Contractual liability, except for those contracts incidental to the business, such as a lease</li><li>Use of intoxicants</li><li>Injuries to the business&#8217;s employees</li><li>Pollution</li><li>Use of watercraft or aircraft</li><li>Liability related to war or terrorism</li><li>Damage to the business&#8217;s property</li><li>Damage to products or recalls of the business&#8217;s products</li></ul><p>A CGL policy often is offered as part of a business owner&#8217;s package, which also includes property insurance. But a CGL policy does not cover your business for every liability. For instance, a business that makes professional judgments and recommendations also should consider obtaining a professional liability policy. Contact an <a href="http://www.bglawyers.com/Los-Angeles-incorporation/">incorporation law firm</a> to go over the guidelines of how a CGL can help your business. </p><!--more-->Contact a <a href="http://www.bglawyers.com/Los-Angeles-incorporation/">Los Angeles incorporation lawyer</a> so you can help protect your business against either premise or product liability.'
