aS'<p TEXT-ALIGN: center" align="center" /><p TEXT-ALIGN: center" align="center" /><p>Employers should take the following steps to help be certain they have correctly classified members of their sales force as exempt or non-exempt.</p><p /><p /><p><b><u>FOR INSIDE SALESPERSONS:</u></b></p><p /><p /><p><b>1.</b>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Examine whether the employee meets the exemption requirements on a weekly&#160;basis.</p><p /><p><b>2.</b>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Pay close attention to guaranteed draw programs and whether they are in fact&#160;meeting the requirements for the inside sales exemption.</p><p /><p /><p><b><u>FOR OUTSIDE SALESPERSONS:</u></b></p><p /><p /><p TEXT-INDENT: -0.5in"><b>1.</b>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 1.&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Determine whether the employee spends at least 50 percent of his or her work time engaged in pure sales.</p><p /><p TEXT-INDENT: -0.5in"><b>2.</b>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 2.&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Allocate incidental work appropriately.&#160; For example, an appointment to make a sales pitch to increase business and to also deliver products should be allocated between the two types of work.</p><p TEXT-INDENT: -0.5in" /><p TEXT-INDENT: -0.5in"><b>3.</b>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 3.&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Be sure that job descriptions accurately reflect the employer&#8217;s expectations and the positions actual requirements.</p><p TEXT-INDENT: -0.5in" /><p TEXT-INDENT: -0.5in"><b>4.</b>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 4.&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Monitor employee performance to ensure the employee does not fall below the 50 percent threshold.</p><p TEXT-INDENT: -0.5in" /><p TEXT-INDENT: -0.5in"><b>5.</b>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 5.&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Engage in annual audits to determine if employees are properly classified.&#160; Also, schedule audits whenever there has been a job reorganization or reclassification. </p><p />'
