aS'From <a href="http://www.burlisonlaw.com/blog/" title="Legal Blog">Legal Blog</a> by <a href="http://www.burlisonlaw.com/" title="San Francisco Personal Injury Attorney Brett A. Burlison"><p>San Francisco Personal Injury Attorney Brett A. Burlison</p></a><p>\r\nIn A ruling issued Thursday the California Supreme Court unanimously ruled that retailers may no longer collect ZIP Codes from credit card customers.</p><p>The case involved a 1990 law that prohibits businesses from recording customers personal ID information.&#160; The case was filed by a women in Menlo Park who purchased an item at Williams-Sonoma in 2008 with her credit card.&#160; As requested, she gave the store her ZIP Code and then started getting all those pesky catalogs that we all drop in the recycling nearly every day.<br />The ruling was actually fairly narrow, however, and restricted to the facts of the case.&#160; For instance, stores can still request a ZIP Code when selling online, or in other settings like a gas-station or a bank.<br />The issue that the Court will need to address next is how far across the spectrum of private information does this ruling apply?<br />The case is Pineda vs. Williams-Sonoma Stores, S178241.<br /></p>'
