aS'<p class="MsoNormal">Island\r\nof Molokai, Hawaii - December 11, 2013</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">A\r\nCessna Caravan commuter type plane suffered a catastrophic engine failure\r\nshortly after takeoff Wednesday afternoon, forcing the pilot to ditch the plane\r\nin the water. According to an <a  rel="nofollow" href="http://tbo.com/hawaii-survivor-plane-lost-power-then-glided-20131214/">AP\r\nreport in the Tampa Tribune</a>, passenger C. Phillip Hollstein reported that\r\nthe pilot &#8220;did everything right. He set it up for the best crash-landing you\r\ncould do.&#8221;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">The\r\nplane, belonging to Makini Kai Air, had taken off from Kalaupapa on Molakai\r\nbound for Honolulu. Less than a minute into the flight, a bang was heard from\r\nthe engine, and then silence. After the plane settled in the water, the pilot\r\nand eight passengers all made it out of the damaged plane. Most people had\r\ndonned like jackets and were rescued from the water at the crash site. But\r\nHawaii State Health Director Loretta Fuddy, who made it out of the plane with\r\nthe others, died while in the water. Several of the passengers suffered minor\r\ninjuries and were taken to hospitals on Oahu. Mr. Hollstein, 70, swam about\r\nhalf a mile to safety reaching the Molokai shore in six foot high waves. The\r\nNTSB is investigating the crash, but the investigation will be hampered because\r\nthe plane sank in deep water and is unlikely to be recovered.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">This\r\nis the second caravan crash in less than two weeks. On November 29<sup>th</sup>\r\na similar <a  rel="nofollow" href="http://www.airplanecrash-lawyer.com/PracticeAreas/Recent-Air-Crashes.asp">Caravan\r\ncrashed in a remote area of Alaska</a> killing four people.</p>'
