aS'\r\n\r\n<p>The intent of the foreign tax credit is to\r\nreduce the double tax burden that could occur when foreign source income is\r\ntaxed by both the U.S.\r\nand the foreign country from which the income is generated.&#160;&#160; IRC Section 901.&#160; However, the U.S. Circuit Courts of Appeal are\r\ndivided on the test to use to determine when a foreign tax pay qualifies as a foreign\r\ntax credit.&#160; </p>\r\n\r\n<p>In <i>PPL Corporation v. Commissioner </i>and <i>Entergy Corporation v. Commissioner</i>,\r\nboth companies took a foreign tax credit for the windfall profits tax each paid\r\nto the U.K.&#160; The Internal Revenue Service (IRS) disallowed\r\nthe foreign tax credits.&#160; Thereafter, the\r\nU.S. Tax Court ruled in favor of PPL and Entergy holding that a foreign tax,\r\nsuch as the windfall profits tax, can be used as a credit against U.S. income tax\r\nif the foreign tax is imposed on income already earned, and the basis of gross\r\nreceipts and net income.&#160; Treas. Reg.\r\n&#167;1.901-2.&#160; The IRS argued Treas. Reg.\r\n&#167;1.901-2 did not apply because the U.K. windfall profits tax was not\r\npredominantly an income tax based on gross receipts and net income.&#160; Instead it was calculated as a percentage of\r\nan imputed value when PPL and Entergy purchased ownership in British companies\r\nfor less than the alleged actual worth of the British companies.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Fifth Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals,\r\nhearing <i>Entergy</i>, affirmed the Tax\r\nCourt decision.&#160; However, in hearing <i>PPL, </i>the Third Circuit reversed the Tax\r\nCourt.&#160; The Third Circuit agreed with the\r\nIRS and held that how the tax was calculated, and not its practical effect,\r\nwould determine whether a tax paid to a foreign government qualified as a\r\nforeign tax credit.&#160; PPL appealed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>By agreeing to hear <i>PPL, </i>the U.S. Supreme Court will hear a tax case whose decision\r\naffects hundreds of millions of dollars and has broad implications for U.S. companies\r\nwho operate internationally.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">Givner &amp; Kaye focuses on sophisticated income tax planning and\r\ncompliance, tax litigation and procedure, estate planning, and asset protection\r\nplans for individuals and businesses in Beverly Hills,\r\nCalabasas, West Los Angeles, Hollywood, and\r\nother areas of Los Angeles, Orange,\r\nVentura, San Bernardino,\r\nRiverside and Santa Barbara Counties.&#160; Call Los Angeles&#160;Estate Planning and\r\nAsset Protection Plan Attorneys Givner &amp; Kaye at <a target="&#95;blank" href="tel:%28310%29%20207-8008">(310) 207-8008</a> today.</p>\r\n\r\n<!--more-->The intent of the foreign tax credit is to\r\nreduce the double tax burden that could occur when foreign source income is\r\ntaxed by both the U.S.\r\nand the foreign country from which the income is generated.&#160;&#160; IRC Section 901.&#160; However, the U.S. Circuit Courts of Appeal are\r\ndivided on the test to use to determine when a foreign tax pay qualifies as a foreign\r\ntax credit.&#160; '
