aS'<p><strong>The Effect of Prior Injury on a Personal Injury Lawsuit</strong></p><p>If you have a trick knee due to an old football injury or back problems stemming from a previous car accident, you may think you cannot sue for the same injury if another accident worsens the condition.&#160; After all, even though this accident was the fault of someone else and now the previous injury is much worse, your knee or back was already damaged.&#160; What options do you have?</p><p>The answer is more than you think if you have the right personal injury attorney on your side.&#160; While a person responsible for causing an accident is only accountable for the harm this accident caused, if your lawyer can prove he or she was negligent and that negligence caused the accident, which in turn worsened your condition, you may be able to collect compensation to the degree that your injury was aggravated.</p><p><strong>A clear case of negligence </strong></p><p>Shopping at Home Depot should not be hazardous to your health &#8212; just your pocketbook.&#160; Unfortunately, for one painter, a routine visit to the big box supply store resulted in a lot more than an empty wallet. On this occasion, a piece of lumber that had been improperly stacked on the racks above became dislodge when the painter removed a piece of molding from one of the lower shelves.&#160; The heavy wood fell on his head.</p><p>This victim already suffered from spinal problems, for which he had previously received treatment.&#160; Despite the fact that the Home Depot incident occurred two years later, personal injury attorney Gary A. Sernaker was able to prove that this new accident re-injured the victim.&#160; As a result, a verdict rendered in California federal district court netted his client over $300,000.00.</p><p><strong>Contact a personal injury lawyer </strong></p><p>Whether the injury you suffered is brand-new or represents a worsening of a pre-existing condition, do not assume you know the outcome of a