aS'<p>Although you are not required by law to have a lawyer, you should still consult with one to protect your rights, even if you know you are innocent. The advice and expertise of a lawyer can result in faster and better results for you, which is why it is always recommended that you should be represented by a lawyer for a criminal case. </p><p>If you wish to not have a lawyer represent you in court, you should still seek advice from one. An attorney&#8217;s advice will help you understand the nature of the charges against you, possible defenses you could use in court, plea bargains that would most likely be offered to you, as well as what could potentially be your punishment if you are convicted.</p><p>If you choose to have a lawyer represent you, a lawyer will evaluate all aspects of the circumstances regarding your case, explain what to expect at every step of the legal process, and take all necessary action to ensure that your legal rights are protected. Having a lawyer will also save you time because they will research any litigation pertaining to your case, interview witnesses, collect all important records and documents, prepare necessary paperwork, and plan your defense strategies for you. Lawyers are also acquainted with important legal rules that are hidden in court interpretations of state and federal constitutions and they are familiar with local court procedures that are not put into writing. </p><p>If you know you are innocent and you want to meet with a lawyer, you should act as soon as possible. Lawyers need plenty of time to prepare; therefore, it is always better to start looking for a lawyer sooner than later. Deadlines also are a key factor in acting as fast as possible. You do not want to miss a deadline that could potentially cause you to lose your individual rights.&#160; </p><p>In some cases you may not be able to afford a lawyer. In situations such as this, you may be eligible to be represented by the Public Defender&#8217;s Office. Many attorneys offer free consultations in which you can be provided with information regarding attorney fees and whether or not you are entitled to a Public Defender. </p><p>This article has been provided by the <a href="http://www.tncriminallawfirm.com/">Nashville criminal defense law firm</a>, Law Offices of Thomas T. Overton, 615-250-8000, www.tncriminallawfirm.com.</p><!--more--><p>Although you are not required by law to have a lawyer, you should still consult with one to protect your rights, even if you know you are innocent. The advice and expertise of a lawyer can result in faster and better results for you, which is why it is always recommended that you should be represented by a lawyer for a criminal case.&#160; This article has been provided by the <a href="http://www.tncriminallawfirm.com/">Nashville criminal defense law firm</a>, Law Offices of Thomas T. Overton'
