aS'<p font-weight: bold; ">A Las Vegas Security Guard was found not guilty on the charge of Battery.</p><p>A security guard is considered a private person for the purpose of arresting a trespassing public school student who was kicked-out of his class at a Las Vegas High School. &#160;The student decided that he would jump the wall and go over to a private school across the street from his high school. &#160;The Student disregarded the posted signs warning &quot;No Tresspassing.&quot; &#160;The student was apprehended for trespassing and during a search for weapons disregarded the security officer\'s request to put his hand on the fence so the officers could conduct a pat down for weapons.</p><p>When the student made a furtive move with his elbow to the security officer\'s head the officer took the student to the ground and handcuffed him. &#160;After the take-down the officer noticed that the student had a blooding nose. &#160;The officer called for LVMPD and the school nurse.</p><p>It was determined that the student was not seriously injured and the student was returned to his public high school. The Nevada case of <u font-weight: bold; ">State v. Waddell,</u>&#160;118 Nev. 206&#160;(2002) held that a private citizen can only use that force which is reasonable and necessary under the circumstances.</p><p></p><!--more-->Where a public offense is committed in the presence of a private security officer, the officer has the common law right to use reasonable force to make a citizen\'s arrest.'
