aS'<p class="MsoNormal">When\r\nsomeone close to us dies, it&#8217;s natural to grieve deeply and then try to move on\r\nwith our lives. Yet if the person <a href="http://www.injury-attorneys.com/">died</a>\r\nduring fairly routine <a href="http://www.injury-attorneys.com/">surgery</a>\r\nand was relatively young and in decent health, we actually owe it to ourselves\r\nand others to inquire about the exact circumstances of the person&#8217;s demise. We\r\nmay just learn something that can help save other lives. </p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal"><u>Massive\r\nBlood Transfusion Protocols</u></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">Far\r\ntoo often, human error plays a significant role in many unexpected surgical\r\ndeaths. Perhaps one of the least expected causes of death during an operation\r\ninvolves &#8220;bleeding out&#8221; or massive hemorrhaging. Furthermore, when a hospital\r\neither doesn&#8217;t have a Massive Blood Transfusion Protocol (MTP), or frequently\r\nfails to follow it, a serious crisis can quickly escalate into death. When\r\nproper blood supplies aren&#8217;t readily administered, cardiac arrests and major\r\norgan shutdowns can quickly follow. Metabolic acidosis, hypothermia and\r\ncoagulation problems can prove deadly. (Patients who lose 50% or more of their\r\nblood in less than three hours are usually thought to be experiencing massive\r\nbleeding.) </p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">Before\r\nsigning consent forms for yourself or anyone you love, always ask what type of\r\nMTP the hospital or surgical clinic has in place. Of course, long before the\r\nday of surgery, you must <i>always</i>\r\npersonally discuss your chronic medical conditions (or those of the designated\r\npatient) and daily prescription dosages with the surgeon, specifically asking\r\nthat all such information be transmitted <i>immediately</i>\r\nto the anesthesiologist. A quick call to the latter doctor&#8217;s office to inquire\r\nif the information was both received <i>and\r\nreviewed</i> may wind up saving your life.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">&#160;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal"><u>Key\r\nMassive Blood Transfusion Protocol Elements</u></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Before the actual day of your\r\nsurgery, be sure to ask if the following key MTP provisions are standard at the\r\nhospital, clinic or other healthcare facility.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst">?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;\r\nOne or more designated blood transfusion\r\nservice doctors will be notified as soon as any surgical patient begins showing\r\nsigns of ma<a name="&#95;GoBack"></a>ssive blood loss. <i>[This individual should monitor the choice and administration of the\r\nproper blood (and other products) that will restore proper coagulation and\r\nother laboratory values];</i></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle">?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;\r\nA high-speed blood transfusion pump must\r\nbe readily available to quickly administer all of the blood supplies needed. (Far\r\ntoo often, these are <a href="http://www.cnn.com/2012/04/08/health/cohen-donor-safety/index.html?hpt=hp&#95;c1">located\r\nnearby</a> but never put to proper use in every emergency);</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle">?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;\r\nMajor vital signs are carefully measured\r\nand monitored before, during and after each transfusion;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle">?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;\r\nThere must be a standing procedure for rapidly\r\ntransferring blood products to and from each surgical suite so that a patient&#8217;s\r\nfunctioning can be normalized as quickly as possible; and</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle">?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;\r\nCareful, ongoing monitoring of patient\r\nhypothermia, electrolytes and blood coagulation properties must be provided.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpLast">&#160;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">The\r\n<a href="http://www.injury-attorneys.com/">Demas Law Group</a>\r\nhas been providing the highest quality of legal services to Californians for\r\nnearly twenty years. We take great pride in meeting our clients&#8217; needs while\r\nworking together to win your case and obtain the maximum compensation allowed\r\nby law. We are here to help you during this difficult time. Call our team of\r\nSacramento personal injury lawyers at  <a href="https://mail.google.com/mail/?hl=en&shva=1#search/sylvia/13636a11bff5bd3d">888\r\n776 0977</a> to speak with an attorney. To learn more about why\r\nyou should hire us <a href="http://www.injury-attorneys.com/top-reasons-to-hire-demas-law-group.html">click\r\nhere</a>.</p>'
