aS'<p>\r\n\r\nBy Kelly J. Shook - Associate<br />Schwartz &amp; Eichelbaum Wardell Mehl and Hansen, P.C.<br />800.488.9045 | <a href="http://www.edlaw.com/">www.edlaw.com</a> | <a href="mailto:information@edlaw.com">information@edlaw.com</a> </p><p>\r\n\r\n</p><p class=" " line-height: normal;">As\r\nthe 2011-2012 school year grows closer, budget and tax rate adoption are likely\r\non the forefront of administrators&#8217; minds. Below are a few tips and reminders\r\nas your district proceeds through the budget and tax rate adoption process:</p><p>\r\n\r\n<b>Budget</b></p><p>\r\n\r\nThe\r\ndistrict&#8217;s superintendent prepares and recommends a budget to the board of\r\ntrustees. &#160;The board of trustees then\r\nadopts the final budget. For most districts, the budget must be adopted by\r\nAugust 31.&#160; When proceeding through the\r\nbudget adoption process, please remember:</p><p>\r\n\r\n?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Post the\r\nSummary of the Proposed Budget on the district&#8217;s website or in the\r\nadministrative offices at the same time the notice of budget hearing is\r\npublished.</p><p>\r\n\r\n?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The notice\r\nof the budget hearing must show per student and aggregate spending on\r\ninstruction, instructional support, central administration, district\r\noperations, debt service and any other category designated by the commissioner,\r\nas well as a comparison to last year&#8217;s spending in those categories.</p><p>\r\n\r\n?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The notice\r\nof budget hearing must be published at least 10 calendar days before the\r\nhearing.&#160; Check your local newspaper\r\npublication dates and timelines to ensure that you submit the notice to the\r\npaper on time.</p><p>\r\n\r\n?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The district\r\ncan adopt the tax rate at the same board meeting as the budget.&#160; Only one hearing is required, at which\r\ncitizens may speak to either the budget or the tax rate or both.&#160;&#160; </p><p>\r\n\r\n?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Once a final\r\nbudget is adopted, post the budget on the district&#8217;s website.</p><p>\r\n\r\n?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Remember\r\nthat budgets may be adjusted at any time, as many times as needed, through the\r\nbudget amendment process.</p><p>\r\n\r\n&#160;</p><p class=" " line-height: normal;"><b>Tax Rate </b></p><p>\r\n\r\nDistricts\r\nmust also adopt their tax rate by the later of September 29 or 60 days after\r\nreceiving the certified appraisal roll.&#160;\r\nOnce districts receive the certified appraisal roll (which should have\r\nbeen sent out July 25), districts may no longer rely on certified estimated\r\nvalues for setting the tax rate and will not be able to use the early tax rate\r\nelection process.&#160; At this point in the\r\ngame (in August), if your school district has not yet taken action toward\r\nadopting a tax rate but is considering adopting a tax rate that is higher than\r\nthe rollback rate, it will need to hold a tax rate election on the November 8,\r\n2011, uniform election date by ordering your election no later than September\r\n7, 2011.&#160; TREs could be a whole separate\r\nTexas ISD article, so we won&#8217;t go into more detail than that.&#160; Be sure to contact your attorney if you plan\r\non conducting a TRE to be sure that all timelines and procedures are followed.&#160; Regardless of whether your district plans on\r\nholding a TRE, when adopting the tax rate, remember the following:</p><p>\r\n\r\n?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The total\r\namount of property taxes imposed cannot exceed the preceding year&#8217;s tax rate\r\nunless the school district gives notice of intent to consider an increase and\r\nconducts a public hearing. </p><p>\r\n\r\n?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The tax rate\r\nmust be adopted via an order or ordinance, and specific motion language must be\r\nused to set a tax rate that exceeds the effective tax rate.</p><p>\r\n\r\n?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; You still must\r\npost your 72 hour meeting notice in addition to the 10 day notice of tax rate/budget\r\nhearing.&#160; School districts do not have to\r\nadopt the budget and tax rate at the same meeting, but remember to publish separate\r\nnotice if you will adopt your tax rate at a later date than your budget\r\nadoption.</p><p>\r\n\r\n?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; If your\r\nschool district is subject to the equalized wealth notice, you must wait to\r\nadopt a tax rate until after the commissioner certifies your wealth\r\nequalization.</p><p>\r\n\r\n?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Unlike the\r\nbudget, tax rates are set once adopted, and cannot be amended.</p><p>\r\n\r\n&#160;</p><p class=" " line-height: normal;">The\r\ninformation in this article serves only as a preliminary starting point\r\nregarding the budget and tax rate adoption process.&#160; Please consult with your school attorney if\r\nyou have any specific questions regarding these issues.</p><p>\r\n\r\n</p>'
