aS'<p>Commercial drivers who spend long hours on endless highways increase accident risk due to drowsiness, slower reaction time, impaired judgment and lack of focused attention, according to the <a href="http://www.fmcsa.dot.gov/" target="&#95;blank">Federal Motor Carrier Safety Administration</a> (FMCSA).&#160; </p><p>To combat driver fatigue and prevent trucking accidents, on January 4, 2004, FMCSA established revised Hours-of-Service regulations that limit the amount of time commercial truck drivers are allowed to drive.&#160; </p><ul type="disc"><li>Drivers may drive up to 11 hours, but are limited to 14 hours on duty in a given period. The 14-hour duty period may not be extended with off duty time for meal and fuel stops.&#160; Only the use of a sleeper berth can extend the 14-hour on duty period. </li><li>Drivers may split on duty time using two-hour periods of rest in the berth, as long as certain conditions are met and neither rest period is less than two hours. </li><li>Drivers are limited to a maximum of 60 hours on duty in seven consecutive days, or 70 hours on duty in eight consecutive days.&#160; Drivers can restart the seven or eight-day period by taking at least 34 consecutive hours off duty.&#160; </li></ul><p>To assure compliance with the regulations, FMCSA also mandates that commercial drivers keep detailed logbooks of on and off-duty time, sleeper berth time, and hours of driving. A driver&#8217;s logbook must be updated daily&#8212;every time the driver starts or stops driving. Drivers can be fined if their logbooks are not current or completed properly.</p><p>In a trucking accident lawsuit in Missouri, log books are one way to verify the time a driver spent on the road. In the hands of a skilled <a href="http://www.gatewayinjurylaw.com/attorneys/" target="&#95;blank">trucking accident lawyer in Saint Louis</a>, logs that show a violation of the maximum number of driving hours or the minimum number of sleeping hours can be used to prove negligent behavior. Evidence of negligence in a lawsuit can help your attorney build a case for compensation for your medical expenses, time off from work, and pain and suffering. </p><p>If you have been injured in a St Louis trucking accident, you may want to pursue a trucking accident settlement. The qualified <a href="http://www.gatewayinjurylaw.com/" target="&#95;blank">Saint Louis personal injury attorneys</a> at McChesney &amp; Ortwerth can help you obtain all you are entitled to. Call 888-453-0149 toll-free to reach a skilled attorney at McChesney &amp; Ortwerth.</p><!--more-->In a trucking accident lawsuit in Missouri, log books are one way to verify the time a driver spent on the road. In the hands of a skilled trucking accident lawyer in Saint Louis, logs that show a violation of the maximum number of driving hours or the minimum number of sleeping hours can be used to prove negligent behavior. Evidence of negligence in a lawsuit can help your attorney build a case for compensation for your medical expenses, time off from work, and pain and suffering.'
