aS"<p>Studies have shown that Americais not producing enough American graduates from the fields of\r\nScience, Technology, Engineering and Math. They are supposed to fill the increasing and fast demand for highly technical jobs in the mentioned expertise. Furthermore, according to the National Science Foundation, there are not that many Americans who are enrolling in these STEM degrees. It is feared that there would be a demand for 800,000 workers with STEM degrees but only 550,000 Americans will have the qualifications to meet such demand come 2018.</p>\r\n<p>The United States&#8217; immigration policies, on the other hand, make it hard to formulate and make use of aggressive strategies that could tap immigrant employees and entrepreneurs. They could have covered the deficit as well as further development and innovation within the STEM fields.</p>\r\n<p>US Senators, in a rare political team up from both the Republican and Democratic parties, are working together to solve both problems &#8211; through another immigration law reform. They are pushing to pass the Startup Act 2.0 into a law. \r\n</p>\r\n<p>The Startup Act 2.0 bill intends to ease the restrictions on immigrants who have advanced STEM degrees or are pursuing these degrees in the United States. According to the Senators who are pushing for Startup Act 2.0, the bill will encourage entrepreneurs and innovators within the numbers of these foreign graduates to stay and start their own businesses in the country. Such will attract and retain foreign talents as entrepreneurs, and pave the way for the creation of more jobs. More jobs would definitely mean a better economy.</p>\r\n<p>Young companies were noted to have created the most number of new jobs during the past years. They account for the average of 3 million net new jobs created between the years 1985 to 2005. It is also interesting that more than 40% of the companies listed in Fortune 500 were built by an immigrant or a child of an immigrant, and 60% of foreign graduate students in the United States back in 2010 were from science and engineering courses. It would indeed be such a waste of talent if the US, because of its\r\nstrict immigration policies, will continue to drive them back to their own countries despite having earned their degrees in the country.</p>\r\n<p>The proposed bill also looks forward to be able to encourage investment in startups and exempt these young companies from capital gains tax and some other forms of tax credit, provided they do meet the required amount as annual revenue. The effects of increased business startups will hopefully give rise to better policies and continued analysis that could foster economic growth.</p>\r\n<p>Startup Act 2.0 could indeed be an immigration breakthrough that will allow America to continue to reel in the highly skilled workers the country needs to compete in the global economy. Senator Moran, a prime mover of this bill, sees it as a way to get America's economic engine roaring once again. However, he does fear that the looming elections politics might get in the way of signing the Startup Act 2.0 bill into law.</p>"
