aS'<p>Federal Disability Retirement benefits exist for Federal and Postal employees, whether under FERS or CSRS, for two primary purposes: &#160;(A) &#160;to allow a Federal or <a title="Visit also the  USPS Disability Retirement forum" href="http://uspsdisabilityretirement.com/" target="&#95;blank">Postal employee</a> who has a medical condition which prevents him or her from performing all of the essential elements of his or her job, to receive an annuity because of one\'s service to the Federal Sector, based upon <a title="The minimum criteria and more" href="http://www.myfederalretirement.com/public/380.cfm?sd=129" target="&#95;blank">minimum qualification criteria</a> (18 months of Federal Service under FERS; 5 years under CSRS) and (B) to encourage that Federal or Postal employee to continue to contribute in the private sector, but working at some other job, and begin a &quot;second&quot; career, if possible. &#160;It is not an entitlement; it is a benefit which is progressive in the sense that it recognizes a compassionate need to compensate in return for the many years that the Federal or <a title="Disability Retirement  information at the PostalReporter.com" href="http://www.postalreporter.com/editorials/articles/mcgill.htm" target="&#95;blank" data-mce-href="http://www.postalreporter.com/editorials/articles/mcgill.htm">Postal employee</a> has contributed to the work force, as well as recognizing the intelligent paradigm of encouraging continuing contribution in a different career path. &#160;Most Federal and Postal employees do not &quot;want&quot; to file for, or become eligible to receive, <a title="The home page of Robert R.  McGill" href="http://federaldisabilitylawyer.com/" target="&#95;blank">Federal Disability Retirement benefits</a> under FERS or CSRS. &#160;It is not a &quot;choice&quot;. &#160;Rather, most Federal and Postal employees, after many, many years of service, have come to a point of recognition in both the extent, severity and chronici