aS'<br /><p>Individuals undergo surgical procedures for a variety of reasons&#8212;ranging from elective cosmetic surgery to change appearance to emergency surgery to save a life. The ability to successfully file a medical malpractice suit depends on the standard of care patients receive, regardless of outcome.</p><p>In a helpful list of frequently asked questions pertaining to medical malpractice law, <a href="http://medical-malpractice.lawyers.com/Medical-Malpractice-FAQs.html#20">Lawyers.com</a> explains that state law generally defines medical negligence and that the medical community typically defines the standard of care used to measure negligence. While the dissatisfaction of surgical patients may justify malpractice claims, the real issue involves the quality of treatment they receive.</p><p><b>The reasons for dissatisfaction represent key factors for a claim</b></p><p /><p>Dissatisfaction with the outcome of a surgery does not automatically provide grounds for malpractice lawsuits. Consider the following examples:</p><ul><li>A patient undergoes rhinoplasty to reduce the size of his nose. After healing from the successful surgical procedure, he does not like his appearance.</li><li>Another patient undergoes the same procedure, but emerges with a three-inch scar running down the side of his face, which remains even after the completion of healing.</li></ul><p>Clearly, the first surgeon operated within the typical standard of care, but the second procedure may merit additional investigation. If the patient can prove that errors occurred creating scars nowhere near the nose&#8212;such as slip of the scalpel&#8212;he may have grounds for a successful medical malpractice suit.</p><p><b>An experienced malpractice attorney can help assess your case</b></p><p>Identifying a breach of the standard of care requires the help of an attorney with extensive experience with local medical malpractice laws who can assess the potential merits of a case. The <a href="http://www.rbrlawfirm.com/aop/oklahoma-medical-malpractice/medical-malpractice/">Oklahoma medical malpractice attorneys</a> at the law firm of Ryan Bisher Ryan Phillips &amp; Simons have extensive experience protecting the rights of medical malpractice victims throughout Oklahoma&#8212;often relying on assistance from a network of out-of-state physicians to obtain evidence needed to develop an effective case. Call us at 405-528-4567 to arrange a no-cost consultation and learn how we can help.</p><p>Ryan Bisher Ryan Phillips &amp; Simons<br />323 NW 63rd St.<br />Suite 110, Oklahoma City, OK 73116<br />Phone: 405-528-4567</p><!--more-->The ability to successfully file a medical malpractice suit depends on the standard of care patients receive, regardless of outcome. Here is a helpful list of frequently asked questions pertaining to medical malpractice law.'
