aS'How will filing for bankruptcy effect my divorce litigation?<p>If you are considering filing for <strong><em>bankruptcy</em></strong>, the first thing you want to do is consult with a <em><strong>bankruptcy</strong></em> attorney. He or she will advise you if filing is even an option for you. If it is and you are in the process of a <em><strong>divorce</strong></em> or thinking of filing for <strong><em>divorce</em></strong>, you absolutely want to discuss this issue with your <em><strong>matrimonial attorney</strong></em>.  If you are in the process of a <em><strong>divorce</strong></em> (i.e. you or your spouse has filed a Complaint for Divorce), filing for bankruptcy will definitely have an effect on your litigation.  Specifically, it will cause a stay to be issued in your matrimonial litigation.  This means that <em><strong>divorce case</strong></em> will not be able to proceed forward until the stay is lifted or your debts (or your spouses&#8217; debts if he/she is the one who has filed) have been discharged.  However, there are certain exceptions to this rule which are set forth under the Bankruptcy Code.  For instance, if your spouse has filed for bankruptcy in the middle of your <strong><em>divorce litigation</em></strong> and then he/she stops paying support, you can still file in the Family Court to enforce any support award that was previously entered.  The Family Court cannot however modify that award if a stay is in place.  You and/or your bankruptcy attorney can also ask the Bankruptcy Court to lift the stay if necessary.  Please refer to the Bankruptcy Code for more exceptions.  Accordingly, if you are very close to resolving your divorce litigation, you may want to wait to file for bankruptcy, if possible, so that your filing will not interrupt the divorce process.    </p>What if my spouse files for bankruptcy AFTER our divorce? <p>The majority of individuals getting divorced enter into a contract called a Property Settlement Agreement (&#8220;PSA&#8221;), which is then incorporated into their <em><strong>Final Judgment of Divorce</strong></em>.  The PSA should always set forth which party is responsible to pay which debt.  For instance, if the parties are $20,000.00 in credit card debt, it is likely that one party will agree to pay off $10,000.00 of the debt and the other party will do the same.  However, what happens if this credit card debt is in joint names and one spouse files for bankruptcy after the PSA is entered into?  The answer is that the debt which the other spouse was responsible to pay, will now become your debt!  So, what do you do then? </p><p>There are a few things you could do if you find yourself in this position, it all depends on the terms of your PSA.  For instance, if you  are paying support to your spouse and then he/she files for bankruptcy and leaves you with $10,000.00 of additional debt that he/she was supposed to pay, you can ask the Family Court to reduce or terminate your support obligation (depending on the duration and amount of alimony you are required to pay under the terms of your PSA) in order to make up for the additional debt you are now required to pay.  If you are not the supporting spouse but, your ex-spouse owns certain property, you can ask the Family Court to enter a Judgment against your ex-spouse, in the amount of $10,000.00, and you can place a lien against an asset owned by your ex-spouse.  Thus,  when he/she attempts to sell that asset, you can get paid from the sale of same and/or he/she will have to pay you for the amount owed before the asset can be sold.</p><p>&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8211;</p><p><em>Sarah Martine has been an associate at the family law firm of Adinolfi &amp; Lieberman since 2005.  Her practice is focused primarily on family law issues including <a title="Divorce & Separation" href="http://www.sjfamilylawyers.com/aop/new-jersey-divorce-separation/">divorce</a>, alimony, child custody and child support.  She has been chosen as a <strong><a href="http://www.superlawyers.com/new-jersey/lawyer/Sarah-N-Martine/9772a157-55db-40c5-bfd2-39df1255a508.html">SuperLawyers Rising Star</a> </strong>every year since 2008.&#160; For more information, please contact <a href="http://www.SJFamilyLawyers.com">www.SJFamilyLawyers.com</a></em></p><!--more-->Couples contemplating bankruptcy as part of a divorce action need to be educated about not only bankruptcy law, but how it can impact their ongoing divorce litigation.'
