aS'<p class="MsoNormal">If you are considering filing a lawsuit against a California Corporation, you may choose to file as part of a class action.&#160;&#160;A class action lawsuit is essentially when a group of people &#8211; called Plaintiffs in legal terms &#8211; file a lawsuit together against a Defendant.&#160;Defendant can be a person or corporation.&#160;A class action lawsuit can potentially be filed in state or federal court.&#160; The rules and requirements for when a lawsuit can be filed in federal court are always the same but the rules and requirements for when a lawsuit can be filed in state court may differ from one state to the next.&#160;California, for instance, does not follow the federal rules for determining when a case can be certified as a class action lawsuit according to California attorney Emery Ledger of Ledger &amp;amp; Associates.&#160;</p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">Under California law, there are essentially two different statutes that could apply for a class action lawsuit against a California Corporation.&#160; The more general statute is found under California Code of Civil Procedure Section 378 and reads as follows:</p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">(a)All persons may join in one action as plaintiffs if:</p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">(1)They assert any right to relief jointly, severally, or in the alternative, in respect of or arising out of the same transaction, occurrence, or series of transactions or occurrences and if any question of law or fact common to all these persons will arise in the action; or</p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">(2)They have a claim, right, or interest adverse to the defendant in the property or controversy which is the subject of the action.</p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">(b)It is not necessary that each plaintiff be interested as to every cause of action or as to all relief prayed for. Judgment may be given for one or more of the plaintiffs according to their respective right to relief.</p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">The second statute that may apply to a class action lawsuit against a California Corporation is found under California Civil Code Section 1750 and is commonly known as the &#8220;Consumers Legal Remedies Act (CLRA)&#8221;.&#160; Under the CLRA, consumers may file suit against a company for unfair methods of competition or unfair or deceptive acts or practices.&#160; The point of the statute is to protect consumers from businesses or companies that attempt to mislead or deceive consumers in business negotiations or practices.&#160; Under both statutes, the Plaintiffs may recover actual as well as punitive damages; however under the general statute the Plaintiffs must show that the Defendant acted with malice. Under the CLRA, however, the malice requirement is not necessary.&#160; Additionally, under the CLRA, Plaintiff&#8217;s may also obtain an order enjoining the methods, acts, or practices; restitution of property; court costs and attorney\'s fees; and any other relief that the court deems proper.&#160; This is a particularly attractive option if your goal is to get the business to stop conducting its business.&#160; </p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">Which section of the code to file under is a decision that should be discussed in more detail with an experienced California attorney.&#160; Many factors go into decisions regarding whether to file as an individual or a class and where to file your lawsuit and they should be made with the help of a qualified legal professional.&#160; If you would like to discuss your situation with regard to A California Corporation with California attorney Emery Ledger, please feel free to contact him at his firm, Ledger &amp; Associates, at 1-800-300-0001 or online at <a href="http://www.ledgerlaw.com/">www.ledgerlaw.com</a>.</p><!--more-->If you are considering filing a lawsuit against a California Corporation, you may choose to file as part of a class action.&#160;&#160;A class action lawsuit is essentially when a group of people &#8211; called Plaintiffs in legal terms &#8211; file a lawsuit together against a Defendant. Seek the advice of a personal injury attorney.'
