aS'<p>Road accidents involving commercial &quot;big rig&quot; trucks can be much more complicated than typical auto accidents.</p><p>Trucks are far more complex vehicles than cars, so there can be more possible causes of an accident.&#160; And when a commercial truck causes an accident, there may be several possible defendants&#8212;the truck driver, trucking company, truck owner/lessor, cargo shipper, maintenance company, and more.</p><p>To bring a successful claim for damages for injuries suffered in an accident caused by a commercial big rig truck in Georgia, you will have to prove both what happened in the accident and who is legally responsible for those events occurring.</p><p>To do that, you\'ll need the help of an 18-wheeler accident attorney. But you can be a big help to your <a href="http://www.georgiatruckaccident.com/" target="&#95;blank">Georgia truck accident attorney</a> by fully recording the events of the accident at the time. How?&#160; Follow these steps:</p><ul><li>Take pictures.&#160; If you have a camera or cell phone that takes pictures, take pictures of everything&#8212;the vehicles, roadway, people, items along the road. You can\'t take too many, and can\'t know what may prove important later. Police who arrive on the scene to write an accident report probably will take pictures too&#8212;if it seems they won\'t, ask that they do.</li><li>Get contact information. If there were witnesses to the accident, get their names and contact information.&#160; Do the same for other people who take pictures or talk to witnesses or participants in the accident.</li><li>Write down all truck license and ID numbers.&#160; A big 18-wheel rig may have components owned by, leased by, or maintained by different parties.&#160; So write down all the license and registration numbers and names you see on the truck, trailer, and any other components.&#160; Your semi truck accident attorney in Georgia will value this.</li><li>Give accurate information to the police.&#160; Don\'t sign or agree to any police report without reading it carefully and being sure it is accurate.</li><li>Don\'t apologize or give any opinions.&#160; While still experiencing shock in the immediate aftermath of an accident, accident victims often instinctually say &quot;I\'m sorry,&quot; even when it was not their fault.&#160; But an admission of fault may seriously compromise your case.&#160; So don\'t admit anything&#8212;in fact, don\'t give any opinions at all about the accident, at the scene or later.&#160; When talking to the police and others, honestly tell the facts but nothing more.</li></ul><p>After leaving the scene of the accident&#8212;</p><p>Get medical attention immediately.&#160; Do so even if you don\'t think you need it&#8212;to protect both your health and any injury claim that may arise from the accident.&#160; Many injuries become apparent only after some time, with delayed effects.&#160; If you don\'t see a doctor immediately to document your condition and then later sue for damages for such delayed-effect injuries, an opposing insurer may argue that your injuries are your own fault due to your failure to get medical care&#8212;or even that they didn\'t result from the accident at all.</p><p>Preserve your vehicle.&#160; It is evidence in your case.&#160; Its condition can help show what happened in the accident.&#160; And it will have to be examined to prove that no mechanical defect in it contributed to the accident.</p><p>Truck accident attorney in Georgia</p><p>After you record the evidence at the scene of the accident, immediately consult with a&#160;<a href="http://www.georgiatruckaccident.com/Atlanta-trucking-accident/" target="&#95;blank">Georgia truck accident lawyer</a>&#160;to preserve the evidence in the trucking company\'s records.</p><p>Federal regulations allow trucking companies to destroy their driver logs and other records after only six months.&#160; These records can be critical evidence when asserting your claim for damages from the accident&#8212;so meet with your lawyer in time to be sure that the trucking company isn\'t throwing out evidence.</p><p>Your Georgia truck accident attorney can ensure that doesn\'t happen while following up on collecting additional vital evidence for you.</p><p>If you or a family member has been injured in a truck accident, contact the Georgia trucking accident lawyers of Henry Spiegel Milling at 866-959-3877 for a free consultation.</p><!--more-->After you record the evidence at the scene of the accident, immediately consult with a&#160;Georgia truck accident lawyer&#160;to preserve the evidence in the trucking company\'s records.'
