aS'<p><strong><em>Premises liability</em></strong></p><p>Restaurants, bars and saloons that sell alcoholic beverages are called dram shops. Under Arizona law, injured parties can hold dram shops liable if an intoxicated dram shop patron harms them as a result of consuming alcohol sold by the facility.</p><p><strong><em>Holding liable parties accountable</em></strong></p><p>When determining liability in a drunken driving case, a <a href="http://www.tucsoninjurylaw.com/negligent-security/" target="&#95;blank">Tucson premises liability lawyer</a>&#160;may find that an Arizona bar served the driver when it was apparent the driver was already intoxicated.</p><p><a href="http://www.azleg.state.az.us/ars/4/00311.htm" target="&#95;blank">Arizona Revised Statute &#167; 4-311(D)</a> is Arizona\'s dram shop law, and it holds a licensed restaurant or bar liable for serving intoxicated individuals or minors under these conditions:</p><ul><li>The establishment sold liquor to an individual who was obviously intoxicated</li><li>The individual consumed the alcohol purchased</li><li>The alcohol consumption was the proximate cause of injury or property damage</li></ul><p>Under this law, &#8220;intoxicated&#8221; means that the person was inebriated to the point where impairment was obvious because of uncoordinated physical action or significant physical dysfunction.</p><p>Proximate cause in this case indicates a direct relationship between the resulting injury and the fact of intoxication. There is no other intervening cause that resulted in injury except for the dram shop&#8217;s liquor sale and resulting intoxication. For example, suppose the intoxicated patron had time to sleep off the drunken stupor, drive home safely and drink more alcohol at home. Then, after drinking at home, the individual drove again and caused an accident. The dram shop&#8217;s counsel could argue that the alcohol consumed at the restaurant was not the proximate cause of the driving accident.</p><p><strong><em>For an experienced premises liability lawyer</em></strong></p><p><a href="http://www.tucsoninjurylaw.com/" target="&#95;blank">The Law Office of William D. Nelson, P.C.</a> has over 25 years of experience representing clients in injury cases. If you suffer injury on someone else&#8217;s property or are the victim of a drunk driving accident based on dram shop liability, find out how we can help.</p><p /><p><strong>Law Office of William D. Nelson, P.C.<br />4400 E. Broadway Boulevard<br />Suite 801</strong></p><!--more-->Under Arizona law, injured parties can hold restaurants and bars (dram shops) liable if an intoxicated dram shop patron harms them as a result of consuming alcohol sold by the facility. Arizona\'s dram shop law holds the licensed restaurant or bar liable for serving intoxicated individuals or minors who subsequently harm others because of their drunken condition.'
