aS'<p>New Jersey Senator Mike Doherty and Assemblywoman Valerie Vainieri Huttle are calling for a complete dismantling of the state&#8217;s red-light camera enforcement operation, which is currently suspended. The lawmakers claim these devices are an invasion of privacy and have done little to make New Jersey intersections safer. State officials suspended the red-light program, which photographs intersections to catch drivers disobeying traffic signals, when the Department of Transportation discovered that 63 of the program&#8217;s 85 cameras weren&#8217;t timed correctly with light cycles, according to NJ.com.</p> \r\n<p>These cameras have resulted in millions of dollars in fines for drivers in New Jersey, and they weren&#8217;t working properly. <a href="http://www.consoleandhollawell.com/pages/hamilton-township-car-accident-attorneys/">Car accident attorneys in Hamilton Township</a> and rest of the state are confident that officials probably won&#8217;t issue blanket refunds to all affected drivers. They&#8217;ve already spent that money.</p>\r\n<p>Currently, the state is not issuing tickets at 63 of the red-light camera locations. That could change when the Department of Transportation verifies the devices actually take pictures when the lights turn red, and not green or yellow.</p>\r\n<p>Intersections are common sites for car accidents. Measures designed to reduce the occurrences of people disobeying traffic signals are, on the surface, very good things. However, these measures go a step too far when they infringe on the rights of those who are obeying the law.</p>\r\n<p>Would it surprise people to know that the state may or may not have digital images of every driver stopped at all of New Jersey&#8217;s malfunctioning red-light cameras? Glossing over the potential for thousands of people to receive erroneous traffic tickets, the issue of privacy seems to take the front seat. Does the state have the right or legal authority to photograph anyone sitting in their cars? </p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.consoleandhollawell.com/pages/toms-river-car-accident-lawyers/">Car accident attorneys in Toms River</a> and other parts of the state understand the importance of measures to increase traffic safety, and don&#8217;t diminish their importance. What the state has to balance is the rights of citizens against unreasonable searches by their government with the benefits these red-light cameras offer in terms of reduce accident risks. We&#8217;re all looking forward to the Department of Transportation&#8217;s analysis.</p> &#160;<!--more-->The suspension of New Jersey\'s red-light camera program raises a number of questions about privacy rights versus the need to increase safety on state roadways. Two New Jersey lawmakers are calling for the program\'s ouster. What do you think?'
