aS'<p>If you are involved in a motor vehicle accident, make sure you follow these important first steps.</p><p><b>Step 1</b>: Call the accident in to 9-1-1.</p><p>Your first responsibility is to contact 9-1-1 and report the accident. First responders will be sent, including the police and emergency medical personnel. If neither you nor anyone else involved in the accident has a cell phone or other means of calling for assistance, flag down a passing vehicle and request that they contact help on your behalf. Never, ever leave the scene of an accident before the police arrive, even if the other car involved does or the other driver tells you it is okay. Only when the police officers at the scene tell you that it is okay to leave or medical personnel inform you that it is vital you be transported to the ER immediately should you comply.</p><p><b>Step 2</b>: Cooperate with all first responders.</p><p>Cooperate with the police by providing all requested facts regarding your accident. Don&#8217;t move your car from the position in which it was left after the accident unless the police direct you to do so, even if it is blocking traffic. You should inform anyone else involved in the accident not to move their vehicles either, and inform the police if they did so anyway. </p><p>Allow medical personnel to examine you and answer their questions regarding how you feel as clearly and honestly as possible. If the EMTs want to take you by ambulance to the hospital, let them.</p><p><b>Step 3</b>: Collect information from all parties.</p><p>If you are able to speak to the other people involved in your accident, including witnesses, make sure you get the following information and note it down, if possible:</p><p>*Name of the other driver or witness<br />*Phone numbers, addresses, and any other contact information for the other driver or witness<br />*Other driver&#8217;s insurance policy number, policy provider name, and contact information<br />*Other driver&#8217;s vehicle license plate and registration numbers and driver&#8217;s license number</p><p>Once the police arrive, you&#8217;ll want to make sure to collect their business cards as well, so you can contact them later to request a copy of your accident report.</p><p><b>Step 4</b>: Take photos of the scene or write down description.</p><p>If you have a camera or camera phone handy, the best thing you can do is snap photos of the accident scene. Make sure you include things like skid marks on the road, vehicle damage to your car and any others involved, and anything relevant like road conditions (patches of ice, giant pothole, faulty traffic light, etc.). In lieu of photos, scribble down notes as soon as you can, so that important details aren&#8217;t forgotten.</p><p>Article presented courtesy of The Law Offices of Larry H. Parker, <a href="http://www.larryhparkerriverside.com/">Riverside CA automobile accident attorneys</a>, 800-333-0000, <a href="http://www.larryhparkerriverside.com/">www.larryhparkerriverside.com</a>.</p><p>We also help people across <a href="http://www.larryhparker.com/" target="&#95;blank">California</a> and <a href="http://www.larryhparkerphoenix.com/" target="&#95;blank">Arizona</a> with offices in <a href="http://www.larryhparker.com/our-offices/long-beach-ca/" target="&#95;blank">Long Beach</a>, <a href="http://www.larryhparker.com/" target="&#95;blank">Los Angeles</a>, <a href="http://www.larryhparkerbakersfield.com/" target="&#95;blank">Bakersfield</a>, <a href="http://www.larryhparkerfresno.com/" target="&#95;blank">Fresno</a>, <a href="http://www.larryhparkerphoenix.com/" target="&#95;blank">Phoenix</a>, and <a href="http://www.larryhparker.com/our-offices/tucson-az/" target="&#95;blank">Tucson</a>. </p><!--more--><p>First steps to take when involved in an accident&#160;courtesy of&#160;our&#160; <a href="http://www.larryhparkerriverside.com/">Riverside CA automobile accident attorneys</a>...</p>'
