aS'<div class="post hentry uncustomized-post-template">\r\n<a name="6996295145493676068"></a><div class="post-body entry-content">October 2, 2009 (by Horatio Algren) According to reports by drunk driving lawyers in Los Angeles,\r\na North Tustin was sentenced 15 years to life after deadly accident.\r\nThe teen identified as Milad Moulayi now age 18 was sentenced to the\r\nmaximum amount of time in jail allowed by law, by Superior Court Judge\r\nCarla Singer for an accident that occurred August 28, 2008.<br /> <br />The\r\nsentenced stems from a single car crash that took the life of another\r\nteen after Moulayi had allegedly drank several shots of rum and was\r\ndriving at an estimated 100 miles per hour according to prosecutors. <br /><br />The\r\npassenger in the high speed crash that was killed was a student at the\r\nFoothill High School, along with Moulayi and identified as Mackenzie\r\nFrazee. In court Moulayi apologized to the Frazee family and asked for\r\nforgiveness.<br /> <br />The accident according to witness testimony and\r\nexpert testimony painted Moulayi as being stumbling drunk from at least\r\n10 shots of Sailor Jerry Rum and told by friends not to drive. It was\r\ntestified that at least three other teens turned down his offer for\r\nrides home. Frazee accepted the ride in order to return home, since she\r\nhad not asked permission. Experts testified that the Mercedes was\r\ntraveling at approximately 100 miles per hour when the teen lost\r\ncontrol and <a href="http://criminalrights.blogspot.com/2009/10/santa-ana-teen-sentenced-15-years-to.html">slammed into a concrete light pole</a>. <br /><br />Moulayi\r\nwas treated for minor cuts and bruises and Frazee who was wearing a\r\nseatbelt at the time of the crash was pronounced dead from blunt force\r\ntrauma. Moulayi had a blood alcohol level of 0.11 shortly after the <a href="http://www.ehlinelaw.com/">crash</a>.\r\n</div></div><!--more-->According to reports by drunk driving lawyers in Los Angeles,\r\na North Tustin was sentenced 15 years to life after deadly accident. Authorities are getting harder and harder on teen DUI offenders. &#160;'
