aS'<br /><p><b>Dealing with divorce in Texas</b></p><p>Nobody wins a divorce. Money and children change hands, and emotions are bent, broken, and assuaged. </p><p>Dealing with divorce is hard, unpleasant work. You once loved the person you are now divorcing. That relationship never ends&#8212;it only changes, regardless of the presence of children. </p><p>Just as you had a choice to marry, you have a choice about how to deal with divorce. Hurt, anger, and fear are understandable, but they can also make the divorce process difficult. Even with the help of good divorce attorneys, your behavior&#8212;and that of your partner&#8212;largely determine the success of your divorce. Even if considering divorce, it is not too late to try <a href="http://www.mayoclinic.com/health/marriage-counseling/MY00839/METHOD=print" target="&#95;blank">counseling</a> to discuss issues or to seek an amicable separation. </p><p><b>Doing divorce right</b></p><p>If you decide to divorce, take steps to keep yourself, your children, and your spouse out of a contentious divorce battle. Consider the following tips:</p><ul><li><b>Seek legal counsel</b>: Speaking with skilled divorce attorneys before separating from your spouse can help you structure future divorce discussions with your spouse. Demands for divorce made during a heated argument serve to polarize the situation before you or your partner understand the emotional and legal roadmap of divorce.</li><li><b>Speak with your spouse</b>: Talk to your spouse about separating&#8212;preferably in person, not by phone or email. If the divorce is your idea, give your partner time and space to consider his or her feelings. Do not use legal information as a threat to coerce agreements from your partner.</li><li><b>Decide how to proceed</b>: Work with your spouse to keep the level of conflict and financial expense low&#8212;consider working out custody, financial, and property arrangements through mediation or the collaborative divorce process. If you can agree with your spouse on the issues, retain an experienced divorce attorney to review and prepare your Settlement Agreement and other necessary court documents.</li><li><b>Children and divorce</b>: If you have children, keep quarreling to a minimum and work with your spouse to emotionally and financially support your children through the process.</li></ul><p><b>Contact us</b></p><p>Despite best efforts, divorce is difficult. It is not a game, and though it may end up feeling like battle, it cannot be won. To help craft a successful divorce and build a better future for you and your family, retain the experienced and capable <a href="http://www.thetxattorneys.com/">Fort Worth divorce attorneys</a> of Sisemore, Childress &amp; Associates, PLLC, 603 East Belknap Street, Fort Worth, TX 76102. </p><!--more-->You have a choice about how to deal with divorce. Your behavior&#8212;and that of your partner&#8212;largely determine the success of your divorce.'
