aS'<p>Florida\r\nRule of Procedure 3.190 Pretrial Motions, Section (c)(4) allows <a href="http://www.denmonlaw.com/st-petersburg-criminal-attorney" title="St Petersburg Criminal Attorney">St Petersburg, Florida Criminal Attorney</a>&#8217;s to file Motions to Dismiss for the follow reasons: (1) The defendant\r\nhas already been pardoned for the crime charged, (2) the defendant has\r\npreviously been charged with the same crime (double jeopardy), (3) the\r\ndefendant has already been granted immunity for the crime charged, or (4) when\r\nthere are no disputed material facts and the disputed material facts do not\r\nestablish a prima facie case of guilt against the defendant.</p><p>Numbers (1)- (3) listed above are\r\nfairly simple and self-explanatory and rarely defenses. Most agencies are\r\ncautious and will not charge a person with a crime to with they have already\r\nbeen charged, pardoned, or granted immunity from. \r\n\r\n</p><p text-indent: 0.5in;" class="MsoNormal">Number (4) listed above is more\r\ncommonly used as a tool by defense attorneys. The rule allows defense\r\nattorney&#8217;s to make an argument on paper that a criminal charge should be\r\ndismissed based on a lack of evidence that a crime occurred. Here&#8217;s an example:</p>Mary gets pulled over for running a\r\nstop sign. Mary is driving and Tom, her friend is a passenger. The car is\r\nregistered to Bill, Mary&#8217;s dad. Bill is not in the vehicle. The officer who\r\nstops Mary asks if he can search the vehicle that she is driving. Mary gives\r\npermission for the search. The Officer located cocaine underneath the passenger\r\nseat concealed in a tin box. The tin box was also completely concealed under\r\nthe seat. Both Mary and Tom tell the officer that they had no idea that the\r\ncocaine was in the vehicle and it does not belong to them. The Officer charges\r\nMary with Possession of Cocaine and the State Attorney&#8217;s Office proceeds with\r\nprosecution for the alleged crime.<p></p><p></p>Florida\r\nlaw requires that the a charging agency such as the State attorney&#8217;s Office\r\nprove &#8220;knowledge&#8221; of the drugs in order to prove a possession charge such as\r\nMary&#8217;s Possession of Cocaine charge. A C-4 motion allows the defense attorney\r\nto list the undisputed facts surrounding Mary&#8217;s charge: The car was registered\r\nto someone else, the cocaine was concealed and Mary says she did not know about\r\nthe cocaine. The State Attorney&#8217;s office would likely not be able to dispute\r\nthese facts and a judge would likely grant the Motion to dismiss because there\r\nare no disputed facts and the state cannot establish a prima facie case of\r\nguilt against Mary because they cannot prove that she knew about the drugs.&#160; &#160;&#160;\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; If the\r\nState Attorney&#8217;s Office does dispute the facts, they can file a traverse or\r\ndemurrer indicating there are disputed facts and a judge will determine if the\r\nC-4 Motion should or should not prevail. </p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; By\r\nusing a C-4 motion, a defense attorney can attempt to achieve a dismissal of a\r\ncase in lieu of further litigation. Mary&#8217;s circumstances as well as numerous\r\nothers can warrant the filing of a C-4 Motion to dismiss. If you think the\r\nfacts of your case warrant a C-4 motion, you should contact an experienced\r\ndefense attorney immediately. </p>\r\n\r\n<!--more-->By\r\nusing a C-4 motion, a defense attorney can attempt to achieve a dismissal of a\r\ncase in lieu of further litigation. Mary&#8217;s circumstances as well as numerous\r\nothers can warrant the filing of a C-4 Motion to dismiss. If you think the\r\nfacts of your case warrant a C-4 motion, you should contact an experienced\r\ndefense attorney immediately.'
