aS'<p>When sharing North Georgia&#8217;s road with trucks&#8212;whether dump trucks hauling dirt across town or big rigs, transporting cargo across the country,&#160; auto drivers need to be alert and cautious.</p><p>Operators of heavy trucks require more time to reach a full stop than passenger cars. If a car&#8212;which weighs an average of 5,000 pounds&#8212;is traveling 55 miles per hour, it can reach a full stop within 130 to 140 feet. Contrast trucks, a big rig&#8212;which can legally weigh up to 80,000 pounds in the United States without an overweight or oversize permit&#8212;will require about 400 feet before it can come to a full stop. Clearly, a multi-ton tractor trailer truck cannot go from highway speeds to zero in a split second. </p><p>A second factor that plays a role in stopping and slowing a large tractor/trailer is the amount of time it takes the operator to respond. To reach an appropriate speed, a trucker might have to switch through ten gears as well as apply the breaks. Beyond gear switching and breaking, another delay to stopping is the driver&#8217;s perception and reaction time. Depending on the individual driver, it will likely take at least three-quarters of a second before processing the fact that he or she needs to reduce speed. A trucker, therefore, might cover over 100 feet before recognizing that it&#8217;s time to hit the brakes.&#160; </p><p>If traveling conditions are dangerous&#8212;such as from slick roads or weather conditions that impede visibility&#8212;the lead time between initiating a stop to stopping can double. Under ideal circumstances, for instance, it takes a car traveling 55 miles per hour about 4.6 seconds to stop. If it&#8217;s snowy, the time needed to stop increases to over ten seconds. The average 18-wheeler is also between 70 and 80 feet long, so jackknifing&#8212;a situation in which the tires lose traction so that the cab and the trailer, no longer in accord, form a V or L shape&#8212;is also a possibility when a driver swerves or breaks suddenly to avoid a collision.</p><p>Keeping in mind that a big rig will need 400 feet to stop under ideal conditions, safety advocates strongly recommend applying the three-second rule to determine the minimal distance a driver should maintain between his or her vehicle and the one ahead. By waiting three seconds from the time the rear of the vehicle in front of you passes a certain point before your front bumper reaches that same marker, you will have a 243-foot safety zone between you and the other vehicle if you are traveling at 55 miles per hour. If you use a six-second benchmark, you&#8217;ll place 486 feet between you and the other vehicle.&#160; A truck operator, therefore, should use the higher benchmark favoring safety and protection of life and property.</p><p>Clearly, the faster the flow of traffic, the greater the distance must be between cars and trucks in order to maintain a reasonably safe distance. Around Metropolitan Atlanta, where speeds are relatively high and highways are busy, cautious drivers will find it nearly impossible to stay a comfortable distance away from trucks that accompany them on the road.&#160; Consequently, accidents that result from following too closely [rear-enders] regularly occur.</p><p>If you or someone you know has been seriously harmed as a result of a trucking accident on Georgia&#8217;s congested roads, we strongly recommend that you seek the advice of a qualified personal injury attorney who knows Georgia laws and fully understands the long-term implications of injury caused by trucks. With more than 35 years of experience trying Georgia lawsuits, the <a title="Georgia law firm" href="http://www.robertswindholz.com/">Georgia law firm</a> of Robert&#160; S. Windholz, with North Georgia headquarters in Alpharetta, will carefully review your case and provide solid, trustworthy advice on how to move forward. We have represented victims of personal injury and wrongful death since 1973</p><p>Don&#8217;t allow anyone to pressure you into accepting a settlement or agreeing to representation that raises any reasons for concern. Seek a seasoned professional who will provide options and respect your right to make your own decisions. </p><p>The <a title="personal injury attorneys" href="http://www.robertswindholz.com/attorneys/">personal injury attorneys</a> at the Metro Atlanta law firm of Robert S. Windholz would be happy to speak with you. Simply call us at <strong>678.990.1584</strong> for a free phone consultation regarding your lawsuit</p><!--more-->The personal injury attorneys at the Metro Atlanta law firm of Robert S. Windholz would be happy to speak with you. Simply call us at 678.990.1584 for a free phone consultation regarding your lawsuit'
