aS'<p>Today\'s housing market is rough. The house next door to mine is currently for sale for<br />1/3 the price I paid for my home in 2004. But despite the slump and the fact<br />that my home is extremely underwater, my home is important to me. It is where I<br />raise my young son and teenage nephew. For many individuals today the bad<br />economy combined with the terrible housing market has led them to walk away<br />from their homes. But for many more, their home is something they want to save<br />despite the hardships that saving it will impose. For many of these individuals<br />a Chapter 13 Reorganization is the best way to save their home.</p><p>How Chapter 13 Works:</p><p>A Chapter 13 Bankruptcy is designed to allow you to set up a plan to pay back<br />your debt over the course of three to five years. During this time you will<br />catch up any secured debt you are behind on, pay any priority debt such as<br />taxes and child support, and pay off your unsecured debt at some portion of<br />what you owe based on what you can afford.</p><p>This Chapter 13 Plan is not negotiated with your creditors. Your creditors are not<br />required to vote on or approve the plan and participation is not voluntary. The<br />Chapter 13 Plan is created by you in conjunction with your attorney and is<br />submitted to the court for approval. While your creditors have the right to<br />object to the plan they must do so using a legal argument and cannot disagree<br />merely on principle. Objections by creditors are common and are dealt with<br />either by giving additional information to the creditor, by negotiating some language<br />they would like to see in the plan, or by going before the judge and letting<br />him rule on the objection. The creditor does not have the right to force you to<br />make any changes to the plan.</p><p>Once the plan has been approved by the court, the debtor must continue to make the<br />court approved payments for the length of the plan. If any changes occur, the<br />individual must keep their attorney informed as he may be able to make changes<br />to help the clients plan succeed.</p><p>After all payments under the plan have been received the court will evaluate the case<br />to determine if all elements of the plan have been complied with. If the Debtor<br />has done everything that the court has asked of them then he will receive a<br />discharge of all his unsecured debt and his secured debt will be deemed<br />current.</p><p>Lien Stripping:</p><p>Many individuals fall behind on their mortgage payments for some reason other than<br />the affordability of the first mortgage payment. Some of these individuals<br />cannot afford their credit card debts. For others it may be auto deficiencies.<br />But for a great deal of individuals the reason they fall behind on their first<br />mortgage payment is that they are struggling with a second or third mortgage<br />that is weighing them down. For many of these individuals a lien strip is<br />available to help ease their burdens and save their home. A lien strip, which<br />is only available in a Chapter 13 Bankruptcy, is an adversary proceeding filed within<br />a bankruptcy case which is used to show the court that all of the equity in<br />your home is consumed by the debt owed to the first mortgage company. If you<br />can prove that no equity remains for the second, third or fourth mortgage to<br />attach to then these mortgages are removed from your property and paid back as<br />unsecured debt for pennies on the dollar.</p><p>Example Client 1:</p><p>Before Filing</p><p>Income:&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; $3,000.00 net per month</p><p>Mortgage:&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; $890.00 per month</p><p text-indent: 0.5in;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; $6,200.00 behind (6 months plus cost and attorney fees)</p><p>Credit Card Bill:&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; &#160;$1,000.00 per month</p><p text-indent: 0.5in;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; $30,000.00 in total credit card debt</p><p>Living Expenses:&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; <u>$1,600.00&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;  </u></p><p class=" ">Monthly Expenses:&#160;&#160;&#160; $3,490.00</p><p class=" ">Monthly Balance:&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; -$490.00 per month.</p><p class=" "></p><p class=" ">After Filing:&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </p><p>Income:&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; $3,000.00 net per month</p><p class=" ">Chapter 13 Payment: $1,200.00 per month (Includes Mortgage, Back Mortgage Payments&#160; </p><p class=" ">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; and Credit Card Debt.)</p><p class=" ">Living Expenses:&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; <u>$1,600.00&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </u></p><p class=" "><u></u>Monthly Expenses: &#160;&#160; $2,800.00</p><p class=" "></p><p class=" ">Monthly Balance:&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; $200.00&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </p><p></p><p>After Filing:&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </p><p>Income:&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; $3,000.00 net per month</p><p class=" ">Chapter 13 Payment: $1,150.00 per month (Includes Mortgage, Back Mortgage Payments&#160; </p><p class=" ">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; and Credit Card Debt.)</p><p class=" ">Living Expenses:&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; <u>$1,600.00&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </u></p><p class=" ">Monthly Expenses: &#160;&#160; $2,750.00</p><p class=" ">Monthly Balance:&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; $250.00&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </p><p class=" ">Call us today to find out how you can get a Fresh Start on your Bright<br />Future!!!</p><p class=" ">(248) 629-6367</p><br />Example Client 2:Before FilingIncome:&#160;&#160; &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; $3,000.00 net per monthMortgage:&#160; &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; $850.00 per month&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; $5,700.00 behind (6 months plus cost and attorney fees)Second Mortgage:&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; $250.00 per monthThird Mortgage:&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; $125.00 per monthCredit Card Bill:&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; $1,000.00 per month&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; $30,000.00 in total credit card debtLiving Expenses: &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; <u>$1,600.00&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </u>Monthly Expenses:&#160;&#160;&#160; $3,825.00Monthly Balance:&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; -$825.00 per month.<!--more-->Chapter 13 Bankruptcy is an excellent method to save an individuals home.&#160; Many individuals who cannot afford their home outside of bankruptcy can afford the home once the Chapter 13 Plan is approved and the individuals debts have been addressed.'
