aS'<p>\r\n\r\n&#160;&#160; Its funny how issues come up again and again.&#160;&#160;&#160; Last year, I consulted with a client who had questions regarding placing a GPS device on her husbands car.&#160; She suspected that he was having an affair and thought that this would provide some proof.&#160; After consulting with her, and advising against it, I posted a blog concerning this issue and the state of the law in Michigan.</p><p /><p>&#160; Last week, another client asked a similar question, although this was a man who knew that his wife had an affair but thought that she was still involved with this other man.&#160; He was convinced that putting a GPS on her car was the right way to go, especially since he was the title owner of the vehicle.&#160; I reviewed the blog with him, and he&#160;determined that this was not the best course of action for him to take.</p><p /><p>&#160;&#160; Here is a reprint of that blog from Nov. 2011;</p><p>Recently, a client met with me about a possible divorce.  She suspected that her Husband was having an affair, and that, along with other issues, prompted this meeting.  While she had her suspicions, she did not have any specific proof and wanted some information on things to do.</p><p>   One of her thoughts was to have a GPS device hidden in or on his car to track where he went.  It seemed that there were significant periods of time where the husband would &quot;disappear&quot; and she wanted to know where he was.  </p><p>   This method of investigation sounds like a great idea except for one fact.  In Michigan, it is illegal to place a GPS device on a vehicle without the owners knowledge and consent.  In fact, it is a misdemeanor punishable by up to 1 year in jail and/or a fine of up to $1000.00.</p><p>   So, she asked me, what if the Husband did not own the car.  Well, the statute further prohibits the tracking of the location of a motor vehicle without the consent and knowledge of either the owner of the car or the authorized operator of that vehicle.</p><p>   There are exceptions according to Michigan statutes and, in fact, a professional investigator can place a device on a car, but only in limited circumstances.  Before making any decisions about this activity, you should consult with an attorney to get answers to all your questions.</p><p>   Contact the Law Offices of Eugene Lumberg and Eric S. Lumberg for a free consultation.  You can call us at 248-626-8383 or e mail at <a href="mailto:lumberglaw@gmail.com">lumberglaw@gmail.com</a></p><!--more-->Can you put a GPS on your spouses car if you own it?'
