aS'<p>In 1996, Wyeth Pharmaceuticals introduced a new hormone replacement therapy drug called Prempro.&#160; The drug was released to treat hot flashes and other symptoms associated with menopause.&#160; Prempro soon became a popular prescription for a number of women.&#160; At its peak an estimated 15 million women were using the menopause drug.</p><p>Six years after the drugs introduction, The National Institutes of Health (NIH) found Prempro and similar drugs to be a possible danger to a number of prescribed users.&#160; Their study conducted in 2002, found that Prempro significantly increases the risk of stroke, blood clots, heart attacks and breast cancer.&#160; </p><p>After the study was released the drugs popularity decreased sharply.&#160; For many women, however, the damage was already done.&#160; The side effects caused by Prempro could follow them for the rest of their lives.&#160; Side effects of the drug can include increased risk of breast cancer, ovarian cancer, endometrial cancer, stroke, heart attack, or blood clot.</p><p>If you have been affected by side effects associated with Prempro please contact your doctor.&#160; Your doctor can explain health risks and provide proper medical advice.&#160; </p><p>If you have suffered from Prempro side effects you may have a claim for compensation.&#160; Prempro side effect victims deserve justice.&#160; To receive a free consultation from an experienced pharmaceutical lawyer please contact us at 800-561-4887 or visit our website at <a href="http://www.bestattorney.com/">http://www.bestattorney.com</a>.&#160; Our <a href="http://www.bestattorney.com/prempro-side-effects-health-complications.html">Prempro lawyers</a> can help you receive a fair settlement and provide you with the guidance you need.</p><!--more-->In 1996, Wyeth Pharmaceuticals introduced a new hormone replacement therapy drug called Prempro.&#160; The drug was released to treat hot flashes and other symptoms associated with menopause.&#160; Prempro soon became a popular prescription for a number of women.&#160; At its peak an estimated 15 million women were using the menopause drug.'
