aS"<p>The vehicle for transfer of an ownership interest in a small business is usually called a buy-sell agreement.&#160; The name of the agreement, however,&#160;barely begins to describe the various benefits that&#160;it can bring to the owners of the business.&#160; Since most small businesses often pay out most or all of their profits in salaries, an equity interest in the business would be much less valuable if its owner was not assured of being able to sell that interest back to the business or to other shareholders. With professional advice,&#160;a buy-sell&#160;agreement can be tailored to meet the objectives of each small business.&#160; Unfortunately, money is an issue in the organization of most small businesses and the buy-sell agreement is either an afterthought or something that the owners put off as something they will do when the business begins to generate a profit.&#160; More often than not, the owners wait too long and then&#160;one of the three &quot;Big D's&quot;&#160;happens (death, disability or divorce&#160;of an owner), and then it's too late.</p><p>So now you have the buy-sell agreement.&#160; What about the valuation of the interests covered by the agreement when&#160;a &quot;triggering event&quot; occurs?&#160;&#160;How do the owners place&#160;a dollar value on the interest to be purchased?&#160; How do you do that with an entity (for example a closely held corporation) whose stock, by its very nature, has little or no liquidity?&#160; Enter one of the real benefits of the buy-sell agreement.&#160; The agreement can set the price for the shares according to a predetermined formula agreed to by the owners prior to the triggering event.&#160;&#160;The formula can be as varied as the value shown on the company's books, the value arrived at by a third-party appraisal, or some other valuation method.&#160; Once the valuation method is selected, it is important that the value be revisited regularly (at least annually,&#160;and not less often than every other year) so that it remains current.</p><p>A buy-sell agreement may also serve as an orderly method for maintaining control over the company despite a change in the composition of the owners.&#160; In a family run business, it is important that a departing owner's interest be purchased by those that will continue the business.&#160; For children who decide that they do not want to carry on in the business, cash, perhaps generated by an insurance policy on a senior owner, might be an alternative to inheriting part of the business.&#160; Regardless, shareholders should avoid conflicts between the terms of the buy-sell agreement and their Wills.&#160; When the terms of the Will and the agreement cannot be reconciled, the odds for litigation increase, defeating the smooth transition that was anticipated in the first place with the preparation of the buy-sell agreement.&#160; If a Will predates the agreement, it may be necessary to draft a new Will that is consistent with the agreement (should contain a provision that business interests are to be disposed of in accordance with the terms of the buy-sell agreement).</p><p>A properly drafted buy-sell agreement, like any good contract, can avoid future disputes by establishing agreed rights and duties.&#160; Think twice about further delaying the preparation of this important document.</p><p /><p />"
