aS'<p>This information was provided by the <a title="Winston-Salem workers compensation attorneys" href="http://www.charlespeed.net/aop/personal-injury/winston-salem-workers-compensation/" target="&#95;blank">Winston-Salem workers compensation attorneys</a> at Charles Peed and Associates, PA., 877-514-0995, <a title="www.charlespeed.net" href="http://www.charlespeed.net/" target="&#95;blank">http://www.charlespeed.net/</a></p><p><b>Workers compensation</b> was established to provide medical benefits and money for employees injured on the job.&#160; Workers compensation protects workers and their families by providing a safety net for the consequences of injury or death arising from the worker&#8217;s occupation.&#160; In exchange for giving up the right to sue an employer for the injury, the employee receives compensation and medical benefits.&#160; The employer enjoys immunity from suit in exchange for a fixed liability.&#160; Under the workers compensation system, what should you do when you are injured on the job?</p><p>The first thing you should do is to seek medical attention for your injury.&#160; Once your condition is stabilized, you must report your injury to your employer, orally and in writing.&#160; Make your report immediately, or as soon after your injury as is medically practicable.</p><p>A critical part of the workers compensation program is the requirement of an independent medical examination.&#160; This examination is conducted by a doctor chosen by the insurance company and who reports the results of the examination to the insurer.&#160; You must make sure that the doctor understands your work environment and responsibilities.&#160; When you go to the examination, have a list of questions prepared.&#160; Keep notes of the visit.&#160; If the doctor places restrictions upon your return to work &#8211; either on the type of work you may do or when you may return to work altogether, make sure to communicate those restrictions to your employer.&#160; If you have already been treated by a physician for your injury (for example, in an emergency room), make sure that you have records of the treatment and any recommendations or restrictions discussed with that physician.</p><p>You should provide as much information to your employer as possible.&#160; Your employer will provide information about your injury or illness to its insurance company.&#160; The insurance company may then file a notice of denial, to dispute either the entire claim or portions of the claim.&#160; You must be notified in writing of the denial, and the reasons for the denial must be provided.&#160; You may then contest the denial, and the more information and support that you have for your claim, the more likely you are to prevail.</p><!--more-->This information was provided by the <a title="Winston-Salem workers compensation attorneys" href="http://www.charlespeed.net/aop/personal-injury/winston-salem-workers-compensation/" target="&#95;blank">Winston-Salem workers compensation attorneys</a> at Charles Peed and Associates, PA., 877-514-0995, <a title="www.charlespeed.net" href="http://www.charlespeed.net/" target="&#95;blank">http://www.charlespeed.net/</a>'
