aS'<p>The precise details behind financial difficulties are unique for every individual.&#160; The current economic downturn has caused many people to lose their jobs, while others continue to work, but at significantly reduced income levels.&#160; Increasing health care costs have caused medical emergencies to become unaffordable, and some events such as divorce or the loss of a loved one have caused many to turn to credit to make ends meet.</p><p>Filing bankruptcy is an excellent option to help some individuals achieve the financial fresh start they need, but it is not always the right solution.&#160; The <a href="http://www.uscourts.gov/FederalCourts/Bankruptcy/BankruptcyBasics.aspx">Federal Courts</a> provide information on the basics of bankruptcy law, but bankruptcy attorneys in Winston-Salem can help you assess your situation to determine if filing bankruptcy is the right solution for you and if this is the right time to file.&#160; For example, if unemployment is the underlying reason for your current financial situation, and if that situation virtually ensures you are likely to experience similar issues once your debt is discharged, it may not be the right time to file.</p><p><strong>Dischargeable debt in bankruptcy</strong></p><p class="WebText">The federal bankruptcy law allows individuals in Winston-Salem to discharge <i>unsecured</i> debt, such as credit card balances and personal loans, through Chapter 7 bankruptcy if they pass a means test based on income and household size for the applicable state.&#160; Individuals who file Chapter 13 bankruptcy mainly due to arrearages on <i>secured</i> debt, such as home and auto loans or home equity lines of credit, can retain these assets, provided they have enough income to pay the full arrearage during the course of the bankruptcy plan while still meeting their basic needs.&#160; It is also possible for unsecured debt to be discharged in a Chapter 13.</p><p>Bankruptcy is typically not the right solution when individuals primarily have debt in the form of recent outstanding income taxes, child support, or student loans because these debts are not typically dischargeable.&#160; An experienced bankruptcy attorney can often help individuals find other solutions when bankruptcy is not appropriate for their unique circumstances.</p><p><strong>Contact a knowledgeable bankruptcy attorney</strong></p><p>For the best results, you need experienced legal support.&#160; The <a href="http://www.allmanspry.com/">Winston-Salem bankruptcy attorneys</a> at Allman Spry Leggett &amp; Crumpler, P.A.&#160; represent individuals in bankruptcy proceedings.&#160; We offer valuable advice, counseling, and representation to debtors throughout both Chapter 7 and Chapter 13 proceedings.&#160; For more information, contact us today.&#160; We serve both business and consumer bankruptcy clients in the Winston-Salem-Greensboro-High Point Piedmont Triad area and throughout North Carolina.</p>'
