aS'<p><b>New construction brings jobs and a renewed economy</b></p><p>According to the Associated General Contractors of America, Massachusetts suffered a loss of 1,500 jobs in the last part of 2010. While job loss is a harsh blow to individual and to industry alike, the 1.4 percent decline represented fewer jobs lost than in other states across the nation. An increase in construction jobs is a leading indicator of an improving economy.&#160; </p><p><b>Construction is demanding&#8212;and dangerous</b></p><p>Construction safety is an important factor in recessionary recovery in Boston&#8212;requiring regulation and responsibility on the part of all parties. As more construction jobs are created, the chance for being injured on-the-job also increases. Attention to injury prevention is vital to ensure the safety of a construction workplace, and the success of any construction project.&#160; </p><p>Building the future of Boston, or any city, means accidents happen, including the following:</p><p>?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Crane and scaffolding accidents</p><p>?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Welding and explosive incidents</p><p>?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Machine accidents</p><p>?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Vehicle accidents</p><p>Suffering injury on a Boston construction site leads to a workers compensation claim, and often to a <a href="http://www.attorneysheehan.com/practice-areas/workers-compensation-and-construction-accidents/" target="&#95;blank">Boston construction lawyer</a> if that claim is denied, or contested. Personally and professionally understanding workers compensation is important. </p><p><b>Do Fewer Jobs Mean Fewer Injuries?</b></p><p>Even though there have been fewer jobs available during the recent economic downturn, fewer jobs does not mean fewer construction injuries. Advocacy groups report the following points concerning construction safety in our state:</p><p>?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; A 2011 report by the Massachusetts American Federation of Labor-Congress of Industrial Organizations (AFL-CIO) reports that the number of fatal workplace accidents continue to fluctuate without a consistent up or down trend.</p><p>?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Construction remains one of the most hazardous Massachusetts workplaces with 10 fatal accidents in 2010. Five of those deaths resulted from falls.</p><p>?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; A 2008 report from the Massachusetts Division of Occupational Safety (DOC) notes a decline in non-fatal accident and injury, owing to a decrease in reporting of recordable injury-only incidents. &#160;</p><p>Construction wages finance the future of many families, and workers compensation benefits can help a family remain afloat after a worksite injury. Massachusetts offers <a href="http://www.mass.gov/Elwd/docs/dia/publications/ee&#95;english.pdf" target="&#95;blank">information on workers compensation claims</a> for individuals. So remember to pay attention on the job and keep your eyes on your future.</p><p><b>Contact us about Boston construction accidents</b></p><p>With 15 years experience helping injured workers, John J. Sheehan is a Boston construction lawyer dedicated to securing appropriate benefits for clients throughout Massachusetts. If you are injured in a construction or other accident, contact us today.</p><p>Law Office of John J. Sheehan<br />44 School Street, Suite 815<br />Boston, MA 02108<br />(617) 973-1593</p><!--more-->According to the Associated General Contractors of America, Massachusetts suffered a loss of 1,500 jobs in the last part of 2010. While job loss is a harsh blow to individual and to industry alike, the 1.4 percent decline represented fewer jobs lost than in other states across the nation. An increase in construction jobs is a leading indicator of an improving economy.&#160;'
