aS'<br /><p>There are three initial steps a worker must follow when injured while on the job. </p><p><b>1. Seek medical attention.</b></p><ul><li>If you are injured, you have a right to seek emergency medical treatment from a non-designated health care provider.</li><li>But, if you are filing a workers compensation, any follow-up treatment must be by a health care provider on a list of providers authorized by the Workers Compensation Board</li><li>You must see a designated health care provider within 90 days of the accident.</li></ul><p><b>2. Notify your supervisor.</b></p><ul><li>You should notify your supervisor in writing about your injury as soon as possible.</li><li>Under the Pennsylvania Compensation Act, an employee is obligated to notify his or her employer of any injury occurring on the job. </li><li>Injured employees have up to 120 days to report the accident.</li><li>This is a critical step. Failure to do so could result in the loss of workers compensation benefits. </li></ul><p><b>3. Complete Form C-3.</b></p><ul><li>You must complete a claim for workers compensation on Form C-3 and mail it to the nearest Workers Compensation Board office.</li></ul><p><b>Other important follow-up steps</b></p><ul><li>Follow all physician instructions. </li><li>If an independent medical examination is required, this should be done ASAP.</li><li>Consult an attorney for guidance on how to proceed</li><li>Follow your attorney&#8217;s instructions. Attend any hearings that may be held in the case when you are notified to appear. The <a href="http://www.portal.state.pa.us/portal/server.pt/community/workers%27&#95;compensation/10386/about&#95;workers%27&#95;compensation/552721" target="&#95;blank">Pennsylvania Department of Labor &amp; Industry</a> provides useful information about workers compensation claims on its website.</li></ul><p>This information has been provided by <a href="http://www.theworkinjuryfirm.com/">Philadelphia workers compensation attorneys</a> Borjeson &amp; Associates, located at 1500 Walnut Street, Suite 413, Philadelphia, PA 19192-3419. For further information on workers compensation, call 215-772-3020. </p><!--more-->Learn the three initial steps a worker must follow when injured while on the job.'
