aS'<p>The debt problem in America continues to escalate.&#160; Nearly 43 percent of American families spend more than they earn each year.&#160; Average households carry $15,519 in credit card debt.&#160; Personal bankruptcies have doubled in the past decade.&#160; </p><p>With debt running rampant, it is easy to feel overwhelmed, frustrated, and alone.&#160; Filing bankruptcy may seem appealing, but any <strong>Connecticut bankruptcy lawyer</strong> will tell you, it can have a negative effect on your credit and in some cases affect your lifestyle.&#160; There are several programs to help Connecticut residents avoid filing bankruptcy.&#160; <br />&#160;<br /><strong>Programs to avoid bankruptcy</strong></p><p><strong>Debt settlement</strong>&#8212;You, a credit counselor, or your attorney can negotiate with your creditors to reduce your debt, sometimes by as much as 40 to 60 percent.&#160; Consider this option if you cannot keep up with the minimum payments on your debt. </p><p><strong>Debt consolidation</strong>&#8212;You consolidate your bills into one lower monthly payment, possibly at a reduced interest rate.&#160; Late fees and over-the-limit charges on credit card debt may be eliminated.&#160; Because you are paying back your debt, consolidation may have a less negative effect on your credit.</p><p><strong>Debt management</strong>&#8212;A credit counseling agency develops a plan possibly including a reduced interest rate to keep you current on your bill payments and help you avoid bankruptcy in Connecticut. </p><p><strong>Loan consolidation</strong>&#8212;You borrow money to consolidate and replace several loans into one affordable monthly payment.&#160; This does not necessarily address all of your debt, but it may help you enough to avoid bankruptcy.</p><p><strong>Do-it-yourself plan</strong>&#8212;You take a critical look at your finances to see how you can reduce your debt or living expenses or increase your disposable income.&#160; For example, you may be able to sell assets, eliminate lawn care or cleaning services, get a second job, or work overtime.&#160; These steps may help to avoid <a href="http://www.clgmlawoffices.com/practice-areas/connecticut-bankruptcy-filing/" target="&#95;blank">filing bankruptcy in Connecticut</a>. </p><p><strong>Why avoid bankruptcy?</strong></p><p>Bankruptcy will remain on your credit report for ten years. While it may eliminate the reporting of much past negative credit history, future potential lenders will be aware of your bankruptcy filing.</p><p>In addition your right to file bankruptcy in the future will be limited for a period of time.&#160; For instance although you may be able to file a chapter 13 repayment plan, you cannot file another chapter 7 case for eight years after your last chapter 7.</p><p>In some cases bankruptcy also can cause the loss of assets that have significant value or equity above the debts that are secured by the assets. Although Connecticut has a generous homestead exemption or value in your home that you can protect in bankruptcy, you should consult an experienced <a href="http://www.clgmlawoffices.com/attorneys/Richard-Coan/" target="&#95;blank">Connecticut bankruptcy attorney</a> to determine its application in your particular circumstances.</p><p>Also, not all debts can be eliminated through <strong>bankruptcy in Connecticut</strong>.&#160; Back taxes, student loans, and child or spousal support cannot be wiped out by filing Chapter 7.&#160; Thus, you may find yourself still in debt even though you filed bankruptcy. </p><p><strong>Helpful solutions</strong></p><p>You do have options.&#160; A bankruptcy law firm is best equipped to help you understand and explore your options.&#160; You should contact a qualified lawyer as soon as possible to discuss your specific circumstances.&#160; To speak to a <a href="http://www.clgmlawoffices.com/attorneys/Carl-Gulliver/" target="&#95;blank">bankruptcy lawyer in Connecticut</a> today, contact the law firm of Coan, Lewendon, Gulliver &amp; Miltenberger, LLC at 203-745-0172 to schedule a consultation.</p><p><strong>Coan, Lewendon, Gulliver &amp; Miltenberger, LLC</strong><br />495 Orange Street<br />New Haven, Connecticut 06511<br />Phone: (203) 745-0172<br /><a href="http://www.clgmlawoffices.com/">http://www.clgmlawoffices.com/</a></p><!--more--><a href="http://www.clgmlawoffices.com/attorneys/Richard-Coan/" target="&#95;blank">Connecticut bankruptcy attorney</a> Richard M. Coan talks about different steps one can take to avoid bankruptcy.'
