aS"<p>\r\n\r\n&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; So I finally got a diagnosis about my left leg pain.&#160; Two in fact.&#160; Later in the day after Christmas, I got a voicemail message from my primary care physician that the radiologist had read my lumbar MRI and that it looked pretty good.&#160; There was a little spot around L3-4 which might cause some minor discomfort, but that I should keep on pushing prednisone and would be better soon.&#160; He was sure of this since I had been making such good progress over the past week, during which my condition continued to deteriorate.&#160; Then I got a call from my neurosurgeon, who had shoved the MRI disk into his home PC and also discovered that my spine looked great.&#160; No stenosis, no degenerative disease, only a herniated disk at L3-4.&#160; He asked me my symptoms, which I repeated, and he said they were perfect for that lesion, which made me feel just great.&#160; I asked him if this was a subtle finding, to which he responded that a child of four could see it, making me wonder about the age of the radiologist.</p><p>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Next question:&#160; What do I do about it?&#160; He responded that the area of injury could cause exquisite pain and was unlikely to resolve with conservative treatment, especially several weeks downstream with no improvement.&#160; If it did resolve, the lumbar defect would persist, and with my active (psychotic) lifestyle, I could expect it to erupt again at the slightest irritation from running or other exercise, bringing back the rat that keeps on gnawing. &#160;He recommended a microdiskectomy, and soon, which made me feel even better.&#160; The procedure was described as &quot;minimally invasive surgery,&quot; which can be loosely translated as , &quot;It still hurts like hell.&quot; He was off for the week, but offered to draft a partner to perform the surgery in a couple of days, which I declined.&#160; He then offered to have his office set up an evaluation and pre-op so that I could be&#160;his first case for the following week on January 2, 2013.&#160; What a way to ring in the new year.&#160; I jumped at the offer, and the following day limped into my office on crutches to begin arranging my schedule so that I could have the procedure without losing my practice in the meantime. I already had jury trials booked for January 7 and 28 in state and federal court, respectively, and the doctor made it clear there was no way I could cover the first one.&#160; He said to plan on 3-4 weeks for recovery.</p><p>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; By Friday, December 28, I was enjoying the day filling out forms everywhere I went in the bowels of North Carolina Baptist Hospital.&#160; There is even a form (I swear I am not making this up) one has to sign at each clinic stating that you consent to being seen at this visit.&#160; So how many patients show up at the front desk just to tell the receptionist that they object to being seen and have appeared only to give formal notice, before departing in disgust?&#160; I was briefed and&#160;debriefed about my prior medical history, going back to childhood, whether I thought I was pregnant or had AIDs, did I want my wife to receive any medical information about my condition, was I happy about what happened to me, etc.&#160; I was asked 50 times for my name and date of birth, which must be some type of minimal IQ test.&#160; They even demanded to look at my driver's license to confirm that&#160;I was not some phantom patient out on another&#160;Munchausen's binge over the holidays.&#160; Then the poking and prodding began, with bloodwork, manipulation of limbs and the piece de resistance----everyone wanted to see how well I could walk (they were disappointed).</p><p>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; But the best part was the informed consent.&#160; You can die, go blind, or be paralyzed just from the operation itself.&#160; Then there are the potential peripheral neuropathies from positioning, capped by possible injuries to blood vessels, nerves and other adjacent structures, such as the spinal cord.&#160; Anesthesia alone can be catastrohpic, before the surgeon even gets up to bat.&#160; So if a mallet nicks my aorta, or a rongeur collapses a kidney, it's all&#160;part of that global risk one assumes every time the patient goes under the knife.&#160; The chance may be only one in 10,000, but if it happens to you. . . .&#160;</p><p>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Then it was time for pre-op instructions, with a 100-page booklet telling me what not&#160;to do the night before surgery, when, where&#160;and how to arrive and what to expect.&#160; I am limited to clear liquids&#160;the night before, so I am trying to figure out a way to dilute egg nog to fit my presurgical needs.&#160; I am told to expect an hour of surgery per disk, so with a 7:00 a.m. start time,&#160;I plan to be doing the teaberry shuffle&#160;by noon.&#160; I will even let my wife watch this miracle, assuming the consent forms I signed permit her to do so.&#160; Everyone talks about giving someone else a new fundamental orifice when angered, but I expect to have a new dorsal porthole soon, courtesy of&#160;neurosurgical science.&#160; I have always wanted to know what is going on behind my back, and modern medicine has now devised a way to open up that brave new world&#160;of rear view perspective.&#160; God, it's great to be alive.</p><p>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; What I really miss is walking, something I have been doing since I was 18 months old.&#160; It never occurred to me, watching all those gomers tool around in their hoverounds at the shopping mall and the airport, what the loss of perambulation involves.&#160; My former peripatetic ways have become quite para-pathetic.&#160; I observe the post-Xmas crowd milling around, upright and oblivious, taking for granted the gift of functioning limbs just like I did for six decades.&#160; Grabbing a glass of orange juice in the morning, or brewing up a cup of Irish tea, has become an ordeal of crutches and clutches as each part of my&#160;body strains to mimic what was once an unconscious protocol.&#160; I refuse to talk about bath time.&#160;We forget the trials of those less fortunate who struggle with physical handicaps for a lifetime, a suffering no amount of money or comfort can assuage.&#160; The next time I take a pain-free step, I plan to relish the experience of mobility. But I also hope that, the next time I spy someone crippled by whatever malady has taken&#160;away&#160;his precious walk, I will also remember what it was like when that luxury was, albeit briefly,&#160;stripped from me.&#160; I will in addition try to be more charitable to those who suffer chronic pain for reasons of pathology over which they have no control, and even&#160;to those who do. These are my new year's resolutions.</p><p />"
