aS'<p><strong>Why talking and texting can lead to serious auto accidents</strong></p><p>Most people know that talking or texting while driving is dangerous, and can lead to injuries and fatalities. It is important to be aware of the laws governing cell phone use, and the penalties for disregarding them.&#160;If you or someone you know has been a victim of an injury due to&#160;a car accident where the other driver was using their cell phone, you will want to get in touch with a <a href="http://www.dubofflawgroup.com/practice-areas/maryland-auto-accident-lawyer/">Maryland auto accident lawyer</a>&#160;who will make sure your situation is professionally handled. The following statutes apply in the state of Maryland:</p><p /><ul><li>As of October, 2010, no cell phone may be used unless a hands-free device is engaged to make the call.&#160; Secondary enforcement is the rule in this case, meaning that a police officer must have a separate reason for pulling an offender over.&#160; Fines are forty dollars for the first offense, and one hundred dollars for any subsequent offenses.</li><br /><li>In 2009, Maryland made texting while driving illegal, although reading text messages on a handheld device is not.&#160; Enforcement in this case is primary, meaning that a police officer retains the right to pull an offender over simply for texting while driving.&#160; Fines can be up to five hundred dollars.</li><br /><li>Drivers under the age of 18, or those with learning permits, are prohibited from using cell phones while driving.</li><br /><li>Bus drivers in the <a href="http://dc.gov/DC/">District of Columbia</a> are forbidden from using a cell phone when passengers are present.</li><br /><li>The above laws do not apply to emergency situations, such as when it is necessary to dial 9-1-1 while driving.&#160; They also do not apply to Global Positioning Systems (GPSs).</li><br /><li>Maryland is considering adding certain elements to its distracted driving legislation in 2010&#8212;including making it illegal to read text messages from a hand-held cellular device while operating a motor vehicle.</li></ul><p /><p><strong>The dangers of driving while using your cell phone</strong></p><p>It is easy to become complacent while using a cell phone, even while driving.&#160; We may believe that we are immune to the dangers associated with such behavior.&#160; After all, we use cell phones every day, and in a wide variety of circumstances.&#160; Special hazards are associated with cell phone use while driving car, as indicated by the following:</p><p /><ul><li>In a study by the University of Utah, those who used cell phones while operating their vehicles were found to be just as impaired as drunk drivers.</li><br /><li>In the same study, motorists using cell phones were found to be nine percent slower to hit the brakes than those not similarly distracted.</li></ul><p /><p><strong>Contact an auto accident attorney in Maryland today</strong></p><p>To discuss your car accident in Maryland with a skilled <a href="http://www.dubofflawgroup.com/attorneys/">auto accident attorney in Maryland</a> from DuBoff &amp; Associates, Chtd., contact us today. Our lawyers will fight to protect your rights and help you win any damages you are owed if you or someone you love has been seriously injured due to an auto accident.</p><!--more-->A <a href="http://www.dubofflawgroup.com/practice-areas/maryland-auto-accident-lawyer/">Maryland auto accident lawyer</a> at the law firm of DuBoff &amp; Associates talks about how using a cell phone while you are driving is a serious and dangerous offense, which can cause a number of accidents, injuries or fatalities due to the lack of concentration on the road from cell phone use.'
