aS'<p>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; In New York, a capital improvement to real property must satisfy the following three conditions: 1) it must substantially add to the value of the real property, or appreciably prolong its useful life; 2) it must become part of the real property or become permanently affixed such that removal would materially damage the real property or the tangible personal property itself; and 3) it must be intended to become a permanent installation.&#160; A failure to satisfy all three conditions will result in the NYS Department of Taxation and Finance&#160;(&quot;Department&quot;) refusing to recognize a project as a capital improvement. </p><p>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; In one instance,&#160;a contractor installed a truck scale on real property it owned.&#160; The installation was treated as a capital improvement and no sales tax was paid.&#160; The contractor was audited and the capital improvement designation rejected.&#160; The contractor challenged the audit.</p><p>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The truck scale was a 60 foot by 11 foot, 20 ton piece of equipment costing over $42,000.&#160; The useful life of the scale was estimated at 20 years.&#160; Installation required that the scale sit on and be bolted to reinforced concrete piers.&#160; A concrete and asphalt ramp was also installed for purposes of entry and exit.&#160; The auditor&#8217;s position was that the bolting of the scale to the concrete piers in the ground did not permanently affix it to the real property.</p><p>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Whether tangible personal property becomes a part of the real property or is permanently affixed is dependent upon the nature of the item installed, as well as the method of installation.&#160; The contractor installed the scale on its own property intending to use it for the duration of its 20 year useful life.&#160; Given the scales size and weight, it was viewed as not readily moveable.&#160; If the contractor were to try and move it, the scale would have to be disassembled, removed and the land excavated and leveled to avoid safety hazards.&#160; These factors, when viewed in their entirety, greatly outweighed the one fact relied upon by the auditor that the scale was &#8220;only&#8221; bolted to the ground.</p><p>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The auditor&#8217;s determination that the installation of the truck scale did not constitute a capital improvement was rejected.&#160;</p><p>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; In another instance, an amusement park owner installed a roller coaster on its park grounds.&#160; The owner treated the installation as a capital improvement and paid no sales tax.&#160; The owner was audited and the capital improvement designation rejected.&#160; The owner challenged the audit.</p><p>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; At issue was a wooden roller coaster with a wood and steel support structure.&#160; The roller coaster was anchor bolted to concrete piers installed in the ground.&#160; The entire coaster covered almost 2 acres of land.&#160; In addition to the roller coaster itself, the project required the installation of a station house used by customers to line up and board the ride.&#160; The cost for the entire project was approximately $2 million.&#160; </p><p>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The Judge reviewing the audit stated that when deciding whether or not an installation meets the definition of capital improvement, it is &#8220;necessary to determine the [amusement park owner&#8217;s] intention of making the roller coaster a permanent installation.&#8221;&#160;&#160; That intent is to be deduced &#8220;from all the circumstances at the time the property is annexed to the realty&#8230;&#8221;&#160; Factors for review include the nature of the item installed, the method of installation, the relation of the owner to the real property, and the application of the item installed to the use of the real property.&#160; </p><p>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The Judge found that the nature of the roller coaster and the method of its installation supported a finding of permanency.&#160; He added, &#8220;Clearly this is not an article that can be moved about at will.&#8221;&#160; Any removal would damage the roller coaster and the ground upon which it was installed.&#160; Permanency was also supported by the fact that that the real property was owned by the amusement park operator.</p><p>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The auditor&#8217;s determination that the installation of the roller coaster did not constitute a capital improvement was rejected.&#160; </p>'
