aS'<p>The <a title="Ohio defense lawyers" href="http://www.ohio-criminal-lawyer.com/" target="&#95;self">Ohio defense lawyers</a> of Robey &amp; Robey review over the latest in the case of Connick vs. Thompson.&#160; </p><p>The U.S. Supreme Court has agreed to review Connick v. Thompson, a Louisiana case testing the limits of prosecutorial immunity from a lawsuit based upon the prosecutor\'s office alleged failure to properly train its lawyers about their obligation to disclose evidence that it helpful to the defense.</p><p>In this case, Mr. Thompson was accused of an unrelated armed robbery case,&#160;in addition to a murder charge&#160;in the 1984 death of Raymond Liuzza, Jr., in New Orleans.&#160;The prosecutors chose&#160;to hold the armed robbery trial first, in hope that a conviction in the first case would effectively preclude Thompson from testifying in his murder trial. Thompson\'s lawyers later learned that prosecutors withheld exculpatory evidence in the robbery trial, that the real perpetrator had a different blood type than Thompson. He was found guilty of the robbery and elected not to testify in his murder case. He was convicted in the murder case and sentenced to death. On appeal, Thompson\'s lawyers claimed the&#160;prosecutors\'s failure to reveal the helpful evidence violated their obligations under the law in Brady&#160;v. Maryland. This failure to turn over helpful evidence deprived Thompson of his right to testify in his murder trial. Lower courts agreed and awarded Thompson&#160;$ 14 million&#160;for&#160;his wrongful conviction. The prosecutor\'s office then appealed the case to the U.S. Supreme Court claiming &quot;prosecutorial immunity&quot; to such lawsuits.</p><p>&#160;The&#160;lower courts&#160;that have ruled against the prosecutor\'s office in this case&#160;were correct.&#160;The prosecutor\'s office withheld helpful evidence from the defense, which put&#160;an innocent man on death row.&#160;Then they try to shirk responsibility for that act. That is simply wrong. Common sense alone tells us that the role of the prosecutor is to seek justice&#160;- not&#160;convictions. If the evidence is that a person didn\'t commit a crime, then the prosecutors should say so. Criminal justice should&#160;never be a game played by prosecutors, who will stop at nothing to win. Instead, it should be about fairness. Without fairness in the&#160;system, there can be no justice. And that means justice for all. When prosecutors don\'t play fair, they should be punished. Just like raising a child, punishment serves as a proper means to teach that child right and wrong. In this case, the prosecutors were wrong and should be punished. That punishment is a large verdict against them.&#160;It hits them where it hurts - the wallet. Sometimes, that&#160;is the only language prosecutors understand.&#160;&#160;</p><p>Criminal law has a lot of complexities that may be difficult to understand without trained legal guidance.&#160; If you are facing immunity charges in Ohio, contact a <a href="http://www.ohio-criminal-lawyer.com/aop/Ohio-Criminal-Law/">Cleveland criminal lawyer</a> from the law firm of Robey and Robey today by calling toll free 888.228.5545 or submitting your <a title="case online" href="http://www.ohio-criminal-lawyer.com/contact-us/" target="&#95;self">case online</a>.</p><p /><p /><!--more--><p>The <a title="Ohio criminal defense lawyers" href="http://www.ohio-criminal-lawyer.com/ohio-criminal-cases/" target="&#95;self">Ohio criminal defense lawyers</a> of Robey &amp; Robey law inform you about the U.S. supreme court case of Connick v. Thompson and what it means to immunity law.&#160; </p>'
