aS'\r\n\r\n<p margin: 0in 0in 10pt;">Since its inception in April, 2013, the Suffolk County\r\nTraffic and Parking Violations Agency (&#8220;SCTPVA&#8221;) has been assessing drivers who\r\nreceive tickets an administrative fee at the conclusion of their court cases.\r\nThe purpose of this administrative fee is to raise revenue to cover some of the\r\noverhead costs in the issuing and processing of traffic tickets. It has been\r\nthe policy of the SCTPVA to impose the administrative fee in all cases, even\r\nthose cases in which drivers have had their tickets for certain equipment\r\nviolations dismissed upon the showing of proof that the necessary repairs were\r\ndone within the timeframe of state law. </p>\r\n\r\n<p margin: 0in 0in 10pt;">On December &#160;17, 2013,\r\nthe Suffolk County Legislature voted to approve a law that will prohibit the\r\nSCTPVA from assessing an administrative fee in those cases in which drivers are\r\nfound not guilty or their tickets are dismissed. The County reportedly will\r\nissue refunds to those drivers who already have paid an administrative fee for\r\ndismissed tickets. The &#8220;not so good news&#8221; is that the SCTPVA will make up for\r\nthis loss of revenue by increasing the administrative fee for drivers who are\r\nfound guilty or plead guilty to tickets. The amount of the increase in the administrative\r\nfee&#160;will be&#160;small. However, the total amount of fine and fees for guilty pleas can be\r\nquite substantial. While drivers may be able to get some relief from the SCTPVA\r\non the points for driving infractions, they are learning that traffic tickets\r\nin Suffolk County are very&#160;costly. </p>\r\n\r\n'
