aS'There are <b>1.4 million traumatic brain injuries</b> in the U.S.\r\nannually according to the <a href="http://www.cdc.gov/">Centers for Disease\r\nControl and Prevention</a><p><b>The number of diagnosed traumatic brain injuries\r\nhas been rising</b>, with 10,963 cases in 2000 and 27,507 in 2008, according to\r\nDefense Department reports.&#160; The U.S. <b>military reported 20,199 diagnosed traumatic brain\r\ninjuries in the first 9 months of 2009</b>.&#160;\r\nOf those, 15,828 were diagnosed as mild.&#160; The military wants to be able to test soldiers as soon as\r\npossible, even in the field, as traumatic brain injuries that go undetected or\r\ntreated can lead to serious consequences, such as dementia, depression and\r\nother problems. Repeated concussions can have very serious consequences, so the\r\nearly detection of concussions can prevent further damage from being done.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">An American company is working on developing a unit that the\r\nmilitary could use in the field to test for mild head injuries. They are\r\ndeveloping a mobile unit that makes it possible to take an electroencephalogram\r\nreading in the field, using a hand held device connected to a disposable headset\r\nplaced on the forehead.&#160; The\r\nreading would complement the usual tests for cognitive function that are done.\r\nBrainScope of Bethesda, Maryland, is testing its technology at nine U.S.\r\nmedical centers.&#160; Data from these\r\nstudies will help it improve its algorithms and develop better ones for use in\r\nits product.&#160; The company is\r\ntalking with U.S. Regulators about the requirements for market clearance.</p><p class="MsoNormal"><a href="brain">Brain injury attorneys</a> who represent people across the country who suffered <a href="http://brain-injury-lawyer.com/practice-areas/current-research/">traumatic brain injuries</a>&#160; can be reached at 1-888-395-3551.&#160; </p><!--more-->U.S. military reports increase in traumatic brain injuries.&#160;&#160;'
