aS'<p MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt" class="MsoNormal">As reported in Long Island Newsday, increased penalties for use of a cell phone while driving&#160;became effective June 1, 2013. Specifically, a driver convicted of&#160;talking&#160;on a cell phone or texting&#160;is now&#160;subject to a 5 point penalty on his or her driving record and a minimum fine for a first offense of $150.00.&#160;This is a stiff penalty that will affect a driver\'s insurance premium. Additionally, if the driver has a clean record, the 5 point penalty will leave the driver one point shy of the level at which the NYSDMV imposes the $300.00 Driver Responsibility Assessment (&quot;DRA&quot;). If the driver does have points within the last eighteen months, the DRA will be triggered and&#160;the driver will be subject to a loss of driving privileges if the 5 points takes the overall point total to 11 or above. Newsday also reported that NYSDMV is stating that a driver\'s license will be revoked if the driver has 3 cell phone convictions within eighteen months (similar to the way in which a license is revoked for 3 speeding convictions within 18 months). Apparently, Governor Cuomo is also seeking&#160;more severe&#160;penalties for junior and probationary drivers convicted of improper use of cell phone. &#160;&#160;<p /></p><p>It remains to be seen how the Southampton and Suffolk County courts will treat tickets for improper use of cell phone and texting now that the penalties have been increased. Our goal always is to obtain the maximum point reduction possible and dismissals for our clients. Drivers charged with a traffic violation for improper use of cell phone or texting in a Southampton or other Suffolk County court can contact our office and receive a free consultation as to how best to respond to the ticket.&#160;&#160; <p /></p><p><p /><p>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;</p></p>'
