aS'<p class="MsoNormal">A new <a href="http://www.prweb.com/releases/2013/1/prweb10359994.htm">article</a> in the New England Journal of Medicine touches on the link between faulty metal on metal hip implants, and the flawed 510(k) approval process. </p><p /><p /><p class="MsoNormal" /><p>&#160;</p><p /><p class="MsoNormal">In order for a medical device to make it to the sales market, it must be approved by the Food and Drug Administration. (FDA)&#160; The FDA has an approval &#160;process that determines what is likely to be safe for customers to use.&#160; But what if the approval process is flawed?&#160; &#160;Could patients be getting products that should never have passed the safety test?</p><p /><p /><p class="MsoNormal" /><p>&#160;</p><p /><p class="MsoNormal">The FDA has a special process for approving medical devices.&#160; It&#8217;s called the 510(k) process.&#160; If a new medical device is substantially similar to something that is already on the market, the device receives FDA clearance and is not subject to the tests that a device with totally new components would be subject to. </p><p /><p /><p class="MsoNormal" /><p>&#160;</p><p /><p class="MsoNormal">The <a href="http://www.anapolschwartz.com/practices/hip-implant-lawsuits/depuy.asp">DePuy ASR XL</a> was approved by the FDA because each of its individual components were substantially similar to prosthetic hips that were already on the market.&#160; However, some of those previous devices had been recalled due to a high revision risk. </p><p /><p /><p class="MsoNormal" /><p>&#160;</p><p /><p class="MsoNormal">These components in the DePuy ASR XL were used in nearly 100 different devices during a span of 50 years.&#160; They had never been used together in one device.&#160; The DePuy ASR XL was a totally new device, yet it did not have to go through the approval process that a new device would. &#160;</p><p /><p /><p class="MsoNormal" /><p>&#160;</p><p /><p class="MsoNormal">The DePuy recall which spawned the <a href="http://www.anapolschwartz.com/practices/hip-implant-lawsuits/depuy.asp">DePuy lawsuits</a> and other metal on metal <a href="http://www.anapolschwartz.com/practices/hip-implant-lawsuits/depuy.asp">hip implant lawsuits</a> demonstrates that the 510(k) approval process is flawed and should be updated to keep faulty, ineffective devices out off the market. </p><p /><p /><p /><p><a href="https://plus.google.com/103224636578810205141/posts" rel="author" target="blank">Read more about Michael Monheit on Google+</a></p>'
