aS'<p TEXT-ALIGN: justify">Wills and probate cases in Florida can be complex and wills can serve many purposes.&#160; These documents provide a means of determining answers to questions that are bound to come upon your passing, or at a time when you are unable to make your own decisions.&#160; Although most people are familiar with, or at least have heard of a last will and testament, many people are not familiar with living wills.&#160; Both types of wills provide direction in very different circumstances. &#160;A wills lawyer in Jacksonville can help you determine if only one will or both are necessary for your particular situation.&#160; </p><em>Jacksonville wills and probate</em><p TEXT-ALIGN: justify">?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; <b>Living Wills in Jacksonville.</b>&#160; Living Wills are documents that serve as a blueprint of your medical wishes.&#160; They provide answers to your family about what types of treatments you do and do not want performed on you, in the case that you are unable to speak for yourself.&#160; These documents are often used when you have suffered a catastrophic illness or are comatose and unable to provide your doctors and nurses with the answers they need.&#160; </p><p TEXT-ALIGN: justify" /><p TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in; TEXT-ALIGN: justify">?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; <b>Last will and testament.</b>&#160; This is the document that comes to mind when people mention that they are preparing a will, or that a will has been executed.&#160; This document directs your executor on how your assets should be distributed among your friends, family, and favored organizations.&#160; </p><p TEXT-INDENT: 0in" /><p TEXT-ALIGN: justify">?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; <b>Probate</b>.&#160; This is the process by which your assets are distributed to your friends and family, according to the directions included in your last will and testament. </p><em>Why have a will?</em><p TEXT-ALIGN: justify">A person should have a will to ensure that his or her final wishes are fulfilled.&#160; Simply telling your family what you would like done with your assets does not ensure that your wishes will be followed.&#160; A family may inadvertently disregard your wishes by forgetting what they were, or they may contest those wishes.&#160; </p><p TEXT-ALIGN: justify" /><p TEXT-ALIGN: justify">Having a will that provides directions as to who should receive which assets ensures that your wishes will be fulfilled.&#160; A wills lawyer can help you prepare a last will and testament that meets your needs, and handles your family&#8217;s needs, with compassion and in accordance with your last requests. </p><p TEXT-ALIGN: justify" /><p TEXT-ALIGN: justify">If you already have a will, your position in life may have changed.&#160; If you prepared your will while you were working and now find yourself contemplating retirement, it is time to revisit your will. A good rule for changing your will is that, whenever you have experienced a major life change, you should meet with one of our <a href="http://floridaelder.com/aop/wills-probate/" target="&#95;blank">Jacksonville, Florida wills and probate lawyers</a>. You have become a parent or a grandparent, you have bought your first home or your last home. &#160;Events such as these call for a new will to be prepared. </p><p /><em>Contact us</em><p>For estate planning guidance, contact&#160;an experienced&#160;<a href="http://floridaelder.com/" target="&#95;blank">wills lawyer in Jacksonville</a>&#160;at Grady H. Williams, Jr., Attorneys at Law, P.A.</p><!--more-->A good rule for changing your will is that, whenever you have experienced a major life change. You should meet with one of our <a href="http://floridaelder.com/aop/wills-probate/" target="&#95;blank">Jacksonville, Florida wills and probate lawyers</a>&#160;for estate planning guidance, our&#160;<a href="http://floridaelder.com/" target="&#95;blank">wills lawyer in Jacksonville</a>&#160;at Grady H. Williams, Jr., Attorneys at Law, P.A. can help.'
