aS'<p>Child custody and support are among the most pressing issues in a divorce.&#160; Divorcing spouses can reach an agreement about child custody and support through mediation, negotiations, or other out-of-court alternative dispute resolution.</p><p>Once the couple reaches an equitable child support agreement that complies with state guidelines, a judge almost always gives court approval.&#160; But if negotiations fail to produce a settlement, the judge determines child support obligations for the spouses.</p><p>The judge&#8217;s calculation of child support is based upon child support guidelines in that state.&#160; For example, the child support guidelines in Tennessee and Kentucky take into account a variety of factors, including:</p><ul MARGIN-TOP: 0in" type="square"><li>The combined income of both parents</li><li>Overnights spent with the child</li><li>Costs for health insurance</li><li>Age of the child</li><li>Extraordinary medical costs</li></ul><p><b>A Clarksville divorce attorney can help you take legal action</b></p><p>Parties to the child support agreement must honor its terms or face legal consequences.&#160; In both Tennessee and Kentucky, concerned parents can consult a&#160;qualified and&#160;experienced <a href="http://www.kennedylawfirmpllc.com/">Clarksville divorce law firm</a>&#160;for help with child support enforcement.</p><p>Even if your ex-spouse moves to a different state, it is still possible to have a child support order enforced under the Uniform Interstate Family Support Act (UIFSA), as well as the federal Child Support Recovery Act of 1992.&#160;&#160; Also, the <a href="http://ncsea.org">National Child Support Enforcement Association</a> is another valuable resource that lists agencies nationwide that can help with child support enforcement at little to no cost to you.</p><p>For the parent who fails to pay, the penalties can include the following negative repercussions:</p><ul MARGIN-TOP: 0in" type="square"><li>Wage garnishment</li><li>Fines</li><li>Jail time for failure to comply with a court order</li><li>Withholding of a federal tax refund</li><li>Seizure of property</li><li>Suspension of a professional or occupational license</li><li>Revocation of a driver&#8217;s license</li><li>Denial of a passport</li></ul><p>If a parent falls behind in paying child support, the overdue amount is called arrears.&#160; While the amount in arrears cannot be reduced due to financial hardship&#8212;such as the loss of a job&#8212;the delinquent spouse should petition the court for a reduction in future child support payments.&#160; It is important to note that child support obligations cannot be discharged through personal bankruptcy.</p><p><b><i><u>Contact us today</u></i></b></p><p>If you are looking for a Clarksville divorce firm to help you with divorce, child support enforcement, or any other family legal matter, The Kennedy Law Firm, PLLC can help you.&#160; Our caring, compassionate Clarksville divorce lawyers serve clients throughout Tennessee and Kentucky.&#160; Call us today at 1-931-266-4107 or <u><a href="http://www.kennedylawfirmpllc.com/contact-us/">contact us online</a></u>. We look forward to speaking to you about your situation.</p><p /><p /><!--more-->If you are looking for a Clarksville divorce firm to help you with divorce, child support enforcement, or any other family legal matter, The Kennedy Law Firm, PLLC can help you.&#160; Our caring, compassionate Clarksville divorce lawyers serve clients throughout Tennessee and Kentucky.&#160; Call us today at 1-931-266-4107 or contact us online. We look forward to speaking to you about your situation.'
