aS'<p class="MsoNormal">Evidence is a crucial part of any disability claim. Providing complete and accurate information is often a key to success for new applicants.&#160; Fortunately, there is also hope for applicants who have received a denial of benefits.&#160; The Social Security appeals process allows applicants&#8212;preferably with the help of a <a href="http://www.davidallensocialsecurity.com/">Sacramento disability attorney</a>&#8212;to provide additional evidence to support their claims following a denial.&#160; </p><p /><p class="MsoNormal"><b>Information in the initial application</b></p><p>The initial applications for SSDI and SSI require the applicant to provide a great deal of information.&#160; This includes income and employment data as well as detailed medical records&#8212;dates of treatments and procedures, names of medications, and contact information for doctors, hospitals, and other medical professionals.&#160; This is only a starting point for the Disability Determination Services (DDS) that decide initial claims.&#160; The DDS uses this information to conduct a full investigation before ruling on a claim.&#160; Providing complete and accurate information can help expedite this process.</p><p /><p class="MsoNormal"><b>Information relevant to disability claims</b></p><p>To qualify for SSDI or SSI, adults must have a medical condition that has or will prevent them from working for at least 12 consecutive months or that has been diagnosed as terminal.&#160; Therefore medical records are important evidence in evaluating most disability claims.&#160; </p><p class="MsoNormal">The physical demands of various occupations differ greatly and a condition that may be disabling to a construction worker may not be disabling for an office worker.&#160; While some conditions are <a href="http://www.ssa.gov/disability/professionals/bluebook/AdultListings.htm">automatically disabling under Social Security regulations</a>, for most individuals the inquiry is more complicated.</p><p class="MsoNormal">That is why the DDS also investigates the employment and education records of applicants.&#160; DDS uses this information to determine what types of work an applicant previously performed, what other types of work the applicant is qualified to perform, and whether the medical condition claimed precludes those types of work.&#160; </p><p class="MsoNormal">More highly educated applicants may have more difficulty qualifying for SSDI or SSI because they are likely qualified to perform a wider variety of work with minimal physical demands.&#160; Of course this does not apply to minor children seeking SSI benefits for whom the inquiry is primarily medical.</p><p class="MsoNormal">For those who received a denial of SSDI or SSI benefits, it is important to consult a disability attorney in Sacramento before proceeding too far in the appeal process.&#160; Applicants may continue to submit new evidence to support their claim up to the close of their hearing with the Office of Disability Adjudication and Review (ODAR).&#160; After that phase, SSA closes the record and rarely accepts new evidence.&#160; While experienced Oakland disability attorneys can help Social Security claimants gather evidence and build a compelling claim, it may be difficult for them to help claimants who do not consult them until after the hearing phase.</p><p><b></b></p><p><b>Experienced Social Security Disability attorneys in Oakland and Sacramento</b></p><p>For over 30 years, the Oakland and <a href="http://www.davidallensocialsecurity.com/">Sacramento disability attorneys</a> of David Allen &amp; Associates have been helping individuals facing a denial of Social Security or long-term disability benefits.&#160; They maintain offices in Sacramento, Reno, Stockton, Las Vegas, and Oakland and are available by phone at 1-877-876-4800 or through their <a href="http://www.davidallensocialsecurity.com/contact-us/">internet contact page</a>.</p><p>\r\n</p><!--more-->For over 30 years, the Oakland and Sacramento disability attorneys of David Allen &amp; Associates have been helping individuals facing a denial of Social Security or long-term disability benefits.&#160; They maintain offices in Sacramento, Reno, Stockton, Las Vegas, and Oakland and are available by phone at 1-877-876-4800 or through their internet contact page.'
