aS'<p>&#160;</p><p><b>Stevens Johnson Syndrome causes</b></p><p><a title="Stevens Johnson Syndrome" href="http://www.usasjslawyers.com/sjs-overview/" target="&#95;blank">Stevens Johnson Syndrome</a> is often triggered by an allergic reaction to some common drugs. Some of these drugs include the following: </p><ul><li><a title="Dilantin Stevens Johnson Syndrome" href="http://www.usasjslawyers.com/sjs-overview/dilantin-stevens-johnson-syndrome/" target="&#95;blank">Dilantin&#160;Stevens Johnson Syndrome</a>: Dilantin is an anticonvulsant that recently has been linked as a Stevens Johnson Syndrome cause. Since 1998, there have been a number of reports of children developing SJS due to the anticonvulsant Dilantin. Recent research shows that the risk of SJS increased with the usage of Dilantin as opposed to other anticonvulsants.</li><li><a title="Motrin Stevens Johnson Syndrome" href="http://www.usasjslawyers.com/sjs-overview/motrin-stevens-johnson-syndrome/" target="&#95;blank">Motrin&#160;Stevens Johnson Syndrome</a>: Motrin, a brand name for the generic drug ibuprofen, has recently been recognized by doctors as one of the causes of SJS. Motrin-induced SJS may cause terrible skin reactions such as exfoliative dermatitis.</li><li><a title="Advil Stevens Johnson Syndrome" href="http://www.usasjslawyers.com/sjs-overview/advil-stevens-johnson-syndrome/" target="&#95;blank">Advil&#160;Stevens Johnson Syndrome</a>: Like Motrin, Advil is a brand name for ibuprofen. Recently Advil has been linked with causing SJS, especially in children where children&#8217;s Advil has been involved. A major concern today is that SJS caused by children&#8217;s Advil may result in rapid blindness or death. Because of these dangers, drug manufacturers have been pressed to add more warnings to their product, specifically addressing the side effects that are linked to SJS. </li><li><a title="Bextra Stevens Johnson Syndrome" href="http://www.usasjslawyers.com/sjs-overview/bextra-stevens-johnson-syndrome/" target="&#95;blank">Bextra&#160;Stevens Johnson Syndrome</a>: Bextra is banned in both Canada and Europe. In 2005, the FDA asked Pfizer, the maker of Bextra, to take it off the market. One of the reasons for the decision of the FDA was that major side effects including heart attacks and strokes occurred more often for patients taking Bextra than for other COX-2 agents. These COX-2 agents have been shown to increase the risk of contracting SJS. </li><li><a title="Feldene Stevens Johnson Syndrome" href="http://www.usasjslawyers.com/sjs-overview/feldene-stevens-johnson-syndrome/" target="&#95;blank">Feldene&#160;Stevens Johnson Syndrome</a>: Feldene, a nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID), is used to treat pain, fever, and inflammation. The drug piroxicam is the generic version of Feldene, which has been around since 1982. Feldene, like the other drugs listed above, has been linked with Stevens Johnson Syndrome. Despite this link, there has been no action taken by the FDA to force the manufacturer to disclose this possible side effect.</li></ul><p><b>Contact us for help</b></p><p>If you believe your usage of popular drugs resulted in Stevens Johnson Syndrome, please contact the&#160;<a title="SJS Attorneys" href="http://www.usasjslawyers.com/attorneys/" target="&#95;blank">Stevens Johnson Syndrome lawyers</a>&#160;of Greg Jones &amp; Associates. You owe it to yourself and your family to see if you can recover compensation for the damages that have been inflicted upon you and your loved ones.</p><ul /><!--more--><a title="Stevens Johnson Syndrome" href="http://www.usasjslawyers.com/sjs-overview/" target="&#95;blank">Stevens Johnson Syndrome</a> is often triggered by an allergic reaction to some common drugs. If you believe your usage of popular drugs resulted in SJS, please contact the <a title="Stevens Johnson Syndrome Lawyers" href="http://www.usasjslawyers.com/attorneys/" target="&#95;blank">Stevens Johnson Syndrome Lawyers</a> of Greg Jones &amp; Associates.'
