aS'<p>Whether you need to hire employees, buy or sell goods and services on a regular basis or hire someone to remodel your office, you need an effective contract to help ensure all parties understand the expectations and the required end result. </p><p><strong>Identifying the terms of a business contract</strong></p><p>Without a well-drafted legal agreement, you can easily end up in a costly and time-consuming legal dispute. A review of the <a href="http://www.legislature.mi.gov/(S(rcclmv45gnt1lq2nqwy0xz45))/mileg.aspx?page=MCLIndex&objectname=mcl-chap566" target="&#95;blank">Michigan Legislative Website</a> illustrates the complexity of contract law and provides justification for seeking experienced legal assistance to review any contract before you sign. However, you can work with a skilled attorney to draft an effective contract by following these guidelines:</p><ul><li>Spell out what the contract covers. You may need another party to perform one specific job or service, or you might need to retain someone to provide goods or services on an as-needed basis for an unspecified period. Be specific on the details.</li><li>Put every point in writing.&#160; Never assume certain verbal agreements will provide the protection you need. As you negotiate the terms with the other party, take copious notes, and include every point in the written contract. </li><li>Make sure your contract clearly identifies all involved parties.&#160; Your contract may be with one other person. However, either of you may use outside contractors or others to perform required tasks. Spell out the details to help ensure that the failure of outside parties does not result in non-compliance.</li><li>Include all payment terms.&#160; In addition to specifying the entire dollar amount of the contract, you need to identify specific events that require payments and any events that require additional funds. And, when payments occur over an extended period, identify all payment dates and interest rates or other penalties for late payment. </li><li>Identify the conditions that end the contract.&#160; The contract may naturally end once both parties satisfy its conditions. But you need to include a legal way to end the contract early, such as if the other party fails to meet deadlines, charges more than agreed or consistently performs substandard work.</li></ul><p><strong>Contact an experienced contract attorney in Troy and Detroit, Michigan</strong></p><p>The law firm of <a href="http://www.hclawyers.com/" target="&#95;blank">Hickey, Cianciolo, Fishman &amp; Finn, P.C.</a> has decades of experience helping businesses throughout Michigan promote smooth and mutually beneficial business transactions through clear and thoroughly drafted contracts. By retaining an experienced <a href="http://www.hclawyers.com/practice-areas/business-law/business-contracts/" target="&#95;blank">business law attorney in Troy, Michigan</a> now, you can negotiate and finalize agreements that avoid common legal pitfalls, decreasing the likelihood of litigation down the road. From their offices in Troy, our attorneys provide zealous representation and practical legal advice to business clients throughout the Detroit metropolitan area. Call us at 248-247-3300 to schedule a consultation.</p><p>Hickey, Cianciolo, Fishman &amp; Finn, P.C.<br />901 Wilshire Drive<br />Suite 550<br />Troy, Michigan 48084<br />Phone: 248-247-3300 </p><!--more-->Whether you need to hire employees, buy or sell goods and services on a regular basis, or hire someone to remodel your office, you need an effective contract to help ensure all parties understand the expectations and the required end result.'
