aS'Teenage drivers, who suffer from Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder, have a higher susceptibility to distractions while driving, and therefore have a higher risk of accidents. A study into teenage drivers and Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder is still in progress, but early findings seem to suggest that these teenagers may be at a higher risk of accidents because of the inability to filter out distractions.<br /><br />The studies are being conducted by a professor at the University of Buffalo, and the final results of the study are not expected be out for several years. However, Prof. Greg Fabiano has found enough to indicate that teen drivers with ADHD may be at a higher risk of accidents. His research is now focusing on how parents can encourage their children with ADHD to drive safely.<br /><br />The study is being funded by a grant from the National Institutes of Health, and involves two separate groups of teen drivers. The first group was exposed to additional driver education, and had monitoring devices fitted into their cars to monitor their driving behavior. The second group of teen motorists had additional driver education, the monitoring devices, and these drivers also signed contracts with their parents to reward good driving behaviors and punish bad driving behavior. <br /><br />Prof. Fabiano has already noticed some interesting things. Contrary to popular belief, teenagers actually like having monitoring devices in their cars, because these devices can help convince their parents that they are driving safely. Not surprising to <a href="http://www.lntlb.com/" title="Los Angeles Car Accident Attorney">Los Angeles car accident lawyers</a>, the study also shows that most teenagers believe that they can text while driving without any negative consequences. Besides, Fabiano is warning that texting while driving could prove especially hazardous to teen drivers with ADHD. These drivers already suffer from challenges with concentration and focusing, and the risks of an accident are amplified when you add cell phones to the equation.<br /><br /><!--more-->Teenage drivers, who suffer from Attention Deficit Hyperactivity \r\nDisorder, have a higher susceptibility to distractions while driving, \r\nand therefore have a higher risk of accidents. Not surprising to Los Angeles car accident lawyers, the study also shows\r\n that most teenagers believe that they can text while driving without \r\nany negative consequences.'
