aS'<p class="MsoNormal"><b>Social Security Disability Insurance (SSDI)</b></p><p class="MsoNormal">According to the <a href="http://www.ssa.gov/policy/docs/statcomps/di&#95;asr/2010/di&#95;asr10.pdf">Annual Statistical Report on the Social Security Disability Insurance Program</a>, nearly 9.4 million individuals in the United States were receiving Social Security Disability benefits at the end of 2010.&#160; This number has more than doubled during the past 20 years.&#160; Of these, 87 percent were disabled workers.&#160; Nearly half of recipients are over the age of 55.&#160; Disabilities involving muscular-skeletal conditions&#8212;such as bone, muscle, or joint problems&#8212;are the most common bases for benefits.&#160; But mental disorders such as depression and other mood disorders are also quite common.</p><p class="MsoNormal">On average, disabled workers in 2010 received a monthly benefit of $1,067.&#160; This amount tends to increase with age, with the average disabled worker under the age of 25 receiving only $560 per month and the average disabled worker over age 60 receiving $1,205 per month.&#160; The Social Security Administration (SSA) computes individual benefits based on the beneficiaries&#8217; earnings so the amounts vary from person to person.&#160; Claimants who feel their benefit amount is not a correct reflection of their earnings should consult a <a href="http://www.davidallensocialsecurity.com/">Sacramento Social Security Disability lawyer</a>.</p><p class="MsoNormal">In 2010, California was home to 722,715 SSDI beneficiaries. Although the highest number of any state, this number is actually only 3 percent of the population between the ages of 18 and 64.&#160; This is below the national average of 4.5 percent and gives California the fourth lowest percentage of SSDI recipients in the nation&#8212;behind only Hawaii, Alaska, and Utah.</p><p /><p class="MsoNormal"><b>Supplemental Security Income (SSI)</b></p><p class="MsoNormal">According to the <a href="http://www.ssa.gov/policy/docs/statcomps/ssi&#95;asr/2010/ssi&#95;asr10.pdf">Supplemental Security Income Annual Statistical Report</a>, over nine million people received federal Supplemental Security Income (SSI) payments, federally administered state supplement payments, or both, in 2010.&#160; Of these, about one million were under the age of 18.&#160; About 30 percent of those receiving SSI benefits remain eligible for less than 5 years.&#160; But another 40 percent of beneficiaries remain eligible for between 5 and 15 years.</p><p class="MsoNormal">About 30 percent of SSI applicants ultimately receive benefits, although the number is around 40 percent for applicants under the age of 18.&#160; Denial rates have climbed sharply in over the last 10 years, increasing over 10 percent since 2001.&#160; Claimants who receive an initial denial, however, have the right to appeal and, with the help of <a href="http://www.davidallensocialsecurity.com/">Social Security disability lawyers in Oakland</a> and Sacramento, can present a compelling case for benefits to SSA.</p><p /><p class="MsoNormal"><b>Experienced Social Security Disability lawyers in Oakland and Sacramento</b></p><p class="MsoNormal">For over 30 years, the Oakland and <a href="http://www.davidallensocialsecurity.com/">Sacramento Social Security Disability lawyers</a> of David Allen &amp; Associates have been helping individuals facing a denial of Social Security or long-term disability benefits.&#160; They maintain offices in Sacramento, Reno, Stockton, Las Vegas, and Oakland and are available by phone at 1-877-876-4800 or through their <a href="http://www.davidallensocialsecurity.com/contact-us/">contact page</a>.</p><p /><!--more-->For over 30 years, the Oakland and Sacramento Social Security Disability lawyers of David Allen &amp; Associates have been helping individuals facing a denial of Social Security or long-term disability benefits.&#160; They maintain offices in Sacramento, Reno, Stockton, Las Vegas, and Oakland and are available by phone at 1-877-876-4800 or through their contact page.'
