aS'<p><b>Motorcycles</b></p><p>According to the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA), in 2008 there were more than 5,000 deadly motorcycle accidents, with 73 fatalities in Arkansas. Because motorcycles are small and offer little in the way of protection to riders, motorcycle accidents easily cause severe and sometimes fatal injury to those riding them. Plus, it is easy for drivers of automobiles and trucks to accidentally run into these much smaller and harder to see vehicles.</p><p>Consider the following statistics:</p><p>?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; <a href="http://www.nhtsa.gov/" target="&#95;blank">NHTSA</a> reports motorcycle deaths are 37 times the number of car accident deaths.</p><p>?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Motorcycle fatalities continue to rise, with the latest data showing the highest number ever recorded in 2008.</p><p>?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; In states with enacted or reinstituted helmet laws, motorcycle fatalities declined.&#160; Unfortunately, Arkansas helmet laws apply only to riders under 21.</p><p>?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; <b>Large Trucks</b></p><p>Weighing up to 80,000 pounds and possessing the length of several smaller cars, semi-trucks dominate any traffic landscape. Points worth noting include:</p><p>?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; In 2008, more than 4,200 people died in collisions with large trucks and another 90,000 suffered injuries.</p><p>?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The number of large trucks involved in fatal accidents declined 17.4 percent from 1999 to 2008.</p><p>?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Whereas 23 percent of passenger car drivers involved in fatal truck accidents were intoxicated, only two percent of truck operators involved in fatal accidents were driving under the influence of alcohol or drugs.</p><p>?&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The leading driver errors for truck operator and passenger car drivers are the same?speeding and failing to stay in the proper lane.</p><p>Small and agile, the size of a motorcycle puts its riders at risk. The enormous size and slow maneuverability of large trucks puts vehicles in their path at risk. But passenger cars, outnumbering motorcycles or large trucks, statistically cause more accidents between vehicles large, small, and in-between.</p><p><b>Contact Arkansas accident lawyers</b></p><p>With years of experience with personal injury, the <a href="http://www.justicetoday.com/aop/" target="&#95;blank">Arkansas truck accident attorneys</a> at Nolan, Caddell &amp; Reynolds are committed to the successful pursuit of fair compensation for clients injured in truck accidents throughout Arkansas, Oklahoma, New Mexico, Washington D.C., and Texas. Contact us today for a free initial consultation.</p><p>Nolan Caddell &amp; Reynolds<br />5434 Walsh Lane<br />Rogers, AR 72758-8946<br />(479) 464-8269</p><p>&#160;</p><p>&#160;</p><p /><!--more-->According to the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA), in 2008 there were more than 5,000 deadly motorcycle accidents, with 73 fatalities in Arkansas. Because motorcycles are small and offer little in the way of protection to riders, motorcycle accidents easily cause severe and sometimes fatal injury to those riding them. Plus, it is easy for drivers of automobiles and trucks to accidentally run into these much smaller and harder to see vehicles.'
