aS'<p class="MsoNormal" MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt">A debilitating injury can be a major financial setback.&#160; It can prevent a person from working and necessitate costly medical treatments.&#160; While some injured individuals may receive income from workers compensation or a civil lawsuit, others may find that Social Security Disability Insurance (SSDI) or Supplemental Security Income (SSI) is their only option.<p /></p><p class="MsoNormal" MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt">For some deserving individuals, obtaining social security benefits is simply a matter of filing the necessary applications and waiting for approval.&#160; Unfortunately, the social security bureaucracy&#8212;designed to prevent fraud and abuse of the social security system&#8212; also has a record of denying benefits to deserving individuals.&#160; When this occurs, it becomes necessary for that claimant to file an appeal.&#160; An experienced <a href="http://www.robertrosenfeldlaw.com/social-security-disability/">South Bend social security disability attorney</a> can help claimants navigate the complex appeal process and get the benefits they deserve.<p /></p><p class="MsoNormal" MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt"><b mso-bidi-font-weight: normal">The Social Security appeal process<p /></b></p><p class="MsoNormal" MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt">After an initial denial, a claimant may request a review of his or her claim be a different SSA staff member.&#160; Sometimes this review will result in the granting of benefits, but more often the denial stands and an appeal is necessary.&#160; SSA uses a <a href="http://www.ssa.gov/pubs/10041.html#how">multi-leveled appeal system</a> that starts with a hearing before an administrative law judge (ALJ).&#160; A claimant can then appeal an unfavorable decision by an ALJ to the Appeals Council.&#160; <p /></p><p class="MsoNormal" MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt">Following a denial by the Appeals Council, claimants wishing to pursue their claims further must enter the federal court system and have their cases reviewed in a United States district court.&#160; Getting a favorable decision early in the appeals process is crucial.&#160; The farther a claim moves in the appeals process, the more time a claimant must wait for benefits, and the less likely a claimant will ultimately get a favorable decision.&#160; <p /></p><p class="MsoNormal" MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt">South Bend social security attorneys know the law governing SSDI and SSI claims.&#160; An attorney helps clients complete their required paperwork and gather necessary records.&#160; Lawyers also represent clients at hearings and in other interactions with SSA.&#160; They know what facts ALJs need to hear and know how to present a Social Security claim at hearing effectively.&#160; By consulting a <a href="http://www.robertrosenfeldlaw.com/">South Bend social security lawyer</a> early, claimants can put forward their best arguments earlier in the appeals process, making a favorable decision more likely and avoiding unnecessary delays and expenses.<p /></p><p class="MsoNormal" MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt"><b mso-bidi-font-weight: normal">Contact an experienced South Bend disability attorney today</b></p><p class="MsoNormal" MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt">Attorney Robert C. Rosenfeld has been a leading social security disability and Supplemental Security Income advocate in Indiana for over 35 years.&#160; He uses his wealth of experience to help clients obtain the Social Security benefits to which they are entitled.&#160; His offices are located at 1202 Lincoln Way East, South Bend, Indiana 46601.&#160; He is available by phone at 574-233-9459 or toll free at 1-800-707-7070.&#160; Prospective clients can also leave a message on his <a href="http://www.robertrosenfeldlaw.com/contact-us/">online contact page.</a><p /></p><p class="MsoNormal" MARGIN: 0in 0in 10pt"><i mso-bidi-font-style: normal">Robert C. Rosenfeld<br />1202 Lincoln Way East<br />South Bend, Indiana 46601<br />1-800-707-7070<p /></i></p>'
