aS"<p>\r\nBeginning January 14, 2014, &quot;applicable large employers&quot; (&quot;ALE&quot;) must offer their &quot;full-time&quot; employees (and their dependent children) the opportunity to enroll in an employer-sponsored health care plan.&#160; This provision is referred to as the employer mandate or employer responsibility provision of the Patient Protect and Affordable Care Act (&quot;ACA&quot;).</p><p><i>See our blog dated April 12, 2013 for more information on the definition of an ALE.</i></p><p><i>The IRS has proposed transition rules for health plans that run on fiscal year basis and those rules may postpone the effective date of the employer mandate.&#160; See our blog dated April 3, 2013 for more information on the transition rules.</i></p><p>A &quot;full-time&quot; employee is any employee who &quot;is employed on average at least 30 hours of service per week with an employer.&quot;&#160; For purposes of the rule, if the employee averages 130 hours of service per month ((30x52)/12=130), that average is treated as the equivalent of 30 hours of service per week.</p><p>An hour of service is an hour worked and for which payment is due or an hour for which the employee is entitled to payment for holiday pay, vacation pay, medical leave, etc.</p><p>If the employer knows that an employee will accumulate on average 130 hours of service per month, no additional calculation is necessary.&#160; The employee must be offered coverage under an employer-sponsored health care plan as of the effective date applicable to that employer in 2014.</p><p>If the employee's actual hours of service vary, the employer may determine the employee's hours of service using a look back period.&#160; As the name implies, the decision is made after the fact looking at the employee's actual hours of service during a specific period of time.</p><p>For currently employed or &quot;on-going&quot; employees, the look back period is called the &quot;standard measurement period&quot; or &quot;SMP.&quot;&#160; the SMP may be from 3-12 months in length and the employer selects its length.&#160; It may be followed by an administrative period or &quot;AP&quot; which may be up to three months long.&#160; The purpose of the AP is to provide time to perform the calculation for each employee and take steps necessary to enroll eligible employees.</p><p>SMPs of different length may used for employees covered by collective bargaining agreements and those not covered, employees covered by different collective bargaining agreements, hourly and salaried employees, and employees whose workplaces are in different states.</p><p>All employees who average 130 hours per month during the SMP must be offered the chance to enroll in an employer-sponsored health plan with coverage starting at the end of the AP.&#160; </p><p>The period following the AP is called the &quot;stability period&quot; (&quot;SP&quot;) and it must be at least six months in length.&#160; If the SMP was longer than six months, the SP must be at least as long as the SMP.&#160; During this time, any employee found to be &quot;full-time&quot; during the SMP is treated as full-time regardless of the actual hours of service accumulated by the employee during the SP.</p><p>The calculation for hourly employees is done using actual hours of service.&#160; For non-hourly employees, the employer may use a days-worked or weeks-worked equivalency method if that method will not understate the employee's hours of service.&#160; Under the days-worked method, the employee is credited with 8 hours of service per day for each day in which the employee has at least one hour of service.&#160; Under the weeks-worked method, the employee is credited with 40 hours of service per week for each week in which the employee as at least one hour of service.</p><p>Hours of service include hours for all forms of paid leave.&#160; In addition, special rules apply to unpaid leave under the FMLA and USERRA.&#160; Additional rules also apply to new employees, employees who work less than three months, employees who change statuses, and employees who terminate and are rehired.&#160; <i>For more on those special rules, see our next posting.</i></p><u><b><p>DISCLAIMER:&#160; THIS ARTICLE IS THE AUTHOR'S INTERPRETATION OF THE \r\nAPPLICABLE LAW.&#160; IT DOES NOT CREATE AN ATTORNEY-CLIENT RELATIONSHIP AND \r\nAN ATTORNEY-CLIENT RELATIONSHIP IS SPECIFICALLY DISCLAIMED.&#160; FOR THE \r\nAPPLICATION OF THE LAW TO SPECIFIC FACT SITUATIONS, READERS SHOULD \r\nCONSULT THEIR EMPLOYMENT LAW COUNSEL.</p></b></u><!--more-->This article summarizes the proposed rules for determining which employees must be offered coverage under an employer-sponsored health insurance plan under the Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act beginning January 1, 2014."
