aS'When someone files for bankruptcy protection and that person decides \r\nto liquidate his or her debts, the case usually falls under the realm of\r\n <a href="http://www.goldenstatelawgroup.com/explaining-chapter-7-filings-consumer-bankruptcy-lawyers-san-diego.html" title="Chapter 7 bankruptcy">Chapter 7</a>\r\n of the United States Bankruptcy Code.&#160; As such, the debtor&#8217;s assets \r\nwill be liquidated, or sold off, and the proceeds will be used to at \r\nleast partially satisfy his or her creditors.&#160; However, there are \r\nsituations where a debtor can attempt to keep an asset as long as he or \r\nshe continues to make payments on it.\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>This is known as reaffirmation, and if someone intends to take this \r\nstep he or she will likely sign a reaffirmation agreement after the \r\nbankruptcy case is complete.&#160; When this takes place, the debtor must \r\ncontinue to make payments as he or she otherwise would.&#160; According to a \r\nreport issued by the federal government, more than 300,000 reaffirmation\r\n agreements were signed by debtors last year, which represents more than\r\n 20 percent of the total number of bankruptcy cases that were closed.</p>\r\n<p>Reaffirmation agreements do usually mean that a debtor gets to retain\r\n an asset, but there is another side to that decision, and that is that \r\nif the debtor falls behind with the payments again he or she may lose \r\nthe asset and have few if any options left for retaining it.&#160; This \r\nagreement represents a new credit agreement and one that must be taken \r\nvery seriously.</p>\r\nSan Diego Bankruptcy Lawyers\r\n<p>One of the most difficult aspects of filing for bankruptcy protection\r\n involves giving up assets that may have either been valuable or held \r\nsentimental value.&#160; However, this is often simply a price that&#8217;s paid \r\nwhen such a level of protection is sought.&#160; Debtors should not allow \r\nthemselves to make bad decisions simply because they want to hang onto \r\nsomething.&#160; Instead, they should seek professional advice before taking \r\nthis step.</p>\r\n<p>If you are sick and tired of dealing with serious financial \r\ndifficulties and you want to put an end to them once and for all, seek \r\nthe help of <a href="http://www.goldenstatelawgroup.com/bankruptcy-overview-bankruptcy-attorneys-san-diego.html" title="San Diego bankruptcy lawyers">San Diego bankruptcy lawyers</a> who have been helping creditors move on with their lives for many years.&#160; Contact the <strong>Golden State Law Group </strong>today to schedule a free initial consultation.</p><!--more-->If you are sick and tired of dealing with serious financial \r\ndifficulties and you want to put an end to them once and for all, seek \r\nthe help of San Diego bankruptcy lawyers who have been helping creditors move on with their lives for many years.&#160; Contact the Golden State Law Group today to schedule a free initial consultation.'
