aS'<p>The federal government is recommending fines for the builders of the \r\nnew Mississippi River bridge, near north St. Louis, after a construction\r\n worker fell off the bridge to his death this past spring.&#160; <a href="http://www.tolbertbeadleandmusgraveblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/cranesky.jpg"></a></p>\r\n<p>The U.S. Occupational Safety &amp; Health \r\nAdministration is pressing for a $15,300 fine against the construction \r\ncompanies that were responsible for the project, saying there were four \r\nserious safety violations that directly contributed to the worker&#8217;s \r\ndeath.</p>\r\n<p>In all cases, workers&#8217; compensation is designed to pay survivor&#8217;s \r\nbenefits to the family of an employee killed on the job. A wrongful \r\ndeath lawsuit may also be filed against parties other than the victim&#8217;s \r\nemployer. Entities that may face such third-party liability lawsuits \r\ninclude subcontractors or equipment manufacturers.</p>\r\n<p>It&#8217;s important to note that OSHA&#8217;s investigation and any subsequent \r\nfines levied as a result, are separate from any civil litigation family \r\nmembers may bring in the event of a wrongful death in the workplace. \r\nStill, OSHA&#8217;s findings may be an important part of that civil case \r\nbecause you have an unbiased government agency uncovering multiple \r\nsafety violations just before a fatal incident. Even if those violations\r\n didn&#8217;t directly contribute to the death, their presence establishes a \r\npattern of negligence with regard to worker safety.</p>\r\n<p>According to <a target="&#95;blank" href="http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/metro/bridge-builders-face-fines-over-worker-s-death/article&#95;9432655b-18fe-5e23-840f-eb5092580d48.html">The St. Louis Post-Dispatch</a>,\r\n the 35-year-old carpenter was employed by a company that was working on\r\n a piece of equipment called an aerial man lift. That lift is similar to\r\n a cherry picker, and it&#8217;s typically used to lift a person up to a crane\r\n so he or she can disconnect or connect certain construction materials.</p>\r\n<p>It&#8217;s believed he was operating the machine when it tipped over while he was still in the bucket.</p>\r\n<p>According to OSHA&#8217;s citation, the lift had been positioned on a barge\r\n that was regularly used by employees without following the \r\nmanufacturer&#8217;s safety requirements. The manual specifically cautions \r\nagainst using it on a mobile surface or vehicle.</p>\r\n<p>Employers have a responsibility to ensure that their workers are \r\nfollowing safety protocol. That does not appear to have happened in this\r\n case.</p>\r\n<p>In addition to this violation, OSHA cited several more. Investigators\r\n say the construction company had no outlined safety practices or \r\nprocedures for pipe piling installations. There was also reportedly a \r\nfailure on the part of the company to protect employees who were \r\ninstalling those pilings, and workers weren&#8217;t properly trained on how to\r\n safely operate the man lift.</p>\r\n<p>The work was being done as part of a nearly $650 million project to \r\nrealign and reconstruct Interstate 70, as well as several local roads on\r\n both the Illinois an Missouri sides of the river. The project is \r\nexpected to be completed by 2014.</p>\r\n<p>Interestingly, this is not the first time one of those companies, \r\nbased in Kansas City, has come under scrutiny from OSHA for a fatal work\r\n accident. According to OSHA records, back in 1997, a 19-year-old and \r\nseveral co-workers were working on a nighttime caisson drilling project.\r\n Apparently, the worker was struck and killed by a load block that fell \r\nfrom the swivel shackle attachment, after the wire rope load line \r\nparted.</p>\r\n<p>The employer has now sued the family of the deceased worker claiming that the liability is limited by an ancient law that limits the recovery for a worker that is killed while working on the sea.&#160; The company is claiming because this incident happened on the river this law should apply and limit what the family can get from them.</p><!--more-->Employer sues family of worker killed in tragic fall on Mississippi river construction project.'
