aS'<p>When New York State <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/16/nyregion/16divorce.html" target="&#95;blank">altered their divorce laws 2010</a>, they became the 50th and final state to allow no-fault divorce proceedings.&#160; However, despite the fact that every state allows it, many people are still confused by the difference between fault and no-fault divorce.&#160; An experienced divorce attorney in Lake Charles, Louisiana can explain this difference.&#160; </p><p><strong>Divorce without blame</strong></p><p>At its most basic, a no-fault divorce is one in which neither spouse blames the other for the end of the marriage.&#160; Neither spouse needs to prove guilt or establish grounds in order to proceed with a no-fault divorce.&#160; One frequent basis cited as the cause for a no-fault divorce is irreconcilable differences, or that the spouses have lived separately for a specific period of time.</p><p>One of the primary advantages of a no-fault divorce is that they tend to be less contentious.&#160; By allowing that human relationships are complex and ever changing, no-fault divorce allows people who no longer find their marriage workable to separate amicably without enduring the emotional stress of establishing grounds.&#160; No-fault divorces also tend to be easier on children of divorcing couples, since children are not forced to watch their parents endure the struggle of a traditional divorce action.</p><p>You may believe a no-fault divorce might be right for your particular situation, but the only way to know for sure is to speak with experienced <a href="http://www.margaretedwardslaw.com/practice-areas/divorce/" target="&#95;blank">divorce attorneys in Lake Charles</a>.</p><p><strong>Experienced, reputable divorce attorney</strong></p><p>If you face a family law action in the Lake Charles area of Louisiana, put the experience and reputation of Margaret A. Edwards on your side.&#160;Ms. Edwards,&#160;a <a href="http://www.margaretedwardslaw.com/" target="&#95;blank">Lake Charles divorce lawyer</a>&#160;will give you a straight forward assessment of your case, then fight aggressively to achieve the best possible outcome.</p><p>The Law Firm oF Margaret A. Edwards<br />830 Moss Street<br />Lake Charles, LA 70601<br />(337) 436-2883</p><!--more-->When New York State altered their divorce laws 2010, they became the 50th and final state to allow no-fault divorce proceedings.&#160; However, despite the fact that every state allows it, many people are still confused by the difference between fault and no-fault divorce.&#160; An experienced divorce attorney in Lake Charles, Louisiana can explain this difference.'
