aS'<p MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt" class="MsoNoSpacing"><strong>Can my juvenile record be expunged</strong>?<p /></p><p MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt" class="MsoNoSpacing"><i mso-bidi-font-style: normal">Elissa B. Heinrichs, Esq.<p /></i></p><p MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt" class="MsoNoSpacing"><p>&#160;</p></p><p MARGIN: 0in 0in 12pt" class="MsoBodyText">Although Pennsylvania seals juvenile records, thereby shielding them from the public eye, college and employment applications routinely question whether applicants have entered into a consent decree (CD) or been adjudicated delinquent.&#160; Under certain circumstances, an individual with a juvenile record can file a petition to have the record expunged.&#160; </p>What does expungement mean and what records are included?<p MARGIN: 0in 0in 12pt" class="MsoBodyText">Expungement is the process of removing information so there is no trace or indication that the information existed.&#160; A Court Order, signed by a judge, is sent to specific offices that maintain juvenile records such as the Clerk of Courts, the Office of the District Attorney, the local Police Department, and the Juvenile Probation Department.&#160; The Order gives each agency at least thirty (30) days to expunge the records and return an Affidavit which certifies its compliance.&#160;&#160; However, PENNDOT is not required to destroy its records, so any adjudication that resulted in a license suspension will still appear on a driving abstract. </p>How do you request an expungement?<p MARGIN: 0in 0in 12pt" class="MsoBodyText">You must first file a Petition with the Court of Common Pleas and provide a copy to the District Attorney who has 30 days to respond. </p>How do I answer questions about prior consent decrees and adjudication after my records are expunged?<p MARGIN: 0in 0in 12pt" class="MsoBodyText">Once a record has been expunged, you no longer have a legal obligation to disclose information about the contents of that record.&#160; </p><p MARGIN: 0in 0in 12pt" class="MsoBodyText"><i mso-bidi-font-style: normal">If you would like to discuss your situation with us, kindly contact Elissa B. Heinrichs, Esq, at Mellon, Webster &amp; Shelly, P.C. (tel. 1-215-348-7700) for a free consultation.<p /></i></p>'
