aS'<a href="http://www.fagellaw.com/Information&#95;Center/Cerebral&#95;Palsy.aspx" title="Cerebral palsy">Cerebral palsy</a> is a neurological disorder caused by damage to the brain before, during, or after birth.&#160; Even though the symptoms of cerebral palsy involve motor coordination problems and affects muscle movement, it is not a disorder caused by damage to the muscles or nerves, but rather by damage to the motor areas of the brain that prevent the brain from properly controlling movement and posture. <br /><br />The majority of children with cerebral palsy are born with the disorder.&#160; Cerebral palsy is not a progressive disorder, meaning it does not worsen over time.&#160; At this time there is no cure for cerebral palsy. <br /><br />Depending on the part of the brain that has been affected, there are a range of symptoms and the severity can range from mild to severe.&#160; Symptoms may include lack of muscle coordination, problems learning, moving, crawling, sitting, walking, talking, seeing, hearing, seizures, developmental disabilities, swallowing, and eating.&#160; Children with cerebral palsy may also have muscle paralysis that can affect the arms or legs. <br /><br />It&#8217;s important to understand that the signs of cerebral palsy may not present themselves immediately after birth, but may take several years to become apparent.&#160; This creates a difficult challenge for parents, especially if the cerebral palsy was the result of medical malpractice, as the statute of limitations places time limits on how long a family may wait to file a lawsuit.&#160; Therefore, if the family suspects the child may have cerebral palsy, they should see a doctor right away.&#160; If is determined the child has cerebral palsy, the family should contact a cerebral palsy lawyer right away.&#160; There are tests a doctor can perform to see if cerebral palsy exists, including a CT scan, neurological examination, EEG, MRI, vision test, hearing test, and blood tests.<br /><br />What are the causes of cerebral palsy<a href="http://www.cerebralpalsydoctorlawyer.com/Cerebral&#95;Palsy/Causes&#95;of&#95;Cerebral&#95;Palsy.aspx"></a>?<br /><br />Cerebral palsy may be caused by many factors including those which may be unknown.&#160; Cerebral palsy may result from a lack of oxygen flow to the brain of the baby, premature delivery, delivery mistakes, severe jaundice that is not treated promptly, brain trauma, and specific infections with the mother including meningitis. &#160;<br /><br />Because cerebral palsy can have a lifetime of consequences for both the child and the family, any case involving a baby with cerebral palsy needs a careful investigation of the facts and circumstances surrounding the labor and delivery to find out if this disorder could have been prevented.&#160; In many cases, evidence in the medical records, including the fetal monitor strip will show significant problems during labor that should have resulted in an immediate response by the medical personnel, including a possible earlier delivery.<br /><br />If your child has been diagnosed with cerebral palsy, medical malpractice may be the cause.&#160; You should contact California cerebral palsy lawyer Dr. Bruce Fagel right away for a free consultation at (800) 541-9376.&#160; Dr. Fagel is a medical malpractice attorney and a licensed medical doctor.&#160; <br /><br />Visit us on Facebook and Twitter:<br /> Facebook: <a href="https://www.facebook.com/birthinjury" title="Facebook">https://www.facebook.com/birthinjury</a><br /> Twitter: <a href="https://twitter.com/fagellaw" title="Twitter">https://twitter.com/fagellaw</a><br /><br /><!--more-->Cerebral palsy is a neurological disorder caused by damage to the brain before, during, or after birth.&#160; If is determined a child\'s cerebral palsy was caused by medical malpractice, the family should contact a cerebral palsy lawyer right away.'
