aS'\r\n\r\n<p class=" " line-height: normal;">WHAT IS\r\nINTERNAL DISPUTE RESOLUTION IN A HOMEOWNERS ASSOCIATION DISPUTE? </p>\r\n\r\n<p class=" " line-height: normal;"> </p>\r\n\r\n<p class=" " line-height: normal;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; This procedure is described in Civil\r\nCode sections 1363.810 et seq.&#160; If a\r\nproperty owner requests internal dispute resolution, the association must\r\nparticipate in internal dispute resolution.&#160;\r\nHowever, if the association requests internal dispute resolution, the\r\nproperty owner is not required to participate in internal dispute\r\nresolution.&#160; The association is required\r\nto provide a fair, reasonable and expeditious procedure for resolving a\r\ndispute.&#160; At internal dispute resolution,\r\na representative of the association, usually a board member and the property owner\r\nmeet and confer in person in an effort to resolve their dispute.&#160; The parties are required to &#8220;explain their\r\npositions to each other, and confer in good faith in an effort to resolve the\r\ndispute.&#8221;&#160; Civil Code section 1363.840\r\n(b)(4).&#160; There are no third parties\r\npresent, such as a mediator or an arbitrator.&#160;\r\nThe property owner has no control over who the association designates as\r\nits representative.&#160; The representative\r\nmight be one board member.&#160; The\r\nrepresentative might be more than one board member.&#160; The representative might be the community\r\nmanager.&#160; There is an on-going dispute\r\nregarding whether attorneys for property owners are permitted to attend\r\ninternal dispute resolution.&#160; This issue\r\nmay have to be decided by a future court case or legislation.&#160; If the property owner and the representative\r\nof the association reach an agreement at internal dispute resolution, the\r\nagreement is to be memorialized in writing and is generally binding on the\r\nparties, subject to certain conditions.&#160; </p>\r\n\r\n<p class=" " line-height: normal;"> </p>\r\n\r\n<div border-width: medium medium 1.5pt; border-style: none none solid; border-color: currentColor currentColor windowtext; padding: 0in 0in 1pt; margin-right: 0in; margin-left: 0.5in;">\r\n\r\n<p class=" " padding: 0in; border: currentColor; line-height: normal;"> </p>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p class=" " line-height: normal;"> </p>\r\n\r\n<p class=" " line-height: normal;">For\r\nmore information on Homeowner Association law, Eminent Domain or other matters\r\ninvolving real estate, please contact Barry A. Ross, Esq. at 949-727-0977;\r\ne-mail:&#160; <a href="mailto:barry@rossrealestatelaw.com">barry@rossrealestatelaw.com</a>; or\r\nvisit our website: <a href="http://www.rossrealestatelaw.com/">www.rossrealestatelaw.com</a>.&#160; For a FREE DOWNLOAD of the California\r\nHomeowner Association Members Guide, please go to <a href="http://www.rossrealestatelaw.com/">www.rossrealestatelaw.com</a>. </p>\r\n\r\n'
