aS'<p class="MsoNormal">\r\nAccording to the U.S. Department of Labor, the trucking industry employs more than three million truck drivers each year. Because the majority of commercial truck drivers cross state lines, the Federal Motor Carrier Safety Administration (FMCSA), which is a branch of the U.S. Department of Transportation, is responsible for establishing and enforcing truck driver regulations. The FMCSA was established in 2000 to prevent commercial vehicle related fatalities and injuries. Before 2000, when the FMCSA was established, truck driver regulations varied from state to state. Due to the inconsistency of truck driver training and regulations, a large number of preventable commercial truck accident injuries and deaths occurred. </p><p class="MsoNormal"><b>Commercial Driver&#8217;s License</b></p><p class="MsoNormal">Any person who operates a vehicle weighing 26,000 pounds or more must hold a commercial driver&#8217;s license (CDL). To obtain a CDL, individuals must pass a written test and a driving skills test in which they must perform a set of required driving maneuvers. The FMCSA requires all CDL applicants to be at least 21 years of age.</p><p class="MsoNormal"><b>Physical Examination</b></p><p class="MsoNormal">The FMCSA requires all truck drivers to pass a physical examination conducted by a licensed medical examiner every two years. During an examination, a truck driver&#8217;s hearing, vision and blood pressure will be checked. The mental health history of the driver will also be reviewed. Truck drivers cannot suffer from epilepsy, heart conditions, vision or hearing issues, alcohol or substance abuse, diabetes or any type of condition that limits their mobility. Truck drivers who do not pass a physical examination are not allowed to operate a commercial truck.</p><p class="MsoNormal"><b>Hours-of-Service</b></p><p class="MsoNormal">To ensure truck drivers are getting the necessary rest to properly perform their job, the FMCSA established regulations on how long a truck driver could drive. Truck drivers who carry cargo may drive a maximum of 11 hours after ten consecutive hours off duty. Truckers who carry passengers may drive a maximum of ten hours after eight consecutive hours off duty. Failure to comply with the FMCSAs Hours-of-Service (HOS) can result in the loss of a CDL.</p><p class="MsoNormal"><b>Experience Matters</b></p><p class="MsoNormal">Unfortunately, because many truck drivers do not comply with regulations, thousands of innocent motorists are still being injured or killed in truck accidents every year in the U.S. If you have been injured or have lost a loved one in a truck collision, a knowledgeable <a href="http://www.sacramento-personalinjurylawyers.com/truck-accident.html">Sacramento truck accident attorney</a> can assist you with the claims process. Due to the involvement of federal and state government agencies, truck accident claims are often difficult to litigate. With an experienced <a href="http://www.sacramento-personalinjurylawyers.com/">Sacramento personal injury lawyer</a> by your side, you can rest assured your case will be properly handled.&#160;&#160;</p><!--more-->According to the U.S. Department of Labor, the trucking industry employs\r\nmore than three million truck drivers each year. Because the majority of commercial\r\ntruck drivers cross state lines, the Federal Motor Carrier Safety\r\nAdministration (FMCSA), which is a branch of the U.S. Department of\r\nTransportation, is responsible for establishing and enforcing truck driver regulations.&#160;'
