aS'An on-going problem facing all employers is the\r\nmisclassification of employees as independent contractors. &#160;The IRS is\r\nextremely interested in the misclassification of employees because it results\r\nin the failure to pay employment taxes. &#160;Taxpayers are concerned because\r\nthe trust fund portion of the amount withheld from an employee&#8217;s compensation\r\nis a personal liability of the officer of the corporation, a liability which\r\ncannot be discharged in bankruptcy. &#160;If you or a client faces such\r\nliability, speak to an <a href="http://www.youtube.com/user/GivnerandKaye#p/u/11/w3jLaxn277E" target="&#95;blank" title="Givner & Kaye">expert asset protection</a> and <a href="http://www.youtube.com/user/GivnerandKaye#p/u/13/bkH1Kjl2yPc" target="&#95;blank" title="Givner & Kaye">tax attorney</a>. On September 19, 2011, the Internal Revenue Service signed\r\na memorandum of understanding with the Department of Labor agreeing to share\r\ninformation and other materials in its efforts to reduce the misclassification\r\nof employees as independent contractors. &#8220;We know we can\'t stop misclassification on our own,&#8221;\r\nLabor Secretary Hilda Solis said. &#8220;By joining forces, we\'ll be more able to\r\nstrategically educate employers and enhance compliance.&#8221; The agreement comes as a part of the Labor Department\'s\r\nMisclassification Initiative that was launched under Vice President Joe Biden\'s\r\nMiddle Class Task Force to prevent, detect, and remedy the misclassification of\r\nemployees. DOL\'s Wage and Hour Division, IRS, and agency leaders from\r\nConnecticut, Maryland, Massachusetts, Minnesota, Missouri, Utah, and Washington\r\nsigned memoranda of understanding to work together to combat the practice by\r\nwhich some employers incorrectly classify their workers as independent\r\ncontractors rather than as employees to avoid paying payroll taxes and workers\'\r\ncompensation expenses. IRS Commissioner Douglas Shulman addressed early press\r\nreports that the move signaled IRS\'s intent to launch new investigations into\r\nthe misclassification of employees by specific industries.&#160; &#8220;The IRS is\r\nnot initiating or participating in any new industry-specific investigations in\r\nthis area,&#8221; he said. &#160;The Department of Labor will refer some cases for\r\nIRS to follow up with further investigation, Shulman said. If you or your company\r\nis the target of an IRS investigation contact an experienced <a href="http://www.givnerkaye.com/contact-us/" target="&#95;blank" title="Givner & Kaye">asset protection\r\nand tax attorney today</a>.\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">There are many factors to consider in\r\ndetermining whether someone providing services to the business is an employee\r\nor an independent contractor.&#160; Penalties for failing to properly classify the person\r\ncan be extremely high as a percentage of that person&#8217;s compensation, and by the\r\ntime the problem is noticed there will be at least three years involved.\r\n&#160;You should talk to an asset protection and tax attorney competent in\r\nemployment classification issues. <a href="http://www.givnerkaye.com" target="&#95;blank" title="Givner & Kaye">www.GivnerKaye.com</a> (310) 207-8008</p><!--more-->An on-going problem facing all employers is the\r\nmisclassification of employees as independent contractors. Here we will discus the risks and liabilities involved.'
