aS"<p>Both young people and adults can be protected through guardianship agreements.&#160; Minor children of deceased parents clearly need a competent adult to act as their legal guardian&#8212;help them reach responsible adulthood and to administer the finances until they get there.&#160; Disabled adults and persons who are no longer able to make their own responsible decisions may also require legal guardians.&#160; <strong>IN FLORIDA, A GUARDIAN MUST BE REPRESENTED BY COUNSEL.&#160;</strong></p><p>The guardian is authorized to make financial, legal, and health care decisions for the dependent, called a ward.&#160; These decisions must be reported to the court regularly.&#160; The court retains the authority to remove guardians who do not adhere to the law or do an irresponsible or inadequate job of caring for the ward's affairs.</p><p>Having a guardian appointed may feel like a loss of dignity, freedom, and control to an elder.&#160; The law does provide some less restrictive alternatives, including&#8212;</p><ul><li>Power of attorney&#8212; The principal grants legal rights to an agent to make decisions, but only when the principal becomes incapacitated.</li><li>Representative or protective payee&#8212;A person is authorized to manage only specific benefits including Social Security, veteran&#8217;s benefits, public assistance, or other entitlement program benefits.</li><li>Revocable trust&#8212;A living trust can be set up with a relative, friend, or financial institution as a co-trustee. &#160; The co-trustee takes over only if the older person becomes incapacitated.</li></ul><p>Gillette Law, P.A. can advise on the relative benefits of the different options, depending on the situation.&#160; <strong>THE KNOWLEDGE OF GUARDIANSHIP LAW FREQUENTLY&#160;BENEFITS OUR PERSONAL INJURY CLIENTRS THAT ARE MINORS</strong>.&#160; </p>"
