aS"<p>Generally, to be eligible to claim tax deductions for medical\r\nexpenses, medical expenses should exceed 7.5% of Adjusted Gross Income\r\n(AGI). This means if a taxpayer's AGI is $60,000, and the medical\r\nexpenses incurred are $10,000, the taxpayer could claim deduction for\r\nonly $5,500 of the $10,000.<br />\r\n</p><p>However, this year, perhaps, we would be able to take some\r\ntax deductions from medical expenses, as our income is relatively lower and a lot of people grapple with unemployment.</p><p>As such, the following could provide some insight into how this tax deduction could be useful: </p><p><b>Some Basic Rules </b></p>\r\n<ul><li>Medical expenses must have been paid with after-tax out-of-pocket dollars.</li><li>The expenses must be for medical treatment not just for maintaining good health, although there are a few exceptions such as annual physical or dental exam.</li><li>Costs are deductible in the year paid in cash or by credit card.</li><li>Medical care does not have to be provided in the US. However, medical drugs from outside the US, must be legally approved for import.</li></ul>\r\n<p><b>Are Medical Insurance Premiums Tax Deductible?&#160;</b></p><p>It depends. Premium insurance premiums must have been paid with after-tax dollars. So, Cobra, Medicare Parts B and D qualify. However, flexible spending plans or health savings do not qualify. </p><p>As such, out-of-pocket co-payments of lab's fees, doctor's fees, drugs, tests and the like may qualify.</p><p><b>What Treatments Are Tax Deductible?</b></p><p>Generally, the kind of treatments the insurance companies often cover are tax deductable such as:</p><ul><li>Physical therapy;</li><li>Eyeglasses and contact lenses (including solutions);</li><li>Acupuncture;</li><li><b></b>Fertility treatments;</li><li>Dentures;</li><li>Wigs for hair loss because of a disease;</li><li>Treatment for Alcohol and Smoking.</li></ul><p>Do not forget, still the 7.5% - threshold explained above - applies.</p><p><b>What Treatments Are Not Generally Deductible?</b></p><ul><li>Baby formula;</li><li>Diapers;</li><li>Cosmetic surgeries;</li><li>Hair transplants;</li><li>Gym memberships;</li><li>Spa treatments;and</li><li>Most over-the-counter drugs.</li></ul>IRS publication 502 provides the full list.<!--more-->In this economy, you might be able to deduct some of your medical expenses from your taxes. See how."
