aS'<p padding-top: 0px; padding-bottom: 1.2em; margin: 0px; line-height: 1.91em; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12.222222328186035px; font-weight: normal;">After you file for bankruptcy, something called an&#160;<a href="http://www.tishbankruptcy.com/Practice-Areas/Stopping-Foreclosure-Repossession-And-Garnishment.shtml" color: rgb(96, 148, 0); font-style: italic;">automatic stay</a>&#160;is immediately ordered by the court. An automatic stay stops creditors and banks in their tracks, at least temporarily. In terms of foreclosures, an automatic stay will slow foreclosure proceedings and may even allow you to keep your home permanently.</p><p padding-top: 0px; padding-bottom: 1.2em; margin: 0px; line-height: 1.91em; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12.222222328186035px; font-weight: normal;">If you decide to file bankruptcy under Chapter 7, the stay provides more time to arrange for other housing or to gather more funds to pay your mortgage. A stay will also temporarily stop repossession activities and keep your utilities on. This will give you time to breathe while you reorganize your life.</p><p padding-top: 0px; padding-bottom: 1.2em; margin: 0px; line-height: 1.91em; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12.222222328186035px; font-weight: normal;">If you file bankruptcy under Chapter 13 filing, the automatic stay gives you the opportunity to restructure your debts and prevent foreclosure altogether. While the stay is in place, you will have time to make delinquent payments on your home mortgage. This means that the stay may keep you from losing your home.</p><p padding-top: 0px; padding-bottom: 1.2em; margin: 0px; line-height: 1.91em; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12.222222328186035px; font-weight: normal;">The automatic stay has many other benefits in bankruptcy. These should be discussed with an attorney so that you fully benefit from the power of the automatic stay in your bankruptcy filing.</p>'
