aS'<p TEXT-ALIGN: left" left"><strong>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; LECOMTE, EMANUELSON and DOYLE</strong></p><div center"><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p TEXT-ALIGN: center; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" center" /><p TEXT-ALIGN: center" center">&#160;&#160; 155 SOUTH MAIN STREET</p><p TEXT-ALIGN: center" center">&#160; PROVIDENCE, RHODE ISLAND 02903</p><p TEXT-ALIGN: center" center">&#160; (401) 454-3111</p><p TEXT-ALIGN: center" center">&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;</p><p TEXT-ALIGN: center" center" /><p TEXT-ALIGN: center" center">PLEASE RESPOND TO</p><p TEXT-ALIGN: center" center">QUINCY OFFICE</p><p TEXT-ALIGN: center" center" /><p TEXT-ALIGN: center; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" center">&#160;&#160;&#160; ATTORNEYS AT LAW</p><p TEXT-ALIGN: center; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" center">&#160;&#160;&#160; BATTERYMARCH PARK II</p><p TEXT-ALIGN: center; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" center">&#160;&#160;&#160; ONE PINE HILL DRIVE, SUITE 105</p><p TEXT-ALIGN: center; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" center">&#160;&#160;&#160; QUINCY, MASSACHUSETTS 02169</p><p TEXT-ALIGN: center; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" center">&#160;&#160;&#160; (617) 328-1900</p><p TEXT-ALIGN: center; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" center">&#160;&#160;&#160; FACSIMILE&#160; (617) 328-2030</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p TEXT-ALIGN: center" center" /><p TEXT-ALIGN: center" center">Philip M. Howe</p><p TEXT-ALIGN: center" center">phowe@lecomtelaw.com</p><p TEXT-ALIGN: center" center">&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;&#95;</p><p TEXT-ALIGN: center" center" /><p TEXT-ALIGN: center" center">Extension 203</p><p TEXT-ALIGN: center" center" /></div><p>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </p><p TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in"><b>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: normal" /><p /><p><b>Re: &#160;&#160; Recent Developments in Massachusetts Insurance Law,</b></p><u>Fourth Quarter of 2010&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </u><p /><p TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The following will summarize the Massachusetts decisions which impact the insurance industry for the fourth quarter of 2010. </p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; <u>CONSUMER PROTECTION</u></b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b><u /></b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b>* <u>The insurer violated the Consumer Protection Act by delaying to make a reasonable settlement offer after liability had become clear.</u></b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b><u /></b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The Appeals Court ruled that the excess liability insurer delayed in making a reasonable settlement offer after liability in the underlying automobile collision case had become clear. The measure of damages was the loss of the use of the $3.5 million offer, that is the interest on that amount, for the period of time from when the insurer should have made a reasonable offer to the date when it did.</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The Court relied on the Supreme Judicial Court&#8217;s decision in <i>Bobick v. United States Fidelity and Guarantee Co., 439 Mass. 652 (2003).</i> The Court ruled that &#8220;&#8230;even where the plaintiff initially rejected a tardy but reasonable offer of settlement, the Supreme Judicial Court has reiterated that &#8216;quantifying the damages for the injury incurred by the plaintiff as a result of [an insurer&#8217;s] failure under G.L.c. 176D, s.&#160; 3 (9) (f), does not turn on whether the plaintiff can show that she would have taken advantage of the an earlier settlement opportunity.&#8217; &#8221; Hopkins<i> v. Liberty Mutual Insurance Company, 434 Mass.556 (2001). </i>Page 4.</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The Court went on to rule,&#8221;&#8230;we think the plaintiffs&#8217; recovery here should not turn on conjecture as to what they might have done had [the insurer] not abused its position&#8230;.Our analysis is informed by the purpose of the statutory scheme, which is not to require the insurer to extend an initial offer that must be accepted by the claimant, but, rather, to initiate the process of settlement negotiations promptly, and thereby facilitate out-of-court resolution&#8230;.&#8217; The statute [ G.L.c. 176D, s. 3 (9) ] does not call for [a] defendant&#8217;s final offer, but only one within the scope of reasonableness.&#8221; Page 5.</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The Court further ruled, &#8220;The record here established that the plaintiffs were injured when the settlement process was inexplicably delayed, thereby compounding their frustrations and fears as a result of prolonged and deliberate neglect of their meritorious claim.&#8221; Page 5.</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The lead plaintiff had been rear-ended by the Insured driver and suffered life-threatening injuries. She was initially hospitalized for over three months. An investigator&#8217;s report to all the insurers within a month of the accident described the accident, the lead plaintiff&#8217;s paralysis and hospitalization. A second report two and a half months later stated that the driver of the Insured truck &#8220;was clearly liable&#8221;. Page 2. The trial judge found that the insurer, &#8220;&#8230;did not delay its settlement offer to conduct the investigation needed to make liability reasonably clear; it delayed it because it thought it would be in a better strategic posture if the offer were postponed until the mediation and it did not wish the mediation to occur until the trial was imminent.&#8221; Page 3.&#160; </p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">Rhodes<b><u> v. AIG Domestic Claims, Inc.,</u></b><b>&#160; 2010 Mass. App. LEXIS 1507 (November 23, 2010)</b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b>* Even though the insurer&#8217;s denial of the claim for defense under a general liability policy was erroneous, it was not an unfair claims practice as it was based on a &#8220;plausible interpretation&#8221; of the policy.</b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The Policy provided for an Automatic Extended Reporting Period for claims against the insured if reported to the insurer within thirty days of the termination of coverage and &#8220;if no other similar insurance is in force&#8230;&#8221; [Page 2.] The Court ruled that the insurer bore the &#8220;burden of proving any applicable exclusion&#8230;&#8221; citing <i>Camp Dresser</i> <i>&amp; McKee, Inc. v. Home Ins. Co., 30 Mass. App. Ct. 318, 568 N.E. 2d 631, 635 (1991). </i>Citing <i>Camp Dresser</i> the Court also ruled that the Court will choose the interpretation of policy language more favorable to the insured where there are two rational interpretations.</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The insured had purchased another policy as &#8220;a renewal policy that was intended to provide seamless, identical coverage from one year to the next.&#8221; [Page 6.]&#160; The Court ruled that this policy did not satisfy the &#8220;other similar insurance&#8221; provision. But, the Court went on to rule, the insurer&#8217;s position, that there was &#8220;other similar insurance&#8221; was &#8220;based on a &#8216;plausible interpretation&#8217; of the policy&#8217;s terms, [and as a result] it did not violate Chapter 93 A [the Consumer Protection statute]&#8221;, even though the denial was erroneous, citing <i>Gulezian v. Lincoln Insurance Co. 399 Mass. 606 506 N.E. 2d 123, 127 (Mass. 1987).</i> [Page 7.]</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">New England<b><u> Environmental Technologies v. American Safety Risk Retention Group, Inc.,</u></b><b> 2010 U.S. Dist. LEXIS 96547 (USDC MA, 2010).</b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; <b><u>CAPTIVE INSURER</u></b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b><u /></b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b>* A captive insurer is bound by M.G.L. c. 176D, the Unfair Claims Practices Act, despite <i>Morrison v. Toys &#8220;R&#8221; Us, 441 Mass. 451 (2004).</i></b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The insurer was the wholly owned subsidiary of the parent, who manufactured the defective lawnmower at issue. The plaintiff recovered a judgment against the lawnmower against the lawnmower manufacturer and then brought an action against the manufacturer and the captive insurer for violations of c. 176D, Section 3, the Unfair Claims Settlement Act. The manufacturer and the captive insurer argued that they were not bound by c. 176D as they were not &#8220;engaged in the business of insurance&#8221;. The captive insurer had no employees and no one from the insurer was involved in the investigation, negotiation or litigation of the underlying claim. [Page 2.]</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The Court ruled that the manufacturer was not in the business of insurance but the captive insurer was, despite the ruling in <i>Morrison </i>that a self-insured toy retailer was not in the business of insurance. The Court found persuasive that the captive insurer is registered as such in Vermont and is regulated by Vermont. It is a for profit entity, &#8220;calculates premiums it charges based on its experience and costs, calls itself an insurance company and has issued a policy that states it provides commercial general liability and other coverage.&#8221; [Page 2.] The Court relied on <i>Barrett v. Massachusetts Insurers Insolvency Fund, 412 Mass. 774, 775-776(1992) </i>and ruled that the captive insurer was formed for business reasons and provided economic advantages to its parent. The Court also found persuasive <i>Miller v. Risk Management Foundation of Harvard Medical Insts., Inc., 36 Mass. App. Ct. 411 (1994)</i> which ruled that the defendant Risk Management had interposed itself&#160; between the captive insurer and the claimant.</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b><u>Lemos v. Electrolux North America, Inc.,</u></b><b> 78 Mass. App. Ct. 376, 2010 Mass. App. LEXIS 1534 (December 2, 2010).</b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; <u>DUTY TO DEFEND</u></b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b>* The Duty to Defend an action alleging malicious prosecution based on an underlying action arose when the underlying action was filed, not when it terminated. As the date of filing the underlying action predated the coverage at issue, there was no duty to defend.</b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The underlying action was filed in January 1998 and terminated April 2000 following settlement. The coverage at issue began in March 2000. The Court ruled that for the purposes of coverage, under an &#8220;occurrence&#8221; type policy, the &#8220; &#8217;occurrence&#8217; is the filing of the [underlying] malicious action, not it&#8217;s termination.&#8221; This follows the majority of jurisdictions. [Citations omitted.] (Page 2.) </p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in">The Court went on to rule, &#8221;A plaintiff suffers actual damages from a malicious prosecution on the filing of the underlying complaint, which at a minimum triggers the need to invest the time, money, and effort to prepare a defense. [FN4] While the termination of the underlying action is a required element and a necessary condition precedent before the malicious prosecution claim accrues for the purposes of the statute of limitations, it is not an event that causes harm to the plaintiff and therefore not an &#8216;occurrence&#8217; within the meaning of the policy&#8221;. (Page 3.)</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in">The Court concluded, &#8220;In fact, information readily knowable by [the insurer] from publicly available court records demonstrated that [the policyholder] dispute with the trust [in the underlying action] had settled well before coverage commenced on March 15, 2000.&#8221;</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b><u>George H. Billings v. Commerce Insurance Company</u></b><b>, 458 Mass. 194, 936 N.E. 2d 408, 2010 Mass. LEXIS 799&#160; (November 4, 2010).</b> </p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; <b><u>DUTY TO DEFEND SEXUAL HARASSMENT</u></b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b>* There is no duty to defend an action for sexual harassment as it comes within the policy exclusion for intentional acts.</b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </b>The Policy excluded coverage for, &#8220;conduct of the Insured or at the Insured&#8217;s direction that is committed with wanton, willful, reckless or intentional disregard of any law or laws that is or are the foundation for the Claim&#8230;&#8221; The Court cited <i>Highland Ins. Co. v. Aerovox, Inc. 424 Mass. 226, 231 (1997)</i> for the ruling that, where the Insured has demonstrated the existence of coverage, &#8220;the burden shifts to the insurer to prove an exclusion applies.&#8221; [Page 6.]</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The Court ruled that in order to satisfy the &#8220;intentional acts exclusion&#8221; the actions at issue need only be done willfully. It is not necessary that they be done with knowledge by the actor that he is breaking the law. The Court ruled, &#8221;The word &#8216;willful&#8217;, even in criminal statutes, means no more than that the person charged with the duty knows what he is doing. It does not mean that, in addition, he must suppose that he is breaking the law.&#8221; <i>American Surety Co. v. Sullivan, 7 F. 2d 695, 606 (2d Cir. 1925).</i> [Page 8.]The Court ruled further that the Insured knew that his actions were wrong as the record from a prior arbitration included findings that he inappropriately touched and propositioned several employees. [Page 7.] The parties had agreed that the arbitration was a final judgment</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b><u>Manganella v. v. Evanston Insurance Company,</u></b><b> 2010 U.S. Dist. Ct. LEXIS 113608; 110 Fair Employment Practice Cases (BNA) 1319 (USDC MA 2010).</b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; <u>ERISA</u></b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b><u /></b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b>*The Plan could, following a Department of Treasury Regulation, eliminate an option for the participant to transfer from the Profit Sharing Plan to the much more profitable Retirement Plan.</b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The employee requested and received before he retired a monthly benefit estimate of $4,775 in retirement benefits. He could at that time have transferred his profit-sharing funds into the retirement plan, but did not. Later, when he tried to exercise his transfer option and begin receiving benefits as previously estimated, the Plan informed him that the Plan had since the prior benefit estimate been amended to foreclose the transfer option. The result was a monthly benefit of $2,200. </p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The Court noted that the U.S. Supreme Court has recognized the &#8220;centrality of ERISA&#8217;s object of protecting employees&#8217; justified expectations of receiving the benefits their employers promise them.&#8221; <i>Cent. Laborers Pension Fund v. Heinz, 541 U.S. 739, 743; 124 S. Ct. 2230, 159 L. Ed. 2d 46, (2004).</i> To that end ERISA memorializes an anti-cutback rule which provides in pertinent part:</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; &#8220; (1) the accrued benefit of a participant under a plan may not be decreased&#160; by an amendment of the plan other than an amendment described in section 1082 (d)(2) or 1441 of this title.&#8221; [Page 4.]</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; But, the Court also ruled in the &#8220;compendium of relevant Treasury Department regulations is a clear grant of safe passage for plan amendments that eliminate transfer options (even when the elimination may have the incidental effect of reducing benefits.)&#8221; [Page 4.]</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The Court was unhappy with its result but, nonetheless, stood by it writing,&#8221; We have warned before, in the ERISA context, that hard cases have a propensity to make bad law.&#8221; <i>Burnham v. Guardian Life Ins. Co., 873 F 2d 486, 487 (1<sup>st</sup> Cir. 1989) </i>[Page 7.]</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><i>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </i></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b><u>Tasker v. DHL Retirement Savings Plan et al.,</u></b><b> 621 F. 3d 34; 2010 U.S. App. LEXIS 20611; 49 Employee Benefits Cases (BNA) 2635 (1<sup>st</sup> Cir. October 6, 2010.</b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; <u>HOMEOWNERS</u></b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b><u /></b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b>* The claim for cracks in the foundation due to settling was excluded under the policy exclusion for &#8220;settling, shrinking, bulging or expansion, including resultant cracking.&#8221;</b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b>&#160;</b>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Cracks in the foundation were caused by the builder&#8217;s use of improper subsurface fill.&#160; The Court ruled that the exclusion applied.</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b><u>Kelley v. Iantosca,</u></b><b> 78 Mass. App. Ct. 147; 935 N.E. 2d 783; 2010 Mass. App. Ct. LEXIS 1348 (2010)</b> </p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><i>&#160; </i>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; <b><u>POLICY INTERPRETATION</u></b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b>* <u>The Homeowner&#8217;s Policy covered damage from seepage of water&#160; but excluded coverage for surface water.</u></b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b><u /></b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The Appeals Court affirmed a summary judgment that there was no coverage based on the above exclusion. The Court relied on <i>Jussim v. Massachusetts Bay Ins. Co.,</i> 415 Mass. 24, 31 (1993) in which the Supreme Judicial Court ruled that the above exclusion foreclosed the insured &#8220;from invoking the train of events rule.&#8221; The Court in the case at bar ruled that, if an excluded event occurs anywhere in the chain of causation, then the insured is not entitled to coverage. (Page 3.)</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; In the instant case, moisture had gotten into the wood sill on the top of the foundation at the back of the house, and the moisture had caused the sill, the adjoining floor joists and wall studs to rot. The insurer&#8217;s expert found that the concrete patio had been installed at a higher grade than the foundation and tipped towards the rear wall of the house. Rotting of the wooden sill and other wooden framing elements of the rear wall of the house was the result of a moist or wet condition caused by surface water in the form of rain or snow. (Page 1.)</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; A detailed Dissent took issue with the majority, arguing that an Endorsement to the Policy created additional coverage for &#8220;Fungi, wet or dry rot&#8221; and asserted that the facts presented exactly the type of damage covered from &#8220;seepage of water over a period of time.&#8221; (Page 4.) The Dissent went on that, &#8220;the surface water exclusion &#8230; simply cannot reasonably be interpreted to negate coverage for rot caused by (hidden) seepage. Interlacing these confusingly drafted paragraphs&#8230;would negate the very existence of the additional coverage.&#8221;&#160; The Dissent relied on <i>Slater v. United States Fid. &amp; Guar. Co.,</i> 379 Mass. 801, 803 (1980) in which the Court ruled that the &#8220;language in an insurance policy must be given its ordinary meaning, however, and construed in the sense that the insured will reasonably understand to be the scope of his coverage.&#8221;(Page 4.)</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b><u>Boazova v. Safety Insurance Company,</u></b><b>&#160; 2010 Mass. App. LEXIS 1610 (December 16, 2010).</b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b><u>COMMENT</u></b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b><u /></b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The extensive Dissent seems to be setting the stage for an appeal to the Supreme Judicial Court. <b>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; <u>PRIVILEGE</u> </b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b>*There was no waiver of the attorney client privilege by the client&#8217;s accidental forwarding to opposing counsel of an email intended only for his own counsel.</b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in">Defense counsel had blind copied his client on an email to opposing counsel.&#160; The client responded to defense counsel but inadvertently hit &#8220;reply all&#8221; intending only to respond to his own attorney. As a result, the email went to opposing counsel who argued that he should be permitted to introduce the email at trial because defense counsel failed to properly preserve its confidentiality.</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in">The Superior Court noted that this was the second time in six months that this had happened. The Court ruled that the privilege had not been waived but the defendant &#8221;&#8230;and his counsel should not expect similar indulgence again&#8230;They, and others, should take note. Reply all is risky. So is bcc. Further carelessness may compel a finding of waiver.&#8221;</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in">The Court found that &#8220;the content of [the client&#8217;s] response [the email] leaves no room for doubt that he intended his communication for his own counsel only. Twenty-eight minutes later, [defense counsel] noticed what had happened, and sent an email to opposing counsel demanding deletion. Opposing counsel declined.&#8221; The Court ruled, &#8220;On balance, and perhaps with some indulgence for human fallibility, the Court finds that [defense counsel] has met his burden of showing that he took reasonable (although not maximum) steps to preserve to preserve the confidentiality of the particular communication in issue.&#8221; [Page 2.]</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in">The Court noted that, &#8220;&#8230; a consensus seems to be emerging in the case law; a client does not lose the benefit of the attorney-client privilege for an otherwise privileged communication through inadvertent disclosure if the client proves that he and his counsel took reasonable steps to preserve the confidentiality of that particular communication. See <i>McMahon v. Universal Golf Construction Corp., 20 Mass. L. Rptr. 59 3, (Mass. Super. 2005); Commerce &amp; Industry Insurance Co. v. E.I. du Pont de Nemours and Company, 12 Mass. L. Rptr. 5744 (Mass. Super 2000)</i> citing<i> In re Reorganization of Electric Mutual Liability Insurance Company, Ltd. (Bermuda), 425 Mass. 419, 412, 681 N.E. 2d 838 (1997).&#8221;</i></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b><u>Charm et al. v. Kohn et al.,</u></b><b> 27 Mass. L. Rep. 421; 2010 Mass. Super. LEXIS 276 (Superior Court of Mass. At Suffolk, September 30, 2010.)</b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b><u>COMMENT</u></b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b><u /></b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; While there are no coverage issues in the <i>Charm </i>decision, the inadvertent disclosure of privileged material is an issue of keen interest to all.</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; <b><u>SUBROGATION</u></b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b><u /></b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b>* When the stolen painting was recovered, the insurer, which had paid the appraised value at the time of the theft, did not own the painting. It simply had a right to reimbursement , with compound interest, of what it had paid.</b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in">The insurer paid the theft claim, which included the appraised amount of the painting. The painting was later recovered and the heirs of the Insured offered to pay the insurer what it had paid on the claim. The insurer argued that it had taken title to the painting under the Subrogation Agreement which the Insured had signed in exchange for the claim payment.</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in">The Subrogation Agreement provided that, &#8220;&#8230;the assured does hereby subrogate to said insurer all right, title and interest in and to the property for which claim is being made hereunder&#8230;Assured also agrees to turn over to said insurer, any such recovery which may be made, or reimburse said insurer in full to the extent of the payment for such property which may be recovered.&#8221; [Page 2.]</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in">The Court ruled that the terms, &#8220;Subrogation and assignment are not the functional equivalent of each other. [citation omitted.] Subrogation is not a direct transfer of ownership of property. Rather, &#8216;[i]t allows the substitution of one person in place of another&#8230; so that he who is substituted succeeds to the rights of the other.&#8217; &#8221; <i>East Boston Savings Bank v. Ogan, 428 Mass. 327, 329, 701 N.E. 2d 903 (1970). </i>When an insurer settles a claim and thereby acquires a subrogation right, whether by agreement or by operation of law, it succeeds to any right of action that the insured may have against a third party whose negligence or wrongdoing caused the loss, and may recover the loss from that person on a pro tan (to the extent of its payment) basis.</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in" /><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b><u>Apthorp v. OneBeacon Insurance Group, LLC et al.,</u></b><b> 78 Mass. App. Ct. 115; 935 N.E. 2d 365; 2010 Mass. App. LEXIS 1342 (October 18, 2010). </b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in">Please contact us if you would like copies of any of the above decisions.</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Very truly yours,<b><u /></b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><b><u /></b></p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Philip M. Howe</p><p LINE-HEIGHT: 150%">PMH</p>'
