aS'The number of baseball players who suffer head injuries and \r\nconcussions is on the rise, leading to speculation that the recent focus\r\n of attention on football players with TBIs may be seeping into the \r\nbaseball world.&#160; At least 18 players have suffered head injuries severe \r\nenough to land on the disabled list this season, five more than were \r\nreported last season.\r\n<p><b>Who Is Most At Risk?</b></p>\r\n<p>While it is easy to see how football players could be in danger of \r\nconcussions or TBIs, fans may have a little more trouble understanding \r\nhow a baseball player is at serious risk.&#160; After all, the players wear \r\nreinforced batting helmets and the catchers wear masks, so they should \r\nbe protected.</p>\r\n<p>However, it turns out that catchers are at the highest risk of \r\nconcussion injuries of any player, representing 55 percent of this \r\nyear&#8217;s DL list for concussion.&#160; One catcher, Boston Red Sox&#8217;s David \r\nRoss, was on the list twice during the season for concussion injuries.&#160; \r\nSome, such as John Jaso, were out for far longer than the normal \r\nseven-day mandated period and have lost the opportunity to play for the \r\nseason.</p>\r\n<p><b>Are There Really More Concussions?</b></p>\r\n<p>Some experts believe that the number of concussion injuries is not \r\nrising but that awareness of these injuries is increasing.&#160; After the \r\nrecent NFL settlement in which the organization agreed to pay players \r\nmillions of dollars to settle old head injury claims, all sports have \r\nbecome aware of the possible implications of a head injury.</p>\r\n<p>Concussions were once thought to be minor, but recent studies have \r\nshown that the effects can linger for months or years after an injury.&#160; \r\nBecause everyone is individual when it comes to healing patterns, it is \r\nimpossible to say which concussions will heal quickly and which will \r\nrequire further intervention or cause further problems.</p>\r\n<p>For those who have been injured in an <a title="accident" href="http://www.scarlettlawgroup.com/practice-areas/automobile-accidents">accident</a> involving a <a title="Traumatic Brain Injury" href="http://www.scarlettlawgroup.com/practice-areas/traumatic-brain-injury">traumatic brain injury</a>,\r\n an attorney may be able to represent your rights and help you recover \r\ndamages from the person, agency, organization or other entity \r\nresponsible for your TBI.&#160; You may be able to recover money to pay for \r\nmedical treatment and other expenses, depending on the nature of your \r\ninjury.</p>'
