aS'I have, on numerous occasions, heard successor Trustees tell me that \r\nmom, dad, grandma, or grandpa &#8220;put me in charge and I&#8217;ll do things my \r\nown way when I decide to do them.&#8221; If this is the attitude the Successor\r\n Trustee takes he/she will more than likely get sued by one or more of \r\nthe beneficiaries.<br /> <br /> The Successor Trustee has specific duties that are spelled out in the Trust\r\n document and the Probate Code. The Successor Trustee owes a fiduciary \r\nduty to the original Settlor(s) (person who initially established the \r\nTrust) above any other person. If the Settlor(s) has passed away, that \r\nfiduciary duty shifts to the remainder beneficiaries of the Trust. A \r\nfiduciary duty means that the Successor Trustee must place the interests\r\n of the other beneficiary(ies) above their own. This principal must \r\nalways be kept in mind when making Trustee decisions.<br /> <br /> Few \r\npeople have experience in Trust Administration and would benefit from \r\nthe counsel and direction of an experienced estate planning attorney to \r\nassist them in reducing their personal liability.'
