aS'<p left">A/DISCLAIMER TRUST</p><p left">The <a href="http://www.wightlawoffice.com">A/Disclaimer Trust</a> is just like the <a href="http://www.wightlawoffice.com">A/B Trust</a>, with the only difference being the Surviving Spouseis not required to create the B Trust, but has the option of creating the B Trust based on the size of the estate and federal estate taxes. After the first spouses away, the Surviving Spouse would decide whether to create the B trust based on the size of the estate and the estate taxes in effect at the first spouse&#8217;s death. For example, if the estate tax exemption amount was 2 million at the first spouse&#8217;s death and the estate was valued at 4 million, the Surviving Spouse would create the B Trust and place 2 million in the B Trust and 2 million in the A Trust. Each spouse would receive the 2 million exemption which would allow the entire estate to pass without estate taxes upon the Surviving spouses death if the same 2 million exemption amount was in effect at the Surviving spouses death. The advantage of the A/Disclaimer Trust is the flexibility it allows in not creating the B Trust if it is not necessary. The disadvantage of the A/Disclaimer is the possibility of estate taxes in the event the law changes after the first spouse passes away and not protecting the deceased spouse&#8217;s assets in the event the B Trust is not created and the Surviving Spouse remarries.</p><p left" /><p left">For more information on <a href="http://www.wightlawoffice.com">San Diego estate planning law</a>, please visit our website <a href="http://www.wightlawoffice.com">http://www.wightlawoffice.com</a>. </p>'
