aS'<p color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; line-height: 19px; ">The very nature of an Article 9 security interest is that it is created by contract. It results from an agreement between the debtor and one of his or her creditors. However, the security interest created may be of concern to and possibly affect the rights of third parties.&#160; Because bankruptcy affects the rights and priority of creditors, it is very important for creditors to become fully secured in the interest so that they will get paid in full.&#160; Thus, to understand how a creditor becomes fully secured it is essential to understand the concept of attachment.</p><p color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; line-height: 19px; ">Under Article 9, if a security interest has been created and becomes enforceable as between the two parties, the debtor and the secured property, with respect to a particular piece of property, then it has&#160;<em>attached&#160;</em>to that property. Stated another way, the collateral owned by the debtor is attached to contract when a security interest is created. If the security interest has not attached, it isn&#8217;t enforceable by or against anybody and it is worthless.</p><p color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; line-height: 19px; ">Accordingly, section 9-203(b) provides that a security interest is enforceable against the debtor and third parties with respect to collateral only if three criteria are met. First, value must have been given by the secured party to the debtor.&#160;This means the secured party must give something of value in some form or another (generally money) to the debtor.</p><p color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; line-height: 19px; ">Second, the debtor must have actual rights in the collateral. This means the debtor must have ownership or at least the power to transfer rights in the collateral.</p><p color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; line-height: 19px; ">Third, there must be a signed a security agreement covering the collateral granting the security interest to the creditor. Although some transactions attach automatically and do not require a signed security agreement, this is the general process by which a security interest attaches. In some instances it will be sufficient for the agreement to be oral. However, most often it is a written otherwise recorded security agreement authenticated by the debtor.&#160; Therefore, if any of these three conditions are not met, the transaction fails to create a security interest in the collateral.</p><p color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; line-height: 19px; ">So attachment of a security interest is about as fundamental as you can get in a secured transactions. Although a creditor also needs to &#8220;perfect&#8221; the security interest in addition to attaching, this process can be very confusing depending on the type of collateral.</p><p color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; line-height: 19px; ">If you are thinking about granting or obtaining a security interest, it is extremely important to know and understand your rights whether you&#8217;re a creditor or a debtor. &#160;Contact Roddy Lanigan or Eric Lanigan of Lanigan and Lanigan, P.L., in Winter Park, Florida. Our attorneys know the ins and outs of Article 9 secured transactions and will make sure your collateral is protected.</p>'
