aS'<p>In the wake of the Casey Anthony trial, newfound scrutiny is being directed toward the burden of proof and its role in criminal and civil proceedings.&#160; How could the jury acquit Ms. Anthony in light of the seeming abundance of circumstantial evidence and suspicious behavior?&#160; The answer likely lies in the burden of proof.&#160; The burden of proof is the obligation that a party has to prove his or her claims or defenses.&#160; Trials, in the civil realm and criminal realm, do not determine actual guilt or innocense.&#160; Juries are tasked with determining, based upon the evidence submitted to them at trial, whether the party with the burden of proof has met their burden.&#160; Even where a juror personally believes that an individual has committed a crime, that juror has a duty to acquit a defendant when the prosecutor does not meet the burden of proof.</p><p>In criminal trials, a prosecutor representing the state bears the burden of proof.&#160; The state must prove its case beyond a reasonable doubt.&#160; What constitutes reasonable doubt depends upon the common sense of a reasonable person.&#160; Reasonable doubt is defined in the Colorado Jury Instructions as follows:</p><p>Reasonable doubt means a doubt based upon reason and common sense which arises from a fair and thoughtful consideration of all the evidence, or the lack of evidence, in the case.&#160; It is not a vague, speculative, or imaginary doubt, but one that would cause reasonable persons to hesitate to act in maters of importance to themselves.</p><p>CJI Civil, 4th: 3:3.&#160; Reasonable doubt is the highest burden of proof required by the American legal system, and poses a daunting hurdle to prosecutors.&#160; In some cases, a defendant may chose not to put on any evidence.&#160; Defendants may chose to call no witnesses and cannot be compelled to testify.&#160; Because the burden of proof lies with the state, and the defendant has no obligation to prove his or her own innocense, a defendant may chose to limit their case to cross examination of state witnesses and opening/closing remarks.</p><p>In civil trials, the plaintiff bears the burden of proof.&#160; Like defendants in criminal trials, defendants in civil trials do not have an evidentiary burdens to meet, with the exceptions of certain affirmative defenses.&#160; If the plaintiff fails to meet his or her burden in proving the case, the jury is required enter a verdict for the defendant.&#160; However, the burden of proof is different in a civil case as opposed to a criminal case.&#160; The burden of proof in a civil case is preponderance of the evidence.&#160; To prove something by a preponderance of the evidence means to prove that it is more probably true than not.&#160; It is often remarked that the preponderance of the evidence standard only requires the plaintiff to prove his or her case by 50.01 percent.&#160; The preponderance of evidence standard is considered to be significantly lower standard than the beyond reasonable doubt standard.&#160; In many cases where an individual is found not guilty in a criminal case, liability has been found in a civil action.&#160; Perhaps the most famous example of this deviation is the case of O.J. Simpson, who was acquitted or murder in a criminal case but held liable in a civil suit.&#160; </p><p>Finally, in some situations, courts use a third standard, called clear and convincing evidence.&#160; The clear and convincing evidence standard is a standard between preponderance of the evidence and reasonable doubt.&#160; A fact has been proven by clear and convincing evidence if a juror finds it to be highly probable and no serious doubt exists.&#160; Oftentimes, the clear and convincing evidence standard is used in specific parts of criminal and civil trials where lawmakers think the burden should be higher or lower than the burden typically used.&#160; For instance, after Jon Hinckley Jr. was found not guilty by reason of insanity in the attempted assassination of Ronald Reagan, Congress passed the Federal Insanity Defense Reform Act, 18 U.S.C. &#167; 17.&#160; Under this act, the burden of proof is upon the defendant to prove insanity by clear and convincing evidence in a federal criminal case.&#160; Under Colorado law, juror damages for non-economic losses are capped at $250,000.00, adjusted for inflation, under C.R.S. &#167; 13-21-102.5.&#160; However, if the court finds by clear and convincing evidence that a higher amount is justified, the non-economic loss award can be raised.</p><p>The burden of proof shapes the proceedings and strategies employed in criminal and civil courts.&#160; If you are an injured victim, it is important to remember that you bear the burden of proving your case by a preponderance of the evidence.&#160; If you or a loved one have been injured, call the attorneys at Bell &amp; Pollock today.\r\n\r\n</p><p>If you or a loved one has been injured, call the law firm of Bell &amp; Pollock, P.C., 303-795-5900 or <a title="Denver Injury Attorneys" href="www.bellpollock.com">www.bellpollock.com</a> and <a title="Denver Injury Attorneys" href="www.championsofthepeople.com">www.championsofthepeople.com</a>, Denver Injury Attorneys, Champions of the People.&#160; You can access all of our free podcasts on our website, just click on &quot;Bell &amp; Pollock on the Radio&quot; </p><!--more-->If you or a loved one has been injured, call the law firm of Bell &amp; Pollock, P.C., 303-795-5900 or www.bellpollock.com and www.championsofthepeople.com,\r\n Denver Injury Attorneys, Champions of the People.&#160; You can access all \r\nof our free podcasts on our website, just click on &quot;Bell &amp; Pollock \r\non the Radio&quot;'
