aS"The <i>LA Times</i> reported last week, &#8220;Baseball has a long way to go to match the NFL when it comes to embarrassing off-the-field issue&#8230;but with six players having been cited for drunk driving this year, the commissioner's office is seeking wider powers to discipline players involved in alcohol-related incidents.&#8221;<br /><br />After reading the headline, &#8220;Bud Selig seeks ability to discipline off-the-field alcohol-related offenders,&#8221; I remember thinking just how important it is that people in a position of power have the ability to shape our social norms and spread awareness about vital issues like drug and alcohol related offenses, including DUI.&#160; &#160;<br /><br />For example, the <i>Times</i> quoted Pat Courtney (a spokesman) saying the following, &quot;Obviously, any time a player is arrested for DUI or illegal conduct, we're concerned,&quot; and &quot;Alcohol issues are certainly an issue we'll be taking up in negotiations for a new Collective Bargaining Agreement.&quot;<br /><br />This is such great news for everyone and especially for younger fans.&#160; After all, Major League Baseball (MLB) players are considered to be heroes for much of our nations&#8217; youth.&#160; It is refreshing to hear that even though celebrity status might already be attached, the pressure is on to regulate the actions any offender. <br /><br />The Collective Bargaining Agreement (CBA) between MLB and the players union expires Dec. 11 and as part of the negotiations underway, MLB is asking for a provision that would allow Commissioner Bud Selig to discipline players linked to &quot;drugs of abuse&quot; or other illegal conduct away from the workplace, according to the <i>Times</i>. &#160;<br /><br />The bottom line is, players who test positive for marijuana and cocaine are currently ordered to counseling but more can always be done.&#160; The problem with drinking and driving seems to also be on the rise in 2011. &#160;<br /><br />For instance, Cleveland Indians outfielder Shin-Soo Choo is the most recent player to be cited for driving under the influence, the report indicated.&#160; He was stopped by police recently in Sheffield Lake, Ohio, and given a Breathalyzer test that showed the player had a blood-alcohol level of .201 (more than double Ohio's legal limit of .08) said the <i>Times</i>.<br /><br />Others on the list include Choo's teammate, Austin Kearns, Seattle's Adam Kennedy, Detroit's Miguel Cabrera, Oakland's Coco Crisp and Atlanta's Derek Lowe, all of whom have been arrested since Jan. 1 for suspicion of DUI. &#160;<br /><br />Hopefully, if the Commissioner gets his way, the overall number of future offenses will drop and news reports about players will focus more on their ability to entertain America with their skills on the field and not their exploits off it. &#160;"
