aS"<p>\r\n\r\nThe new Transfer on Death Instrument recently enacted in Illinois has a hole in its administration that might prove costly to those you use it and lawyers who recommend it or fail to warn of its probelms.</p><p>The new instrument was meant to avoid probate by having real property transferred at death with having to go to court.&#160;&#160; A person could designate someone to receive the property at their death and that is why it is called an &quot;Instrument&quot; and not a &quot;Deed&quot; because it conveys no present interest upon its execution.</p><p>Here's the problem: the person receiving the property may be restricted from selling it or otherwise encumbering it for two years after the death of the Grantor.</p><p>EXAMPLE:&#160;&#160; Uncle Hiram finds that he has only three legal heirs: Moe, Larry and Curley. He decides to leave the farm to Curley because he was the funny one.&#160; Instead of doing a Will which would require Probate, his lawyer advises him to use the new TRANSFER ON DEATH INSTRUMENT.&#160;&#160; Uncle Hiram pens in Curley.&#160; Uncle Hiram passes on.&#160; Curley&#160; is not really a farmer at heart.&#160;&#160; It takes someone with defective olfactory processes or a strong stomach and Curley has neither.&#160; He wants to sell the place --- not so fast.&#160; Moe and Larry are not happy heirs.&#160;&#160; Without their permission, Curley can't sell the place for TWO YEARS.</p><p>If Uncle Hiram had willed it, the probate court would have given Moe and Larry six months to contest the Will but that would have been the cutoff and Curley would have been home free.&#160; Instead, he has to run the place or hire someone to run it for an additional EIGHTEEN MONTHS longer than what probate would have taken.&#160;&#160; Moe and Larry don't have to hire a lawyer and contest the Will --- just do nothing and refuse to comply with Curley's sale of the farm.&#160;&#160; Might cause Curley to pay a visit to Uncle Hiram's lawyer with a lawyer of his own.</p><p>As they say, doctors bury their mistakes; lawyers put their's in writing, often have them notarized and then filed with the courts forever or in some dark chasm of a law firm's musty storage rooms awaiting retrieval.</p><p /><p>Dave Blocher</p><p /><p /><p /><p>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;</p><!--more-->The new Illinois TRANSFER ON DEATH INSTRUMENT can have unintended consequences --- user beware!"
