aS'<p>When people die without wills (intestate), the decision on how to divide assets falls to probate court.&#160; Throughout Arkansas, including Little Rock, probate laws state that the assets are divided, according to specific rules, between the members of the immediate family.&#160; In fact, probate court gets involved even when a will is present.&#160; </p><p>Some arguments against probate and <a href="http://www.plastiraslawfirm.com/aop/little-rock-probate/" target="&#95;blank">probating a will in Little Rock</a>&#160;are included below.</p><ul><li>It is expensive</li><li>Assets can be tied up in probate for an extensive period of time, especially if anyone contests the will</li><li>Even for uncontested wills, there are concerns about how long it will take for court proceedings to run their course and release the assets</li></ul><p>If you are considering protecting your beneficiaries in Arkansas, you should contact a probate and <a href="http://www.plastiraslawfirm.com/who-we-are/" target="&#95;blank">gift tax attorney in Little Rock</a>.&#160; This article was provided by The Plastiras Law Firm, located 101 South Spring Street, Suite 300, Little Rock, Arkansas 72201.</p><!--more-->When people die without wills (intestate), the decision on how to divide assets falls to probate court.&#160;Some arguments against probate and <a href="http://www.plastiraslawfirm.com/aop/little-rock-probate/" target="&#95;blank">probating a will in Little Rock</a>&#160;are included below.&#160; If you are considering protecting your beneficiaries in Arkansas, you should contact a probate and <a href="http://www.plastiraslawfirm.com/who-we-are/" target="&#95;blank">gift tax attorney in Little R'
