aS'<p>In two recent blogs I wrote of releases that organizations are increasingly using to preclude a <a title="Boston Injury Lawsuit" href="http://www.boston.com/business/articles/2010/06/25/goodyear&#95;families&#95;settle&#95;miss&#95;crash&#95;lawsuit/" target="&#95;blank">lawsuit</a> for negligence as a result of an athletic activity. The release operates prospectively such that it will bar a future claim. At the end of a case, another type of release is used, and that is the acknowledgement of the receipt of a sum of money in a settlement in return for a release of all claims. You will note that it is appropriate to use the term &#8220;release&#8221; in both contexts despite the term having very different implications for the person who sues. </p><p>What does the release which arises as the result of a settlement mean? It ends a case against that defendant regardless of what may occur with respect to the <a title="Boston Personal Injuries" href="http://www.feinbergalban.com/practice-areas/Personal-Injury/" target="&#95;blank">injuries</a>. In other words, even if the injury worsens such that surgery is necessitated, the person releasing, the releasor, acknowledges that this is &quot;a full and final release&#8221; of all claims and its purpose is to preclude forever any additional claims. This acknowledgement recognizes that any further medical treatment is the burden of the releasor. </p>Two recent blogs dealt with the issue of settling one claim against one of several defendants. The release of all claims as against one defendant will not stop the person from proceeding against the additional defendants. Two caveats should be considered: it is wise to have the release explicitly reference the fact that the case will proceed against the additional defendant(s) and, secondly, all tactical considerations should be considered in resolving a case against one but not all of the defendants.<!--more-->Law firm of Feinberg &amp; Alban, experienced in handling cases related to <a title="Injury Lawsuit in Boston" href="http://www.feinbergalban.com/" target="&#95;blank">injury lawsuit in Boston</a>, discusses various implications of a release from a legal perspective...'
