aS'<p>Both individuals and businesses in Raleigh generally have two options for filing bankruptcy:</p><ul><li>Those with little or no income and few assets may qualify for a liquidation bankruptcy under Chapter 7.&#160; This form of bankruptcy is generally considered to be the simplest form&#8212;most assets are sold, with the proceeds used to repay certain creditors at least part of what they are owed.&#160; The bankruptcy laws allow individuals to keep certain assets, but it is important to note that not all types of debt can be eliminated&#8212;certain debt, such as taxes, child support, and a host of others must be repaid.</li><li>Those who qualify as having enough income to repay debt can file for other forms of bankruptcy, under which they restructure loans so they can be repaid over an extended period, often as many as five years.<br />The procedures for filing bankruptcy vary based on the type of bankruptcy that the debtor qualifies for.&#160; </li></ul><p>In general, however, any bankruptcy filing will follow a process similar to the following:</p><ul><li>Obtaining the credit counseling that is a legal requirement before filing bankruptcy</li><li>Choosing the right type of bankruptcy based on your situation</li><li>Gathering detailed financial information required for the court to determine qualification for bankruptcy and itemize each debt item that must be dealt with during the bankruptcy process</li><li>Filing a petition for bankruptcy within the court</li><li>Working with court-appointed trustees and creditors to reduce or eliminate your debt based on the type of bankruptcy being filed</li><li>Finalizing the process that must be followed for repayment or dissolution of debt in court</li><li>Working through whatever liquidation or debt repayment process required by the court</li></ul><p>Even a so-called simple <a href="http://www.jnl-law.com/aop/Raleigh-bankruptcy/chapter-7/">Raleigh Chapter 7 bankruptcy</a> filing can be complicated.&#160; Failure to properly complete even one form can abruptly halt the process.&#160; And, any debt details that were missed are not protected by bankruptcy law, so debtors can find themselves still facing debt problems after the bankruptcy process is complete.<br />Getting guidance from a qualified Raleigh bankruptcy attorney offers the best chances for obtaining the fresh start offered by bankruptcy.&#160;&#160; </p><p>Joshua Levy is a <a href="http://www.raleigh-nc.org/portal/server.pt?space=CommunityPage&cached=true&parentname=Login&parentid=0&in&#95;hi&#95;userid=2&control=SetCommunity&CommunityID=208&PageID=0" target="&#95;blank">Raleigh</a> bankruptcy lawyer with the skills you need to help you through every step of the process.&#160; When you need a bankruptcy lawyer in Raleigh, Levy Law Offices have the experience to get the fresh start you need.</p><p>Levy Law Offices<br />140-B Wind Chime Court<br />Raleigh, NC 27615 </p><!--more--><a href="http://www.jnl-law.com/attorneys/">Raleigh bankruptcy attorney</a>, Joshua Levy, discusses the steps to filing bankruptcy in Raleigh, NC.'
