aS'<p /><p>Every country aspires to export goods and services abroad.&#160; This not only boosts the economy of the country in question, but promotes the country itself and may lead to the ability to more easily import goods and services at more favorable rates.&#160; However, the import export business is a difficult one for even seasoned business people to master.</p><p>While starting any import export venture is difficult, you can take a number of steps to help ease the process.</p><p>-&#160;<b>Use industry directories. </b>Before setting up an import export venture, always be fully aware of the industry directories of foreign countries.&#160; These contain a great deal of information regarding possible import export activities, and are often available via consulates and embassies.</p><p>- <b>Communicate with the consulate</b>. You must also communicate directly with the consulate of the particular country with which you wish to do business in your own country, in order to establish the products you want to trade.&#160; Countries often maintain lists of products available for import and export in order to help you make these decisions.</p><p>-&#160;<b>Contact the taxation department of your home country.</b> You must do so in order to obtain a registration number and ensure you are complying with all of your local import export business regulations.&#160; The requirements can vary greatly from country to country regarding import and export, and additional documentation or licenses may be required to trade in certain products abroad.</p><p>-&#160;<b>Check the trading relationship between your country and the countries with which you wish to trade. </b>&#160;There may be embargoes or other trade restrictions set against the countries where you wish to do business.</p><p>- <b>Hire custom brokers.</b>&#160; Small businesses that do their own shipping paperwork often run into lengthy delays at ports and borders.&#160; Custom brokers know the best ways to avoid these delays.&#160; And, regardless of how prepared you are, be ready for diversions and detours that might unexpectedly arise.</p><p><em><strong>Import export lawyers | </strong></em><a href="http://www.customslawyer.net/"><em><strong>Customs attorneys</strong></em></a></p><p /><p>Do not let U.S. Customs issues negatively affect your business. Let one of our <a href="http://www.customslawyer.net/attorney-profiles/">import law attorneys</a> at Peter S. Herrick, P.A. help you.&#160; For a free opinion of your dispute with U.S. Customs or your maritime law issue, call us toll free at 1-888-341-9952 or <a href="http://www.customslawyer.net/contact-us/">contact us online</a>.&#160; Peter S. Herrick, P.A. has locations in the ports of Miami and Long Beach.&#160; As a federal law practice, we represent clients in virtually every U.S. port.</p>'
