aS'<p>Probate in California is defined as legally settling the deceased&#8217;s property, which is referred to as their estate.</p><p>If a will has been drafted, it names an executor of the estate. The executor then contacts a probate attorney in the county were the person was a resident. Once the will is admitted to probate, the executor is responsible for carrying out the decedent&#8217;s written instructions and completing the probate process.</p><p>The California probate process generally includes the following stages to ensure that debts are paid and assets are properly transferred: Heirs and beneficiaries are notified of the proceedings and the petition for appointment of the personal representative. Next, the personal representative (or executor or administrator) is appointed by the court. After that, all creditors are given the opportunity to file claims against the estate and the property is inventoried. Finally, once the probate court is satisfied that all procedures have been properly followed, the court issues an order establishing how the estate must be distributed. A full probate will take a minimum of six months and all filings are part of the public record.</p><p>Certain possessions and property are not subject to probate proceedings. For example, a life insurance policy payout can be paid to a beneficiary designated on the policy without being approved by the probate court. Other types of possessions and property that do not go through probate include: anything that is held in joint tenancy, community property or is titled as &#8220;payable upon death&#8221;.</p><p>California residents who have assets with a gross value of more than $100,000 that are not held in a trust or as stated above will need to go through the probate process. This amount includes the gross value of their real estate assets. So, a $250,000 house with a<br />$249,000 mortgage is counted as having a gross value of $250,000!.</p><p>Your <a href="http://www.generationsprobate.com/">Sacramento estate planning attorney</a> can help you decide if a will or a trust is the proper instrument for you and your family.</p><!--more--><p>Your <a href="http://www.generationsprobate.com/">Sacramento estate planning attorney</a> can help you decide if a will or a trust is the proper instrument for you and your family.</p>'
