aS'<p>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; As everyone knows, some lawyers spend a lot of time and money advertising on television, in phone books, on billboards, and in other media as well. &#160;Recently, the Indiana Supreme Court has made changes to the Indiana Rules of Professional Conduct that will impact how some lawyers market their practices.&#160;&#160; Specifically, the <a href="http://www.in.gov/judiciary/supreme/">Indiana Supreme Court</a> has issued <a href="http://www.in.gov/judiciary/press/2010/1015.html">new rules of professional conduct</a> (the changes may be read in their entirety <a href="http://www.in.gov/judiciary/orders/rule-amendments/2010/prof-conduct-1014.pdf">here</a>) which go into effect January 1, 2011.&#160; One of the new rules is that attorneys must wait <a href="http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/sns-bc-in--accidents-lawyers,0,4156775.story">30 days</a> before contacting potential clients with a solicitation of any kind.&#160; Accident victims are still free to contact an attorney at any time.&#160; This is a form of advertising that Greene &amp; Schultz has <i>never</i> engaged in.&#160; However, it is lawful and will now simply have some minimal regulations placed on it.&#160; </p><p TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in">Unless you have been in a car accident in the last seven to ten years, you may not even be aware that this practice has been going on.&#160; &#160;This type of marketing is what is known as &#8220;Direct Mail&#8221; and works something like this: Police reports from car accidents are <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Public&#95;records">public records</a>.&#160; Lawyers with active Direct Mail marketing campaigns then purchase copies of police reports and send advertising solicitations in the mail to the person who was not &#8220;at fault,&#8221; hoping to sign them up as clients.&#160; I&#8217;ve seen many of these solicitations, and they range from one page letters with a refrigerator magnet included, to high gloss multi-page brochures.&#160; Some even include videos or DVDs.&#160; Most of the material is quite professional and would be something a person might expect to receive after they had already retained a lawyer&#8217;s services, or had the person initiated the contact with the law firm(s).</p><p TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in">Over the last seven years, this practice has grown to the point where people who are involved in accidents get ten to fifteen packets in the mail from different lawyers.&#160; Clients of mine frequently marvel that they would get so much mail from lawyers just two or three days after the wreck that they couldn&#8217;t get it all out of their mailboxes.&#160; This form of advertising is effective because it is a direct solicitation aimed at a specific group of people who have a significantly higher probability of needing or considering legal assistance than the general public.&#160; However, while it is effective, it is also highly objectionable to many people who are the unsuspecting recipients of these solicitations.</p><p TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in">At Greene &amp; Schultz, we try to make very thoughtful advertising decisions that weigh both the effectiveness of our marketing with how we think we will be perceived by the public.&#160; If we believe the public will perceive us to be &#8220;just another ambulance chaser&#8221; then we will choose not to advertise in that particular manner.&#160; Some of you may have even heard our office&#8217;s advertisements on the radio and our sponsorships of <a href="http://www.npr.org/">NPR</a> or <a href="http://www.pbs.org/">PBS</a>.&#160; Advertising professionals sometimes refer to the overall effort of a business to market their firm as &#8220;branding.&#8221;&#160; It&#8217;s no surprise that Betsy and I hope the Greene &amp; Schultz &#8220;brand&#8221; with the public stands for our core beliefs of being excellent trial lawyers who fight for our clients against giant insurance companies, not ambulance chasers who are only interested in making a fast buck.</p><p TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in">There is certainly nothing wrong with advertising one&#8217;s business and I am not insinuating that lawyers who advertise in ways that our firm doesn&#8217;t are somehow doing something ethically wrong.&#160; I don&#8217;t believe that to be the case.&#160; Most people forget that before he was the 16<sup>th</sup> President of the United States, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abraham&#95;Lincoln">Abraham Lincoln</a> was a trial lawyer from Illinois, who advertised for clients in a local newspaper.&#160; Really, advertising boils down to a matter of taste and a person&#8217;s preference in how they wish to be perceived.&#160; I am a firm believer that when it comes to advertising, the old adage &#8220;you get what you ask for&#8221; is very applicable.</p><p TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in">Having said all this, there are a few reasons why I believe law firms should not engage in direct mail solicitations, or why I believe the new Rule of Professional Conduct restricting the practice and adding a 30-day waiting period is a good idea.&#160; First, it is simply my belief that this type of advertising is inappropriate because it is much more intentional and personal than radio, television, internet, or phone book.&#160; An injured person or family who has lost a loved one is receiving a packet of information in their mailbox addressed to them from a law firm they did not initiate contact with.&#160; I have had clients tell me that they were &#8220;disgusted,&#8221;&#160; &#8220;offended,&#8221; etc.&#160; One client who lost her son in an accident told me that it did not escape her notice that the law firm sending the packet in the mail to her did so on the day of her son&#8217;s funeral. This not only hurts the image of the law firm sending the direct solicitation, it hurts the image of the legal profession.</p><p TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in">Second, the law firms that send direct mail don&#8217;t know who has been injured and who has not.&#160; Therefore, they send solicitations to many people who aren&#8217;t even injured.&#160; My guess is that well over half the people who receive these solicitations aren&#8217;t even hurt.&#160; Again, this tarnishes the profession because all of these uninjured people tell their friends about receiving packets in the mail from lawyers &#8220;and I wasn&#8217;t even hurt.&#8221;&#160; It makes all of us look like ambulance chasers.&#160; Even worse, it creates a ready-made audience for calls for &#8220;tort reform.&#8221; When non-injured people receive these direct solicitations, it feeds the myth that the <a href="http://www.uschamber.com/legalreform">United States Chamber of Commerce</a> is trying to sell that there are &#8220;too many frivolous lawsuits&#8221; or that &#8220;trial lawyers are wrecking our economy.&#8221;&#160; Enemies of the Civil Justice System are then emboldened to try to restrict an injured person&#8217;s access to the courthouse, and the direct mail solicitations by lawyers are &#8220;Exhibit A&#8221; as to why caps on damages or other &#8220;tort reform&#8221; ideas should be passed into law.</p><p TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in">Opponents to the new rule change argue that insurance adjusters or defense attorneys are not barred from making contact with victims, and this point has been a matter of much debate in <a href="http://www.theindychannel.com/news/25402881/detail.html">public discussion forums</a>.&#160; However, the rule also does not prevent injured parties from contacting a lawyer once they realize that they are dealing with an insurance company that does not have the injured party&#8217;s best interest at heart. In fact, it has been my experience that direct contact by an insurance adjuster who is &#8220;investigating&#8221; the claim makes an injured person realize they need help from a lawyer. </p><p TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in">Incidentally, Indiana attorneys who do not follow our state&#8217;s <a href="http://www.in.gov/judiciary/rules/prof&#95;conduct/index.html">Rules of Professional Conduct</a> can be charged with misconduct. The Indiana Supreme Court has final authority over attorney discipline. To obtain information on an attorney&#8217;s status with the Court visit <a href="http://www.courts.in.gov/citizens">www.courts.in.gov/citizens</a>.&#160; A section titled, &#8220;look up an attorney&#8217;s status with the bar&#8221; allows visitors to learn whether an attorney has been disciplined by the Court. </p><p TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in">We at <a href="http://greeneschultz.com/">Greene &amp; Schultz</a> agree with this rule change and believe that it will help clear the air a little when it comes to public perception of the Plaintiff&#8217;s bar.&#160; To quote <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Randall&#95;T.&#95;Shepard">Chief Justice Shepard</a>, &#8220;Indiana is fortunate the overwhelming majority of attorneys act in a reasonable and honorable manner.&#160; These rule changes are designed to ensure that practice continues.&#8221;&#160; The legal profession always has been, and always needs to be, an honorable profession.&#160; It is in the public interest for lawyers to conduct themselves differently than door-to-door solicitors.&#160; We have the honor of being active participants in the third co-equal branch of both our State and Federal Governments.&#160; Sometimes, we just need to be reminded of who we are, and who we are supposed to be. </p><p TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in"><em>Additional research&#160;compiled by Lori M. Craig, R.P.</em></p><!--more-->It is in the public interest for lawyers to conduct themselves differently than door-to-door solicitors.'
