aS'<p class="WebText">Every day, people suffer injury in accidents caused by negligence on the part of someone else. The types of injuries are as varied as the types of accidents, which include slip and fall accidents, injuries caused by defective products, medical malpractice, and a seemingly endless list of other accidents. But with nearly three million people injured each year in U.S. motor vehicle crashes, these may be the most common accidental injuries.&#160; </p><p class="WebHeading2"><strong>The most typical injuries range from moderate to severe</strong></p><p class="WebText">Not all accidental injuries are severe.&#160; Many will heal completely over time.&#160; But not all accident victims are this fortunate. Depending on the type of injury, many victims can expect their lives&#8212;and the lives of their families&#8212;to change dramatically. The following are some of the most common types of accidental injuries:</p><ul><li><div class="WebBulletList"><b>Fractures.</b> Most fractures occur to the upper and lower limbs, and many are treatable with splints and casts, followed by therapy. However, surgery may be required, particularly for serious hip and knee injuries. While these injuries are common in auto accidents, they are also common in slip and fall and construction site accidents, as well.</div></li><li><div class="WebBulletList"><b>Back injuries.</b> The wrenching motion of a collision is a common cause of back injuries, but any type of fall can cause such injury as well. In the best cases, treatment involves pain medication and physical therapy, but surgery may be required in certain cases.</div></li><li><div class="WebBulletList"><b>Head and neck injuries.</b> While brain injuries are more common in side-impact accidents, neck injuries such as whiplash occur more frequently in rear-end collisions.&#160; And car accidents are not the only cause of head injuries. Head injuries can be the result of slip and fall accidents, and can be common in construction site accidents. In most cases, whiplash heals over an extended period, but it can leave victims with chronic pain. Head injuries may involve traumatic brain injury (TBI), which can lead to temporary or permanent brain function impairment.</div></li><li><div class="WebBulletList"><b>Spinal cord injury.</b> According to <a href="http://www.brainandspinalcord.org/media-center/FactsAboutSCI.html" target="&#95;blank">BrainandSpinalCord.org</a>, about 11,000 new cases of spinal cord injury occur each year, with the majority caused by motor vehicle accidents, slips and falls, and sports or recreation activities. These injuries can be debilitating to both victims and their families, often causing permanent disability in the form of paralysis of the limbs.</div></li></ul><p class="WebHeading1"><strong>Contact an experienced Chicago injury law firm for a free consultation</strong></p><p>From offices in Chicago, the personal injury lawyers of Phillips Law Offices offer quality and comprehensive legal services to the injured and their families throughout Illinois.&#160;With over six decades of experience, our services have earned us many awards&#8212;including <i>Top Lawyers in Illinois</i>, <i>Top 100 Trial Lawyers in Illinois</i>, and <i>Most Million Dollar Plus Settlements in Illinois in a Single Year</i>. We charge on a contingency fee basis. This means you do not pay us anything unless there is a settlement or a winning verdict at trial.&#160; Call (312) 470-6761 today for a free consultation with one of our <a href="http://www.phillipslawoffices.com/" target="&#95;blank">Chicago personal injury attorneys</a> about your case.</p><p>Phillips Law Offices<br />161 N. Clark St., Suite 4925<br />Chicago, IL 60601-3296<br />(312) 346-4262</p><!--more-->Every day, people suffer injury in accidents caused by negligence on the part of someone else. The types of injuries are as varied as the types of accidents, which include slip and fall accidents, injuries caused by defective products, medical malpractice, and a seemingly endless list of other accidents. But with nearly three million people injured each year in U.S. motor vehicle crashes, these may be the most common accidental injuries.&#160;'
