aS'<p class="MsoNormal">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; If you are involved in a child custody case in Illinois there will probably be an independent mental health expert appointed by the judge, called a &#8220;604(b)&#8221; after the statute which authorizes such appointments. These examinations sometimes contain sensitive mental health information and the issue has arisen as to whether these reports are confidential. Most mental health records in Illinois are confidential.</p><p /><p class="MsoNormal">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; However, pursuant to the case of <b><u>Johnston v. Weil</u></b>, a 604 examination is <u>not</u> confidential under the Mental Health Confidentiality Act because there is no therapeutic relationship between the evaluator and the litigant who is evaluated.&#160; The matter was recently decided by the Supreme Court of Illinois (case number 109693).&#160; I on behalf of the American Academy of Matrimonial Lawyers filed an Amicus Brief in that case, which the Court agreed with. The Appellate Court in that case had suggested that motions could be made pursuant to local rule for protective orders to avoid inappropriate dissemination. For example, Cook County Circuit Court Rule 13.4(a)(i)(h) now states that:&#160; <i>&#8220;At the time of the appointment of an evaluation pursuant to 750 ILCS 5/604, the court may issue a protective order prohibiting the parties or their attorneys from disseminating the contents of said report for purposes other than the litigation or to the minor children or to anyone who is not a party to the litigation.&#8221;</i> &#160;Not only can a protective order be obtained by local rule in Cook County, but it has long been available throughout Illinois upon a proper showing.&#160; <b><u>Skolnick v. Altheimer &amp; Gray</u></b>, 191 Ill.2d 214, 730 N.E.2d 4, 13 (2000).</p><p /><p class="MsoNormal" /><p>&#160;</p><p /><p class="MsoNormal">&#160;</p><p /><p class="MsoNormal">&#160;</p><p /><p class="MsoNormal"><br />Paul L. Feinstein<br />Paul L. Feinstein, Ltd.10 South LaSalle Street, Suite 1420<br />Chicago, Illinois 60603-1078<br /><br />Phone &#160;312-346-6392<br />Fax&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; &#160;312-346-0810</p><p /><p class="MsoNormal"><a title="mailto:PFeinlaw@aol.com" href="mailto:PFeinlaw@aol.com">PFeinlaw@aol.com</a><br /><a href="http://www.paulfeinstein.com/">www.paulfeinstein.com</a></p><p /><p class="MsoNormal"><br />Matrimonial Trials and Appeals since 1980</p><p class="MsoNormal"><br />Fellow of the American Academy of Matrimonial Lawyers since 1991</p><p class="MsoNormal">Member, Appellate Lawyers Association</p><p class="MsoNormal">Martindale-Hubbell&#160; AV &#160;Rated</p><p /><p>&#160;</p>'
