aS'I am writing today to discuss a phenomenon that I have been seeing increase in my practice,&#160;especially&#160;as the economy has changed. &#160;I often times joke about it being new spouse syndrome, but the reality is, it is not a joking matter. &#160;<p>We can take two parents who are divorced or who have never been married, but have been able to co-parent their children with no real arguments or fights, and instantly change their dynamic of parenting by adding a new spouse to either side. &#160;Being a step-parent is hard and often times, these individuals want to have more say in the lives of the children. &#160;This is not necessarily a bad thing, as they will be spending a great deal of time with the kids.</p><p>But what I am referring to, is this change of parenting relationship that causes the arguments and fights that we want our children to avoid. &#160;Often times, these can only be resolved in court, and costs for the parties increase. &#160;Most often it is money, but not always.</p><p>It is important to remember, whether you are a new spouse, or have a new spouse, that the children are still the most important factor in your parenting situation. &#160;No matter how angry or upset a party can be about the situation afterwards, conflict resolution is still better for your children. &#160;Utah offers a step-parenting class, and I would recommend this class to anyone who will be a step-parent to take this class with your spouse. &#160;This class can help ease the transition for both the parents and the children at the same time. &#160;</p><!--more-->When adding a new spouse into a parenting relationship, it is important to remember, that you all love and want the best for the children. &#160;A step-parenting class may be an important step in forming those bonds and relationships sooner and resolve many of the conflicts that come between parties after one re-marries or marries for the first time.\t'
