aS'<br /><p>The Social Security Administration offers a variety of programs that can give much needed financial support to you and your family during difficult times. These programs are not mutually exclusive&#8212;you can qualify and receive benefits under more than one program at a time. Social Security Disability lawyers are well versed in these programs and their requirements and can inform you which programs may help you and your family. </p><p><b>Social Security Disability Insurance (SSDI)</b></p><p>If you contributed to the Social Security system and are disabled and unable to work steadily for a year or more, you may qualify for benefits under SSDI. You can usually start receiving these benefits six months after your disability began. The benefits continue so long as you remain disabled and unable to work.</p><p><b>SSDI for you spouse and minor children</b></p><p>Along with the SSDI benefits you receive, members of your household may be entitled to additional <a href="http://www.ssa.gov/pgm/disability.htm" target="&#95;blank">SSDI benefits</a>. Your children under the age of 18 and your spouse may each receive additional monthly payments as high as 50 percent of your monthly benefit amount. Your family members need not be disabled to qualify. Your spouse can collect so long as he or she is caring for your child or children under the age of 16, or is over the age of 62. </p>Your children under the age of 18 may also qualify for payments under SSDI. This includes biological children as well as adopted children, stepchildren, and dependent grandchildren. If your child is a full-time high school student, he or she can remain eligible for SSDI up to age 19. <a href="http://www.buchanandisability.com/do-i-need-an-attorney/">Social Security Disability attorneys</a> often help clients determine if they are eligible for any of these programs. <p /><p><b>SSDI for disabled children over the age of 18</b></p><p>If you qualify for SSDI and have a child who suffers from a disability, he or she may be eligible to receive additional SSDI payments regardless of age. So long as your child meets the <a href="http://www.ssa.gov/">Social Security Administration</a> (SSA) definition of a disabled adult and his or her disability began before age 22, your child can receive additional benefits from the SSA. </p><p><b>Supplemental Security Income (SSI)</b></p>If you are disabled or over 65 and your income and financial resources are below a certain level, you may qualify for monthly SSI benefits. SSI is available to everyone, regardless of work history. Therefore, even if you have not worked enough to qualify for Social Security Disability Insurance (SSDI), you may still qualify for SSI.<p /><p>In addition, the programs are not mutually exclusive. If you do qualify for SSDI, you can still collect SSI benefits in addition to your SSDI benefits. This program is designed to provide a little extra security for families that are struggling because of lost income due to disability. An experienced <a href="http://www.buchanandisability.com/do-i-need-an-attorney/">Social Security Disability attorney</a> can help you to collect benefits from both programs. </p><!--more-->The Social Security Administration offers a variety of programs that can give much needed financial support to you and your family during difficult times. These programs are not mutually exclusive&#8212;you can qualify and receive benefits under more than one program at a time.'
