aS'<p class="MsoNormal" center" margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: center; text-indent: 0.5in;"><b>&#8220;Bueller?... Bueller?... Bueller?&#8221;</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" center" margin-bottom: 6pt; text-align: center; text-indent: 0.5in;"><b>An\r\nUpdate on Truancy Laws</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" center" margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: center; text-indent: 0.5in;">By Andrea L. Mooney, Associate, Eichelbaum Wardell Hansen\r\nPowell &amp; Mehl, P.C.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify;">Now that the school\r\nyear is back in full swing, it is time for schools to review the &#8220;old&#8221; law and\r\nfamiliarize themselves with the new developments in the issue that every\r\ndistrict faces: student attendance.&#160; Of\r\ncourse, it is every school&#8217;s goal that students be consistently present at\r\nschool so that each may meet his or her own individual educational goals and\r\nbenchmarks.&#160; Moreover, with the\r\nadditional pressures placed on schools, including maintaining the average daily\r\nattendance and meeting accountability testing standards, it has become all the more\r\ncritical that every student attend class on every school calendar day.&#160; Unfortunately, sometimes the only way to\r\nresolve the issue of an excessively absent student is to file truancy\r\ncharges.&#160; </p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify;"><b>&#160;</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" margin-bottom: 6pt;"><b>&#8220;Parent\r\nContributing to Nonattendance&#8221;</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify;">As a review,\r\nthe general rule is that a child is &#8220;truant&#8221; if he or she fails to attend\r\nschool for ten or more days or\r\nparts of days in a six-month period or\r\nfor three or more days or parts\r\nof days in a four-week period.&#160; There are two types of truancy charges.&#160; The first is a &#8220;Parent Contributing to Nonattendance.&#8221;&#160; This is a Class C misdemeanor filed against a\r\nparent for failing to require the child to attend school.&#160; This charge is usually most appropriate when\r\nthe excessively absent student is young and unable to be responsible for and\r\narrange for his or her own attendance at school.&#160; The proper procedure for pursuing this charge\r\nis to have the school&#8217;s attendance officer file a complaint against the parent\r\nin a constitutional county court if the county has a population of 1.75 million\r\nor more, a justice court, or a municipal court where the parent resides or the\r\nschool is located.&#160; </p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify; text-indent: 0.5in;">&#160;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" margin-bottom: 6pt;"><b>&#8220;Failure to\r\nAttend School&#8221;</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify;">The second type\r\nof truancy charge, a &#8220;Failure to Attend School&#8221; charge, is a Class C\r\nmisdemeanor filed against a student who is 12 years or older and younger than\r\n18 years.&#160; Generally,\r\njuvenile courts have original and exclusive jurisdiction over these types of\r\ntruancy cases.&#160; Therefore, the proper\r\nprocedure is usually to file a referral to juvenile court. &#160;However, many counties do not have juvenile\r\ncourts.&#160; In those counties, or if a\r\njuvenile court waives its jurisdiction, a &#8220;Failure to Attend School&#8221; charge can\r\nbe prosecuted by filing a complaint in the constitutional county, justice, or\r\nmunicipal court in the same manner as &#8220;Parent Contributing to Nonattendance&#8221;\r\ncases. &#160;In fact, when the truancy charge\r\ninvolves an older student and there is a discrepancy over who the responsible\r\nparty is for the student&#8217;s failure to attend school as required, it is not\r\nuncommon for a school attendance officer to file a &#8220;Parent Contributing to Nonattendance&#8221;\r\ncharge against a parent as well as a &#8220;Failure to Attend School&#8221; charge against\r\nthe student.&#160; </p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify; text-indent: 0.5in;">&#160;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify;">During the 2013\r\nLegislative Session, the Texas Legislature added Subchapter E-1 to the Texas\r\nEducation Code, which provides new procedures that schools should follow to\r\nprosecute and sanction students for &#8220;school offenses.&#8221;&#160; An example of one new amendment is &#167;\r\n37.143(a), under which a peace officer now may not issue a citation to a child\r\nwho is &#8220;alleged to have committed a school offense.&#8221; &#160;In the context of truancy, it is important to\r\nmake the distinction as to whether a &#8220;Failure to Attend School&#8221; charge is\r\nconsidered a &#8220;school offense&#8221; and thus falls under the requirements set forth\r\nin these amendments.&#160; &#167; 37.141(2) defines\r\na &#8220;school offense&#8221; as &#8220;an offense committed by a child enrolled in a public\r\nschool that is a Class C misdemeanor other than a traffic offense and that is\r\ncommitted on property under the control and jurisdiction of a school district.&#8221;&#160; Based on this definition of &#8220;school offense,&#8221;\r\nit seems that these amended provisions are not overly relevant in the context\r\nof a &#8220;Failure to Attend School&#8221; charge since although it is a Class C\r\nmisdemeanor, it is seldom committed on school property (in fact, the offense is\r\na result of the student not being at school when required).&#160; However, it is prudent to be aware of these\r\nnew &#8220;school offense&#8221; amendments, as they apply to all Class C misdemeanors,\r\nother than traffic offenses, that occur on school property.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify;">&#160;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" margin-bottom: 6pt; text-align: justify;"><b>Let&#8217;s Bring the Student Back to School</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify;">The goal of\r\ntruancy standards is not to punish the excessively absent student, but to\r\nreturn him or her to the classroom.&#160; In\r\nthis Legislative Session, the Legislature re-emphasized our state&#8217;s preference to\r\nremedy the underlying issues that are making a student miss school, rather than\r\nimposing consequences for absences after the fact.&#160; As such, beginning September 1, 2013, under\r\nthe newly enacted Texas Education Code &#167; 25.0915(c), if a school district files\r\na truancy complaint without including a statement that complies with Subsection\r\n(b), namely stating that the school applied truancy prevention measures to the\r\nstudent, that the truancy measures failed to meaningfully address the student&#8217;s\r\nattendance, and whether the student is eligible to receive or receives special\r\neducation services, then the court must dismiss the truancy complaint.&#160; In effect, the Legislature is now requiring\r\nthe school to provide evidence of its attempts to address the student&#8217;s truancy\r\nwithout the need for court intervention before the school can pursue truancy charges.\r\nPresumably, this is an attempt by the Legislature to not only assist courts in\r\nmanaging their caseloads, but also to ensure that truancy statutes are carried\r\nout for their intended purpose &#8211; to bolster school attendance, not criminalize\r\nstudents and their parents. &#160;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify; text-indent: 0.5in;">&#160;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify;">The Legislature has also\r\nincreased judges&#8217; discretion in how a student may discharge fines that may be assessed\r\nagainst him or her in the court&#8217;s judgment on a &#8220;Failure to Attend School&#8221;\r\ncharge.&#160; Now, under the newly added Articles\r\n42.15(d)(1) and 45.041(b-3)(1) of the Texas Code of Criminal Procedure,\r\njuvenile court judges and justice and municipal court judges may allow a\r\nstudent to perform community service or receive tutoring as a way for the\r\nstudent to &#8220;work off&#8221; the fines.&#160; This\r\nappears to be another attempt of the Legislature to &#8220;rehabilitate&#8221; the student,\r\nrather than punish him or her financially.&#160;&#160;\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify; text-indent: 0.5in;">&#160;</p>\r\n\r\nApparently,\r\nthe legislative intent behind these new amendments is not to punish students,\r\nbut merely to encourage them to attend school consistently.&#160; Certainly, it is counterintuitive to have a\r\nstudent miss instructional time to attend judicial proceedings on truancy\r\ncharges, and it is definitely not the desire of schools to sully a student&#8217;s\r\nrecord with criminal charges or to make him or her suffer the financial burden\r\nof fines.&#160; Although time will tell if\r\nthese amendments will actually achieve more consistent student attendance, they\r\nappear, at least in theory, to be consistent with school districts&#8217; objectives.&#160;'
