aS"<p>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Just a blog-post reminder, of the importance of not bypassing the application of the Bruner Presumption when a Federal or Postal Employee is separated from service for his or her medical inability to perform his/her job.&#160; It is well-established law that an employee&#8217;s removal for his or her&#160;medical inability to perform the essential functions of&#160;the job or position, constitutes <i>prima facie</i> evidence that he is entitled to disability retirement as a matter of law, and that the burden of production then shifts to OPM to produce evidence sufficient to support a finding that the applicant is not entitled to disability retirement benefits. See <i>Bruner v. Office of Personnel Management</i>, 996 F.2d 290, 294 (Fed. Cir. 1993); <i>Marczewski v. Office of Personnel Management</i>, 80 M.S.P.R. 343 (1998). </p><p>Further, in more recent cases, the Merit Systems Protection Board has held that the Bruner Presumption also applies where &#8220;removal for extended absences is equivalent to removal for physical inability to perform where it is accompanied by specifications indicating that the decision to remove was based on medical documentation suggesting that the appellant was disabled and unable to perform her duties.&#8221; <u>McCurdy</u> v. <u>OPM</u>, DA-844E-03-0088-I-1 (April 30, 2004), citing as authority <u>Ayers-Kavtaradze </u>v. <u>Office of Personnel Management</u>, 91 M.S.P.R. 397 (2002). </p><p>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; If a Federal or Postal employee is about to be removed, a &quot;preemptive action&quot; of attempting to negotiate with the Agency is often a good idea -- to let the agency know that, if the removal action is properly characterized, then the employee will forego his/her appeal rights.&#160; The benefit to the agency is:&#160; they get the vacant position to fill, and no litigation headaches before the Merit Systems Protection Board.&#160; The benefit to the employee:&#160; Application of the Bruner Presumption, and an enhanced chance that his/her disability retirement application will be approved at the First Stage.</p><p>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; On the flip-side, if the termination has already occurred, but it is not characterized as a termination based upon a &quot;medical inability to perform one's job&quot;, then it is often a good idea to file an appeal with the MSPB and attempt to negotiate a change in the substantive basis for the termination.&#160; All of this, of course, presumes that the employee does in fact suffer from a medical condition which impacts his or her ability to perform the essential elements of the job.</p><p>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Sincerely, Robert R. McGill, Esquire</p><p /><p /><p>&#160;</p>"
