aS'<p>Some people mistakenly believe that estate planning is for either those who are wealthy or those who are elderly. On the contrary, however, estate planning is essential for anyone who wants to reap the maximum benefits from their assets during their lifetime and provide for their loved ones after death.&#160; Sometimes, the estate planning process can be complicated - depending on the size of your estate.&#160; However, with proper guidance from an experienced attorney, you can rest assured that your affairs will be in order. </p><p>Listed below are answers to commonly asked questions to help guide you through the estate planning process. </p><p><strong><em>How do I choose a good estate planning attorney?</em></strong></p><p>In addition to having specialized training or experience, good <a href="http://www.longandlongllc.com/greensburg-estates/estate-planning-lawyer/" target="&#95;blank">Murrysville estate planning attorneys</a>:</p><ul><li>Offer a meaningful, free consultation where they discuss options to meet your objectives and help you make informed decisions</li><li>Emphasize the importance of reviewing your estate plan periodically - every two to three years or as certain circumstances change</li><li>Clearly explain how the law firm will charge for the services</li></ul><p><strong><em>What is the difference between a Living Will and a Last Will and Testament?</em></strong></p><p>A <a href="http://www.portal.state.pa.us/portal/server.pt?open=514&objID=616602&mode=2" target="&#95;blank">living will</a> is a written document that states in advance what type of health care and treatment you want in the event that you are incapacitated and unable to speak for yourself.&#160; A last will and testament is a written document that states how you want assets distributed after your death.</p><p><strong><em>What is probate and do I want my estate to avoid it? </em></strong></p><ul><li>Probate refers to the specific process of dealing with a deceased person\'s property.&#160;The purpose of probate is to:</li><li>Validate wills</li><li>Pay creditors</li><li>Distribute assets to beneficiaries as indicated in the will</li><li>Settle disputes </li></ul><p>In Pennsylvania, most estates require some form of probate, particularly when a person dies intestate (without a will). People think probate is expensive and causes delays in distributing assets to their heirs. This is not always true. Probate is generally quick and inexpensive in Pennsylvania. </p><p><strong><em>Find out more from a high quality estate planning attorney in Westmoreland County</em></strong></p><p>At <a href="http://www.longandlongllc.com/" target="&#95;blank">Long &amp; Long, LLC</a>., we combine three generations of experience with client care to provide straightforward advice tailored to each individual client\'s needs.&#160; </p><p><br /><strong>Long &amp; Long, LLC.<br />101 West Pittsburgh Street<br />Greensburg, Pennsylvania 15601<br />Phone: 855-805-2683</strong></p><!--more-->Estate planning is essential for anyone who wants to reap the maximum benefits from their assets during their lifetime and provide for their loved ones after death.&#160; Sometimes, the estate planning process can be complicated - depending on the size of your estate.&#160; However, with proper guidance from an experienced attorney, you can rest assured that your affairs will be in order.&#160; Contact Long &amp; Long, PC, estate planning law firm in Murrysville and Greensburg to learn more.'
