aS'<p><strong>Proving Liability in a Missouri Injury Claim</strong></p><p>Anyone who incurs injuries due to the negligent or willful acts of others has the right to expect full compensation for all related expenses. But even in seemingly straightforward accident situations, liability may not be as obvious as it seems. If you seek a settlement or jury award from the parties you believe caused your injuries in Missouri, you need to understand a little about how state liability laws work. Then obtain advice and representation from an experienced personal injury attorney.</p><p><strong>The complexity of identifying liability</strong></p><p>A driver who rear-ends a stopped vehicle might appear to be the obviously liable party in the accident. But even this simple example might have complexities, such as the following:</p><ul><li>The driver of the front vehicle might have suddenly cut off the other driver and then stopped.</li><li>The driver of the rear vehicle may have appropriately applied the brakes, only to discover that recent brake repairs failed.</li><li>After stopping behind the front vehicle, a third vehicle may have rear-ended the driver of the rear vehicle, pushing it into the front vehicle.</li></ul><p>These examples illustrate the importance of talking to attorneys who have experience with these matters. They understand the potential complexities behind any type of accident and use investigative specialists when needed to unravel the true causes.</p><p><strong>Understanding Missouri comparative negligence law</strong></p><p>You can find helpful advice about what to do after an accident and other details about Missouri personal injury law by reviewing the information on the Lawyers.com[cjs1]&#160; website. But a key point in determining negligence involves Missouri comparative negligence law.</p><p>The law addresses the fact that more than one individual may share liability for a given accident&#8212;including an injured victim. Under Missouri law, even a victim whose negligence contributed to the accident can still pursue compensation from others, but the law reduces their damages based on their degree of negligence. Theoretically, an injured individual with 99 percent of liability for an accident can still pursue one percent of damages from others who shared liability.</p><p>Looking at a different aspect of the law, Missouri follows joint and several liability rules that determine liability when more than one party has responsibility for your damages. When one party has 51 percent or more of the fault, the victim can pursue full compensation from that liable party, leaving him or her to settle any differences with other at-fault individuals. On the other hand, if no single party has the majority of fault, the victim must pursue compensation from each liable party based on degree of responsibility.</p><p><strong>Contact an experienced St. Louis personal injury attorney for a free consultation</strong></p><p>If you incur injuries from any type of <a href="http://www.gatewayinjurylaw.com/aop/St-Louis-automobile-accidents/">accident</a> in Missouri caused by negligent or willful acts of other parties, you need to learn your legal options before taking action to pursue compensation. When you call an experienced St. Louis injury attorney at McChesney &amp; Ortwerth, you receive advice and representation from a respected firm with the skills and resources needed to prove liability and protect your rights for the full and fair compensation you deserve. Contact us at 888-906-6938 to schedule a free consultation and learn how we can help.</p><!--more-->Anyone who incurs injuries due to the negligent or willful acts of others has the right to expect full compensation for all related expenses. But even in seemingly straightforward accident situations, liability may not be as obvious as it seems. If you seek a settlement or jury award from the parties you believe caused your injuries in Missouri, you need to understand a little about how state liability laws work.'
