aS'<br /><br />A revolutionary new technology would use a series of tiny electrical impulses from implanted devices to allow a paralyzed person with a spinal cord injury to move his limbs. Preliminary tests have revealed almost miraculous results. In one case, a person who had suffered a stroke and had been left paralyzed in one arm was able to begin playing golf. In another case, a person paralyzed from the chest down was soon able enough to do deep knee bends. Both are cases where the patients were looking at years of severely restricted movement.<br /><br />The technology works through implanted microstimulators that deliver a series of automated impulses. These impulses can lead to muscle contractions that help the person to imitate the natural movements of his limbs. All the technology requires to benefit more spinal injury patients is the right bandwidth or electronic spectrum. The nonprofit Alfred Mann Foundation has appealed to the government for the use of four bands of electromagnetic spectrum. That would not have been a problem, except that these four bands are already being used by other major entities. <br /><br />The Foundation wants to use 413 to 419 MHz, which is currently being used by emergency land mobile radio. 426 to 432 MHz and 438 to 444 MHz are being used by the military for radar, and 451 to 457 MHz is being used by commercial television stations for breaking news or traffic reports. Portions of the spectrum are currently being used by private users under part 15 of title 47 of the Code of Federal Regulations. These devices are typically used in low power transmitters, for example, in baby monitors. It is this part 15 that the Alfred Mann Foundation is looking at in order to operate this revolutionary technology. <br /><br />However, the current users of the bandwidth spectrum are not too keen on sharing their bandwidth for the operation of a medical device. They have their concerns. Say for instance, there is a television crew breaking news at a site using the spectrum. If there is a patient nearby with the implanted device, the high-power transmission could seriously impact the functioning of the device, threatening the safety of the patient.<br /><br />The Alfred Mann Foundation says these concerns are not valid, because the device is engineered to resist harmful interference. Further, according to the Alfred Mann Foundation, there is no question of choosing another section of the bandwidth. This is the only section that allows the technology to work the way it is meant to. <br /><br />Obviously, this is a difficult situation. The kind of results the technology has shown so far are bound to excite <a title="Spine Injury Attorneys Los Angeles" href="http://www.brain-spineinjury.com/">California spine injury lawyers</a>. Hopefully, there can be some sort of compromise which will allow the technology to be used safely to benefit patients, without harmful interference.<br /><!--more-->A revolutionary new technology would use a series of tiny electrical impulses from implanted devices to allow a paralyzed person with a spinal cord injury to move his limbs. The kind of results the technology has shown so far are bound to excite <a href="http://www.brain-spineinjury.com/" title="Spine Injury Attorneys Los Angeles">California spine injury lawyers</a>.  However, the current users of the bandwidth spectrum are not too keen on sharing their bandwidth.'
