aS'The Bay Area has always been a region known for its emphasis on public mass transit.&#160; As such, there are large numbers of buses, trains, and subways that operate every day in cities like San Francisco, Oakland, and San Jose.&#160; Due to the volume of buses, however, and the hectic pace of urban living, collisions and accidents are unfortunate and tragic occurrences that happen all too often.&#160; In an effort to curb these potential disasters from happening the MUNI system in San Francisco is trying a different way of monitoring operator safety by monitoring their drivers with cameras to ensure that they are not paying more attention to their phones than the road. &#160;<br /><br />In the past few years a real problem that has been encountered with drivers is the problem of cellular phones, and more specifically, with texting.&#160; Operators both in MUNI as well as other transit agencies in California have found that their drivers are texting on the job, even while driving.&#160; One such case resulted in a massive tragedy in the Los Angeles area in 2008, when a train conductor, who was believed to be paying more attention to the texts he was receiving than the rail, crashed a train, killing 25 people.&#160; More locally, a MUNI subway operator crashed as a result of him paying more attention to texts than to the road.&#160; His train slammed into another rail vehicle, hurting 12 people, according to the San Francisco Chronicle. &#160;<br /><br /><br />According to the Chronicle MUNI is going to start implementing cameras located in the operator&#8217;s cab in all light rail vehicles in the system.&#160; The cameras will record the drivers as they work, ensuring that they do not engage in texting or use their mobile phones to talk.&#160; If they are caught in either activity, they will find that they will not be working for MUNI any longer, according to Commissioner Mike Florio.&#160; Hopefully this plan will succeed.&#160; Though MUNI has been experiencing a general drop in accidents, and especially grievous ones, the addition of cameras ensuring that MUNI drivers are engaging their jobs and not their friends is a comforting one for all pedestrians and motorists in San Francisco.<br /><br />If you&#8217;ve been hurt in a bus accident, or any accident involving a motor vehicle, please do not hesitate to contact Allegiance Law.&#160; We are an aggressive, experienced law firm that is committed to helping out anyone who has been wronged on the road, especially if they&#8217;ve been struck and hurt by a bus or subway.&#160; If you feel like you have a case, please give us a call.&#160; Your &#8220;small&#8221; claim may be much larger than you think.&#160; You can contact us at (415) 404-6395.<br /><br /><a href="http://www.allegiancelaw.com/">Allegiance Law</a>: <a href="http://www.allegiancelaw.com/personal&#95;injury">The San Francisco Personal Injury Attorneys</a>&#160; &#160;<br /><br />'
