aS'<p />\r\n<p />\r\n<p>One frequent statement after a motorcycle crash is &#8220;I didn\'t see him&#8221;. This statement represents the problem that many motorcycle riders face&#8211;they are not very visible.</p>\r\n<p />\r\n<p>This dilemma known as motorcycle conspicuity is simply &#160;that motorcycles are harder to see than cars and trucks. Some avid motorcycle riders have taken it upon themselves to add lighting to their motorcycle to help make it more visible.</p>\r\n<p />\r\n<p>You may even recall, watching a young person riding a bicycle with an antenna attached to a flag. This was a knowing parent\'s attempt to make their child more visible to motorists and keep them safe. A motorcycle rider is well served to follow that example and make themselves more visable to other motorists.&#160;</p>\r\n<p />\r\n<p>Another way that a motorcycle rider can help make himself more visible is to wear brightly colored clothing or reflective material. Unfortunately, that is not much in keeping with the motorcycle rider image many strive to maintain. Additionally, motorcycle riders are well advised to keep headlights on even in the daytime. Studies have shown that this increases their visibility and thus decreases susceptibility to a motorcycle accident.</p>\r\n<p />\r\n<p>Common sense dictates that a prudent motorcycle rider may try to avoid the busy highways in large cities like Houston during rush-hour traffic. Sometimes in rush-hour traffic, it is difficult to see even large cars and trucks due to the limited space and congestion. In those conditions motorcycle riders are much more likely to be involved in an accident.</p><p /><p>Greg Baumgartner is&#160;the founder of the Baumgartner law firm, which is dedicated to helping personal injury victims seek civil justice. If you would like to speak with an experienced accident lawyer&#160;call the Baumgartner firm at (281) 587-1111 or <a  rel="nofollow" href="www.texastriallawyers.com">contact us</a>.</p>'
