aS'<p>When you file for personal bankruptcy, you can choose the best way for your debt to be handled. If you file for Chapter 13, you play an integral role in determining how you pay off your debt. Even with Chapter 7, you and your attorney can negotiate with creditors to find a way to fit your needs.</p><p>Bankruptcy can be complicated. If you&#160;are looking to <a href="http://www.percivallaw.com/practice-areas/jackson-bankruptcy-filing/" target="&#95;blank">file bankruptcy in Jackson</a> or elsewhere, contact a qualified bankruptcy attorney for assistance. </p><p><b>Chapter 7</b></p><p>Often called &quot;a fresh start,&quot; <a href="http://www.uscourts.gov/FederalCourts/Bankruptcy/BankruptcyBasics/Chapter7.aspx" target="&#95;blank">Chapter 7 bankruptcy</a> is a liquidation of your non-exempt assets. It allows you to discharge debts in four to six months in exchange for liquidating assets, if any exist, to pay creditors.</p><p>Chapter 7 is for individuals, companies, or corporations who cannot afford to pay back their debts. A court-appointed trustee determines if you are able to keep some of your assets, such as your home (provided it does not have much equity), your car, and personal belongings. During Chapter 7, the trustee collects your non-exempt assets, reduces them to cash, and makes distributions to creditors. If you do not have non-exempt assets, your case is considered a &quot;no-asset case&quot; and there is not any actual liquidation of assets.</p><p><b>Chapter 13</b></p><p>Chapter 13 bankruptcy in Jackson is for individuals who are overcome by debts, but have a regular income that gives them the ability to repay a portion of their debt within three to five years with help from the court.</p><p>Chapter 13 allows you to create a plan to use a certain percentage of future income to pay creditors. If the court-appointed trustee approves the plan, you are under the court&#8217;s protection while repaying your debts. Penalties and other fees are often removed from the total amount owed, interest rates are usually lowered, and creditors are asked to take a percentage of the total as payment in full.</p><p>You must pay the trustee the agreed-upon monthly payment on time and without fail. If you miss one payment, the bankruptcy may be nullified, you lose the advantages gained by filing and your creditors are free to sue you directly for payment.</p><p /><p /><p><b></b></p><p><b>Quick Guide:</b></p><p><b>Bankruptcy Type</b></p><p>Chapter 7: Liquidation </p><p>Chapter 13: Reorganization </p><p /><p><b>When to Use</b></p><p>Chapter 7: When an individual, company or corporation is unable to repay debts</p><p>Chapter 13: When you have an asset of value, like a home, and you have a regular income that will enable you to repay a portion of the debt.</p><p><b>Discharge</b></p><p>Chapter 7: Orderly, court-supervised liquidation of assets for discharge of debt in about six months </p><p>Chapter 13: Reorganization of debt with structured repayment; remaining debt discharged after final payment</p><p><b>Time Span</b></p><p>Chapter 7: Typically four to six months</p><p>Chapter 13: Typically three to five years</p><p /><p><b>Asset Retention</b></p><p>Chapter 7: Trustee determines if you can keep assets such as a home, car or personal belongings</p><p>Chapter 13: Protection of your assets and personal belongings</p><p><b>Creditor Contact</b></p><p>Chapter 7: Stops harassing phone calls</p><p>Chapter 13: Stops harassing phone calls</p><p><b>Foreclosure</b></p><p>Chapter 7: Eliminates foreclosure</p><p>Chapter 13: Halts foreclosure</p><p><b>Lawsuits</b></p><p>Chapter 7: Ends lawsuits</p><p>Chapter 13: Ends lawsuits</p><p><b>Outcome</b></p><p>Chapter 7: Helps you get a fresh start</p><p>Chapter 13: Helps you regain financial freedom</p><p /><p /><p><em></em></p><p><em>This information has been provided by the </em><a href="http://www.percivallaw.com/practice-areas/jackson-bankruptcy-law-firm/" target="&#95;blank"><em>bankruptcy law firm in Jackson</em></a><em>, TN, of Sherry M. Percival:</em></p><p><em>Percival Law Offices, P.C. <br />219 North Parkway #1, Jackson, TN 38305<br />(731) 424-3897</em></p><!--more-->Which type of bankruptcy is right for you?&#160; Percival Law Offices, P.C., a <a href="http://www.percivallaw.com/practice-areas/jackson-bankruptcy-law-firm/" target="&#95;blank">bankruptcy law firm in Jackson</a>, TN, explains the differences between chapter 7 and chapter 13 bankruptcy.'
