aS'<p>Many people who are genuinely disabled often face the disappointment that their initial claim for disability benefits has been denied by the Social Security Administration (SSA). Unfortunately, most people are denied on their initial application. In those circumstances, that claimant is entitled to an appeal, and can seek to prove his or her claim again. </p><p>In most states, the first appeal is called a &#8220;Request for Reconsideration&#8221;. As the name suggests, SSA will take another look at the claim and reconsider their initial decision. Generally, the request for reconsideration must be made by the claimant or an attorney within 60 days of the initial denial. However, if you miss the deadline tell your lawyer if you had &#8220;good cause&#8221; for failing to file the appeal on time, as they may still be able to help you file the appeal. </p><p>During this stage SSA may obtain additional evidence. You may be asked to attend another consultative examination or to complete additional forms. The claimant and attorney can also submit new evidence to be considered. Expectations for a reversal of the initial unfavorable determination should be kept low, as fewer than fifteen percent of claims are awarded at reconsideration. </p><p>There are ten &#8220;prototype states&#8221; that skip the reconsideration process: Alabama, Alaska, California (Los Angeles North and West areas), Colorado, Louisiana, Michigan, Missouri, New Hampshire, New York (Brooklyn and Albany areas), and Pennsylvania. In these states, after the initial denial is received, you may appeal by requesting a formal hearing. </p><!--more-->The <a href="http://www.1800cantwork.com/aop/social-security-disability-insurance-ssdi/">SSDI</a> and <a href="http://www.1800cantwork.com/aop/supplemental-security-income-ssi/">SSI Attorneys</a> at the Law Offices of Eric A. Shore P.C. discuss appealing SSDI and <a href="http://www.1800cantwork.com/">SSI Disability</a> Benefits Denial.'
