aS'<p>\r\n\r\nBy Dr. Carol A. Simpson - Associate<br />Eichelbaum Wardell Hansen Powell &amp; Mehl, P.C.<br />800.488.9045 | <a href="http://www.edlaw.com/">www.edlaw.com</a> | <a href="mailto:information@edlaw.com">information@edlaw.com</a> </p><p></p><p>The\r\nday you drive away in a new vehicle is always exciting.&#160; So is the day that the new vehicle breaks\r\ndown on the side of the road, though it is exciting in a different way. No one\r\nknows when a bus or other vehicle the district purchases may turn out to be a\r\nlemon. Though such an occurrence is unlikely, it is also unpredictable.&#160; It is always better to be prepared for that\r\nevent rather than lamenting that you wish you had the necessary documentation\r\nto prove your vehicle is a lemon and possibly qualify to have the manufacturer\r\nbuy back or replace the vehicle.</p><p>\r\n\r\nA\r\nproblem vehicle has three ways to be declared a &#8220;lemon&#8221;:&#160; </p><p>\r\n\r\n1.&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;\r\nThe\r\nvehicle was in the shop for the same problem or defect twice within the first\r\n12 months or 12,000 miles (whichever comes first) AND twice more during the 12\r\nmonths or 12,000 miles following the first repair AND the problem is still not\r\nrepaired; OR</p><p>\r\n\r\n2.&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;\r\nThe\r\nvehicle was taken for repair of a serious safety hazard once during the first\r\n12 months or 12,000 miles (whichever comes first) AND once more during the 12\r\nmonths of 12,000 miles following the first repair AND the problem is still not\r\nrepaired; OR</p><p>\r\n\r\n3.&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;\r\nThe\r\nvehicle was out of service for warranty repair for a total of 30+ days (not\r\nnecessarily consecutive days) during the first 24 months or 24,000 miles, AND\r\nthere were two repair attempts during the first 12 months or 12,000 miles after\r\ndelivery, AND a substantial problem still exists. Days for which you had a\r\nloaner vehicle do not count toward the 30 days out of service.&#160; Tex. Occ. Code Ann. &#167; 2301.605 (West 2012).</p><p>\r\n\r\nA\r\n&#8220;serious safety hazard&#8221; is a life-threatening malfunction that substantially\r\nimpedes a person&#8217;s ability to control or operate a vehicle for ordinary use or\r\nintended purposes, or creates a substantial risk of fire or explosion.&#160; Tex. Occ. Code Ann. &#167; 2301.601(4) (West\r\n2012).</p><p>\r\n\r\nWhile\r\nthere are state laws that protect consumers (including school districts) from\r\nlemon vehicles, there are certain documents that are required to make a Lemon\r\nLaw claim.&#160; Because the timeline to file\r\na Lemon Law claim is tight, it is essential that districts always maintain\r\nthese records on vehicles, especially buses, so when problems start to pile up,\r\nthe documents are ready and available.</p><p>\r\n\r\n<b>The Invoice</b></p><p>\r\n\r\nThe\r\nfirst document you will need to produce to make a Lemon Law claim is the\r\npurchase invoice.&#160; The invoice should\r\nshow the date the vehicle was delivered, the company selling the vehicle, and\r\nthe mileage on the vehicle when it was delivered.&#160; Many school districts purchase their vehicles\r\nthrough the TASB &#8220;Buy Board&#8221;, but the vehicle is actually invoiced from a\r\nvehicle dealer.&#160; It is the dealer&#8217;s\r\ninvoice that you need to retain. &#160;The\r\ndealer must also provide you a Manufacturer&#8217;s Certificate of Origin, which will\r\nshow the mileage on the vehicle at the time of delivery. Keep this document, as\r\nwell. Also keep the card of any sales representative that you deal with during\r\nthe transaction.</p><p>\r\n\r\n<b>The Warranty</b></p><p>\r\n\r\nVirtually\r\nevery new vehicle comes with some sort of manufacturer&#8217;s warranty.&#160; By state law, every school bus must have a\r\nbumper-to-bumper warranty for the first two years of ownership, with unlimited\r\nmileage. 37 Tex. Admin. Code &#167; 14.52(a).&#160;\r\nThis is known as the Texas Minimum Warranty. The dealer must provide the\r\nManufacturer&#8217;s New Vehicle Warranty, plus a warranty of every major component\r\npart. These will be the warranties for the tires, battery, engine and possibly\r\nthe chassis. ALL these warranties are essential documents when making a Lemon\r\nLaw claim, so they should not be discarded or left in the glove box of the vehicle.\r\nIn addition, a bus warranty start date can be reset from the actual delivery\r\ndate to the date the bus actually begins service in your district if you notify\r\nthe delivering dealer of the date on which you place the bus in service. To\r\nreset the date, you must give notification of the in-service date to the\r\ndelivering dealer within 90 days of the original delivery date.&#160; This conserves the district&#8217;s warranty if,\r\nfor example, you receive a bus in early June but do not put the bus into\r\nservice until the beginning of the following school year.</p><p>\r\n\r\n<b>The Pre-Service Checklist\r\n(buses only)</b></p><p>\r\n\r\nThe\r\nTexas School Bus Specifications require that a school bus purchaser complete a\r\npre-service checklist and keep the completed form with the bus title.&#160; An example is found in the Texas School Bus\r\nSpecifications brochure that is available through the Texas Administrative Code\r\nwebsite as the attached graphic in 37 Tex. Admin. Code &#167; 14.52(a).</p><p>\r\n\r\n<b>The Repair Invoices</b></p><p>\r\n\r\nBecause\r\nan initial repair within the first 12 months or 12,000 miles triggers the\r\nremedies of the Lemon Law, it is essential to demand an invoice for any\r\nwarranty service.&#160; Dealers are sometimes\r\nreluctant to provide such invoices, especially since they do not charge the\r\ndistrict for warranty service.&#160; However,\r\nif the same issue recurs to the point that you may have a Lemon Law claim, you\r\nwill need to produce evidence that you have had the vehicle in for repairs for\r\nthat defect, and the mileage on the vehicle at the time of each repair. That\r\ninformation is typically found on the repair invoice.&#160; The repair shop will probably not mail you a\r\ncopy of the invoice later.&#160; Ask for the\r\ninvoice at the time you pick up the vehicle, and wait for it to be printed, if\r\nnecessary.&#160; If a vehicle is inoperable\r\nand you are unable to reach the delivering dealer to have the vehicle towed,\r\nhave the vehicle towed yourself but get an invoice for the tow. A bus that\r\ncannot be operated at all is a &#8220;serious safety hazard.&#8221;</p><p>\r\n\r\n<b>The Maintenance Records</b></p><p>\r\n\r\nIn\r\ndefending a Lemon Law claim, manufacturers will want to see your maintenance\r\nrecords for the vehicle. Make sure you have some documentation of every oil\r\nchange, every tire rotation, every coolant change per the manufacturer&#8217;s\r\nspecifications.&#160; While commercial records\r\nare just fine and typically identify the mileage on the vehicle at the time of\r\nthe service, locally kept records for in-house service are acceptable, as well,\r\nbut make them consistent.&#160; The more\r\ninformation on the date, mileage and service performed (including grade of oil,\r\ntype of filter, etc.) the better.</p><p>\r\n\r\nBefore\r\nyou file your Lemon Law claim you will want to consult with your district&#8217;s\r\nattorney about additional steps to take. The attorney will want to see the\r\nabove documentation to verify the claim. The manufacturer will get one more\r\nchance to repair the problem, and will probably bring a consulting engineer to\r\ntry to intimidate your personnel. You must make sure that your transportation\r\nfolks are on the same page regarding the condition of the bus and are prepared\r\nto verify that the problem still exists. Good documentation can be the key to a\r\nreplacement vehicle.</p><p>\r\n\r\n</p>'
