aS'<p>Most crimes can be broadly categorized as either felonies or misdemeanors. However, what do those terms even mean? Many people will be surprised to discover that, depending on the state, a misdemeanor can actually bring more jail time than a felony. That&#8217;s why, if you are accused of a crime, you need to seek the services of an experienced Scranton criminal defense lawyer who can advise you about your options.</p><em><strong>Pennsylvania law and the felony/misdemeanor distinction</strong></em><p>Felony and misdemeanor are confusing terms - mostly because, while they are used to categorize crimes across the United States, the meaning of the terms differs from state to state. In Pennsylvania, there are three degrees of felony and three of misdemeanor, with each characterized by the penalty associated with it.</p><p>Scranton criminal defense lawyers are knowledgeable about these distinctions as laid out by Pennsylvania law. That law defines a <a href="http://www.pitt.edu/~weinberg/grading.htm" target="&#95;blank">first-degree felony</a> as a crime bringing a penalty of more than 10 years in prison. Second-degree felonies are punished with no more than 10 years, and third-degree felonies with no more than seven years. Further complicating this picture are the penalties for misdemeanors, which may overlap with those for felonies. So, a first-degree misdemeanor has a maximum sentence of five years, a second-degree brings no more than two years, and a third-degree misdemeanor has at most a one-year sentence. This differs from the rules in other states where, for example, a felony may be any crime that brings a sentence over five years and a misdemeanor is everything under that sentence. </p><p>A high degree of variation exists in terms of which crimes are classified as felonies and misdemeanors, and the apparent seriousness of the offense alone will not necessarily let you know what to expect. For example, a crime of theft might be a misdemeanor the first time it occurs, but can elevate to a felony after multiple offenses. It is the case, however, that a felony conviction bars you from voting or holding public office &#8212; rights that may be restored after the completion of your penalty. Misdemeanors carry no such restriction.</p><p>In short, the line between felony and misdemeanor can be confusing. Only a skilled Pennsylvania criminal defense attorney can help you understand the distinctions between charges, which will bring the highest penalties, and which will be classified as felonies versus misdemeanors. </p><em><strong>Benefit from 50 years of legal service in Scranton, PA</strong></em><p>Felonies and misdemeanors are intended to be very different in terms of their severity and consequences, and yet there is often substantial overlap between them. A skilled lawyer can minimize the consequences for you, not only in terms of your penalty, but in terms of the crime you are charged with in the first place. If you are accused of a crime, seek the help of the experienced, empathetic criminal defense lawyers of <a href="http://www.mkpvlaw.com/" target="&#95;blank">Mazzoni, Karam, Petorak &amp; Valvano</a> immediately. </p><p /><p>Mazzoni, Karam, Petorak &amp; Valvano</p><p>Suite 201, Bank Towers</p><p>321 Spruce Street</p><p>Scranton, PA 18503</p><p>866.629.9664</p><!--more-->Most crimes can be broadly categorized as either felonies or misdemeanors. However, what do those terms even mean? Many people will be surprised to discover that, depending on the state, a misdemeanor can actually bring more jail time than a felony. That&#8217;s why, if you are accused of a crime, you want to seek the services of an experienced Scranton criminal lawyer, one who can advise you on your options.'
