aS'<p>\r\n\r\nA bill providing enhanced protections to employees of the Federal government is on its way to the President for signing into law after the Senate signed the bill on November 13, 2012 (Senate Bill&#160;743), after removing some of the substantive protections in the original bill it received. The bill passed the House of Representatives earlier in 2012 (House of Representatives Bill 3289), so all that remains now is for the President of the United States to sign it, and the majority of its provisions will take effect 30 days thereafter.</p><p>The bill is called the Whistleblower Protection Enhancement Act of 2012. It amends the existing Federal protections primarilly at&#160;Section&#160;2302, in Title 5 of the United States Code. It was proposed because Congress felt that the courts were unreasonably restricting the protections afforded under existing law. The WPA of 2012 clarifies that all disclosures, whether formal or informal, are protected where &quot;the employee or applicant providing the disclosure&#160;reasonably believes that the disclosure evidences any violation of law, rule, or regulation, and occurs during the conscientious carryout out of official duties; or gross mismanagement, a gross waste of funds, an abuse of authority, or a substantial and specific danger to public health or safety.&quot; See&#160;Committee Statement and Views of the Committee on Oversight and Government Reform accompanying H.R. 3289, Rept. 112-508 Part 1, 112th Congress 2nd Session.</p><p>Significantly, the act transfers appeal rights from the United States Appeals Court for the Federal&#160;to the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia because Congress feels the Federal Circuit Court has misapplied the existing whistleblower provisions in a manner that has lead to discourage potential whistleblowers from coming forward. See Committee Statement and Views of the Committee on Oversight and Government Reform accompanying H.R. 3289, Rept. 112-508 Part 1, 112th Congress 2nd Session. The act also expands the scope of the law to Transportation Security Act workers.</p><!--more-->Congress passes Federal Whistleblower Protection Enhancement Act of 2012 in both the House and Senate, clarifying and restoring protections for whistleblowers in Federal government.'
