aS'<p class="MsoNoSpacing">Daniel Carlson is a securities litigation attorney in San Diego who specializes in <a href="http://www.securities-fraud-attorney-san-diego.com/">recovering investment losses</a> for his clients.</p><p class="MsoNoSpacing">Annuities are popular investment vehicles.&#160; But how much do small investors really know about the pros and cons of investing in these products?&#160; In this post I will explain a bit about annuities and their potential risk.<br />&#160;<br />What is an annuity?&#160; - Think of an annuity as a right to the payment of certain annual income.&#160; It may also contain other rights, such as the right to collect an insurance payment under certain conditions under the policy.&#160; When you invest in an annuity, a promise is then made to make payments to you on a certain date, or a series of dates, in the future. In general, annuities fall into two categories: Deferred and Income.&#160; And each functions quite differently.</p><p class="MsoNoSpacing"><strong>Tax-Deferred Annuities</strong></p><p class="MsoNoSpacing">Tax deferred annuities can be great for increasing your retirement savings for some people because unlike 401(k)s or IRAs, there are no contribution limits.&#160; In addition, earnings continue to compound over time tax free.&#160; However, you better be sure that you do not intend to take money out of the annuity before age 59 1/2, or the IRS will hit you with a whopping 10% penalty.&#160; Also keep in mind that most annuities come with an annual fee not usually found in mutual funds.&#160; Be sure you understand all of the fees, costs and other characteristics of the annuity before you invest.</p><ul><li><div class="MsoNoSpacing">Deferred Fixed Annuities are generally more suitable for conservative investors and those looking to protect their nest eggs because they offer a guaranteed rate of return with lower risk.&#160; However, remember that annuities are not FDIC-insured as you would find in a typical CD.</div></li><div class="MsoNoSpacing"></div><li><div class="MsoNoSpacing">Deferred Variable Annuities are more high-risk and potentially dangerous than fixed annuities because they typically involve more market risk/exposure and can result in losses if the underlying investment funds were to decrease. </div></li></ul><p class="MsoNoSpacing"><br /><strong>Income Annuities</strong></p><p class="MsoNoSpacing">Income annuities are generally better for investors who are already retired or very close to it because they offer income for either life or a set period of time.&#160; Remember though that is most cases, you have little or no access to the money used to purchase income annuities.</p><ul><li><div class="MsoNoSpacing">Fixed Income Annuities are generally the safest choice for investors because they offer a guaranteed and predictable payment for life or fixed period of time and are typically not affected by volatility in the market.&#160; Not only does this help shield your investment from market risk, but it also can help you plan for retirement better since you know exactly what you will be receiving each month.</div></li><div class="MsoNoSpacing"></div><li><div class="MsoNoSpacing">Deferred Fixed Income Annuities are the same as fixed income in regards to less risk, there is just a deferral period before the payments begin, which can result in a higher income payout.</div></li><div class="MsoNoSpacing"></div><li><div class="MsoNoSpacing">Immediate Variable Income Annuities are generally more risky because while some amount of payout is guaranteed, that amount will be subject to the volatility of the market and the performance of the underlying investments.&#160; While there is the potential for greater growth if the market does well, there is also the potential for loss if the market does poorly.</div></li></ul><p class="MsoNoSpacing"><br />The bottom line is that as with any other investment, there are pros and cons to investing in annuities and they are somewhat complicated.&#160; Do your homework and understand exactly what type of annuity you are being offered and what risks and fees are associated with it.&#160; These disclosures should always be provided in the annuity prospectus provided to you before you invest.&#160; Be sure to read it, and be sure to ask your broker to explain it to you in detail before investing.&#160; If you are still unsure, you may want to consider seeking a second opinion.&#160; </p><p class="MsoNoSpacing">The foregoing is not investment advice, and should not be relied upon for making investment decisions.&#160; Contact your financial advisor for specific advice, recommendations and information specific to your situation.&#160; If you think that you have been the victim of annuity or other investment fraud, contact <a href="http://www.securities-fraud-attorney-san-diego.com/">Daniel Carlson at the Carlson Law Firm</a> today for a free consultation at 619-544-9300. </p><!--more-->Annuities are popular investment vehicles.  But how much do small investors really know about the pros and cons of investing in these products?  In this post I will explain a bit about annuities and their potential risk.&#160; If you think that you have been the victim of annuity or other investment fraud, contact Daniel Carlson at the Carlson Law Firm today for a free consultation at 619-544-9300.'
