aS'<p>\r\n\r\nFinancial elder abuse is one of the most common financial crimes in the United States.&#160; In fact, in California alone there are over 200,000 reported victims of financial elder abuse each year.&#160; To make matters worse, that statistic does not even take into account the fact that financial elder abuse is statistically one of the most underreported crimes in the state.&#160; However, if you or your loved ones have been deviously taken advantage of, you deserve justice.&#160; In California, the laws recognize this, and an experienced trial attorney can help you secure the retribution that you and your loved ones deserve.&#160; So, what is financial elder abuse, and what are some of the common ways that it takes place?</p><p>California\'s Welfare and Institutions Code (section 15610.30 et seq.) defines financial elder abuse as &quot;a situation in which a person, including but not limited to, one who has care or custody of or who stands in a position of trust, of an elder or dependent adult, takes, secretes, or appropriates their money or property, to <em>any wrongful use</em>, or with the intent to defraud.&#160; The code defines an &quot;elder&quot; as a person 65 years of age or older.&#160; Furthermore, the California legislature has passed numerous laws in order to protect the elderly.&#160; In addition to traditional civil remedies, or lawsuits, perpetrators of financial elder abuse are subject to criminal penalties, including fines and potential jail time.&#160; Further, under the Elder Abuse and Dependent Adult Civil Protection Act (EADACPA) the courts are given great discretion in awarding damages in elder abuse cases, including a provision that allows juries to award noneconomic damages of up to $250,000.&#160; Finally, these laws cover a vast array of different crimes and schemes.</p><p>There are countless different ways that a person can underhandedly commit financial elder abuse.&#160; However, some ways are more common than others.&#160; Some of the most common ways include: (1) telemarketing scams; (2) abuse by children and other family members; (3) credit card insurance or repair fraud; (4) predatory lending; (5) &quot;new best friends&quot; and other unexpected caretakers; and (6) Med-Cal and Medicare fraud.&#160; These kinds of schemes range from simple&#160;acts of petty theft, to intricate schemes to take financial control over the estates and assets of elderly individuals.</p><p>In the coming weeks we will discuss some of the previously mentioned financial elder abuse schemes in more detail, and other common issues in financial elder abuse cases.&#160; However, if you or your loved ones have been taken advantage of, you may not have the time to wait.&#160; An <a href="www.burnsattorneys.com">experienced trial attorney</a> can make sure that you receive the justice that you and your loved ones deserve.&#160; If you or your loved ones have been subject to financial elder abuse, CONTACT US at (213) 687-8080 or visit our website at <a href="http://www.burnsattorneys.com">www.burnsattorneys.com</a>. </p>'
