aS'Most people have heard of a whiplash injury but may not understand exactly what qualifies as a whiplash injury or how to know if they have suffered one. Only a licenses physician can properly diagnose any injury, but understanding what whiplash is and what commons symptoms of a whiplash injury are may help you decide whether or not you need to be evaluated by a physician.  When in doubt head to the doctor for a check-up!\r\n\r\nWhiplash is a general, non-medical term, that refers to a wide range of injuries to the neck. Your neck is where the top of the spine is located. Bones, tendons, ligaments and muscles are all found within the neck. Our spine, while an incredibly strong structure for its size, is not immune from injury. When your neck is thrown backward or forward at an unusually high rate of speed and/or with unusual force the ligaments, tendons and muscles in your neck can be stretched and pulled beyond their normal range of motion. Not surprisingly, the most common cause of a whiplash injury is a car accident. Even a slow speed car accident can have a sever impact on your neck and/or spine. The reason for this is that in a car accident your head is frequently thrown violently back and forth. In some cases your head may even connect with the steering wheel, the window or the head rest potentially making the injury worse. \r\n\r\nOne of the most frustrating things about a whiplash injury is that in most cases it will not present symptoms until a day or two after the actual accident that caused the injury. Unfortunately this means that many victims do not seek an immediate medical evaluation which only delays treatment. Common symptoms of a whiplash injury include soreness, pain and stiffness in your neck, headaches, blurred vision, dizziness and fatigue. Whiplash victims may also experience ringing in the ears, memory problems, fatigue or trouble sleeping and difficulty concentrating. Not all victims experience all symptoms. Each person reacts to a whiplash injury in a unique manner as each accident is unique. In addition, because a whiplash injury does not always present symptoms immediately it is vital that anyone involved in a personal injury accident seek medical attention and have a thorough evaluation to diagnose any and all injuries. While whiplash injuries generally heal within a few weeks, some injuries can have lasting effects and the sooner you begin treatment the better your chance of avoiding a long-term injury.\r\n\r\nIf you think you have suffered a whiplash injury, after seeking medical attention you should consult with an experienced whiplash injury attorney. In California, the victim of a whiplash injury is entitled to compensation for those injuries. The California whiplash injury law firm of Ledger & Associates has been representing whiplash injury victims for over a decade. If you would like to schedule a free and detailed evaluation of your potential whiplash injury case, please contact the attorneys at The Law Offices Ledger & Associates by calling 1-800-300-0001 or visit them online at <a href="http://www.ledgerlaw.com/">www.ledgerlaw.com</a>.<!--more-->If you would like to schedule a free and \r\ndetailed evaluation of your potential whiplash injury case, please \r\ncontact the attorneys at The Law Offices Ledger &amp; Associates by calling 1-800-300-0001 or\r\n visit them online at www.ledgerlaw.com.'
