aS'<p class="MsoNormal">There have been multiple accidents involving school buses\r\nthis past spring, leaving many parents asking why seat belts are not required\r\non school buses. </p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">By Federal and State law, seat belts are not required in\r\nbuses weighing over 10,000 pounds. Since 2009 however, federal law has required\r\nlap and shoulder restraints in new buses under 10,000 pounds. These are\r\ntypically small vehicles made to seat only 10-14 students. </p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">Currently, the National Highway Traffic Safety\r\nAdministration (NHTSA) reports that in larger buses, the spacing and height of\r\nthe seats offer crash protection through &#8220;compartmentalization.&#8221; Compartmentalization,\r\nusing of higher seat backs, protects students from being propelled over a seat.\r\nHowever, it doesn&#8217;t prevent injuries in front or rear-impact collisions, and\r\nonly offers limited protection in other crashes. Furthermore, this crash\r\nprotection assumes that all children will sit properly in their seats, facing\r\nforward, with their feet on the ground, and unfortunately all too often that\r\nisn&#8217;t the case. </p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">Since the tragic IPS school bus accident on March 12<sup>th</sup>\r\n2012 that killed the bus driver and a 5-year-old passenger, there has been a\r\nrenewed debate on whether seat belts on school buses should be mandatory. </p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">The average life span of a school bus is 10-15 years. Limited\r\nmeasures have been taken to improve bus safety, including increasing the height\r\nof seat backs from 20 to 24 inches on new buses. However, school systems financially\r\ncannot retire old buses just because of lower seat backs. Furthermore, many\r\nSchool Boards argue they cannot afford to implement safety belts in their\r\nbusses. New buses with safety belts cost about $10,000 more than older models\r\nwithout safety belts. </p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">Others believe that regardless of seat belts or not, the\r\nbehavior of students on buses needs to be a component. Teaching the importance\r\nof sitting properly in school bus seats can be life saving for children. </p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">From our perspective, school systems have a responsibility\r\nto take reasonable safety measures to protect our own children when they are\r\nbeing transported to and from school. It will be interesting to see how the\r\nschool bus seat belt debate plays out over the course of the year as more\r\nattention is being focused on school bus safety. Tabor Law Firm encourages you\r\nto share your suggestions for safety with your school. </p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">If you or a loved one have been injured due to a school bus accident,\r\ncontact the lawyers at Tabor Law Firm who have first hand experience handling\r\nschool bus accident and injury cases. The initial case evaluation is free. </p><p class="MsoNormal"><a href="http://www.taborlawfirm.com" target="&#95;blank">www.taborlawfirm.com</a></p><!--more-->By Federal and State law, seat belts are not required in\r\nbuses weighing over 10,000 pounds. Since 2009 however, federal law has required\r\nlap and shoulder restraints in new buses under 10,000 pounds. These are\r\ntypically small vehicles made to seat only 10-14 students. \r\n\r\nCurrently, the National Highway Traffic Safety\r\nAdministration (NHTSA) reports that in larger buses, the spacing and height of\r\nthe seats offer crash protection through &#8220;compartmentalization.&#8221; Compartmentalization'
