aS'<p>This plane crash raises an important question. Is it time for regulation of private planes and jets?</p><p><b>It was less than a month ago, February 17th to be exact, when a small plane (Cessna twin-engine) crashed after takeoff in East Palo Alto California, killing pilot and his two passengers (all employees of Tesla Motors).&#160;</b> That plane crashed into a house being used as a daycare center.</p><p><b>Again, a plane crashed into a house on March 4, 2010 in Louissa County, causing major damage and a serious fire that destroyed the house and killed the pilot.</b></p><p>This causes us to stop and consider the potential benefits of regulating private planes more.&#160; In late 2008 TSA, the Transportation Security Administration, projected that if a private jet flew into an urban office building, 3,000 people could be killed (more the September 11th).&#160; TSA proposed imposing security rules on 15,000 private jets.&#160; The proposal met stern opposition from 7,000 private jet owners.&#160; And this is only a small portion of the country&#8217;s 220,000 private airplanes.</p><p>While small planes have been considered less dangerous, primarily being used for recreation and instruction, they are receiving closer review after Joseph Stack intentionally flew is four-seat plane into a Texas office building last week, killing himself and a worker in the building, which was severely damaged.</p><p>Senate Commerce Committee Chairman Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va., said the crash shows private planes must be regulated. &quot;It was horrific,&quot; said Rockefeller, Congress\' leading advocate for imposing security rules on private flights. &quot;It just shows what one person can do.&quot;</p><p>The AOPA, the Aircraft Owners and Pilots Association is working to fight any new regulations as a result of that crash.</p><p><b><i>Blackman Legal Group</i></b>, a private law firm in California, fights to recover financial settlements for the victims and their families when smal