aS'<p class="MsoNormal"><a href="http://www.youtube.com/user/GivnerandKaye#p/u/9/&#95;4Ez8lwb2mc">The 3<sup>rd</sup> biggest mistake in asset\r\nprotection planning</a> is remaining in control after you transfer a valuable asset\r\nby not paying fair market value.&#160;If the parents remain in control, then they will likely be viewed as\r\ncontinuing to own the asset for creditor purposes and they will lose the asset\r\nto a judgment creditor.&#160;For example, part of mom and dad&#8217;s asset protection\r\nplan involves transferring their home to an irrevocable trust for the benefit\r\nof their children.&#160;But they fail\r\nto pay rent to the children&#8217;s trust.&#160;It might be OK for them not to pay rent while the children are minors\r\nliving at home with the parents.&#160;However, once the children are adults, mom and dad must pay rent for the\r\nright to live in the home.&#160;Otherwise, the parents really didn&#8217;t make a gift, and the asset\r\nprotection plan will fail.&#160;What if mom and dad sell the home to a children&#8217;s trust?\r\nIn asset protection planning we often see this mistake: the rent mom and dad\r\npay to the children&#8217;s trust just about equals the amount that the children&#8217;s\r\ntrust owes back to them on the purchase of the home.&#160;That is a big no-no.&#160;The amount of the rent must be determined by an independent appraisal,\r\njust like the sale price of the home must be determined by an independent\r\nappraisal.&#160;There are many other examples, of course.&#160; But the lesson to be learned here is\r\nthat any transfers made in asset protection planning must be made for full fair\r\nmarket value or the parents will still be treated as the owners and will lose\r\nthe assets to a creditor. We suggest you carefully review your asset protection\r\nplan and contact the <a href="http://www.givnerkaye.com/owen-kaye/" title="Owen Kaye, Esq.">expert attorneys</a> at Givner and Kaye today.&#160; <a href="http://www.givnerkaye.com" target="&#95;blank" title="Givner & Kaye">www.GivnerKaye.com</a>\r\n(310) 207-8008</p><!--more-->\r\nHere I discus the 3rd biggest mistake in asset protection planning.&#160;'
