aS'<p class="MsoNormal">A 13-year-old boy who was taking his brand new bicycle for a spin was struck and killed by a public transit bus in Easton, Pennsylvania last week. The boy, who was not wearing a helmet, dashed into the path of the moving bus and neither he nor the driver could stop fast enough.Authorities said the bicycle&#8217;s brakes appeared to have been removed or disabled. &#160;</p><p class="MsoNormal">The director of a local bike coalition said a lot of younger bike riders alter their brakes for \'\'freestyle riding,\'\' which involves spinning the handlebars 360 degrees. They remove the brake cables and rely on coaster brakes - pushing backward on the pedal - or simply drag their feet on the ground to stop. &#160;T<b>his is a huge safety risk, according to the detective in charge of investigating the boy&#8217;s death. He warned all parents to check the brakes on their children&#8217;s bikes to avoid this type of tragedy. &#160;</b></p><p class="MsoNormal"><b>Bicycle accident attorneys</b> and <a href="http://www.brain-injury-lawyer.com/brain-injury-lawyers/"><b>brain injury lawyers</b></a> at <a href="http://www.brain-injury-lawyer.com/"><b>Blackman Legal Group</b></a> represent injured bicycle riders, or the families of fatality victims. &#160;Free consultations are available at <b>1-888-395-3551</b>.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p>\r\n</p><!--more-->A 13-year-old boy who was taking his brand new bicycle for a spin was struck and killed by a public transit bus in Easton, Pennsylvania last week. The boy, who was not wearing a helmet, dashed into the path of the moving bus and neither he nor the driver could stop fast enough. <a href="http://www.brain-injury-lawyer.com/head-injury-lawyers/"><b>Head injury lawyers</b></a> at <a href="http://www.brain-injury-lawyer.com/"><b>Blackman Legal Group</b></a> ...'
