aS'<p>If you receive Social Security benefits, you are not required to include that income on the Chapter 7 Bankruptcy Means Test. &#160;This makes filing for bankruptcy that much easier if you are a debtor who relies on social security in his or her income.&#160;</p><p>As a brief overview,&#160;<a href="http://www.tishbankruptcy.com/blog/2012/06/bankruptcy-is-still-a-strong-option-for-many-above-median-debtors.shtml" target="&#95;blank">the Means Test</a>&#160;requires you to disclose your income from almost all sources received during the six-month period prior to filing for bankruptcy. &#160;After providing all the relevant sources, you will have enough information to calculate your Current Monthly Income (&quot;CMI&quot;), which represents just what it sounds like: the mo&#160;</p><p>As discussed in previous blogs at the Tishkoff Law Bankruptcy Center, if your annualized CMI is less than&#160;<a href="http://www.justice.gov/ust/eo/bapcpa/20120501/bci&#95;data/median&#95;income&#95;table.htm" target="&#95;blank">the median income of your state</a>&#160;for a similar household, you automatically pass the means test. &#160;However, if your CMI is above median, you need to complete the rest of the form and take your expenses into account to determine if you qualify.</p>Social Security Benefits &amp; CMI Calculation Under The Means Test&#160;<p>The Means Test will combine your monthly income from almost all sources to calculate your CMI. However, benefits received under the Social Security Act are one of the few exceptions: Social Security benefits don\'t count as income for means test purposes.</p><p>You therefore need not list your Social Security income on the Means Test when filing for bankruptcy. &#160;However, please remember that you must still disclose your social security income in various schedules included with your bankruptcy paperwork. &#160;These schedules are designed to give the bankruptcy court a snapshot into your budge and expenses. &#160;A qualified bankruptcy attorney should help guide you through this to ensure your filing is not refused.&#160;</p>'
