aS'H-1B visa allows US employers to hire temporary foreign workers in specialty occupations like engineering, medicine, and health, architecture, education, law, business professionals, theology, and arts.<br /><br />That said, Microsoft, a US information technology, one of the software giant companies in America, has suggested an enormous $10,000 fee to employ expatriates for a new category H-1B visas and $15,000 for the new category permanent residency visa, or Green Card. The said company also has advocated more work visas since the recession in 2008.<br /><br />The proposal was revealed by Brad Smith, the general counsel and executive vice president, legal and corporate affairs of Microsoft during a brainstorming session in Washington based last month, suggesting that IT companies should pay $10,000 for each foreign worker they hire under the expanded Science, Technology, Engineering, and Mathematics- commonly known as (STEM) H-1B visa and $15,000 for each Green Card issued from the US permanent residency program. The maximum intake under the new visas would be 20,000 a year.<br /><br />Microsoft currently has 6,000 job openings in the United States, of which more than 3,400 of those are for researchers, engineers, and developers.<br /><br />If this proposal gets accepted, it could hit Indian IT companies the hardest while leaving the US government richer by $5 billion for just a 10 year period. However, the money that would be raised could be used to raise funds for STEM education programmes within the United States. It could also help provide additional resources to recruit and train STEM teachers, broaden access to computer science in high schools, and expand higher education capacity to produce more STEM degrees, according to Smith.<br /><br />For more answers to frequently asked questions, to chat live with Timothy A. Gambacorta, set up an appointment, or simply to learn more about The Gambacorta Law Office, please visit our website at <a href="http://www.gambacortalaw.com/"><b>The Gambacorta Law Office, LLC</b></a><br />'
