aS'CUSTODY CONUNDRUM<br /><br />No-one likes to think about divorce and child custody issues.&#160; If not personally experienced, then most of us are aware of these issues through friends, acquaintances or family members.&#160; We don&#8217;t want to talk or even think about losing any contact with our kids, but many are faced with tough decisions regarding their families in the context of divorce.&#160; New laws enacted in <a href="http://www.fox-shjeflo.com/" Title="California Attorney">California</a> just made these rough decisions even harder.<br /><br />Effective January 1, 2012, portions of the Family Code which govern child custody proceedings were revised. Many family law practitioners believe the new law is troubling in that it places children smack dab in the middle of custody disputes.&#160;&#160; <br /><br />The new law states that children fourteen years and older who want to address the court may testify regarding custody or visitation issues, unless the court feels it is not in the best interest of the child.&#160; If the judge finds it is not in the best interest of the child to testify, the judge will have to explain her reason for precluding the testimony on the record.&#160; Those younger than fourteen can also address the court if the judge feels it is in the best interest of the child.&#160; If a child is not allowed to testify, the judge must find an alternate means of getting a child&#8217;s input on these issues.&#160; <br /><br />Though nothing requires a child to testify, if an attorney for a parent requests that a child fourteen or older testify, the Court will have to allow it unless there is a good reason not to.&#160; <br /><br />All this means that parents may force their children to testify, or, worse yet, coach a child to testify a certain way.&#160; Though some children may want to testify, others may want to just stay out of their parents&#8217; fight.&#160; The new law makes it harder to keep kids out of it. Time will tell how it all will play out, but families in the midst of divorce and custody disputes have some tough decisions to make.<!--more-->Making decisions in custody and visitation disputes in California just got harder.'
