aS'<p>I am somewhat mystified when I see a seminar topic for lawyers on how to prepare a case for arbitration and/or mediation. The fact is the case should be presented in an arbitration hearing or in a mediation setting just as a case is prepared for trial: you put your best foot forward. There is no special preparation for arbitration or mediation. <a title="American Arbitration Association" href="http://www.adr.org/" target="&#95;blank">Arbitration</a> is a hearing out of which comes a final and binding decision with all rights of appeal waived. The individual who serves as arbitrator is often a retired judge but it can just as easily be an attorney and, in fact, it need not be an attorney. The arbitrator is selected by the parties and he/she attests to his/her neutrality. A mediation is an attempt by a neutral to bring the parties together toward resolution. Both sides make a presentation and the mediator spends the rest of the day caucusing with each side and occasionally brings all parties together for an update or assessment. The purpose of mediation is that at the end of the process, usually taking a day but often more than that, the case has been resolved.</p><p>There may be certain strategic considerations in approaching a trial, arbitration or mediation differently. The basic thrust is the same, however. The case must be well-prepared to obtain the best result regardless of the forum. Demonstrative aids and conclusions of experts should be known to the plaintiff&#8217;s <a title="Boston Injury Attorney" href="http://www.feinbergalban.com/attorneys/Robert-Feinberg/" target="&#95;blank">lawyer</a> and presented as part of the case. A shoddy presentation will not result in a favorable arbitration verdict, be it on liability or damages, nor will a poor performance at a mediation result in a satisfactory settlement. It all comes down to preparation, preparation, and preparation.</p><!--more--><p><a title="Boston Personal Injury Lawyer" href="http://www.feinbergalban.com/" target="&#95;blank">Boston injury lawyer</a> Robert Feinberg&#160;offers his perspective on&#160;how to prepare a case for arbitration and/or mediation... </p>'
